!dlim!!jump1! HEROES !jump2!!dlim!!jfrom1! HEROES !jfrom2!!dlim!!pcr
ed! Evan Yee/Daily News !off! 
!capt! Marsha Bender, left, and Treva Tegtmeier were honored Friday
for aiding crime victims. !dtpost!!dlim!!head!Garcetti commends 
ordinary folks for 
grit under pressure!dlim!!head!District Attorney's Office salutes
acts of bravery!dlim! !by1! By  Jesse Hiestand  
!by2! Daily News Staff Writer !dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; By flashing her headlights, Treva Tegtmeier stopped two
gang members from beating and kicking a man who had fought gang
graffiti in his North Hollywood neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the gangsters tried to pull open the door of her car,
she called 911 on her cellular phone. Police arrested the two, and
the Sherman Oaks actress's testimony helped send them to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would do it again,'' said Tegtmeier, one of eight people the
Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office honored Friday for
their bravery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew that it wouldn't stop until somebody stopped it,''
Tegtmeier, 35, said of the September incident. ``I was really
scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Also honored at the 14th annual Courageous Citizens Awards was
Marsha Bender, a Woodland Hills resident who is credited with
stopping a man from beating his wife and then comforting the woman
and her children until police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to force her into the car and closing the door
on her leg and arms,'' Bender said about the incident in the
parking lot outside her Van Nuys office in September. ``Even the
kids had tried to pull the man off his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender said she simply walked out and told the man to leave his
wife alone, which he did by leaving the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just helping someone in dire need. There was no
alternative,'' said Bender, 47, director of a weight-loss center.
``I hope someone will help me if I ever get in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender testified at the man's trial, and he was sent to prison
for three years, district attorney officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Six other Southern California residents were recognized at the
awards luncheon at the Wilshire Grand Hotel in downtown Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they're not heroes, but they are,'' said District
Attorney Gil Garcetti. ``These are people who saw a situation that
needed attention and did it without hesitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The other honorees were:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !bbox! &LR; Roger Furnival, 54, of Santa Monica stopped two men
attacking a woman in West Los Angeles, holding one despite being
stabbed in the side by the accomplice. The men were caught and both
are awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !bbox! &LR; Carrie M. James, 23, of Los Angeles used a baseball bat
to stop a man from beating a woman with a wooden object in
September. She held the man at bay until police arrived, possibly
saving the woman's life. The man is now serving a 25-year-to-life
prison term.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !bbox! &LR; Trista Martin, 26, of Beverly Hills, weighing just 95
pounds, took on two burglars after they broke into a neighbor's
home. She hit one of the men in the face and tried to retrieve her
neighbor's goods from the taxi the men were using as a getaway car.
Her description of the vehicle led to the arrest of the men, both
of whom face long prison terms when sentenced next month.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !bbox! &LR; Albert Pitts, 36, of Los Angeles followed a motorist who
fled the scene of a crash in South Central Los Angeles in March. He
pulled a bleeding child from the wreckage, but the motorist grabbed
the child back and drove away. Pitts followed the woman and called
police on a cell phone. The woman was arrested and is awaiting
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !bbox! &LR; Hector Dominguez, 27, of Santa Ana saw a man shoot and
kill two people outside a La Puente nightclub in March 1998.
Crouching behind a door and using a cell phone, Dominguez called
911 and wrote the license number of the getaway car on his palm.
Police tracked down the car and Dominguez testified against the
suspect, who is awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !bbox! &LR; James Sanchez, 28, of Long Beach saw a couple with two
children leave a Montebello motel without the children in September
1997. He heard water running and banging in the room, which he
entered with the manager's help. He found the boy wrapped in duct
tape and the girl rolled up in a wet bedspread in the bathtub. The
little girl also was bound with duct tape and appeared near death.
Both children survived. The couple who abused them were arrested,
tried, convicted and sent to prison. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
