<SLUG> BC-PEACE-TRAINING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE PROGRAM HELPS TEENS COPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When two Colorado teen-agers went on a bloody
rampage, LAUSD counselor Ron Klemp knew exactly what to do: He
convened students in his Northridge Middle School Peace Institute
in Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In a somber, emotional session, they discussed the tragedy and
brainstormed ways to prevent similar bloodshed in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people like me are scared about being in school,'' said
13-year-old Norma Hernandez. ``One time a guy followed me and my
friend home with a knife and said he was going to kill us both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how people act sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Klemp asked the youngsters what they would do if their friends
were acting strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell someone real fast, and I'd ask them if they have
a problem,'' said Jessie Carpio, 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my friend was acting like an outcast, I would talk to them
and try to make them not an outcast,'' 13-year-old Leidy Montes
chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   Similar discussions took place at other Los Angeles middle
schools and at a Mississippi school, all of which have created
Peace Institutes based on Klemp's model.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is to teach the kids to put themselves in someone
else's shoes, to explore solutions without violence and to learn
how to control their emotions and actions,'' Klemp said.
</P>
<P>
   Next month he is scheduled to present the Middle School Peace
Institute at a conference of the United States' attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ultimate hope is that this program becomes a systemic part
of every middle school, like the DARE program,'' Klemp said,
referring to Drug Abuse Resistance Education now taught in many
schools. ``We are in serious need of teaching the human part of
curriculum.''
</P>
<P>
   Already it's taught at 10 Los Angeles middle schools, most in
the San Fernando Valley, said Klemp, a staff developer and teacher
trainer at Northridge Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1993, the Peace Institute is designed to teach
students to use their brains instead of brawn to resolve conflicts
and to take action against violence.
</P>
<P>
   The institute also serves as a coping tool for students in the
face of news events like the Columbine High School massacre, and
the stresses of teen-age life, he said. They've discussed the
Northridge Earthquake, the Civil Rights Movement, the Kosovo
bombings, the Holocaust and more, Klemp said.
</P>
<P>
   And Klemp believes it works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their awareness level is different from other kids, and when
incidents like these happen it makes their fears more real,'' Klemp
said. ``They want to know how to deal with it and what they can do
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Klemp developed the program as his teacher training project,
after realizing that he was unprepared for counseling students who
face ``death and mayhem'' as part of daily life.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a popular feature at seminars of teachers and law
enforcement officers nationwide trying to reduce violence on
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The program is rooted in the notion that society has grown
tremendously in technology, but has deeply failed in social issues,
Klemp said. He has placed a new demand on the teachers he trains,
emphasizing that learning ``isn't all about test scores,'' Klemp
said.
</P>
<P>
   The study of world peace is woven into the curriculum in some
classes at participating schools, which adds context to issues like
war, racism and violence in history, Klemp said.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 teachers in the Los Angeles Unified School District
have been trained to teach for the Peace Institute. And teachers
say the program helps students find their own answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really come up with their own ideas about how to solve
world problems, and the class discussions get a life of their
own,'' social studies teacher Andrea Naud said. ``It's great for
the kids and builds character.''
</P>
<P>
   The program has been a hit at Brinkley Middle School in Jackson,
Miss. _ the only school outside of Los Angeles to adopt the
curriculum _ where students often visit the home of slain civil
rights leader Medgar Evers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started the program after a fight between two groups of
sixth-grade girls. They thought the only way to solve their problem
was to fight,'' said program Director Lynn Moss. ``It's a rich,
rich program and teaches kids to hold back when their temper is
up.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
