<SLUG> BC-CANYON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND CANYON DIGS IN FOR MASS TRANSIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   More visitors, fewer cars.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the 21st century holds for Grand Canyon National
Park as it moves into the mass-transit era.
</P>
<P>
   A groundbreaking ceremony Friday launched work on the hub of the
canyon's planned light-rail and bus system.
</P>
<P>
   The Canyon View Information Plaza will be more than a bus/train
terminal. It will also be a crossroads for the canyon's walking and
cycling trails, and will provide visitors with the information they
need to negotiate the 1.2 million-acre park.
</P>
<P>
   The plaza will be built 500 to 800 feet back from the South Rim,
near Mather Point. Mather is the first scenic overlook for most
visitors, and the information plaza is designed to play off its
dramatic views.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt was among the nearly 400 people
who attended Friday's groundbreaking. The former Arizona governor
said the project would give the Grand Canyon the best visitor
service of all the national parks.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the project will virtually banish cars from the
park, freeing congested roads and reducing the level of
concentrated auto exhaust, parks spokeswoman Maureen Oltrogge said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's about more than mass transit. Oltrogge said the new
information plaza is designed to handle crowds: as many as 4,200
people per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the information plaza and transit hub will cost
$6.8 million, Oltrogge said, with most funds coming from a 1996
decision that doubled the park entry fee to $20.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be able to plan their trip inside the park and
then move on _ either by train, an alternatively fueled bus,
bicycle or foot. That will make the Grand Canyon the first national
park to offer four transportation options from the same point.
</P>
<P>
   The transit system is expected to be in place by spring 2002,
Oltrogge said. At that time, most visitors will park their cars
outside the Grand Canyon, in Tusayan, and take a 10-minute electric
train ride into the information plaza.
</P>
<P>
   The park won't be entirely carless, however. Campers and those
staying at the South Rim's various lodges will be able to drive in,
but they'll have to rely on mass transit to move about the park,
Oltrogge said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Friday's groundbreaking, parks officials announced
the start of a $55 million capital campaign to pay for various
improvements at the park. Phoenix Newspapers Inc., publisher of
``The Arizona'' ``Republic,'' donated $100,000 to educational
programs.
</P>
<P>
   A Heritage Education Campus will be established in the heart of
the park in restored historic buildings. The Del E. Webb Foundation
kicked off those efforts in January with a $2.5 million
contribution that will pay for restoration of a 1935 Community
Building into an education center. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
