<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Saturday, April 24, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Susan Leh at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-COUNSELORS (Los Angeles) _ The nation's high school
guidance counselors help students with everything from filling out
college applications to coping with unplanned pregnancies. But the
murderous rampage in Colorado focused attention on their critical
role in identifying and intervening when students exhibit the
warning signs of potential violence. By David Baker. (Will move in
the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-TRAINING (Los Angeles) _ Ron Klemp's training didn't
prepare him for the ``death and mayhem'' he has experienced
first-hand during his 27-year career in Los Angeles, where violence
is routine. So he created the Middle School Peace Institute,
teaching students to use their brains instead of brawn to solve
conflicts, and to take action against violence. Serious issues
emerged at Northridge Middle School as students discussed the
Colorado massacre. By Phillip W. Browne. (Will move in the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   HEROES_HONORED (Los Angeles) _ ``Courageous Citizens'' of Los
Angeles are honored, inlcuding Treva Tegtmeier, who, by flashing
the headlights on her car, stopped two gang members from beating
and kicking a man who had complained about graffiti in his North
Hollywood neighborhood. By Jesse Hiestand. &QL; 
(Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
