<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETITGOUT (WHO?) WANTS GIANTS' FANS TO WAIT AND SEE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Ind.)   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When it was time for the Giants to make
their first draft pick, it was a surprise to hear the name Luke
Petitgout.
</P>
<P>
   Even to Luke Petitgout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the Giants liked me and I thought I might go somewhere
in the first round,'' Petitgout, a tackle at Notre Dame who will
play guard for the Giants, said Friday before a 90-minute practice
for Giants draft selections, free agents and assorted veterans.
``But I was like everybody else, I guess. I thought maybe they
liked Aaron Gibson.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson is the 388-pound tackle from Wisconsin who many expected
to be the Giants' first choice. He was taken by Detroit, eight
selections after the Giants picked at No. 19.
</P>
<P>
   At home in Georgetown, Del., last weekend, it did not take
Petitgout and his family long to see that the mention of his name
at the draft left most dumbfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty obvious,'' Petitgout said. ``There was Chris
Berman on ESPN saying, `Luke who?' and Mel Kiper, well, he didn't
know what to say. It was kind of funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Petitgout was raised in rural Delaware, where his father still
farms 80 acres of corn and soybean as a hobby from his regular job
as an ombudsman for the state of Delaware. Although Petitgout is 6
feet 5 inches and 315 pounds, he kept a low profile during his
Notre Dame days, which he said was not difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a place like Notre Dame,'' he said, ``it's not going to be
the left tackle who gets the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   But Friday at Giants Stadium, Petitgout was the center of
attention as he posed for pictures with coaches and the rest of the
draft class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a little overwhelming,'' he said. ``But I'll get
used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the cries of ``Luke who?'' Petitgout is unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not much worried about it,'' he said. ``Publicity isn't
what makes a good football player. People don't know me, but all I
ask is that they wait and see about me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If picking Petitgout was not surprising enough, the Giants then
took Notre Dame's other starting offensive tackle from last year,
Mike Rosenthal, in the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   Petitgout was surprised by that pick, too. ``We had already
talked about how our time together was ending,'' Petitgout said.
``But it's going to be good to have a friend here. And he's a good
football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal is a big football player. At 6-7 and 310 it was not
hard to find him on the practice field today.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel said of Petitgout and Rosenthal: ``You look at
those big bodies and it's no wonder why Notre Dame pounded some
people on the line.'' Notre Dame's offensive line allowed just nine
sacks last season and was ranked 16th nationally in rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, if Rosenthal had been the Giants' first-round
choice and Petitgout the fifth-rounder, there would not have been
much surprise. Rosenthal was everybody's high school all-American.
He was one of the most heavily recruited linemen in the nation when
he graduated from Penn High School in Mishawaka, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Petitgout was a high school tight end and captain of his high
school golf team. He was switched to guard after he redshirted his
freshman season at Notre Dame. He became the starting left tackle
during his junior season. But even after last season ended, it was
Rosenthal who made the majority of the all-star teams, not
Petitgout.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, looking for a quick tackle who could also play left
guard, preferred Petitgout because of his agile feet and
athleticism. Rosenthal said that he was not offended when his
teammate was taken four rounds ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Rosenthal said. ``At Notre Dame, everyone is an
all-American. You learn to check your egos at the door. Luke and I
have always gotten along great.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said that Petitgout, who is quiet with a respectful,
country manner, will succeed in his new high-profile role.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Notre Dame, there's a lot of pressure; it's always there
from coaches, fans and media,'' he said. ``Luke will be just
fine.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
