A1476 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NOTEBOOK-N     04-24 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL'S $25,000 FINE WILL COME FROM APPAREL COMPANY'S POCKETS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla., N.C. Ga., Pa., Ind., Mass.)   (jw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dave Checketts' attempt to bring order to the Knicks was diluted
Friday when the $25,000 fine slapped on Latrell Sprewell was picked
up by an apparel company the guard endorses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got Latrell's back,'' said Jay Coen Gilbert, the
founding partner of And 1, in a radio interview. ``And we want him
to concentrate on playing basketball and helping the Knicks get to
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the week, Sprewell's agent, Robert Gist, was critical
of how the team was using his client and questioned the leadership
of the Knicks' organization. On Wednesday, the day he dismissed
Ernie Grunfeld from his position as team president and general
manager, Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden, said he
held Sprewell accountable for his agent's comments and fined him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who thinks they can step up and take potshots at the
organization and the coach is in for that kind of treatment,''
Checketts said when he handed down his fine. ``I won't stand for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Checketts attended the Knicks' game against
Charlotte but was unavailable for comment. Barry Watkins, a Garden
spokesman, said the team would still take the fine out of
Sprewell's paycheck. He also said Checketts had no reaction to And
1's decision to pay the fine for Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell had been considering whether to appeal the fine through
the players association. But with the company's pitching in, he may
decide to forget about the red tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's saying a lot for them to say that they're taking care
of something like that,'' Sprewell said. ``If they do that, it
makes it easier for it to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell had to get his focus on the game quickly Friday night.
After being late for practice Thursday, he was stuck in traffic and
arrived in the locker room at Madison Square Garden just after 7
p.m. for an 8 o'clock tip-off. Most of the players get to the game
90 minutes before the game.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time Sprewell had been the center of
controversy with the team. Throughout the season, Sprewell has
voiced his displeasure with being the team's sixth man. The
comments made by Gist concerned that very issue. Gist was upset
that a player like Sprewell, a three-time All-Star, has been used
that way by the Knicks. He also said the tension that existed
between Grunfeld and Coach Jeff Van Gundy had filtered down to the
team. While Sprewell said the comments of his agent were ill-timed,
he did not rebut the basis of them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of his teammates were surprised at the fine. Patrick
Ewing, the president of the players association, said he was going
to look into the union's stance on the issue. Now, the matter may
die.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an issue for me,'' Sprewell said. ``I'm not focusing
on it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   KNICKS HAVE SEVEN UP
</P>
<P>
   After the Knicks played Charlotte on Friday night, they had
seven games remaining: Miami twice, Charlotte, Atlanta,
Philadelphia, Indiana and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   As packed as the schedule is over the next two weeks, there is
no way of knowing just how few victories the Knicks can get by with
and make the playoffs. Almost all of the teams jockeying for the
last three spots in the playoff standing play each other this week.
But Coach Jeff Van Gundy was willing to guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a chance? I'd say we have to win five games,'' he said
before his team played the Hornets. ``I didn't say that would get
us in, but it gives us a chance. You never know. But that's a basic
number. Whether it's true or not I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON INVESTIGATION DROPPED
</P>
<P>
   The league has dropped its investigation into a recent report
that described a scene in which Larry Johnson exposed himself to
the Knicks' public relations director, Lori Hamamoto, and used
inappropriate language when addressing her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to both Lori and Larry, and both insist the
incident never took place,'' said Chris Brienza, the league's vice
president for sports media relations. ``The matter is closed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
