<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL NOTEBOOK: READING, WRITING AND OPERA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TINA ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 24: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Few book reviewers are paid more quickly or have a more
appreciative audience than Corey Sheen. He reviews novels and
nature books for the newspaper of the bookstore at Public School
161 in Brooklyn's Crown Heights neighborhood, which pays him in
books. Every Wednesday morning, students can buy books for one
dollar. They depend on reviews like Corey's to help them choose. At
the moment he is recommending ``Salmon,'' about the fish, which in
a recent review he called ``full of intriguing information'' and
``easily read and understood by young children.''
</P>
<P>
   Corey, who is in first grade, should know. Although math is his
favorite subject, Corey guesses he has ``99 books'' at home and has
read them all. His father, Carlos Torres, helps him with the really
hard words.
</P>
<P>
   From kindergarten through fifth grade, P.S. 161 is a
neighborhood school, admitting every student that space permits.
Two years ago it added a competitive middle school, the Crown
School for Law and Journalism, which admits the best applicants
from the same neighborhood. Virtually all the students are black,
mostly West Indians like Corey, who came to New York from Trinidad
four years ago. Nearly 97 percent qualify for free lunches _ not
usually a good sign for academic success _ yet P.S. 161's third
graders' reading scores tower above the city average. Every eighth
grader passed the Regents math exam last year, and all but one
passed the biology exam. On sixth-grade reading tests last year,
the school ranked second of all public schools in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Much of P.S. 161's success can be attributed to its
administrators and staff. Irwin Kurz, the kinetic principal,
arrives at 6 most mornings, and personally greets the children
every day when they enter and leave the building. His staff of
unusually experienced teachers, many of whom he has hand-picked,
call him a demanding leader who inspires them to get the most out
of their students.
</P>
<P>
   But there is much in Kurz's program that other schools could
duplicate. P.S. 161 has an aura of gravity. Students wear uniforms,
with neckties. The teachers dress up as well, many in suits. The
halls are spotless and hushed. Although many classes have 35
students _ one thing he would change if he had the money, Kurz says
_ a visit to numerous classrooms found all the students paying
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers use a phonics-based reading series, but the school has
spent thousands of dollars both from fund-raisers and its very
active Parent Association to supplement the texts with novels. When
students first learn to read, they go to Kurz's office and read a
book to him. Classes read novels together, a chapter a night as
homework, and discuss what they have read. Students write essays
every week.
</P>
<P>
   In Alice Cherry's fourth-grade class they write and illustrate
their own complete books, after studying writing techniques such as
using action to show character. There are high expectations of
teachers, students and parents in every field; 10 years ago for the
school play a music teacher, Ann Aviles, staged ``Carmen.'' Now she
takes a group each year to the Metropolitan Opera. This year,
before seeing a Tchaikovsky opera, the students studied the daily
life and art of late-19th-century Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But hard work, says Kurz, is not enough. ``You need to plan,
monitor and support it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When parents come in June to register for fall kindergarten,
they get a list of skills children are expected to have when they
start school, and specific ways parents can teach them. In school,
students are repeatedly tested. If they fall behind, reading and
math specialists provide tutoring. They also meet with parents as
often as every two weeks, lend them educational games and recommend
ways to work with the child. The lesson of P.S. 161 is that with
creative teaching, constant feedback and intense family
involvement, ``every child can learn'' can be more than a slogan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
