<HEADER>
A1487 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2NDLD-WRI     04-24 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO DEFENSE MINISTERS AGREE ON OIL EMBARGO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Updates and revisions throughout) (rk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the opening day of the NATO summit meeting
Friday, the alliance agreed on a plan to impose an oil embargo on
Serbia and to enforce it by searching ships in the Adriatic Sea
suspected of carrying fuel for forces fighting in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Defense ministers of the 19-nation alliance undertook to enforce
the restrictions after NATO leaders made the decision at a
three-hour session focused on the Kosovo war. The leaders also
decided to order the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, to carry
out heavier airstrikes against overland pipelines and railroads
that carry fuel from the ports of Montenegro to Serbia, a senior
Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance leaders have gathered here to celebrate 50 years of
the alliance, whose celebration has been overshadowed by the Kosovo
war.
</P>
<P>
   At their session, the NATO leaders issued a communique spelling
out their intentions for Kosovo's future. If President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia began to withdraw his forces according to
an agreed-to timetable, the communique said, the allies would
deploy an ``international military force'' and set up an
``international provisional administration'' in the province,
giving it autonomy, but not independence.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of deploying an international force and setting up some
form of protectorate has been intensively discussed in Brussels,
Washington and other NATO capitals. But the communique marked a
formal commitment by NATO to those conditions for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The allies also pledged to seek a U.N. Security Council
resolution to demand the withdrawal of Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   The specification that the force and the interim administration
in Kosovo would be ``international,'' and not necessarily NATO-led,
and the inclusion of the Security Council appeared designed to
encourage the participation of Russia in a diplomatic solution,
which in turn was expected to make it easier for Milosevic to
accept.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the allies officially rejected recent offers
of a settlement made by Milosevic through Russia's Balkan envoy,
former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. Without naming
Chernomyrdin, the communique said the Yugoslav leader's ``offers to
date'' did not meet NATO conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Military leaders have been pushing for ways to choke off oil
supplies to Yugoslavia, arguing that new oil was arriving even as
they were bombing oil installations.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said on Thursday that
``basically it didn't make a lot of sense for us to be bombing
refineries and at the same time not doing enough to prevent the
access of oil by sea.'' She added, ``We are particularly focusing
on oil because that is the way that forces move around.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the European Union pushed through a decision
to ban the supply of oil and refined products to Yugoslavia,
excluding supplies for relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The defense ministers said they would provide ships to conduct
the searches and inspections on the Adriatic, the Pentagon official
said. The effort would be intended to stop oil flowing into the
ports of Bar and Kotor Bay, on the coast of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   But the official said an effort would be made to minimize the
damage to Montenegro, a republic of Yugoslavia that has opposed the
government of Milosevic. ``The question is how to stop the flow of
oil into Montenegro and to stop the flow out of Montenegro without
hurting the Montenegrins.''
</P>
<P>
   In their communique, the 19 leaders reaffirmed the five basic
demands that Milosevic must agree to for the bombing to stop. They
are a verifiable cease-fire; withdrawal of all Serb military and
police forces from Kosovo; the stationing of an international
military presence that would have NATO at its core; the safe return
of the ethnic Albanian refugees to Kosovo, and a willingness to
work toward a political agreement based on accords from the failed
talks held in Rambouillet, France, in February.
</P>
<P>
   The formal 17-point communique of the summit was released
against a backdrop of tough language. Phrases like ``resolve to see
this challenge through'' and declarations that ``NATO will
prevail'' reverberated throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Shea, the NATO spokesman, set a tone that combined
perseverance and defensiveness. He said: ``NATO has an obligation
to succeed. We cannot afford to lose this one.''
</P>
<P>
   At a closed session of the 19 leaders, Clark gave an upbeat
10-minute briefing on the status of the air campaign. He told them
that NATO had ``achieved air superiority at mid to high altitudes
throughout Yugoslavia,'' according to his spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Clark flew back to Brussels Friday night, without meeting with
President Clinton. His spokeswoman said he had to get back to the
war.
</P>
<P>
   And in public briefings by various NATO leaders, their ministers
and spokesmen invoked the idea of ground troops as they tried to
send a unified message. Much of that talk seemed aimed at
Milosevic, since the alliance leaders still insist that the air
campaign is effective.
</P>
<P>
   That option _ of when and how they would enter Kosovo _ was not
addressed in the official 17-point communique on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But there was ``some discussion'' about ground troops at the
closed Kosovo session of the 19 leaders, the Canadian defense
minister, Art Eggleton, said in an interview. The talk focused on
asking the military planners at NATO headquarters to review all
options, but did not get into specifics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Their discussion followed a decision two days ago by NATO's
secretary- general, Javier Solana, to review all plans for
introducing group troops into the region, a decision made at the
request of the allies.
</P>
<P>
   The British, who have been the most vocal on the subject of
ground troops, reiterated Friday that they envisioned a situation
where troops could enter Kosovo after Serb forces had been very
heavily punished and where Milosevic had not given his consent.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain spent
two and a half hours with Clinton in a private dinner at the White
House, trying to explain to the president the necessity of being
prepared to send in troops without Yugoslavia's consent but after
Serb forces had been severely weakened, British officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's chief of the defense staff, Gen. Charles Guthrie,
repeated this theme at a news conference Friday, saying:
``President Milosevic's war machine has been seriously weakened.
It's going to be weakened again, day after day, week after week.''
He added, in reference to going into Kosovo, ``And we will be able
to choose our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie said that there were now about 19,000 allied troops in
Macedonia and Albania and that more be sent in the coming weeks to
be ready to ``to take the refugees back.''
</P>
<P>
   The general said that he was not prepared to say how many troops
would be needed for the operation but that it would need to be more
than the 30,000 proposed as a security force in Kosovo before the
air attacks began.
</P>
<P>
   The British officials stressed that none of the allies would
agree to ground troops' fighting their way into Kosovo. ``We are
not talking about an invasion force,'' Defense Secretary George
Robertson of Britain said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced Friday night that about 2,300 troops
accompanied by heavy armor were being sent to Albania, adding to
the 3,000 American soldiers already there. The new troops were
being sent with 15 tanks, 14 Bradley armored vehicles, eight
howitzers and a company of soldiers armed with anti-tank weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
