<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-24 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: NEW PINOCHET STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   In a new legal strategy, Chile announced that it would request
arbitration from the World Court at The Hague to determine whether
Britain, Spain or Chile has the sovereign right to decide the legal
fate of the former dictator Augusto Pinochet. He has been held in
Britain since October on a warrant issued by a Spanish judge
charging him with various crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: U.S. AIDE'S TRIP PUT OFF
</P>
<P>
   The United States has indefinitely postponed an official trip to
Caracas by an assistant secretary of state, saying ``now is not a
good time'' for him to visit. The action came after Foreign
Minister Jose Vicente Rangel accused Washington of exerting
``elements of pressure'' to prevent President Hugo Chavez from
carrying out the ``peaceful revolution'' he has pledged, and
described American policy toward Cuba as ``a stupidity.''
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ELECTORAL REFORMS PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   The four opposition parties that control the Chamber of Deputies
introduced a package of electoral reforms. One provision would
enable Mexicans living in the United States to vote in Mexico's
presidential elections next year. Another would make it easier for
opposition parties to unite behind a joint presidential candidate
in 2000. President Ernesto Zedillo's governing party, known as the
PRI, opposes the reforms. They are likely to be approved in the
Chamber but blocked by the PRI-controlled Senate.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND: NATIONALISTS FADING
</P>
<P>
   Two polls showed the Scottish Nationalist Party, advocates of
full independence for Scotland, losing substantial ground to the
Labor Party in campaigning for May 6 elections to the new
Parliament in Edinburgh. The Glasgow Herald, whose poll was based
on interviews with 3,255 voters, making it the biggest poll
conducted in Scotland, said Labor appeared headed for a majority of
seats and that the earlier support for the Nationalists, headed by
Alex Salmond was now ``in free fall.''
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: EASING DRUG LAWS
</P>
<P>
   A government commission has recommended that the sale and use of
marijuana be legalized under certain conditions. The
recommendations were part of an overall study of Swiss drug laws,
which have failed to prevent a rise in marijuana consumption. To
prevent the country from becoming a drug haven, purchasers would
have to prove they lived in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: BLACK CRICKETER CONVICTED
</P>
<P>
   Makhaya Ntini, the only black cricketer on the national team and
central to its efforts to recruit black youths to the game, was
convicted of rape. The team, which had supported him through the
trial, immediately suspended him. Ntini denied raping or having
consensual sex with a young woman who asked him for a ride home
from a cricket ground, and his lawyers said they would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: PEOPLE'S POET GETS 13 YEARS
</P>
<P>
   Mzwakhe Mbuli, a musician and writer known as the People's Poet,
was sentenced to 13 years in prison for his part in a 1997 bank
robbery. Mbuli claimed that he was framed because he had
information about drug-running and gun-smuggling by high-ranking
members of the African National Congress. Mbuli said he would
appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
