<HEADER>
A1494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NY     04-24 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BEAT HORNETS, 110-105  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Ewing stared down the shot clock as he stood
on the fringe of the paint with his back against Derrick Coleman
and the ball in his palm. Several seconds ticked off, and the crowd
bubbling inside Madison Square Garden grew edgy. What was he
thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Thoughts of all those missed last-second shots, all those
botched free throws in the pinch could have been circling his head
like buzzards. But Ewing was not pondering failure. Ewing believed
he was going to take the shot, make the shot and be the hero. And
perhaps be the one to salvage this tumultuous season for the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   For once, Ewing's faith was rewarded. After the Knicks watched
their 18-point lead shrink to 1 with 1 minute 2 seconds left, Ewing
provided the critical points of separation when he wheeled past
Coleman and delivered a running jumper with 24 seconds remaining.
That shot gave the Knicks the edge they needed to end their
four-game skid, poke their heads back into the playoff standing and
halt the Hornets' nine-game winning streak by desperately holding
on for a 110-105 victory Friday night. The Knicks (22-21) are tied
with Toronto for eighth place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my shot,'' said Ewing, whose jumper put the Knicks
ahead by 106-102. ``I've been shooting that one my whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a sure thing, though. As the shot clock wound down to
10, Ewing drove left and launched an off-kilter jumper over
Coleman, the player he had scuffled with earlier in the game, and
watched it bound off the rim four times before going in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twice, it bounced twice,'' Ewing said with a smile. No, four
times, he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Ewing said, inhaling deeply, ``it went in, didn't
it?''
</P>
<P>
   The bounce went the Knicks' way. And this time, despite some
nervous moments, the Knicks survived a nearly disastrous fourth
quarter. Somewhere, former team president Ernie Grunfeld might have
been saying, ``So, now they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was dismissed on Wednesday after watching the Knicks fall to
.500 and seeing the organization come apart. But this victory by
the Knicks was not an act of support for Coach Jeff Van Gundy or a
salute to Grunfeld. Next to the 30-point effort of Allan Houston,
Ewing scored 26 points, including 4 in the last two minutes,
because he could run and hop and spin on an Achilles' tendon that
had been given three days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of good bounces had everything to do with it. Just
before Ewing's shot, Marcus Camby missed a free throw with 47.8
seconds left, then tracked it down and started a play that ended up
with Ewing's shot.
</P>
<P>
   The shot came against the player who got in a shoving match with
Ewing midway through the third quarter. Already in the game, Elden
Campbell had been ejected for clobbering Kurt Thomas in the back of
the head and berating an official. Coleman shoved Ewing, who shoved
back. Ewing nearly got himself ejected when he tossed Charlie Ward
aside and rushed toward Coleman. He restrained himself just enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who led by 18 with five minutes left in the third
quarter, watched as the Hornets missed two shots, grabbed two
rebounds and ended the possession when Chuck Person hit 3-pointer
with 4:39 left to make it 96-91. The Hornets cut it to 103-102
after Coleman barged his way inside for a layup and foul that ended
with a 3-point play.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks built a 17-point lead in the opening four minutes of
the third. The frustration with the whole ugly scene for the
Hornets boiled over with 5:50 left in the third quarter. Campbell
missed a layup in traffic, then sent a forearm to the back of
Thomas' head.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was called for a flagrant foul. In his disgust with the
call, Campbell pointed into the face of referee Scott Wall, who
slapped him with a technical foul and ejected him from the game.
With Eddie Jones already out with injury, the Hornets' most
important source of offense was headed to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   This was a switch. Usually, the Knicks are the team quickest to
lose its poise. And they didn't disappoint. After they appeared to
have everything under control, holding a 72-54 lead with 5 minutes
left in the third, Coleman and Ewing got into their scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the bottom began falling out for the Knicks. The
Hornets, using Bobby Phills to drive and a 3-pointer from Chuck
Person, went on a 16-7 run to cut the Knicks' lead to 79-70 with 32
seconds left in the third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
