<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-JAYS-NYT &LR;      04-24 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT JAYS, 6-4  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Wells badly wanted to beat the Yankees, they
all knew that, and Wells's ballyhooed return to Yankee Stadium
arched the eyebrow of a former teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows Boomer wants to stick it to us tonight,'' said
the Yankee, using Wells' nickname. ``Well, I would imagine the guys
in here want to stick it to him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing personal. Wells took a businesslike approach to the
mound, all but ignoring the Yankee Stadium fans who cheered for him
in his first game in New York since being traded to Toronto, and
his former teammates reciprocated, taking him apart bit by bit in a
6-4 victory. Chili Davis slammed a two-run double in a
seventh-inning rally that knocked Wells (3-1) out of the game, and
made a winning pitcher out of Orlando Hernandez (3-1).
</P>
<P>
   Wells will receive his championship ring this weekend, but it
will come without bragging rights attached, after his loss Friday
night. Wells had allowed just four hits in maintaining a 1-1 tie
through six innings, but like many pitchers victimized by the
Yankees, he had worked hard, throwing 84 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill had been 1 for 16 in his career against Wells,
hitting into a double play and striking out in his first two
at-bats, but he drew a walk against Wells leading off the seventh.
Bernie Williams then fouled off four pitches with a full count,
until, on the 10th pitch of the at-bat, he walked, as well; two on,
nobody out. Mel Queen, the Toronto pitching coach, went to the
mound to give Wells a breather.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, aggressive on the bases all night against the
slow-moving Wells, ran again: O'Neill and Williams broke from
second and first, respectively, and Davis ripped a line drive to
right, the ball thumping off the wall. O'Neill and Williams scored,
the Yankees led, 3-1, and Wells was in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez then rolled a single through the middle, driving
home Davis and finishing Wells. After Wells trudged off the mound,
the crowd of 36,529 erupted respectfully in recognition of what he
did for them last year.
</P>
<P>
   Wells looked up briefly and flicked his glove before
disappearing into the dugout. Thanks, but no thanks. Nothing
personal.
</P>
<P>
   Those fans willing to stand in the last of the lingering showers
Friday evening sprinkled a warm greeting on Wells when he emerged
from the Toronto dugout at 7:25 p.m. en route to the bullpen to
warm up.
</P>
<P>
   Wells acknowledged those cheers with a few waves _ pointing with
his glove at the fans in right field _ and Wells was even more
animated in acknowledging the fans while returning from the
bullpen, when he received a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   When Shawn Green grounded out to end Toronto's first at-bat, the
Yankee faithful began rising around the ancient ball park,
anticipating Wells' emergence onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   The last out of Wells' perfect game was shown on the Yankees'
giant video screen, and the chilly air was shaken by the steely
sounds of a song played for Wells when he was in pinstripes _ Van
Halen's ``Running With the Devil.'' For Wells, the ultimate
welcome-home party.
</P>
<P>
   But it was as if Wells postponed his love affair with Yankee
fans, if only for a couple hours. As they stood for him and cheered
for him during Wells' first stroll to the center of the diamond,
Wells did not wave, did not glance into the stands, never looked in
the Yankee dugout. They stood and cheered for him, and Wells stared
downward and dug at the dirt in front of the rubber with his left
foot, as intent as any 6-year-old pushing Matchbox cars through a
sandbox.
</P>
<P>
   The clapping subsided gradually. When the fans in the
right-field bleachers chanted his name, making him the first
opponent to be honored in their roll call, Wells quickly jabbed his
glove in their direction, acknowledging and dismissing them
simultaneously: OK, I know you love me, now shut up while I work.
</P>
<P>
   Then David Wells went about the business of trying to beat the
Yankees, glaring at his old friends from behind the full goatee
that he had to shave when he pitched for George Steinbrenner, the
Yankees' principal owner, tugging on all corners of his uniform,
the top two buttons of his jersey undone. Maybe Wells had plans to
party after the game, straight through Friday night and into
tomorrow morning, but he took this very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, the player who caught the final out of Wells' perfect
game, would get lots of curveballs. Derek Jeter, who anchored the
infield behind Wells, would be jammed with fastballs on the hands.
Wells changed speeds on Davis, throwing curveballs when Davis
expected fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were all business as well, plotting methods of
beating the Boomer. Having watched Wells toil for the last two
years, his former teammates know the left-hander is vulnerable in
two ways: he hates bunts and little chopped ground balls, and he
has difficulty holding runners.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents stole eight bases in Wells' first three starts, the
most stolen bases allowed by any American League pitcher. ``If we
can get on base, that's when he's in trouble,'' said Jorge Posada,
the catcher in Wells' perfect game last May. ``You've just got to
be aggressive with him.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it came to pass that Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees'
lead-off batter, lined Wells' third pitch of the game into left
field, a ringing single. Knoblauch edged off first base, measured
Wells' delivery on the left-hander's first two pitches to Jeter,
then swiped second base. Knoblauch brushed off the dirt, took a
lead off second _ and broke for third. Darrin Fletcher, the Toronto
catcher, was ready, snatching a fastball and then whipping his
throw to third, where Knoblauch was tagged out easily.
</P>
<P>
   Wells had a prolonged fight with Martinez in the second inning.
Martinez fouled off eight two-strike pitches, but Wells cruised
into the middle innings, for the most part, allowing just two hits
through four innings. Hernandez, meanwhile, allowed no hits in the
first four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto broke through with a single run in the fifth, and in the
bottom of the inning, Davis led off with a single before breaking
from second base with Martinez batting. Shortstop Alex Gonzalez
moved to cover second, Martinez lined a single through the hole
Gonzalez had vacated, and Davis took third and eventually came home
with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez pitched out of a two-out, two-on jam in the seventh,
striking out Green, and the fans who cheered for Wells now yelled
for Hernandez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
