<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRUS-COMPUTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WARNING TO BOOT NEWEST VIRUS BEFORE IT BITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Wait! Have you scanned your computer for viruses
lately?
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't, computer experts say, don't even turn on your
computer Monday morning until you take steps to kill a virus that
may be lurking within and set to activate Monday. To do so will
risk losing all your computer's contents and worse, a security
organization warned.
</P>
<P>
   A computer virus called CIH that destroys the contents of hard
disks and then prevents restarting the computer is set to attack at
midnight Sunday, according to the Computer Emergency Response Team
at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The virus attacks stand-alone computers only if they're running
Windows 95 and Windows 98 operating systems, though networked
machines running any operating system can be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Though CIH is more dangerous than the recent Melissa virus, it
can be thwarted by killing it before Sunday at midnight, or by more
labor-intensive methods on Monday morning. Melissa, which last
month brought only a few corporate e-mail servers down, mostly
caused embarrassment by publishing documents without the writers'
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Strain 1.2 of CIH, also known as the Chernobyl virus, is
triggered on April 26, said an emergency response team spokesman.
April 26 is the anniversary of the catastrophic Chernobyl 1986
nuclear accident in Russia. Other strains, identical in effect,
trigger on June 26 and on the 26th of each month.
</P>
<P>
   Your computer is susceptible only if you've done something to
bring the virus into your machine.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is brought into a computer _ through an Internet
download or a network or floppy-disk file transfer _ on an
executable file that has been infected. Executable files, whose
names always end in ``.exe'', do the actual work within a computer.
Every application, such as Microsoft Word or Excel, has at least
one executable file.
</P>
<P>
   Once it's in a computer, CIH lurks until the first time any
executable file is launched after the virus' activation date. It
then overwrites a key portion of the hard disk with random data,
making it unusable. Before doing so, though, it overwrites part of
the computer's BIOS (basic input/output system), making it
impossible to restart the computer once it's turned off.
</P>
<P>
   The virus also infects every executable file that is launched.
Then, when an infected executable file is loaded onto another
machine's hard disk, it infects that machine.
</P>
<P>
   In networks, remote drives can be infected regardless of
operating system if a file on those drives is executed from an
infected Windows 95 or Windows 98 machine.
</P>
<P>
   The best course of action is to kill the virus before it's
activated at midnight Sunday, virus experts say. Computer users
with anti-virus software already installed should make sure they
have the latest anti-virus files downloaded. Those without such
software can download it from a number of Web sites (see list).
</P>
<P>
   If Monday morning arrives and you haven't killed the virus,
don't turn on your computer, experts advise. Instead, boot up from
the write-protected start-up disk you made when you first bought
your machine. Then immediately run updated anti-virus software that
you're sure hasn't been infected.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, some software companies, such as Symantec,
offer software that kills CIH without the need for floppy boot-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Once this crisis has passed, antivirus software should be set to
scan every file brought into a computer. Every file on the machine
should be scanned regularly, and the latest virus profiles should
be downloaded and installed once a week without fail, experts
advise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
