<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-OILERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS GRAB 2-0 SERIES LEAD WITH ANOTHER BIG FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The third period has been the Stars' downfall this
season _ a 20-minute span in which they've been outscored, bumbled
away leads and had almost no success coming back from deficits.
</P>
<P>
   But leave it to the Stars to pick the right time to change their
fortunes. For the second consecutive game, the Stars scored two
third-period goals to bat away the best efforts of the Edmonton
Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Last night before a sellout crowd of 17,001 _ the 39th
consecutive home sellout for the Stars _ the Stars picked up goals
from Jere Lehtinen and Jamie Langenbrunner to take a 3-2 victory
and a 2-0 edge in their best-of-seven Western Conference
quarterfinals series with the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest sign of intelligence is learning from your
mistakes,'' Stars winger Brett Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have done just that. Now, after two home games in
which the Stars controlled the third period, they head to Edmonton
for Game 3 tomorrow with a chance to seize complete control of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was really big. We needed to protect home ice, and that's
what we accomplished,'' center Mike Modano said. ``Now, the ball's
back in their court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' regular-season statistics in the third period are
downright frightening for a team that went 51-19-12. They were
outscored 63-58, they five times lost leads to allow ties and they
were 1-14-2 when trailing after two periods.
</P>
<P>
   But in two playoff games, the Stars have outscored the Oilers,
4-2, and never let them get an inkling that victory was close at
hand. In Game 1, the Stars scored 13 seconds into the third period
to tie the game and make a definitive statement. Last night, the
Stars drove a similar goal through the Oilers' net at just the
right time of the game.
</P>
<P>
   After the Oilers had tied the game at 1-1 at the 8:32 mark of
the third period on a Mike Grier wraparound goal, the Stars bounced
back 1:48 later on a hustling shift by Hull, Lehtinen and Modano.
</P>
<P>
   Modano and Hull flew into the boards to keep a puck in the
offensive zone and pushed the puck down into a scrum of bodies in
front of Oilers goaltender Tommy Salo. Lehtinen picked up the loose
puck and then wristed it through a crowd for the 2-1 lead at the
10:20 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Langenbrunner picked up the game-winner, however, four
minutes later when he took an errant Oilers pass and turned it into
an unassisted goal and a 3-1 Stars lead.
</P>
<P>
   That would prove crucial when Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk
deflected a Doug Weight pass into the Stars goal with 3:11
remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were able to fend off a frantic Oilers attack as Stars
goalie Ed Belfour put in a solid night's work with 17 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling to get the first two, to play well and
hard at home,'' Belfour said. ``But we have to take the same
attitude to Edmonton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will also have to take an improved power play. They
went 0-for-6 with the man advantage last night, including messing
up a 5-on-3 in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   That went right along with the Oilers' Game 1 plan. The Oilers
had a 65-34 edge in hits and put pressure on the Stars all night.
The Stars responded by spending most of the night in the Oilers'
end of the ice, firing 34 shots and adding 21 that missed the net.
</P>
<P>
   Salo was again solid and the Oilers' defense did a great job of
preventing second shots by the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   And all that, of course, made the third period heroics necessary
_ just like in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made the mistakes in third period and it's ended up
costing us the games,'' Oilers defenseman Janne Niinimaa said. ``It
was a little difference, but it was the difference in the game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
