r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-OILERS-SIDEBAR-TE     04-24 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-OILERS-SIDEBAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OILERS FOLLOW GAME PLAN, BUT STILL LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The play was physical. The goaltending was good. The
shots were plentiful. The score was low.
</P>
<P>
   The Edmonton Oilers did everything they said they needed to do
to win Game 2 against the Stars, yet they trail the best-of-seven
series 2-0 after last night's 3-2 loss at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said the first day, we could lose,'' Oilers center Doug
Weight said. ``We could lose playing great hockey and playing our
game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   So the question is: What do they do now?
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers can't play any more physical. They were dangerously
close to playing too physical last night _ six power-play chances
were too many for a talented Stars bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Only an inept Stars power play saved the Oilers from regretting
their plan to play with muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't going to beat them without being physical, and we
hope the series goes longer than four,'' Edmonton coach Ron Low
said. ``That's what we're trying to do, just trying to extend it,
and if you can you keep hitting, maybe you wear them down. That's
our one chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers can't get much better goaltending. If goalie Tommy
Salo was a question mark coming in, he certainly isn't anymore.
</P>
<P>
   He missed Stars' shots No. 1 and No. 29 last night.
</P>
<P>
   He had 27 saves in between, including several late in Game 2 on
players like Joe Nieuwendyk and Mike Modano that kept Dallas' lead
at a single goal for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Salo allowed goal No. 3 with less than four minutes
remaining, a chip shot by Jamie Langenbrunner to seal Edmonton's
loss. Salo had been under heavy fire all game, though, and only his
play had kept the score that close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, he gave us a chance to win,'' Low said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Salo: ``I think we played a great game, and we just ended
up losing. The breaks, we just have to start getting the breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers aren't likely to get many more shots. They had 19 in
Game 2. The Stars only allowed 24 shots per game this season.
</P>
<P>
   If the Oilers are going to win, they have to make better use of
their shots than they did last night.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't like they didn't have chances. On his first day back
from injury, Edmonton winger Bill Guerin twice found himself
standing in front of Stars goalie Ed Belfour. Guerin didn't score
either time.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers had two goals. Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk
scored one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to be changing our game plan,'' Low
said. ``Two one-goal games are pretty indicative of how these games
have gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The score isn't likely to get much lower either. The Stars had
plenty of good scoring chances in Games 1 and 2. Nieuwendyk alone
had a number that were just wide.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do now, Mr. Weight?
</P>
<P>
   ``We can stay out of the box. We can score a little bit on our
chances,'' Weight said. ``We've been in this position before, and
it really doesn't scare us.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there won't be anything changing. It will be our glass
moving instead of theirs. ... We're going to play more of the same
hockey.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
