<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS NOT EXACTLY SHINING, BUT STILL HAVE 2-0 LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Twinkle, twinkle, superStars, how we wonder, where you
are.
</P>
<P>
   Down there on the ice so clear, how is it you've managed to
disappear?
</P>
<P>
   A more pertinent question today: Does it really matter?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: In the end, it probably will.
</P>
<P>
   We came expecting a series of exploding Stars, of Modano, and
Hull, and Nieuwendyk. They would be the difference, we were sure.
</P>
<P>
   Or not.
</P>
<P>
   What we have on our hands, instead, is plain old Stars grit and
resilience, Ken Hitchcock style.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' 3-2 victory over Edmonton last night at Reunion Arena
was yet another testament to the team's famous work ethic and
depth. It gives Dallas a commanding 2-0 lead in this best-of-seven
set with the Oilers, a team that had found itself down 0-2 only
five times in 43 previous playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' message has been sent loud and clear in the Queen's
English, simple enough for even the oafish Oilers to understand: Go
ahead and yuck it up while you tally your meaningless hits; we'll
count the goals and send you a postcard from St. Louis or Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   A word of caution, however. Now that the Oilers have learned
that they're not going to be able to intimidate the Stars, they may
settle down and start playing hockey. They certainly haven't gone
away.
</P>
<P>
   As the Stars were clinging precariously to a 1-0 lead into the
third period, the question that hung over the ice like a cloud of
fog was just how long the team's offensive stars would let young
Oilers goalie Tommy Salo, playing in the first playoff series of
his career, shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   Salo's superb play was the slender thread keeping the Oilers
alive against a far more talented team.
</P>
<P>
   He stonewalled them on half a dozen power-play opportunities,
including a 5-on-3 advantage for 92 seconds in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to finish our chances,'' said Hitchcock, who
didn't bother to conceal at least mild concern as the series shifts
to Edmonton for the next two games. ``We had some great
opportunities, and we just didn't finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're playing all right, but we're going to have to
take it to another level if we expect to win a game in Edmonton.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Carbonneau, the 39-year-old journeyman center who scored the
game winner in the opening game Wednesday, had given the Stars a
quick 1-0 lead only 2:34 into the game just after the Oilers had
killed off a Dallas power play.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau spun around from 15 feet out and flicked a shot past
Salo, who was screened by teammate Rem Murray and Stars winger
Blake Sloan as they danced in front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   But the scouting reports on Salo are proving very accurate: What
he sees, he stops.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Stars, the same can be said of Eddie
Belfour, who was on his way to a 1-0 victory until the game got a
little weird in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars sent a flurry of shots at Salo just over six minutes
into the period, trying to put the Oilers away. Instead, they got a
little cavalier with the puck and Belfour, wandering out of the
goal as he often does, was forced to scoot back quickly and lost
track of Oilers wing Mike Grier, alone with the puck, behind the
net.
</P>
<P>
   When Belfour looked over his left shoulder, Grier came to the
right and knocked in the wraparound to the tie the score at 1.
</P>
<P>
   Riiiinn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
