<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' GONZALEZ FINALLY ENDS HR DROUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Right fielder Juan Gonzalez issued a warning to
the Rangers' American League opponents.
</P>
<P>
   He's back.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, the league's reigning most valuable player, kept the
Rangers atop the AL West with his belated first home run of the
season, a three-run shot that gave the Rangers a 4-2 victory over
the Minnesota Twins last night.
</P>
<P>
   The three-run home run off Mike Lincoln _ on a 1-1, sixth-inning
fastball _ traveled 397 feet and put a smile nearly that length on
Gonzalez's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been trying too hard because I want to help this
team win,'' Gonzalez said, after his first home run since Sept. 22,
1998. ``It's my job to hit home runs and drive runs in. I've been
working hard, but you need to see rewards.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez entered the game hitting .200 (9-for-45) with no
extra-base hits during the previous 12 games and found himself
mired in a season-high, seven-game drought without a run batted in.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Gonzalez to report to the ballpark for early
batting practice for the first time this season. Nevertheless, he
was in good spirits despite his recent struggles, and handled the
slump ``better than I would have expected,'' manager Johnny Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan is a very emotional, up-and-down guy,'' Oates said. ``I'm
not sure how much longer he could have gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez almost put the matter to rest during his previous
at-bat with a deep fly ball that center fielder Torii Hunter chased
down on the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just missed hitting three homers tonight,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, though, knew his homerless drought _ which ended with
his 65th at-bat _ would come to a swift conclusion after his
afternoon batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My time is coming, and it'll be soon,'' Gonzalez said before
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's power _ and 2 1/3 scoreless innings from the bullpen
_ gave right-hander Mark Clark his first victory with the Rangers.
Clark (1-2) pitched a season-high 6 2/3 innings, allowing two runs.
It was only the fifth start of six or more innings by a member of
the Rangers' rotation this season.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, whose sinking, two-seam fastball sets up the rest of his
pitches, induced eight ground-ball outs. He also had a season-high
six strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means I'm where I need to be,'' Clark said. ``My sinker
was down, and all of my pitches feed off that pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark surrendered three doubles in the first five innings, but
he stranded the runners on each occasion. ``I'm going to give up
hits,'' Clark said. ``But I've always been able to make good
pitches when I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins rallied with seventh-inning, run-scoring singles by
Hunter and Ron Coomer, but right-hander Tim Crabtree induced an
inning-ending ground ball to strand the tying run at second base.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Mike Munoz also produced a significant,
eighth-inning strikeout of Twins first baseman Doug Mientkiewicz.
That meant closer John Wetteland needed to record only four outs
instead of five for his sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big strikeout Munoz got on `Alphabet,' '' Oates
said, referring to Mientkiewicz.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who returned to the lineup after
suffering a slight concussion and bruise to his left cheekbone
Thursday, gave the Rangers an insurance run with his ninth-inning,
bases-empty homer off Mike Trombley.
</P>
<P>
   That kept the Twins from playing for one run in the bottom of
the ninth inning after third baseman Corey Koskie's leadoff single.
But the evening's most significant at-bat belonged to Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he took a deep breath when he touched the plate,''
Oates said, ``and so did the manager.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
