<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE CONTINUES TO GIVE STARS' BELFOUR PLENTY OF REST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Star-Telegram staff 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ed Belfour wasn't quite as lonely in last night's Game
2 of the opening-round series with Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, he faced 19 shots and made 17 saves. On Wednesday,
Belfour stopped 12 of 13 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like we worked hard,'' Belfour said. ``They put more
pressure on, they were a little more determined.''
</P>
<P>
   Added coach Ken Hitchcock, ``Anytime can into your own building
and in both meetings they don't get 20 shots on goal, you've got to
be pretty happy with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour stopped the first 12 shots he faced last night. When he
makes several stops in a short span of time. the fans begin to
chant ``Ed-eee! Ed-eee!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought in the first game we didn't generate anything at
all,'' Edmonton coach Ron Low said. ``Tonight, he made a couple of
really good saves.
</P>
<P>
   After the Oilers tied the game in the second period, the Stars
regrouped to build a 3-1 cushion in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely a confidence-builder for us,'' Belfour said.
``We continued to forecheck hard and scored some goals.''  &LR; name:_
Eric Zarate Laughing it off Stars coach Ken Hitchcock yesterday
laughed off comments from Oilers general manager Glen Sather that
Hitchcock was a ``goon coach'' for sending out Grant Marshall to
take a faceoff in the waning seconds of Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall cross-checked Oilers center Todd Marchant on the play
as retaliation for a high stick that had cut the eye of Guy
Carbonneau seconds earlier. Carbonneau also was cross-checked by
Oilers center Doug Weight, who received a five-minute major for
boarding on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock admitted the Stars were upset. ``Guy Carbonneau got
cross-checked from behind and stuck below the eye. And we knew who
cross-checked him from behind and we knew who stuck him,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Sather said he contacted the league to make them aware of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Stars general manager Bob Gainey said he hadn't heard from the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, I hadn't heard from them about the boarding call,
either, so maybe they're not considering every item that goes on in
every game.''  &LR; name:_ Mike Heika Move! Hitchcock said Stars players
not only have to be able to handle the hits of the Edmonton Oilers,
they also have to be able to get out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a player playing against that, your first obligation
is to get out of the way,'' Hitchcock said. ``If you have to stay
with the play to make the right pass, fine. But don't take a hit if
you don't have to.''  &LR; name:_ Mike Heika Facing off Since joining
