<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-DEPUTIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERIFF DEPUTIES DEFEND ACTIONS AT SCHOOL SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Sheriff's deputies have a simple answer for
those who said they moved too slowly in trying to stop the
Columbine High School massacre.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like a Bruce Willis movie,'' said Sgt. Jim Parr,
``where one guy takes on a building of terrorists and in the end
he's coming out smoking cigarettes, cracking jokes and all the bad
guys are dead and all the good guys are alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real life just doesn't work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Many questioned why it took a police SWAT team more than 20
minutes to enter the building when they knew shots were being fired
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have been inside the school instead of outside the
school,'' said Marlene Moore, 23, who visited the shooting scene
Friday. ``They might have been able to save more lives, though it's
hard to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The carnage at Columbine _ which left 15 dead and 23 wounded in
the worst school shooting in U.S. history _ was every police
officer's worst nightmare: armed suspects who could easily blend in
with students, a massive rescue and evacuation operation and a
school wired with dozens of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had approximately 2,000 kids streaming out the doors, and
the gunmen were kids, so it's not like . . . it was really easy to
separate (them),'' Parr said. ``Supposedly one of them had on a
black trench coat. How long does it take to drop a black trench
coat?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many criticized the police response, including a local
radio host who asked what would have happened if the building had
been filled with unarmed cops.
</P>
<P>
   Others like Montay Singleton, 25, were more direct: ``They
should not have waited. They should have just went straight in.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jefferson County deputies said they did.
</P>
<P>
   They said that people watching the tragedy unfold on television
were misled by scenes of the SWAT teams milling around the school.
What the TV cameras didn't show were the officers who were already
in the school while others waited outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have said, `Well, we saw pictures of SWAT teams just
standing out here,'' said sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis. ``Well,
that's very true. There may have been other SWAT teams on the back
side, the front side and SWAT teams waiting for an assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were officers in that school from the minute it went
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The first deputy to respond, Neil Gardner, was actually
stationed at the school. Before he knew it, one of the suspects was
firing at him. On a 911 tape released Friday a dispatcher can
clearly be heard saying ``Seventy-one is under fire.'' Gardner's
call number was 71.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came under fire and exchanged shots with one of the
suspects,'' Parr said. ``The second officer literally arrived two
minutes later. . . . You can't get any faster than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other officers arrived and fired back at the suspects, freeing
Gardner to help more students escape.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, officers arrived from three different jurisdictions _
Jefferson County, Denver and Littleton _ and quickly put together a
makeshift SWAT team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within 20 minutes of the first phone call, the first SWAT team
went through the door,'' Parr said. ``I don't care what city you
live in in this country, if you have a SWAT team at your door
within 20 minutes of the first phone call, you can't beat that.''
</P>
<P>
   Parr said officers had a daunting task: evacuate the building
and rescue the students, while all the while climbing over
explosive devices. Though the first SWAT team entered after 20
minutes, it took heavily armed teams hours of searching to clear
out the sprawling school.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't run willy-nilly into the building and shoot the
place up,'' Parr said. ``We're trying to rescue people at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Parr said the officers had no way to tell victims from
assailants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we found the suspects deceased, we didn't know where
they were in the building,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Al Preciado, an instructor in SWAT tactics for the International
Association of Chiefs of Police, said the officers were right not
to rush to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can only react to the information they have and
information comes slowly in that situation,'' said Preciado,
formally second in command of the Los Angeles Police Department
SWAT team. ``It's very easy to Monday-morning quarterback a
scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``They're damned if they do and damned if they
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Preciado said officers use different tactics in different
situations, and using the wrong methods can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a hostage situation. It wasn't a barricade
situation. It seemed like a suicide mission. There's no prevention
for that.'' &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at (602) 444-8178 or at
bill.muller(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Republic writer Richard Ruelas contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
