<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-DEVILRAYS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINER RELIEF FALLS SHORT AGAIN AS RAYS WIN SIXTH STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Ken Griffey Jr. threw three baseballs
over the center-field wall in the eighth inning Friday night at
Tropicana Field. The first two were directed at Raymond, the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays mascot, who was cavorting on the roof of an outfield
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing funny about the last ball Griffey tossed over.
It was Randy Winn's second major league home run, which crashed off
the platform for the center-field TV camera, 425 feet away, and
landed on the field. It sent the Mariners to a 5-4 defeat against
the surging Devil Rays before 20,322.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay is on a six-game winning streak for the first time
ever. The M's have lost three straight and seven of nine. For the
second game in a row, they lost after leading going into the bottom
of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   This time, a pair of former starters faltered in relief. After
working out of a jam in the sixth to preserve a 4-2 lead, Ken
Cloude walked the leadoff man in the seventh, then surrendered two
hits and a sacrifice fly to tie the game. John Halama got out of
the seventh, then fell behind Winn and gave up the decisive home
run.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Paniagua came on for the fifth straight game to finish up,
and Mark Leiter remains on the disabled list with shoulder
tendinitis. Those two are the lone experienced relievers the M's
have before closer Jose Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way: what we have is not the most conducive
formula for winning,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``Outside of
that, sure I expect everyone here to pitch well. It's not going to
happen all the time, but certainly you've got to have pretty
rounded contribution. If you don't, invariably you're going to
(have to use) the same people every day. It doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloude, whose prior relief appearance earned him a win Sunday,
relieved Freddy Garcia, who allowed just two runs but was not
sharp, giving up eight hits and two walks in five innings. Cloude's
walk to Dave Martinez leading off the seventh preceded a double by
Jose Canseco, and soon the lead was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not good,'' Cloude said of the walk. ``You don't want
to walk the leadoff hitter in a close ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama, a control pitcher without a dominant fastball, was
disappointed with his command in Winn's at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm jumping ahead (in the count) and we lose, it's easier
to swallow,'' Halama said. ``But when I fall behind, that makes it
tougher because that's not the type of pitcher I am.''
</P>
<P>
   This also is not the type of hitting team the Mariners need to
be. Friday's lineup featured David Segui leading off for the first
time in his career and Edgar Martinez hitting second for the first
time since the '95 playoffs. Griffey hit next, but all of the six
players who followed in the order are hitting below .250, and four
are below .200.
</P>
<P>
   John Mabry had an especially frustrating night. He struck out in
the second, grounded into a double play in the third, lined out
with a man on in the sixth and popped up with two on in the eighth.
The left fielder is in a 1-for-12 slump and batting .186.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said he plans to use Butch Huskey more often in left.
</P>
<P>
   Mabry said he's been trying to do too much, which is causing him
to swing at bad pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pressing,'' hitting coach Jesse Barfield said. ``I went 0
for my first 27 the first time I changed teams, with the Yankees
(in 1989). One thing about pressing is you're trying to prove to
your new team that it was worth it to take a chance on you. I can
see the same thing happening with him. He's a totally different
hitter in practice drills than in games. It'll come, because John
is a much better hitter than he's shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got to get him on track. There are too many
right-handed pitchers in this league to have a left-hander not
hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Mabry had company in his struggles. After Segui's three-run
homer in the second, the Mariners managed just four singles and had
only one runner past first base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
