<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS PRODUCE FAN-TASTIC RALLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ One out away from their sixth consecutive
loss, the Angels got a little help from the Kansas City Royals
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels rallied for three runs with two out in the ninth
inning to beat the Royals 4-2 Friday night in front of 13,209 at
Kauffman Stadium, that total including two apparently inebriated
fans who might have inadvertently helped the Angels pull out the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had runners on first and third in the ninth inning
against Royals closer Jeff Montgomery, but trailed 2-1 and were
down to their final out when two fans _ shirtless in the 50-degree
weather _ ran onto in the outfield grass.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fans struggled with five security officers, causing a
delay that lasted nearly five minutes. When play resumed,
Montgomery's second pitch to Orlando Palmeiro fell in the dirt and
skipped past catcher Chad Kreuter. Tim Salmon scored from third to
tie the game and Garret Anderson took second.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro followed with a soft liner to left field, and Anderson
slid around Kreuter's tag in a close play at the plate to give the
Angels a 3-2 lead. Randy Velarde added an RBI single to make it
4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival pitched a 1-2-3 ninth for his second save.
Shigetoshi Hasegawa (1-0) pitched two-thirds of an inning to get
the win in relief of starter Ken Hill, who had his best outing of
the season _ 71/3 innings, two runs, four hits, seven strikeouts
and four walks.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's performance almost went for naught _ until things turned
around in the ninth. But the Angels, who scored their first run of
the night on a passed ball, weren't about to give it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take it, no matter what the circumstances,'' Angels
manager Terry Collins said. ``We needed it. Hopefully it's
something that kick-starts us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter, one win like that can get you on a roll,''
Mo Vaughn said. ``When you're on a four- or five-game losing
streak, the first win is always a climb. A win like that can really
fuel you.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery wouldn't use the delay as an excuse _ ``I don't know
if it affected me or not. I refuse to believe it. I'm not making
any excuses,'' he said _ but Percival felt for his fellow closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had it happen to me a couple times with fans on the
field,'' Percival said. ``Nothing good can come out of it. The fans
look like idiots and it slows down the game. Jeff might've been on
a nice roll, then he's got to stand there for five minutes with no
warmups. It throws you off your game.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the five losses during the Angels' losing streak came
by one run. ``We've been getting some bad breaks but people keep
coming out and playing,'' Anderson said. ``That impresses me.
People still run hard to first, are still backing up throws,
they're still coming out to play and not giving up. Because things
can get sloppy when things aren't going well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill gave the Angels a shot in the arm early, retiring the first
eight batters he faced before walking No.9 hitter Rey Sanchez with
two out in the third. Through five innings he allowed just one hit.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sweeney had a two-run single in the sixth off Hill, but
that was the last hit he allowed before being removed with one out
in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting better, man. Shoot, I feel good,'' he said. ``I
told (catcher Matt) Walbeck we'll just keep slotting that fastball
down and away. We don't have to throw anything else until they make
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling with his mechanics in his first two starts,
Hill has found himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That mechanics thing ... I was thinking about it too much,''
he said. ``Now I've found where I need to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
