<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS DAZED BY DETROIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The 1998-99 season has been a series of lessons and
tests for the Mighty Ducks. After Friday's 5-1 drubbing in Game 2
of their opening-round playoff series with the Detroit Red Wings,
it appears Anaheim is in the middle of its final exam.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks insisted they had learned some valuable lessons from
their Game 1 loss, especially when it came to coping with Detroit's
relentless first-period pressure. Instead, Anaheim simply rolled
over and played dead _ at least for 46 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at how hard they played ... they played with pride
and we didn't ... We were awful,'' said Teemu Selanne, who scored
Anaheim's lone goal in the third period after Detroit had raced out
to a 5-0 lead less than 30 minutes into the game. ``If you lose and
play a good game, you have to accept it, but we didn't have a
chance tonight. They played harder and smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The purple octopus had barely been lifted back to the Joe Louis
Arena rafters when Brendan Shanahan knocked home a rebound exactly
one minute after the opening faceoff and the rout was on. Shanahan
made it 2-0 at 10:14 and Tomas Holmstrom scored at 13:43 to give
the Red Wings a three-goal advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised at our slow start,'' said Anaheim coach Craig
Hartsburg. ``But I was even more surprised by Detroit's start. It
was even better tonight and I didn't think that was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings, who led 2-1 after 20 minutes on Wednesday, took a
4-0 advantage into the first intermission Friday when Doug Brown
ripped a shot off Guy Hebert's shoulder with 42.3 seconds left in
the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Yzerman completed Detroit's onslaught at 9:42 of the
second when he scored the Red Wings' third power-play goal of the
game. It was Yzerman's fourth goal in two games.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks appeared dazed, confused and totally outclassed by the
two-time defending Stanley Cup champions. Detroit outscored,
outskated and outhit Anaheim. Not until 6:13 of the third period,
when Stu Grimson picked up six minutes in roughing penalties for
jousting with Chris Chelios and Darren McCarty, was Anaheim able to
give out some blows rather than absorb them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were one step behind all night,'' said Selanne. ``It's hard
to hit anybody when you're a step late.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's nondescript defensive corps had a night to forget,
especially Ruslan Salei, who was on the ice for all five Detroit
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The second-year defenseman will likely being having nightmares
about Shanahan, as the veteran Detroit winger burned him three
times in the first period alone. Salei was late getting to the net
to prevent Shanahan's first goal, turned the puck over in the
neutral zone on his second goal and was left in Shanahan's wake on
a play that resulted in Holmstrom's goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were outshot 17-8 in the first period, 36-31 in the
game and didn't generate a decent scoring chance until Fredrik
Olausson's backdoor attempt on a power play was smothered by
Detroit goalie Chris Osgood midway through the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are stuck in your zone all game it's tough to play
offense,'' said Anaheim's Paul Kariya, who managed just one shot in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   But as well as the Red Wings played in taking a 2-0 series lead,
Kariya said the Ducks simply didn't rise to the challenge in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the playoffs you've got to raise your game to another
level,'' he said. ``If they are working 110 percent you've got to
raise your level past that and we're not even close.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks they don't have much time to take their game to new
heights, or learn from their latest lesson. Game 3 is set for the
Pond on Sunday at noon and elimination could come as quickly as
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got about 36 hours to fix things,'' said Selanne. ``It's
our turn to show character and come out hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
