<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the top stories from The New York Times News Service
report for PMs of Saturday, April 24.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, (212) 556-1927, will open on Saturday at 9
a.m. ET. To get story repeats before this hour, call (212) 621-1595
for reruns on AP DataFeatures or (214) 980-8305 or 8306 for repeats
on UPI DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   ART ADV: Graphics and photos have been sent, as indicated below,
to NYT graphic and photo subscribers. Clients needing
retransmissions or information, or non-subscribers seeking to
arrange individual purchases, should call (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SENIORS (Littleton) _ The Columbine High School
class of '99 had waited a long time for this year, when finally
they would be on top at their school, when after all the hard work,
they could finally kick back and cruise toward graduation. But now,
the rituals of the waning senior year have given way to services
and funerals. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-WEB (Littleton) _ A look at the world wide web as a
home for lonely outcasts and talking to kids who find solace there.
By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-RELIGION (Undated) _ Pastors in Jonesboro, Ark.,
scene of an earlier school shooting, reach out to those in
Littleton, Colo. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGES-DNA-CLASSES (Boston) _ In what is believed to be a unique
program, Superior Court judges here go to biology classes at MIT to
learn how to understand DNA evidence, which is determining more and
more cases in their courts. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-KOSOVO (Washington) _ A news analysis: Now that the bills
for the Balkan battles are mounting, the real domino effect will be
what happens to the overall budget, the surplus and the plan for
walling off Social Security. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Lipkovo, Macedonia) _ Thousands of refugees are
straggling over the ice-packed mountains, carrying mud-caked
clothes on their backs, whimpering children in their arms, horror
in their heads. U.N. aid workers say that extraordinary numbers of
Albanians seem to be trekking their way through the rugged peaks
that span the border between Kosovo and Macedonia. There are at
least 10,000 on the move, and possibly 10 times that. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-OIL (Buenos Aires) _ YPF was once the butt of one of
Argentina's most enduring jokes as ``the only oil company in the
world that knew how to lose money.'' After an early 1990s overhaul,
however, YPF has since catapulted itself into the second tier of
world energy companies by acquiring exploration fields, gas
stations and pipelines in the most unlikely places, from Peru to
Indonesia to the Texas panhandle. The company is now poised to take
advantage of the expected privatization and selloff of the
Brazilian government's energy holdings and the continuing opening
of Venezuela's huge oil patch in the next few years. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   G7-DEBT (Washington) _ Debt forgiveness is expected to be
discussed at Monday's meeting in Washington of finance ministers
from the Group of Seven nations. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC (Undated) _ The status of efforts in the
recording and electronics industry to hammer out a universal,
pirate-proof technology for distributing commercial music on the
Internet. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's main financial
stories.
