<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSUNA FACES ANOTHER TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers need a right-handed set-up man in the
bullpen. Antonio Osuna could be that man, except for one thing:
he's on the disabled list with a bone spur in his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   But he feels fine; in fact, he threw nearly 15 pain-free minutes
in the bullpen Friday to test the elbow the Dodgers said needed
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooomph,'' Osuna said when asked if the Dodgers acted too
quickly in putting him on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna's bullpen session was witnessed by pitching coach Charlie
Hough, manager Davey Johnson and physical therapist Pat Screnar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw the heck out of the ball,'' Johnson said. ``(Today)
is the critical day. If he's not sore (today), he's not going to
have the surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers struggle to find a capable arm in the bullpen,
Osuna must sit back and watch. If he's pain free today, he'll begin
a rehab stint with Single-A San Bernardino on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who complained of elbow soreness Tuesday, had an MRI on
Wednesday which revealed a bone spur in the same location as the
one surgically removed in September. Osuna is eligible to come off
the disabled list May 3.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said there was no
second-guessing in placing Osuna on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got healthy on the drive back. There's a miraculous road
from Dr. (Frank) Jobe's office,'' Malone said. ``An important
element is dependability, and my concern is maybe he goes out and
pitches well but then he can't pitch (later).
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's something he can pitch with, but my concern is will
it flare up again. I have to listen to what my doctors tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth activated: The Dodgers activated outfielder Todd
Hollandsworth and sent pitcher Robinson Checo to Triple-A
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth, who pulled his hamstring, batted .364 with a
double and three RBI in a rehab stint with San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely had a good test in San Bernardino,''
Hollandsworth said. ``I had to beat the pitcher to the bag (on one
play) and I stretched it out. Then I went (from) first to third two
pitches later. You can't test it much more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth is the Dodgers' fourth outfielder, bumping Jacob
Brumfield to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The demotion of Checo means all three pitchers the Dodgers
acquired from Detroit in exchange for Dave Mlicki and Mel Rojas are
at the minor league level. Checo will start for Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to get the ball over, get more sink on it and make
better pitches,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux works out: Auditioning for a spot in the Dodgers bullpen
is 37-year-old right-hander Mike Maddux. Maddux, who declined a
minor league assignment from the Montreal Expos on April 14, threw
a bullpen session and Johnson's report was favorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful we'll be able to work something out where we'll
have Maddux available,'' Johnson said. ``We don't have a roster
spot right now, but I don't think he's ready to pitch to major
league batters yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, who had a 9.00 ERA in four relief appearances for the
Expos, is 36-34 in his 14-year career. He pitched for the Dodgers
in 1990, going 0-1 with a 6.53 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: The game was delayed 21 minutes because
of rain. . . . Jose Vizcaino started his third straight game at
shortstop. . . . The lineup shuffle continued as Johnson shifted
slumping catcher Todd Hundley to eighth in the batting order. . . .
Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre extended his hitting streak to
11 games with a second-inning single. . . . Cardinals left fielder
Matt Howard left the game in the third inning with a strained left
hamstring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
