<HEADER>
A1528 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     04-24 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOUT TIME: FENWAY THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Dan Shaughnessy  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, some excitement around Olde Fenway. The Red Sox woke up
Friday night. They hit. They got hit. They tackled and scuffled.
After nine innings of head-hunting, knuckle-wielding, toe-to-toe
action, judge Eugenia Williams had the Sox ahead on points, but the
Indians were up, 7-6, on the left-field scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   So the slump continues, but at least the Sox put on a show.
Boston baseball fans are starved for excitement, and Fenway's
Friday Night Fights povided a rare thrill in what has become a
dismal and dull start to the 1999 baseball summer.
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely that Jaret Wright could have been throwing at
Darren Lewis (Lewis was hit with a curveball) in the fifth inning
of this series opener. Cleveland led, 5-2, the Sox had two on, with
no outs, and Wright needed only three outs to qualify for the win.
He was struggling and couldn't be dumb enough to intentionally load
the bases with a three-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   That said, it was great to see Lewis yell at Wright, then accept
the big righty's challenge to come get him on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said a few words to him,'' said Lewis, who was beaned by
Wright last year in the playoffs. ``You have to make a statement .
. . Obviously, he has a maturity problem.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the scuffle, Wright could be seen pointing to his
own head, as if to remind or threaten Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``For somebody to do that, it shows you where his head is,''
said Lewis. ``. . . Hopefully he doesn't get himself or one of his
teammates hurt in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said, ``I can understand why he'd be sensitive, but I
didn't throw at him last year and this pitch was a curveball. I
never try to throw at guys' heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Both benches emptied after Lewis charged Wright. Both bullpens,
too. And that was only the beginning. There was another melee
moments later when Virtual Rheal Cormier hit Jim Thome to start the
sixth. The highlights of Bout II were Jason Varitek's takedown of
David Justice (somebody please call Bobby Grier) and Pedro
Martinez's bearhug restraint of an unusually animated Jimy
Williams. Joe Kerrigan, Boston's emotional pitching coach, was held
back by Saturday's starter, Bret Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just the heat of the moment,'' said Kerrigan. ``We're
just trying to protect our players. I've told our guys to be
responsible where they throw the ball. We would never tell anybody
to throw at anybody's head.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormier, pleading the typical innocence, said, ``I was just
trying to come inside.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it made for an interesting evening at the Fens. The
Sox have fallen to .500 (8-8), which is unacceptable to a rabid
fandom that pays top prices, but the greatest danger is not the
losing, it's the boredom. Boston baseball fans will forgive losing,
choking, off-field embarrassment, high-ticket prices, and abject
front office buffoonery. Just don't bore them to death.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dan Duquette has carved out a team that plays in
his image. The Sox, like their leader, too often are methodical,
cautious, and thoroughly unexciting.
</P>
<P>
   Not Friday night. In the spirit of Bruins forward Ken Belanger,
the Sox broke out the bats and the (boxing) gloves.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like another listless night when Jimy's Guys fell
behind, 5-0, in the fourth. Boston had scored only five runs in the
previous five games, and it seemed unlikely that they could match
that total in a single night. But the first fight appeared to spark
the Local Nine.
</P>
<P>
   After Lewis charged the mound (he and Wright were ejected), the
Boston bats came alive. Back-to-back doubles by Nomar Garciaparra
and Reggie Jefferson emptied the bases and produced a 6-5 lead _ a
lead that was wiped out when tough guy Wilfredo Cordero hit a
two-run homer after Cormier hit Thome with the first pitch of the
sixth. Cormier and Thome were ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Another loss. But Sox fans were entertained by the two fights,
four ejections, seven hits, and six runs.
</P>
<P>
   Will the brawls ignite this slumbering Sox edition?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if that did happen,'' said Lewis. ``But even
though we have been struggling, we know what we are capable of as a
ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who wouldn't say much about the bench-clearing
incidents, said, ``If in fact this is a spark, you can get
something going. But we're going to hit anyway, I believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
