<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICSBULLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS BEAT BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was the most frightening bit of information to come
out of the United Center Friday night. The Celtics had just
finished dunking on Kornel David's Chicago Bulls, 100-71, when the
truth came out: They were tired.
</P>
<P>
   So tired that they probably would have been better off if they
had taken a nap rather than played basketball. So tired that they
dragged through their morning shootaround, wondering where they
would find the energy to play for 48 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't that scare you? A tired and injured Celtics team _ a
team that went to sleep at 5 a.m. Friday after a hellish night in
the air _ still found a way to sneak out of town with a 29-point
win. Now, this is the section of the story where two avenues will
be provided to you. You can say the Celtics are a resilient bunch
that fights through bruises and lack of rest. Or you can surmise
that the Bulls should actually have ``Rockford'' or ``Yakima'' on
their red-and-black jerseys and embrace the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   As Rick Pitino likes to say, the truth is probably somewhere in
the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a victory and this was one of those nights when
everything goes well for one team and nothing does for the other,''
Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   He was being kind. The truth is that it was never a game. Not
even six minutes into it, the Celtics had a 10-point lead. They led
by 16 after one, 20 by halftime, and 26 after three. The only
mystery was whether rookie David would score 20 points (he did,
which led to tremendous applause from the sellout crowd).
</P>
<P>
   It was a good night for everyone in green, and not just because
it was nearly the five-year anniversary of the Celtics' last win
here (April 22, 1994). It was a self-esteem booster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I saw Damon Jones over there playing some ball,'' Walter
McCarty shouted to the rookie point guard. That's because Jones had
14 points, 5 rebounds, and 4 assists the day before his 10-day
contract expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll see you next year,'' Paul Pierce said to Jones, obviously
teasing him.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, Jones will be with the rest of the Celtics Saturday
in Waltham, Mass., watching game tapes. There will be plenty of
good things to see. There were Pierce's 18 points, Ron Mercer's
return to the lineup for the first time in four games, Vitaly
Potapenko's 12 points and 10 rebounds and the performance of a man
Pitino has nicknamed Theo Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   ``No disrespect to Theo,'' Tony Battie said of the moniker.
``He's a great shot-blocker and has had a great year. But I think I
can be more than that in a couple years.''
</P>
<P>
   He was more than that Friday night. He had 15 points, 12
rebounds, 5 assists, and 4 blocked shots. On one of his blocks, it
looked as if he gulped the ball rather than blocked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just concentrating on rebounding and playing defense,''
he said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the numbers, that's what all the Celtics did. They
outrebounded the Bulls by 10 and held them to 32 percent shooting.
Several of those Bull attempts were hideous airballs. After one of
them, a season ticket-holder sitting in his courtside seat simply
put his hands over his face.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Bulls coach Tim Floyd was asked what his goals
were for the team's upcoming road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to continue to compete,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Continue?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, not only did the Celtics play differently than the
Bulls, they talked a different game when it was over. The Bulls
want to get to Secaucus, N.J., as soon as possible and see where
they will be drafting. Pitino, though, says he wants the season to
be extended. He thinks the Celtics are finally playing good
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing well the past two weeks,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Celtics aren't the first team to feel good after
playing the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's still a mystique here,'' Jones said. ``You look up
and see those six championship banners.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Bulls, the banners couldn't put up any
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
