<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1530 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOXINDIANS-BOS     04-24 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOXINDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS BEAT RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were two WWF-style brawls, a flying karate kick straight
out of a Jackie Chan movie, a pile-driving tackle by a Rambling
Wreck from Georgia Tech, four ejections, and enough f-bombs to earn
this game an NC-17 rating.
</P>
<P>
   But a postfight testosterone rush that may have produced the Red
Sox' biggest inning of the season _ their five-run fifth equaled
the number of runs they'd scored in the previous five games
combined _ wore off too soon to satisfy either the Sox or 29,921
ringside observers in Fenway Park Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians emerged from the mud and the blood and the
beer with a 7-6 win over the Sox on a two-run home run by Wilfredo
Cordero, still accorded Public Enemy No. 1 treatment on Yawkey Way
18 months after being banned from Boston in the wake of a domestic
abuse incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd just come running in from the bullpen for two fights and
I was trying to calm down, but the adrenaline was flying,'' said
reliever Jim Corsi, who gave up Cordero's game-winner to the
deepest reaches of center field, 420 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened to carry over to the game, and I wound up
overthrowing a pitch. I made a bad pitch and he hit it right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox lost for the third straight time and seventh time in
the last nine games. Their last hope expired when a deep drive by
rookie Trot Nixon (0 for 23), who was in the game only because
Brawl One principal Darren Lewis had been ejected, died in the
glove of right fielder Manny Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero's sixth-inning home run off Corsi recaptured the lead
for Cleveland after the Sox had battled back, in every sense of the
phrase, from a 5-0 deficit to seize a 6-5 lead in the fifth. The
home run came two pitches after Sox reliever Rheal Cormier was
ejected for plunking Indians strongman Jim Thome in the ribs with a
pitch in apparent retaliation for Indians starter Jaret Wright
hitting Lewis in the fifth. Two batters before, Wright had buzzed
Damon Buford following Troy O'Leary's home run.
</P>
<P>
   While Cormier said he was merely trying to brush back Thome, Sox
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan acknowledged the pitch was no accident.
``You've got to protect your players,'' Kerrigan said. ``I think
Robbie Alomar (the Indians' second baseman) said it best on the
field when he said it's part of the game. I told Robbie we were
just trying to hit (Thome) in the butt. We're not going for the
face or the elbow or the hands. We were trying to hit him in the
butt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox went from passive to passionate after Lewis, whose quiet
demeanor should never be mistaken for a pacific nature, was hit by
a pitch in the left shoulder by Wright, who already had gone home
run (Troy O'Leary), walk, single to the first three batters in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   There's history here: Lewis was beaned in the left earflap of
his helmet in Game 1 of the playoffs last season by a Wright
fastball that he said caused him hearing problems (``it put an hole
in my eardrum'') more than two weeks after the season ended. When
he was hit again Friday night, Lewis barked at the 23-year-old
pitcher, even though Wright said (and replays confirmed) that the
offending pitch was a breaking ball and came at a most inopportune
time for the Indians, given that it loaded the bases with no one
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was,'' Lewis said, ``but it was too close
to my head. That's all I care about. It was too close to my head. I
was hit in the head last year. There's no room for that. I'm not
going to tolerate it, and I wouldn't expect my teammates to
tolerate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright responded to Lewis's invective by stepping off the mound,
discarding his glove and inviting Lewis for a closer encounter.
Lewis wasted no time accepting the summons, going airborne and
dropping the 6-foot-2-inch, 230-pound pitcher with a two-footed
kick. A general melee ensued, one in which Sox first base coach
Dave Jauss tried to pin Wright while Lewis was restrained from
inflicting further mayhem by the smallest man on the field, third
base coach Wendell Kim.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, meanwhile, was pushed to the other side of the diamond,
from where he yelled at Lewis, pointing at his head, an apparent
promise of future beanballs to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I saw that,'' Lewis said. ``It didn't scare me, if it
was a threat, and second of all, it showed a lack of maturity as a
ballplayer on his part. He has some things to learn as a pitcher.
And maybe one day he'll pitch in the National League (where
pitchers bat) and someone will stick one in his earhole and he'll
find out what it's really all about.''
</P>
<P>
   When order was restored and Wright and Lewis were ejected, Sox
bats went to work against Indians reliever Steve Karsay. Jose
Offerman lined a drive that was caught in center field by Kenny
Lofton but brought home Buford to make it 5-3. John Valentin, who
had doubled and scored the Sox' first run in the fourth, tapped out
to third, but Nomar Garciaparra, who had just one RBI in his first
nine games, drove a double into left-center to tie the score.
Reggie Jefferson followed with another line-drive double to give
the Red Sox a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Thome led off the sixth and didn't seem surprised to find a ball
planted in his ribs by Cormier. He headed for the mound with barely
a look at the little Sox lefty. Thome landed a punch to Cormier's
head, but his momentum carried him past the pitcher and sent him
sprawling in the dirt, where he was jumped on by Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Georgia Tech grad Jason Varitek buried David Justice
with a tackle that would have resulted in a 10-yard loss at Foxboro
Stadium, and something set off both Sox manager Jimy Williams and
Kerrigan. Williams, erupting with a torrent of verbiage, was held
back by the $75 million arm of Pedro Martinez, while Kerrigan was
pulled out of harm's way by Bret Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' Williams said when asked what provoked
his anger. But it appeared clear that his anger was directed at
Indians manager Mike Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   The sides dispersed again, this time absent Thome and Cormier,
who had breezed through the first five batters he faced after
replacing starter Pat Rapp, who had been tattooed for five runs on
seven hits, including home runs by Kenny Lofton (leading off the
game) and Travis Fryman (two-run shot into the Sox bullpen in the
fourth).
</P>
<P>
   But then Corsi threw a ball to Cordero, before the Sox exile put
the Indians back in the lead with his 420-foot home run.
</P>
<P>
   The deflated Sox went down in order the next two innings, before
Jefferson doubled to put the tying run aboard with one out in the
eighth. But reliever Paul Shuey struck out Mike Stanley, now 0 for
22, and lefty Paul Assenmacher induced O'Leary to pop to short.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, did the fight accomplish anything?
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't hurt,'' said Saberhagen, scheduled to pitch
Saturday afternoon. ``It keeps everybody together, fighting for one
thing. If anything, it might have woken us up a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not our solution. Our solution is going out and
playing better baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
