<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS SAVE FACE IN OT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ According to unsubstantiated reports, the Great
Clipper in the Sky looked down at the Sports Arena on Friday, shook
his mighty-worried head and said: ``When are they gonna bulldoze
that place?''
</P>
<P>
   He also mumbled something about how his team's wacky skill
against good teams has put him on the bad side of the Great Bookie
in the Sky.
</P>
<P>
   His predicament was created when the Clippers coughed up a
19-point, fourth-quarter lead against the Hall of Fame-heavy
Houston Rockets, but managed to prevail 106-101 in overtime with
13,855 witnesses at the House of Famine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was beginning to think this was going to be the low point of
our season,'' said Clippers guard Eric Piatkowski, who scored seven
of his 28 points _ his second-highest total for this season _ in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   This momentary brush with gloom was inspired when the 8-35
Clippers folded like lawn chairs in the fourth quarter. With
Scottie Pippen (23 points, 10 rebounds, 10 assists, six steals)
spearheading Houston's press, the Clippers coughed up nine
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My young guys kept coming over and saying they were getting
hit,'' said Clippers coach Chris Ford of the fourth-quarter horror
show.
</P>
<P>
   When Ford was asked if the officiating had changed to
accommodate the Rockets' collection of Springfield-bound
superstars, he said: ``You watched the game? You make the call; you
pay the fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nah, we'll just solicit a response from Maurice Taylor (29
points, seven in OT), who's going to be rollin' in dough someday:
``Down the stretch, we felt they (Rockets) would get all the calls.
But it worked out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked like a charm, thanks to a cold-blooded 3-point jumper
by Troy Hudson that tied the score at 89 with eight seconds left in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy when the shot went in,'' Hudson said, ``but not
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets (27-16) weren't exactly thrilled about the way
things turned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maurice Taylor was kicking my butt all over the place,'' said
Hall-of-Fame trainee Charles Barkley (24 points, 10 rebounds) of
the young Clipper who took him to the woodshed for a dozen
third-quarter points.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's third Hall-of-Fame lock, center Hakeem Olajuwon,
scored 18 points and grabbed 12 rebounds but fouled out with 3:15
left in overtime. Clippers rookie center Michael Olowokandi grabbed
a game-high 14 rebounds and scored eight points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
