<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1537 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-GRIZZLIES-     04-24 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-GRIZZLIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS' PLAYOFF PUSH TRAMPLES GRIZZLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Motivation comes from the schedule when a team
is battling for playoff position this late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   It really should not matter the opponent or arena.
</P>
<P>
   But forgive the Sonics if their intentions were amplified by
their last visit here.
</P>
<P>
   In the grand scheme, the Sonics' 97-84 victory Friday night
against the Vancouver Grizzlies kept them in a tie with the
Sacramento Kings for the eighth and final seed of the Western
Conference playoff picture.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which snapped a two-game road losing streak, was
even sweeter in front of a sellout crowd of 19,193 at General
Motors Place. The Sonics lost five of seven games after losing here
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   They are now hoping the exact opposite happens.
</P>
<P>
   It has, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento beat Minnesota Friday night to remain tied with the
Sonics with seven games to play. The Sonics and Kings are just a
half-game behind the seventh-seeded Timberwolves and a game behind
No. 6 Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (April 9 loss against Vancouver) hurt,'' Sonics coach
Paul Westphal said. ``It makes this playoff race tighter than if we
would have been able to pencil that win in. ... Now we need a push.
I figure we need to win four out of our last seven games.''
</P>
<P>
   The next three are the toughest for the Sonics (21-22).
</P>
<P>
   They take on the Western Conference-leading Utah Jazz at the
Delta Center tomorrow. Both teams complete the home-and-home series
by playing again Tuesday at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Sonics must play at Portland the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't count on Sacramento to lose. We have to win games,''
said Sonics forward Don MacLean, who scored 25 points to match Gary
Payton for game-high scoring honors. ``We're going to have to be
consistent if we're going to get on a roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the Sonics have been taking care of business.
</P>
<P>
   Albeit just two games, their victory Friday night came after
crushing Minnesota on Wednesday. Friday night was the first time
the Sonics won consecutive games since March 16.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game where the Sonics displayed the superiority they
insist is there despite the team's record and the loss of All-Star
power forward Vin Baker. The Sonics kept the Grizzlies pinned under
a double-digit lead most of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Leading 79-62 heading into the fourth quarter, the Sonics
watched the Grizzlies use an 11-4 run to pull within eight points
with 7:54 to play in the game.
</P>
<P>
   That was as close as the Grizzlies would get. Vancouver could
get no closer than 11 points in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing more aggressive and just playing faster,''
Sonics forward Detlef Schrempf said. ``We're moving the ball around
and helping each other out on defense. It's imperative that we keep
playing this way. We've got no low post game so we've got to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics took a 60-43 lead at halftime after a dominating
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 42-39 with 8:42 left in the period, the Sonics took off on
a 13-5 run. Payton finished off the barrage when he whirled around
Terry Dehere on the baseline. With Dehere planted, Payton scored an
uncontested layup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tale of two halves in my mind,'' said Grizzlies coach
Brian Hill. ``The first half we came in with no focus, no defensive
intensity whatsoever. They just ran right by us. In the second half
we really didn't have any answers for Payton or Don MacLean. Both
of them were kind of a thorn in our side all night.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight game, MacLean helped the team get off to
a fast start. He scored 11 points in the first quarter, which the
Sonics dominated with their energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get easy buckets, we're pretty good,'' MacLean said.
``I just come out aggressive and try to set the tone. When I have
power forwards guarding me, I'm open a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have adapted to the different style they prefer to
play without Baker. The team used its run-and-gun approach to run
past the Grizzlies from the start.
</P>
<P>
   MacLean seems to benefit most from the pace. He made six of his
first 10 shots, and grabbed seven rebounds. MacLean's quick drives
off the dribble epitomized how the Sonics want to play the
remainder of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Hersey Hawkins fed a streaking MacLean for an easy layup that
put the Sonics in front 27-14 late in the first. The period ended
with the Sonics in front 33-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really took care of things in the first half,'' Westphal
said. ``In the second half we didn't shoot the ball as well and
they really worked hard. They didn't quit, but our defense did a
good job and held them in check.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 0253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
