<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1539 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF500-LADN     04-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF500-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA SPEEDWAY GEARS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ A plot of 529 acres, once the heart of San Bernardino
County's industrial base, will be transformed into a virtual city
by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   Some call it Penskeville or Speed City. However, all refer to
the grounds as the California Speedway, the benchmark for racing
facilities not only in the United States, but throughout the world.
It's expected that nearly a quarter-million people will spend some
time on the speedway grounds for this week's NASCAR racing
tripleheader.
</P>
<P>
   Activity begins Thursday and culminates next Sunday with the
third annual NAPA California 500, the Winston Cup Series event that
will draw more than 115,000 spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Putting stock cars on the two-mile speedway is just part of the
challenge for the California Speedway management team. In fact, the
races are perhaps less taxing than most responsibilities. As with
any city, temporary or not, there are issues such as police and
security, fire safety, medical facilities, utilities,
entertainment, waste management, transportation and life's
essentials, food and drink.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Atherton, the speedway president and general manager, can
be called the mayor of the instant city, and it's not a role he
takes lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we posted a sign on Cherry Avenue saying, `Welcome to the
California Speedway, Population 200,000,' we would be committing
ourselves to meeting or exceeding an expectation of civic
responsibility that comes with being a city,'' said Atherton, who
will preside over his first event at the speedway. ``That is
precisely what we're trying to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the goal set by Roger Penske from the time he first
eyed the abandoned Kaiser Steel property.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amid the rusting and decaying pieces of what used to be a
steel mill, and a backdrop that resembled Hiroshima, he had a
vision of a race track,'' said Les Richter, the Southern California
racing icon who would help build the speedway for Penske and serve
as executive vice president for Penske Motorsports. ``He also knew
how he wanted to treat the people who would come.''
</P>
<P>
   The speedway is capable of providing virtually every need a fan
might have for five days. While the majority of the day's crowd
will leave at the end of the racing day, as many as 20,000 will
camp out for the duration in the 2,000 spots for recreational
vehicles and trailers. It's this group that benefits most in terms
of security and attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take our role so seriously that in many cases, the people
are serviced at a higher level than in their own homes by some
cities or counties,'' said Atherton. ``For the guests in the
infield, it's the equivalent of going to sleep with a policeman,
fireman and ambulance all parked in the driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the speedway is ready to respond to any situation
within its borders. In two years of operation, the track has
experienced one death (heart attack) and transported an average of
12 cases per weekend to area hospitals for more advanced treatment,
mostly heat-related medical emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the usual amenities at the track, fans can expect
things like a concert by rock star Chris Isaak, fireworks,
interactive displays, bands, magicians and mimes.
</P>
<P>
   IWERKS will have NASCAR simulators for children and adults,
while DeWalt will allow fans to perform pit stop duties. If
baseball is preferred, the Anaheim Angels will provide batting and
pitching cages along with the opportunity to make a play-by-play
tape of Jim Edmonds' famous catch in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   In the air, warbirds from the Chino Planes of Fame Museum will
perform flybys, as well the F-16s of the 144th Fighter Wing
stationed at March Air Reserve Base in Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   As with any city of this size, there are various degrees of
comfort. Those in simple tents in the infield will not get the
guest services provided to those in custom-built motorhomes worth
$250,000 and more. The speedway offers newspaper and pizza delivery
for infield RVs, along with a special playground donated by Mattel.
It's such guest services that set the Fontana facility apart from
other tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been the innovator for many new ideas translated to
other Penske tracks,'' said Atherton, ``as well as other tracks.
For the VIP motorhomes, our concierge services are akin to a
five-star hotel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
