<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1595 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SOLDIER-ART-80     04-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SOLDIER-ART-805(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTIVE'S FAMILY STRUGGLES TO COPE WITH UNCERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich., Texas.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Andrew Ramirez was watching a news program when
Max, his son's dog, began barking in the night. Hours before, he
had heard the latest on Kosovo, that three American soldiers were
missing in Macedonia, but had not connected them to his own quiet
life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, an Army official stood outside the fence around Ramirez's
garden, locked so long he no longer had the key, and flashed a
lantern. His message was wrenching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to notify you that your son Andrew is missing in
action with two other soldiers,'' the stranger said. It was not
clear whether his boy was alive or dead. ``I said, `Thank you very
much,' '' Ramirez, a 55-year-old shipping clerk, recalled, looking
away. ``Then I went inside and cried.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town, Ramirez's estranged wife, Vivian, had been unable
to shake off a foreboding that something had gone wrong for her
son, part of the NATO forces in Macedonia on the border with NATO's
enemy Yugoslavia. When she got the call to return home from her job
at K-Mart, she knew. ``Is it Andy?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   And Celia Sanchez, the young soldier's grandmother, thought it
was some twisted April Fool's prank when told the next day that
``Little Andy,'' as his family calls him, had been taken prisoner
by the Serbs. Her daughter had to insist, breaking through a
grandmother's desperate wish that it somehow was not true.
</P>
<P>
   In the three weeks since the bruised faces of Ramirez, 24, Sgt.
Christopher Stone, 25, of Smith's Creek, Mich., and Specialist
Steven Gonzalez, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, first filled television
screens across the United States, the hopes for an early release of
the Americans, captured on March 31, have vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramirezes, who were in the middle of their own emotional
dramas when crisis hit, have banded together in new constellations
while each member struggles against an uncertainty that now seems
as if it will last as long as the war.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO celebrates its 50th anniversary this weekend,
unofficially debating whether to send ground troops to Yugoslavia,
President Clinton has made it clear that however it is fought, the
conflict in the Balkans is unlikely to end quickly. Even now, as
many as 33,000 U.S. reservists are gearing up to join the war
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Since capturing the Americans, Belgrade has turned down requests
from the International Red Cross to see them, in violation of the
Geneva Convention that is supposed to govern the conduct of war. It
has also turned away Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic told an
American television station that he would allow the Red Cross to
visit the prisoners. Nadine Ramirez, Andrew's older sister, said
she had not heard about the promise. ``We'll wait and see,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Red Cross announced in Geneva that its director
would meet with Milosevic in Belgrade on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgrade authorities at first accused the Americans of
spying, which carries a 16-year sentence in Yugoslavia, and said
last weekend that they had separated the three, a move that makes a
commando operation to free them _ always an unlikely and risky
enterprise _ ever more remote.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery surrounding the conditions in which the soldiers are
being held is heightening the anguish of the Ramirezes, whose
letters to Andrew remain undelivered.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Ramirez, a librarian at a local elementary school who
moonlights at the nearby K-Mart, has overcome her natural shyness,
appearing at numerous vigils for her son. She says she struggles to
build a wall between herself and dark thoughts to get her through
each day. But sometimes all that protects her mother's heart is a
thin shell of denial.
</P>
<P>
   She said she tries not to imagine the conditions of her son's
captivity, but her words suggest she does not always succeed. ``I
don't want to close my eyes and picture him in a dark room, maybe
all dirty or hurt or hungry,'' Mrs. Ramirez said. ``Or what's
around him. The sounds around him, also. I try not to think that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Andy'' Ramirez enlisted in 1992, as his brother Steven
had before him. At that time, ``there was no war, no threat of
anything,'' said his mother, who backed his decision. If he had
come up with the idea of joining now, Mrs. Ramirez joked in an
interview at home with her other children, ``we would have tied him
up and put him in the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez planned to leave the Army in May 2000 and join the
Police Department like Steven, 32, who is a detective. Their
sister, Nadine, 34, said Andrew saw the Army as a step toward a
good job, and would probably not have joined to fight a war.
Another relative, who requested anonymity, said that Andrew might
have joined up to fight, ``but would not make a big thing out of
it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's separated parents are both private people,
unaccustomed to publicity and the embrace of outsiders. And each
has handled the attention differently.
</P>
<P>
   As neighbors and well-wishers flocked outside his gate, lighting
candles and offering prayers for his son, the senior Ramirez stayed
inside, the blinds closed tight. He said he was trying to sleep,
for he gets up at 4 to catch the bus to work and has not missed a
day since his son's capture. ``I really don't want to deal with
it,'' he said. ``I'm not geared to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   A stranger might accuse Ramirez, who has not appeared at the
rallies for his son, of indifference, but would be profoundly
mistaken: He would later tell a longtime neighbor, Amparo Lopez,
that he didn't toss out the flowers left on the sidewalk, though
they began dying, so as not to hurt the feelings of the visitors
who troubled to leave them there.
</P>
<P>
   And though he shields himself behind jokes and a gravelly
exterior, saying that he will greet his son, once he is freed, with
the bill for seven years' of tending Max, worry lurks just beneath
the surface. Studying a stack of pictures of his son gleefully
parachuting from an airplane, Ramirez said: ``Look at his face, not
his build. To me, he's still a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the family is fathoming new meaning in the videos
released early in the American soldiers' captivity, shown over and
over. Ramirez wonders if an image that shows his son blinking
frequently is conveying a message, perhaps in Morse code, that he
is suffering. These days, ``life is very cheap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ramirez tried to sidestep the avalanche of attention that
rolled over her family at a time when they felt drained and
frightened. At one point, Steven Ramirez held a news conference at
the Police Department simply to tell reporters to stay away from
the family.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Ramirez surprised her children by swallowing her sorrow
and attending the first candlelight vigil days after her son's
capture. The children did not want her to attend, warning of the
certain media onslaught. But she insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to thank all those people who had supported us,'' she
said, ``and the only way I could reach them all was through
television.''
</P>
<P>
   A close friend of Mrs. Ramirez, Toby Viera, said, ``Her greatest
fear is that as this drags on, people will forget about Andy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Viera, 58, is the godmother of Andrew Ramirez and said she
was proud that he was supporting the effort to end the killing in
the Balkans. ``We should do everything we can to stop the killing
of those poor innocent people,'' she said. ``Otherwise, it'll be
just like what happened to the Jews in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Little Andy made it very personal for me,'' she said.
``He's warm and loving, but also very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's aunt, Loretta Magdaleno, agreed. ``I think Andy had a
job to do, and he was very disciplined,'' she said. ``In my mind,
that's what Andy would be saying: He was doing his job.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nadine, his sister, seeing so many forgotten relatives and
strangers among the hundreds of people who showed up at that first
rally made the reality of his plight sink in. Since then, she has
stood beside her mother at a dozen or so rallies, and she is the
one who watches for news of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Steven, who shares his father's reserve, has avoided the stage
at some of the vigils. As his mother and sister talked with a
reporter, he joined in but asked not to be quoted. But he has
stepped in to support his father and become a bridge holding his
family together.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Ramirez family has talked by phone with the
relatives of the two other American prisoners. They gave one
another solace and fed shared hopes of a meeting soon in Germany
when their boys are free. And Mrs. Ramirez found strength in a call
from President Clinton on Easter Sunday, brushing her hair
beforehand, as if the president were going to walk through the door
instead of phoning her.
</P>
<P>
   On the dining room table are tokens of support from strangers:
purple heather from Ireland, dirt from a holy site at Chemayo,
N.M., a feather sent from East Los Angeles, a teddy bear carrying a
rosary, and a flag that a 4-year-old boy had given Mrs. Ramirez at
a rally in her neighborhood two nights before.
</P>
<P>
   Now the family has hunkered down for the long wait. They are
considering speaking to counselors who can help them prepare for
Andrew's eventual return. Nadine said she prays that her brother
will ``come home safe, and that he's the same as he was before,
that he can laugh about this later on, and just say, `It
happened.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother suggests that may be too much to ask. The most
important thing is that her son, once free, will be ``able to talk
about it,'' she said. ``Just talk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
