<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANDOM-VIOLENCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE, EVEN BEFORE THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lh) 
 By CAITLIN LOVINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before two teen-aged boys began their shooting rampage last
week at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., long before
violent video games, the Internet and nihilistic industrial rock
music, America's young were committing occasional acts of
destruction and violence. If the following examples fail to show a
pattern, it may be because there is none.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, 17-year-old Kenneth Skinner burned an apartment
building in San Francisco, killing eight people. Although the
building was on his paper route, he said he knew none of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Starkweather was 19 in 1958 when he led Caril Fugate,
14, on a weeklong killing spree across Nebraska and Wyoming in
which 11 people were shot, stabbed and strangled to death. Miss
Fugate, who confessed to killing her mother with a shotgun when she
threatened Starkweather, was sentenced to life in prison. Hours
before his death in the electric chair, Starkweather was asked if
he would donate his eyes for medical use. ``Hell no,'' he said.
``No one ever did anything for me. Why should I do anything for
anyone else?''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1966, Charles Whitman, 24, an expert marksman and a
former Eagle Scout and marine, killed his wife and mother. Then he
took a footlocker full of ammunition, shotguns, rifles, Spam
sandwiches and water to a 27-story clock tower at the University of
Texas in Austin, where he was a junior. He shot 46 people in an
hour and a half, killing 16 before he was killed by the police.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy showed a tumor pressing on his hypothalamus. The
psychiatrist he had begun seeing a few months before revealed that
Whitman said he was ``thinking about going up on the tower and
shooting people.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, 18-year-old Robert Benjamin Smith took seven
female hostages in a beauty school and salon in Mesa, Ariz., and
fatally shot five of them, including a 3-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   He waited for the police, then confessed and cited as his
motivation the crimes of Whitman and those of Richard Speck, who
had killed eight student nurses in Chicago that year. ``I just
wanted to get myself a name,'' Smith said at the time. Smith's
student counselor, who was also the basketball coach at Mesa High
School, blamed his ``lack of physical coordination.'' Smith was
sentenced to death but won an appeal and remains in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 Anthony Barbaro, an 18-year-old in Olean, N.Y., entered
his high school, which was closed for Christmas, and set several
fires. When a custodian investigated, Barbaro, who was a member of
the school's rifle team, shot him dead, then fired from a
third-floor window at firemen and passersby, killing two more
people and wounding nine. An investigation of his home turned up
handmade bombs and a diary detailing five months of planning the
attack. Before he hanged himself in his cell, Barbaro told his
uncle that ``the pressure just got the best of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Spencer was 16 in 1979 when she fired on an elementary
school yard from the window of her house in San Carlos, Calif.
Using the .22-caliber rifle her father had given her for Christmas
a month before, she killed the principal and custodian and wounded
eight children and a policeman before she was arrested. Her
explanation at the time: ``I just don't like Mondays ... I did this
because it's a way to cheer up the day.'' Miss Spencer was
sentenced to life in prison; her next parole date is in two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
