</P>
<P>
   Popular art aimed at adolescents often trades in alienation.
Adults who try to comprehend it violate the generational boundary
that is part of its appeal. They risk looking foolish and being
ignored. But it is impossible to understand young people apart from
their interpretations _ and misinterpretations _ of the fashions
and fads they love, for they add to the sense of self that leads
them to act.
</P>
<P>
   In Littleton, the failure of anyone to gaze across this gap
apparently aided disaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-REVIEW-750&AMP;ADD-     04-24 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-REVIEW-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S POOREST ARE BECOMING ITS LOUDEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lh) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Since the Hindu nationalist-led government
collapsed a week ago, the noisy, gaudy spectacle of Indian
democracy has played out here in the capital on familiar public
stages: the steps of Parliament House, the courtyard of the
president's residence and at the closed gates of the Gandhi family
compound.
</P>
<P>
   But the political turmoil that has seen five governments come
tumbling down here in just six years is not merely the result of
cantankerous rivalries among the country's political parties or the
often venal, self-serving antics of its politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Even more crucial are profound political changes taking place in
hundreds of thousands of villages where most of the nation's 980
million people live and vote. Researchers have learned from
election and survey data that in the 1990s the country's most
oppressed people _ the low castes, the poor, the illiterate _ have
been voting and joining political parties in growing proportions,
as have women, who were long at the fringes of the nation's
political life.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these voters are flocking to the caste-based and
regional parties that more directly reflect their own identities
and interests and that now hold the power to make and to break
governments.
</P>
<P>
   The India that for most of its history was dominated by the
dynastic reign of the Nehru-Gandhi family in the Congress Party has
given way to a cacophonous multiplicity of parties, some of them
led by populist politicians who metaphorically poke a finger in the
eye of the country's Brahmin elite at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the poorest Indians are now more likely to vote than
the richest ones. This turns on its head what was true here only a
quarter of a century ago, and what is still true of American and
European democracies: namely, that the prosperous are more likely
to vote than the disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've entered what political scientists call a decade of
realignment,'' said Yogendra Yadav, who has researched these trends
at the Center for the Study of Developing Societies here. ``The
stable alignments have broken down and a new era when these
linkages are rewoven has begun. One of the consequences of this
massive redefinition is instability at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The center's study of survey and voting data found that the
current decade has witnessed increased voter turnout, rising
membership in political parties and a deepening faith in democracy
itself among the people at the bottom of India's deeply inequitable
social structure. The study is to be published soon by Oxford
University Press as part of a book on Indian democracy produced in
cooperation with the University of Pennsylvania's Institute for the
Advanced Study of India.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the trends, the percentage of people from
formerly untouchable castes who said they were members of political
parties rose from 13 percent in 1971 to 19 percent in 1996, while
the percentage from the upper castes who said they belonged to a
party declined from 36 percent to 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of very poor people who believe voting makes a
difference rose from 38 percent in 1971 to 51 percent in 1996, and
jumped from 42 percent to 60 percent for low caste people.
</P>
<P>
   At first, their belief in the power of the ballot seems
puzzling. State and national governments have often failed to
deliver to the poor the most basic services _ education, health
care and clean drinking water among them _ as well as a more
rapidly growing economy that could help more people escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But in a country where government still plays a central role in
the economy and dispensing public goods, politics has given the
lower castes the power to claim a share of patronage _ everything
from schools to housing to wells to jobs in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to come to power to make money,'' said Jairam
Ramesh, an economic policy advisor in the Congress Party. ``The
goodies are in power.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars say politics has also provided a route to something
less tangible but perhaps even more potent politically: pride,
dignity and the confidence to fight back against the kinds of
indignities the low castes have suffered for millennia _ of being
contemptuously called by their caste names, of being forbidden to
draw water from the same wells as the upper castes, of being denied
the right to ride a horse in a wedding procession like an upper
caste groom.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   No place better exemplifies both the failings of government and
the democratic ferment transforming Indian politics than Uttar
Pradesh, India's most populous and most politically powerful state
and one of its most impoverished, dysfunctional ones.
</P>
<P>
   For the first four decades after Indian independence in 1947,
politics in Uttar Pradesh was dominated by upper castes in the
Congress Party, but Congress has been out of power there throughout
the 1990s. ``The Congress Party never saw fit to have a Dalit chief
minister in Uttar Pradesh, though Dalits have the single largest
proportion of voters,'' Ramesh, the Congress economic advisor, said
ruefully, referring to people from castes formerly regarded as
untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, two non-Brahmin, non-upper-caste parties have won
growing clout in Uttar Pradesh, and both have played important
roles in the latest bout of political turmoil in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Mayawati, a Dalit woman and a leader of the Bahujan Samaj Party,
which is built on the votes of Dalits, pulled the rug out from
under the ruling coalition led by the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya
Janata Party, which has been predominantly run by upper castes.
</P>
<P>
   Mayawati, who like many lower caste women goes by one name,
became a symbol of hope to Dalits in two brief terms as chief
minister of Uttar Pradesh in the late 1990s. She lulled the Hindu
nationalist leaders into believing her five members of Parliament
would remain neutral in the confidence vote on April 17. But in the
end, her party's legislators all voted against a government led by
people they believed had betrayed them in Uttar Pradesh politics.
The national coalition government lost power by a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   And last Friday, the Samajwadi Party, whose voting base is with
Muslims and Yadavs, the middling cow herd's caste, foiled the
Congress Party's efforts to form a minority government with the
support of smaller parties. The Samajwadi Party leader, Mulayam
Singh Yadav, said his 20 members of Parliament would not support
any new government unless they were part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mayawati nor Yadav is willing to accept crumbs from the
tables of the two major national parties. They want to be at the
table themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
