<HEADER>
A1621 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-BOMBING-REVIEW-N     04-24 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-BOMBING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ALL IN FAVOR OF THIS TARGET, SAY YES, SI, OUI, JA  (The Week in
Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As commander in chief during the Vietnam War, Lyndon Johnson
insisted on having almost absolute control over what to bomb and
when to bomb it. ``They can't even bomb an outhouse without my
approval,'' he once declared of the American pilots conducting
raids over Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with NATO unleashing its air power against Yugoslavia, an
alliance-full of political leaders is setting its own parameters
for strikes, though not to Johnsonian extremes. And that has bogged
down the military task of choosing targets _ complicated enough
with NATO's multinational command structure _ in a morass of
competing political aims.
</P>
<P>
   France's leadership, including President Jacques Chirac, has
curbed NATO strikes on the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, which
is viewed as less hostile to the West than the government in
Belgrade. Lawyers in Britain review each target its forces hit _
either by air or by cruise missile _ to ensure each is justifiably
a military one.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has vetted the entire list of targets,
Secretary of Defense William Cohen said, but has focused on the
most prominent ones, like President Slobodan Milosevic's party
headquarters and a presidential palace in Belgrade, both of which
were struck last week. Although Clinton has signed off on most
targets, his aides say, he has vetoed others, always exhibiting
what his aides describe as a profound aversion to unintended
civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the Senate recently, Cohen said, ``Each
president of the NATO countries, at least the major players,'' are
given ``an opportunity to at least express their judgment'' on the
targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to be in a position of having the commander in
chief or the president of a country have a chance to look the list
over and make at least a recommendation _ without getting into the
politics of it, but deciding whether or not that is a target which,
if hit, would carry such consequences that it would be
counterproductive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As an alliance with 19 members, NATO operates by consensus, and
so the objection of any one member can in theory scuttle _ or at
least slow down _ decisions large and small. In reality, though,
those countries with the most forces involved have the greatest
influence.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO's headquarters near Brussels, Belgium, the process
assures democratic inclusion but is, to some critics, no way to run
a war. ``Running a list of targets through 19 countries cannot be
an effective way of waging war,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   NATO began its strikes a month ago with a list of 100 targets,
according to a NATO diplomat. Those targets were selected by
military aides to NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark,
working in war rooms in Brussels, Germany and Italy. Although the
aides, from various allies, picked targets for their military
value, their choices were limited from the outset by the North
Atlantic Council, NATO's political arm, which is represented day to
day by ambassadors from each member. The council outlined three
phases of attacks, beginning with air defenses and other purely
military targets and escalating to targets at the heart of
Milosevic's power, like those struck last week.
</P>
<P>
   When the attack began, the council approved strikes in only the
first category. Early in the campaign, however, Clark sought and
received authority to move on to the other phases. Having approved
the broad categories of targets, the North Atlantic Council has now
largely removed itself from reviewing specific targets, though
individual governments have not.
</P>
<P>
   Most major targets still have to be cleared through the
political-military chains of command of each ally, leading to
second-guessing that has frustrated some commanders at NATO and the
Pentagon and, inevitably, slowed the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have these criss-crossing objectives,'' said Andrew
Krepinevich, executive director at the Center for Strategic and
Budgetary Assessments, a research group in Washington. ``On the one
hand, NATO's credibility and viability will be best served by a
quick defeat of Milosevic. On the other hand, many NATO members
have reservations about going after certain targets or have
concerns about the risks to pilots.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the United States, the chain of command flows
from Clark, who also serves as commander of all American forces for
Europe and Africa, to the Joint Chiefs of Staff at the Pentagon. A
group within the Joint Staff, called the J-2T, works closely with
Clark's planners.
</P>
<P>
   From the Joint Staff, decisions on major targets move up through
Cohen's office and, when considered particularly sensitive, across
the Potomac to the White House. Only then do the targets go back to
Clark's staff with a stamp of approval. A White House aide said
that while Clinton approves targets of supreme sensitivity, he has
yet to display President Johnson's penchant for micro-managing from
afar.
</P>
<P>
   Routine strikes against military targets are no longer reviewed
by political leaders. The major targets are still vetted but
approved more quickly, as evidenced by the attack late Thursday on
Yugoslavia's state-run television, which several allies, led by
France, had previously considered too sensitive to strike because
of the potential threat to civilians.
</P>
<P>
   For all its unwieldiness, NATO's consensus approach serves its
purpose, officials say, assuring that each ally stands behind
whatever plan emerges.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO has 18 besides us,'' said Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, a
planner at the Joint Staff who has become a leading Pentagon
spokesman on the war. ``They all have a vote on everything. They
can vote on whether we start this or not. They can vote on whether
we continue. They can vote on everything. And that is the strength,
and probably the weakness a little bit, of what we have going on
here. But the beauty of the fact is we are a coalition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2653 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-BOMBING-REVIEW-N     04-24 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-BOMBING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ALL IN FAVOR OF THIS TARGET, SAY YES, SI, OUI, JA  (The Week in
Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
