<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1622 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEE-CRISIS-REVIEW     04-24 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-CRISIS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TEST: GETTING THE REFUGEES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(mk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Yet another specter is haunting Europe, and not
just Europe this time: the specter of the permanent refugee.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of thousands of Albanians uprooted in Kosovo and
spilling across the borders of Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro,
some diplomats see the crisis as a defining moment in how the world
thinks about the temporarily and permanently displaced.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has declared as a fundamental war aim that the Kosovo
refugees will get the chance to go back home when the fighting
stops. But that isn't the way most wars have ended in this century.
Look around the world, and the refugees who call themselves
Palestinians, or Cambodians, or Bosnians have by and large not
achieved that dream. In fact, millions of people around the world
have become permanent refugees or, at best, have found new lives in
a new diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   So if NATO can accomplish its war aim, and reverse a campaign of
ethnic cleansing, it would be achieving something quite new.
</P>
<P>
   But it certainly will not be easy. Pushing out the Yugoslav
forces who expelled the refugees may well require a NATO invasion.
Even if NATO goes that far, how many Albanians will be eager to
return to a land where their homes have been burned, their husbands
and brothers herded off to unknown fates, their former lives
shattered?
</P>
<P>
   Richard Betts, a political science professor at Columbia
University, warns that in vowing that the refugees will return,
NATO ``may be making a promise we can't keep, or are unprepared to
keep.'' On the other hand, Arthur Helton, who teaches refugee law
at the New York University School of Law, worries that if return
remains the measure of victory or defeat in the conflict, refugees
may be forced or pressured into returning against their wishes.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the end, is it possible that the war will end somewhat
short of the goal, with a deal that implicitly acknowledges that
the refugees will not be able to return safely?
</P>
<P>
   That is already emerging as a fear among refugee advocates and
Albanian-American groups. Some of these people fear that NATO
betrayed a crack in its determination last week when the United
States decided to permit some 20,000 Kosovar refugees being brought
here for safety to be eligible, after a year, to become permanent
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Did this not suggest, some complained, that the refugees might
not be returning to Kosovo once the fighting ends? Would that not
be a victory for ethnic cleansing and its architect, President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia?
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia began a month ago, the office
of the U.N. high commissioner for refugees estimates that almost
600,000 of Kosovo's 1.6 million ethnic Albanians have left their
homes and crossed into neighboring lands. Ominously, NATO said last
week, Yugoslav forces were herding together another 850,000
Albanians inside Kosovo, possibly preparing to expel them, or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   The element in this equation that may make this refugee crisis
different from others is that the Albanian Kosovars are more than
mere byproducts of war. They were the declared reason that NATO
went to war. One analyst calls them the ``glue'' of NATO
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   And for NATO's European members, the motives are not simply
altruistic. Even if the refugees don't flood into Western Europe
itself, NATO officials fear that their continued presence may upset
the delicate ethnic balance of Yugoslavia's neighbors, increasing
instability.
</P>
<P>
   Looking beyond Kosovo, diplomats and relief groups agree that
finding a solution for refugee crises has become one of the world's
greatest challenges. At the century's end, some 22 million people
have been displaced by wars and civil conflicts. Some 2.6 million
Afghan refugees languish in Pakistan, Iran, and camps in other
countries, according to the U.N. Children's Fund. The total number
of African refugees, displaced persons, and still vulnerable
returnees now exceeds 7 million. At least 3.2 million Palestinians
are still classified as refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thinking about these people has evolved over the past
decade,'' said David Malone, the president of the International
Peace Academy, an independent group that studies the United
Nations. ``Before they were considered unfortunate victims of war
whose plight had to be addressed. Over time they have become a
major factor in peace and security. They are increasingly seen as a
source of instability.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly the world is acknowledging that many of these people will
never go home. Still, ``permanent refugees'' pose daunting
challenges not only to relief groups but to the states that might
accommodate them. ``We hate that term; we never use it,'' said
Karen Koning AbuZayd, the refugee commissioner's Washington
representative. ``The term refugee implies a durable solution _
going home, being locally integrated, or being resettled.''
</P>
<P>
   Her agency's insistence on repatriation has sometimes been
criticized when people are encouraged to return to politically and
economically fragile countries. But Ms. AbuZayd says that it is
what most refugees want. In this respect, she said, her agency can
be proud. The numbers of people it cares for had dropped in recent
years from 27 million to 22.5 million, half of them refugees. The
agency has been closing down offices in Central America and Asia.
About 1.7 million Mozambican refugees have gone home.
</P>
<P>
   Some countries, in addition to contributing to U.N. relief
efforts, have been extraordinarily generous in taking people in.
Iran, she notes, is the world's biggest refugee host. In the
Balkans, the biggest host has been Yugoslavia, which has had to
accommodate Serbs driven out of Croatia and parts of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But taking in refugees is not what NATO has been talking about.
Getting them home is. And the Bosnian experience may be
instructive.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton accords that ended the Bosnian war in 1995 specified
that refugees could return home, but achieving safety for them in
their old neighborhoods was another matter. By mid 1997, Helton
says, about 300,000 refugees and displaced people had returned
home, but very few of these went to areas where they would be in an
ethnic minority. Meanwhile, 900,000 remained internally displaced
and another 900,000 live abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Malone thinks that if Kosovo is cleared of Yugoslav pressure,
the refugees will return. ``So it's important for NATO to decide
soon what kind of Kosovo it wants and can achieve,'' he said. ``An
independent state? An international protectorate? A combination of
the two?''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, diplomats and relief workers have begun to wonder
what precedents are being set in Kosovo. Some think the crisis is
only receiving great attention because these refugees are
Europeans, and few lessons will be learned.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Rubenstein, executive director of Physicians for Human
Rights, a private group, has another fear: ``If intervention to
save peoples' lives fails this time and people are not protected or
permitted to return, the impetus to try again next time may simply
not be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
