<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1624 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-IMAGES-REVIEW-     04-24 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-IMAGES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPAGANDA WARS: PICTURES CAN LIE, AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the words that have been spilled to describe the
strategic, military, and bruisingly human dimensions of the
conflict in Kosovo, it is the images that linger. A crying child. A
hillside of houses, burning in unison. The corpse of an ethnic
Albanian lying in the rubble of an explosion. A grainy
black-and-white video of a railroad bridge in a NATO bomber's
sights, then a train coming out of nowhere, and an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The images carry obvious messages. Which is the problem. What
journalists see of the air war is what the NATO allies want them to
see. What they see of the destruction of Kosovo and the bombardment
of Yugoslavia is what the Yugoslavs want them to see. Only on the
borders of Albania and Macedonia, amid the vast vistas of refugee
misery, do journalists have relatively free access and some ability
to cross-check information.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question in my mind we are seeing from NATO what
NATO wants us to see,'' said Al Ortiz, executive producer of the
CBS Evening News with Dan Rather. Still, he said, there is a
difference between the images NATO offers and those that emerge
from Yugoslav control. With NATO, ``You're also able to challenge
and question and dig back and check with sources,'' he said.
``You're not able to do that on the Serbian government side.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of verifying images from isolated or carefully
controlled sites has dogged photo agencies since people first
mouthed the untrue truism, ``pictures don't lie.'' Before the
digital era, photographs were manipulated with artful cropping or
darkroom retouching. In 1906, Frederick Cook took a picture of
himself supposedly atop Alaska's Mount McKinley _ but he wasn't
really there. Soviet authorities routinely airbrushed cosmonauts
and commissars out of pictures when they became inconvenient.
</P>
<P>
   In a war, when propaganda is a weapon, manipulated images are a
chronic problem. Some are scrapped, but others are passed on to the
public hemmed in with caveats. In effect, the news organizations
seem to be saying, here is an image. You decide what it means.
</P>
<P>
   One of the starkest images from the Kosovo conflict raised the
eyebrows of photo editors when it came onto their computer screens
10 days ago. Nonetheless, it became the leading photograph in Time
and Newsweek last week.
</P>
<P>
   The image, which traveled from the camera of a freelance
photographer to a transmitter in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, and then
through the hands of editors in Frankfurt, Germany; Paris, and
Washington, shows the corpse of a middle-aged man. He is lying in a
crater that could have been created by a bomb or artillery strike.
In the background, on a truck, are other bodies, charred and
shredded.
</P>
<P>
   But the body in the foreground is achingly whole, save for an
angry red cavity that covers his calf. The Yugoslav authorities who
took journalists to the site said he was an Albanian refugee
killed, like the others in the image, by a NATO bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Mann, Agence France-Presse's director of photography for
North and South America, was at the end of the chain of editors who
passed the photo on. ``I thought, `They picked up that body and
threw it in there,''' she said. ``But I can't substantiate that. At
the same time I thought we had to show it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other photo and film editors in news organizations around
the world, she is conscious that every image from within Kosovo may
lie. ``We have to question what we're seeing every day,'' Ms. Mann
said. ``You have a sixth sense when you see something _ you know in
your gut something is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Then what?
</P>
<P>
   The picture of the corpse was taken by a freelance photographer,
Vuc Brankovic, who, along with other journalists, was escorted to
the site by the Yugoslav authorities. Brankovic was engaged by
European Photopress Agency, for which he had not done much work
before, an editor there said.
</P>
<P>
   Both The Associated Press, which had a television crew at the
site, and Agence France-Presse clearly warned editors of their
concerns. In a caption, AP listed the source as
``APTN/Serb-Controlled Pool.'' Agence France-Press wrote that the
man was ``claimed by Yugoslav authorities to have been killed in a
NATO air raid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our operating procedure is to tell everything we can in the
caption,'' said Vincent Alabiso, vice president and executive photo
editor of The Associated Press. ``As far as the editors at the
newspapers and magazines are concerned, they have the photo and the
captions explaining the circumstances. They have to make a judgment
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Agence France-Presse photograph made the pages
of Time and Newsweek last week, much of that context was gone.
Time's tight caption read: ``Whose Fault? NATO admits to a tragic
error, but this photo may have been staged.'' Newsweek's caption
made no reference to these concerns. Its article said that
journalists were taken to a site littered with body parts, ``some
perhaps, repositioned for effect by the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News &AMP; World Report used a different photo of the scene.
Its caption stated unambiguously, ``Victims of a NATO bomb dropped
on a column of refugees.'' The magazine's editor, Stephen Smith,
said he was concerned that the magazine had been too categorical.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Stephenson, director of photography of Time Magazine,
said of the dead man in the Agence France-Presse photograph:
``Clearly the guy was in this attack on the convoy and was killed.
We don't know if he was killed in the attack and was dragged over
there. We don't know if the crater was made by an earlier bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Mann, a decision not to transmit the image would have
amounted to censorship. ``You need to have people draw their own
conclusions, given as much as you can know about the situation,''
she said. And she added, ``The fact that all the agencies were
there guarantees that the picture is going to be run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2656 &Cx1f; var-z
