<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET OF WEEK-IN-REVIEW STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, April 25, have moved. This final budget adds
RANDOM-VIOLENCE-REVIEW in the `a' category.
</P>
<P>
   On the section dress page:
</P>
<P>
   WARNING-SIGNS-REVIEW (Seattle) _ The boy stalking victims
through a video dungeon in the game Doom, or laughing at the
slaughter in Oliver Stone's movie ``Natural Born Killers,'' might
well be the next person to shoot up a school in some polished
American suburb. But then again, he might be a quiet scholar with
an odd side. How to tell the difference is one of the more
difficult challenges left by Tuesday's carnage in Colorado. By
Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEE-CRISIS-REVIEW (United Nations) _ Yet another specter is
haunting Europe, and not just Europe this time: the specter of the
permanent refugee. With hundreds of thousands of Albanians uprooted
in Kosovo and spilling across the borders of Albania, Macedonia and
Montenegro, some diplomats see the crisis as a defining moment in
how the world thinks about the temporarily and permanently
displaced. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-HUMOR-REVIEW (Undated) _ Today, alas, the
pronouncements of politicians seem more humorless than ever. That's
probably because, in this era of heightened sensitivities and
ubiquitous cameras, an off-the-cuff quip can bring you a world of
grief (though politicians' private peccadillos often provide laughs
enough). So whether you're a stolid Al Gore or a relentlessly sunny
Elizabeth Dole, it's best to stay on message while minimizing the
ad-libs. By John Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   SURGERY-ETHICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Placebo surgery is on the
rise, to the horror of some doctors who say it is immoral and to
the delight of others who say it is time to apply the same rigorous
scientific standards to surgery as to the rest of the medical
profession. And with it comes a host of thorny questions. By Sheryl
Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   EXTREME-MUSIC-REVIEW (Undated) _ The killing spree by two young
fans of computerized gladiator matches and gut-wrenching industrial
rock last week in Littleton, Colo., was a calamity measured in
lives lost and damaged. But the tragedy at Columbine High School
also marked yet another battle over the meanings and effects of
youth culture. By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   PROFILING-REVIEW (Washington) _ The spring day was bright and
sunny enough for sunglasses, yet cool enough to require a
sweatshirt and baggy sweat pants. As I walked along a busy street
in the predominantly white northwest Washington neighborhood where
I lived, I hardly thought that my clothing or, more important, my
dark skin would attract the attention of the police. But sure
enough, after a few blocks, a brown and white cruiser from the
Capital Police suddenly pulled alongside. A white officer jumped
out and demanded to know what I was doing there. By Steven A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   RANDOM-VIOLENCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Long before two teen-aged
boys began their shooting rampage last week at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., long before violent video games, the
Internet and nihilistic industrial rock music, America's young were
committing occasional acts of destruction and violence. But finding
a pattern is not easy. By Caitlin Lovinger.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-REVIEW (New Delhi, India) _ The political turmoil that has
seen five governments come tumbling down here in just six years is
not merely the result of cantankerous rivalries among the country's
political parties or the often venal, self-serving antics of its
politicians. Even more crucial are profound political changes
taking place in hundreds of thousands of villages where most of the
nation's 980 million people live and vote. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-UNITY-REVIEW (London) _ For most of the half-century it is
celebrating in Washington this weekend, NATO's very existence has
been rooted in the idea of a grand design _ to guarantee the safety
of the West against the East, to forge a common defense of
democracy against tyranny, to prepare, in effect, for World War
III. But now, as NATO's forces press their first true combat
mission in a messy conflict in Kosovo, the allies and their
neighbors are discovering that war is not just about the grand
design of thwarting tyranny, but about niggling details and
political line calls. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-BOMBING-REVIEW (Washington) _ As commander in chief during
the Vietnam War, Lyndon Johnson insisted on having almost absolute
control over what to bomb and when to bomb it. But now, with NATO
unleashing its air power against Yugoslavia, an alliance-full of
political leaders is setting its own parameters for strikes. And
that has bogged down the military task of choosing targets _
complicated enough with NATO's multinational command structure _ in
a morass of competing political aims. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-IMAGES-REVIEW (Undated) _ What journalists see of the air
war in Yugoslavia is what the NATO allies want them to see. What
they see of the destruction of Kosovo is what the Yugoslavs want
them to see. Only on the borders of Albania and Macedonia, amid the
vast vistas of refugee misery, do journalists have relatively free
access and some ability to cross-check information. By Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
