<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BLAIR-NYT &LR;      04-24 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BLAIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR'S WAY WITH WORDS ENLIVENS A CALL TO ARMS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a media blitz reminiscent of an American
presidential campaign, British Prime Minister Tony Blair has so
captured the message at the NATO summit meeting here that his
detractors are wondering who crowned him NATO's ``King Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair made a grand entrance on Wednesday, announcing that he
would fly to Washington early and go immediately to the White House
to brief President Clinton on his new ideas for fighting
Yugoslavia. It was the first stop on his campaign to sound a call
to arms in the United States to win the war over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning he was on Capitol Hill, encouraging Senate
leaders to press harder for victory and earning praise from Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C, who called him ``the most eloquent leader in
the Western world'' _ an obvious, if unintended, slight of
Clinton's acknowledged role as leader of the Western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In those two days, Blair also managed to squeeze in an evening
speech at the Chicago Economic Club _ the first British prime
minister to visit that city _ and spread his message by television:
on CNN's show ``Larry King Live'' after the Chicago speech and,
this morning, on the ``Today'' program on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Blair even self-confidently announced a sweeping new doctrine in
Chicago of ``international community'' that he said was the
underpinning for the war for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all internationals now, whether we like it or not,'' he
said. ``We cannot refuse to participate in global markets if we
want to prosper. We cannot ignore new political ideas in other
countries if we want to innovate. We cannot turn our backs on
conflicts and the violation of human rights within other countries
if we want still to be secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Many European diplomats raised their eyebrows at Blair's
behavior, theorizing that he was trying to make Britain the
important link between the United States and Europe. While none of
them would speak on the record, saying now is not the time to
criticize a fellow NATO member, several referred to him as ``King
Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton, the White House said he did not feel upstaged.
His aides said rather that he was thankful that the British prime
minister's omnipresence was helping persuade the American public
that the United States is not alone in the war against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic. The Clinton-Blair roles called to
mind the way that the former British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher shored up President Bush and American support for the
Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fact of life that our media has a cultural affinity
with the British and that Tony Blair is much sought after,'' said
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. ``Rather than run from that we
try to take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair is not alone in his media blitz. His foreign minister,
Robin Cook, and his defense minister, George Robertson, also took
their cause to Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a considerable strength and determination and unity
of purpose among these legislators about what needed to be done,
and a great awareness of some of the deeper and bigger issues that
are involved in that,'' Robertson said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But giving such pep talks to Congress and holding regular
briefings for the international press is foreign to most of the
other European members of the alliance, who are watching the Blair
machine from a discreet distance. French President Jacques Chirac
declined invitations to appear on several American television
programs, including ``Larry King Live,'' even though France is the
second-biggest contributor of aircraft to the air campaign, with 83
planes, including 61 combat jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans and Italians, whose countries are also key members,
have kept equally low profiles. Italian Prime Minister Massimo
d'Alema came to the summit meeting early, like Blair, but he went
first to meet with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in New York
and ask that the organization find a political solution to end the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   That was not part of the message of Blair, who has been making
almost daily speeches exhorting the British people to support the
war effort since the air campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   Private Eye, the British satirical weekly, has dubbed him
``Winstony Blair'' and satirized Blair's message in a recent issue:
``Never in the field of human conflict have so many airplanes
dropped so few bombs on so few targets. We shall not fight them on
the beaches, we shall not fight them in the hills, we shall not
fight them on the streets. They will never surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair considers it his duty, according to his press secretary,
Alastair Campbell, to invigorate not only the British public but
the American public, the people in all NATO counties and even the
Russian public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1638 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-TRENCHCOA     04-24 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-TRENCHCOATS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 MENACING `TRENCH COAT MAFIA' WAS JUST A JOKE, AT FIRST
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Tad Boles' mother bought him a black duster
for Christmas in 1996 because they were on sale at Miller Stockman,
a western wear outlet, for $99.
</P>
<P>
   A week or so later, Tad's closest friend, Chris Morris, had the
same kind of coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were two little hipster sophomores going down the hallway
_ people started calling them the trench coat mafia,'' recalled
Mrs. Boles, who spoke on condition her first name not be printed.
``I personally thought they looked kind of goofy, but they're
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, it seemed like all of Tad's buddies were wearing the
coats. By last year, their girlfriends bought a business-card size
ad in the Columbine High School yearbook, ``Rebelations,'' and
devoted it to the ``trench coat mafia,'' running a photograph of
the group.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the name sounds a little menacing, now that it is
linked to the two young men behind one of the deadliest school
massacres in American history, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   But it started out as just a tease, a name thrust upon the
ragtag group of outcasts by the more popular kids at Columbine, who
seized on the appearance of the dark, ominous-looking dusters as
new fodder for their unending harassment of those on the fringes.
In the yearbook, Harris and Klebold are not even in the picture
(and those who do appear in it are not wearing trench coats).
</P>
<P>
   In the first hours after the shooting and bombings that left a
teacher and 14 students _ including Harris and Klebold _ dead at
Columbine in this middle class suburb of 35,000 southwest of
Denver, the group was described as devoted to Gothic music and
culture, computer video games with ominous names like Doom, and all
things German, including Hitler, whose birthday coincided with
Tuesday's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, members of the group, their parents and other
Columbine students have said it was just a tiny clique of boys who
had long been losers, finally finding a place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just a group of friends that hung out like everybody
else,'' said Joseph Stair, who was in the Columbine Class of 1998
and is credited with ``founding'' the group, said Friday on NBC's
``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids that did this, they're disturbed,'' Mrs. Boles said
of Klebold and Harris, whom she knew only slightly as Tad's
friends. ``The things that they did had nothing to do with what the
group was about.'' She said the group, ``wasn't about anything else
but hanging out with friends.''
</P>
<P>
   They were into computers. They all played Doom, like Harris. A
Web site attributed to him mentioned the trench coat mafia and
featured drawings of gun-toting monsters and directions for making
pipe bombs. Recently, Mrs. Boles said, members of the group were
more focused on making videos, like the one by Klebold and Harris
that is said to show them killing athletes in a school hallway.
</P>
<P>
   The group used to hang out at Amazing Fantasy Comics in
Littleton, but the manager of the store, Shawn Carey, said members
stopped coming about a year ago because they grew more interested
in paintball and girls. Friends said they were heavily into
role-playing games like Dungeons and Dragons, and often played the
card game ``Magic.'' They liked to drink shots of ``After Shock,''
a brand of cinnamon or peppermint schnapps.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the group, which had anywhere from seven to 20 members,
wore the black lipstick and black fingernail polish associated with
the Goths. But Klebold and Harris did not, friends said; some say
they were not even part of the core of the trench coat group, just
friends of a core member.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Boles, a mother of five, insisted that the trench coat
owners were just like any other teen-agers, interested in bamboo
sword fights, ``Star Wars'' and computer games, but also ``the
teeny-boppers bopping at the prom'' and that great American
teen-age tradition, working on their cars.
</P>
<P>
   When Stair was asked about the group's interest in pipe bombs
and other weaponry used in Tuesday's massacre, he just shrugged.
Members were interested in medieval warfare, too, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it a fascination, but we knew how to
manufacture them,'' Stair said of the bombs that the authorities
believe were built in Harris' garage and later found throughout
Columbine High. ``It was just something we looked at. We looked at
lots of things. It was just something to pass the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbine students said the trench coat group often spoke in
German and wore clothes decorated with swastikas. Klebold was said
to have had a German flag sewn onto his coat. Stair said they took
German classes and read books about Hitler, but ``it really wasn't
a fascination or an obsession at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Denee Taylor, 17, who has six rings in her ear and a stud in her
tongue, has socialized with the group since she came to Columbine a
year ago from Newark Valley, N.Y. The group was ``a little weird,''
she acknowledged, ``but what's wrong with being different?''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Nelson, 18, a Columbine senior who describes himself as ``an
outcast by choice,'' said he had played Doom with Klebold and
Harris over the Internet and, yes, ``they always seemed a little
different to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They dressed a little different,'' Nelson said, noting that
that kind of thing can be stupidly important in high school. ``They
wore the trench coats all the time, 90 degrees, 20 degrees,
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   The preppies and jocks who rule the school taunted the group in
the hallways with sarcastic jibes of ``nice coat.'' Some Columbine
students said members of the group rarely showered, and were
shunned because of their body odor. One member was quoted in
Saturday's Denver Post as saying that they had been pushed against
lockers and had rocks and lunchroom mashed potatoes thrown in their
faces by jocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't dress like them, if you walked or rode your
bike, if you didn't get into sports and weren't athletic, then you
were an outcast,'' said the young man, who was not named in the
Post story. ``It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Koeniger, a 17-year-old junior on the Columbine Rebels
football team, acknowledged that some athletes teased the trench
coat mafia, but said the group often seemed to be asking for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're different, why wouldn't we look at them as weird?''
he asked, recalling a student last year who wore tight jeans, had
long hair and seemed to never shower.
</P>
<P>
   But like so many groups before them, the trench coat mafia
embraced what started as a kind of epithet and made it their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it up; we were like, oh, look at them, the trench coat
mafia,'' recalled Ashly Beeson, 18, who left Columbine a couple of
months ago to escape the cliques and finish her senior year at an
alternative school. ``It's nothing they gave themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As the rest of the people in town appear at makeshift memorials
of flowers and banners, sobbing on television about the events that
have overtaken the community, members of the trench coat mafia and
their friends have spent much of the past week talking to the
police.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities believe that the arsenal of bombs and other
weapons was more than two boys could carry even under their large
trench coats. If they had help, most people suspect it came from
the group.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Boles, a large woman in a housecoat, would not let a
reporter talk to her son, who quit school a few months ago and was,
she said, sleeping upstairs in the small house near noon on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just kids,'' she said, pointing out that her son plays
the cello, while his friend, Morris, plays the violin. ``All of
them are in shock. They're all destroyed; I don't know, they're
never going to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the little ones, even this one's affected, he senses our
moods,'' she said, bouncing her 5-month-old grandson Seth, whose
mother also attended Columbine, on her lap. ``His mom sat here with
us the other day. She said, `We're going to teach our kids
better.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
