<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-705&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS LEADERS MEET, NATO CAMPAIGN ENTERS SECOND MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO began its second month of bombing against
Yugoslavia on Saturday, ordering a new flurry of strikes against
army barracks and industrial sites, disrupting electricity and
water supplies and again knocking state television briefly off the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting here to commemorate the alliance's 50th anniversary,
NATO's leaders have vowed to sharpen pressure on Yugoslavia's
president, Slobodan Milosevic. On Friday, they agreed to impose an
oil embargo enforced by NATO warships plying the Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Although details of that blockade must still be worked out by
NATO's military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, the Pentagon said
allied warships would search tankers suspected of carrying oil to
Yugoslavia and divert them if necessary. A Pentagon official said
Saturday that the allied ships would fire on those that defied the
blockade, first as a warning and then to disable, if not sink,
violators.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's latest step brought a new denunciation from Russia, which
has strongly opposed the raids on Yugoslavia. Russian officials
vowed Saturday to continue shipping oil to Yugoslavia's ports on
the Adriatic coast, Bar and Kotor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blockade is bad,'' Russia's special envoy to Yugoslavia,
Viktor Chernomyrdin, said Saturday in Moscow. ``The problem in
Kosovo can neither be solved by bombing nor by a blockade.''
</P>
<P>
   On the 32nd day of its air campaign against Yugoslavia, however,
NATO showed no signs of easing its raids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to intensify the air operations,'' NATO's
spokesman, Jamie Shea, said Saturday morning. He said NATO forces
carried out ``significant strikes'' despite ``some very bad
weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The second day of NATO's summit meeting shifted to a discussion
of the alliance's long-range strategies, including how NATO can use
its collective resources to slow the proliferation of nuclear,
biological and chemical weapons. But the air war in the Balkans
loomed over the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In opening remarks Saturday morning, President Clinton urged his
colleagues to remember the three American soldiers who were
captured near the Kosovo-Macedonian border on March 31 and remain
prisoners of war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The International Committee of the Red Cross announced Saturday
that its director, Cornelio Sommaruga, would meet with Milosevic in
Belgrade on Monday to discuss the fate of the three Americans and
the plight of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Clinton attacked Yugoslavia's refusal to allow
the Red Cross to visit the prisoners, as explicitly required by the
Geneva Convention of 1949, despite Milosevic's pledge in a
television interview last week. The Red Cross' spokeswoman in
Geneva, Amanda Williamson, said, ``We will be reminding the
Yugoslav authorities of their responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Although cloudy weather limited NATO's air campaign, allied
missiles and aircraft carried out attacks overnight in Yugoslavia's
second- and third-largest cities after Belgrade, Novi Sad and Nis.
</P>
<P>
   The official Yugoslav news agency, Tanjug, reported a
particularly intense barrage of 26 missiles during a half-hour in
Nis. The agency said the railway, water mains, an office building
and the Nis machine industry complex, another of the industrial
sites NATO has been attacking with greater ferocity, had all been
hit.
</P>
<P>
   The state television network, whose studios in Belgrade were
struck early on Friday morning, went off the air again early
Saturday and did not resume for five hours. There was no immediate
explanation for the disruption, but NATO forces hit a number of
television transmitters overnight. And officials have vowed to
knock the television off the air permanently.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials said the strikes in Nis focused on
the airfield and the barracks of Yugoslavia's Third Army, the force
leading the offensive against Albanians in Kosovo. The officials
said allied forces also struck the refinery in Novi Sad, which has
been hit before, and an oil-storage facility, as well as still more
radar sites and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   In London, the deputy chief of the Defense Staff, Air Marshal
John Day, reported strikes on radio relay towers and on electrical
power transformers ``which serve military facilities.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the bombings continue, they are starting to take a toll on
Yugoslavia's civilian society. The strikes on electrical grids have
caused outages. Water pressure has become erratic in some cities.
In many cases, water mains are carried on the bridges that NATO has
been systematically knocking down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an aspect of civilian inconvenience,'' Shea, the NATO
spokesman, said Saturday. ``I acknowledge that, but it is not our
intention to render the life of Serbs any more difficult than it
already is.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's fuel production and storage have been a focus of
NATO's attacks. Despite the damage inflicted to the country's
refineries and depots, however, Yugoslavia has still received
shipments through its ports. Some NATO commanders have argued for
the destruction of the port oil facilities, but some NATO countries
are wary about significant strikes in the Yugoslav federation's
smaller republic, Montenegro, whose government is seen as less
hostile to the West.
</P>
<P>
   France had objected to a naval blockade, but in a meeting of
NATO's defense ministers on Friday, it joined the other allies in
agreeing to a blockade of those shipments. Several countries agreed
to provide ships, though the size of the armada and the range of
its patrols must still be worked out by Clark's staff in Brussels,
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   It could take several days before the blockade begins.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said it was vital to cut off the oil to Milosevic's
military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without oil, the Yugoslav military machine will come to a
halt,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
