</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-MEDIA-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLETON: A SMALL TOWN PROPELLED TO WORLD STAGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Neb., N.Y., Okla.)   (ART ADV: Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By MINDY SINK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The scenes of children fleeing Columbine High
School here on Tuesday afternoon are now seared into the memories
of people around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But while those images have kept people tuned in to their
television sets _ providing an unexpected increase in ratings of
some news programs _ the equipment and people needed to provide the
images have turned a corner of this town into an overnight
international media village.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're from San Diego, do you suppose they drove here?'' said
a Littleton resident, Inez Schaffer, looking at the cluster of
satellite television trucks and blue and white interview tents.
``I've seen them from Alberta and from Nebraska. There's one from
Oklahoma City. I can't believe they could get here that fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Schaffer stood with her daughter, Barbara, looking with
amazement as hundreds of reporters slogged through mud and grass on
a corner of Clement Park, just within sight of the school. ``I'm
shocked,'' said Barbara Schaffer. ``I thought it was in our
backyard, but it's global.''
</P>
<P>
   To get to a tent covering a makeshift memorial where mourners
had left flowers, stuffed animals and condolences, teary-eyed
students had to step over tangles of cables that provided the power
for television camera lights, and make their way past reporters,
some from overseas, looking for accounts of the shootings or tales
of personal sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victims wouldn't want their friends and families hassled
like this,'' said Willow McMurray, a 17-year-old student from
Columbine who had come to lay flowers on the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   While some people recoiled from the media onslaught, others
sought it out. ``The Montel Williams Show'' flew eight Columbine
High School students and six parents to New York on Wednesday.
``They wanted a good and safe place to express their grief,''
Williams said shortly after taping the show, which was broadcast on
Friday. ``The town is inundated with the media right now. Instead
of flying me out there to become part of the rest of the media, the
children came here.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, talking to the media was even a relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good to talk to you guys,'' Kevin Koeniger, a
17-year-old senior told one reporter. Koeniger, who had been
interviewed by Dan Rather on CBS News, added that he wanted
everyone to know what had happened at his school, and that it
helped him to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   Koeniger's friend Beth Bradshaw, also 17, said she had done
interviews with the Fox Network and ``Good Morning America'' on
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   And others found themselves a part of the coverage as well as
the audience. ``Every night we go home and watch it on the news,''
said Teri Haney, whose daughter is a senior at the school. ``It's
helping us heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those living the story said they found themselves drawn to
watching it on television. ``I am glued to the TV coverage,'' said
the Rev. Bill Oudemolen during a memorial service on Friday for
John Tomlin, a 16-year-old sophomore who was killed. ``All of our
hearts and minds are drawn to it because we can't escape it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Similar interest by viewers around the nation was reflected in
the ratings this week. Two networks devoted their newsmagazine
programs to the Littleton killings on Wednesday night and scored
some of their highest ratings of the television season.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday at 9 p.m., ``Dateline'' put on a special hourlong
broadcast on the killings in Colorado and scored a 13.2 rating, the
best rating for an hour of ``Dateline'' this season and the highest
ratings NBC has scored on Wednesday at 9 p.m. all season.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m., ABC's newsmagazine ``20/20'' did almost as well,
hitting a 12.4 rating. That was the highest for that program on
Wednesday night this year, except for Barbara Walters' interview
with Monica Lewinsky. (Each rating point represents 994,000 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   CBS, meanwhile, was squeezed both by the other two newsmagazines
and its own plans for a special edition of ``60 Minutes II.'' A
hidden camera report on abuses in a mental hospital had made news
of its own when the hospital involved, Charter Behavioral Health
Systems, sought a restraining order to prevent CBS from
broadcasting the report. CBS blocked the effort in court.
</P>
<P>
   Had the report not been so long-planned and the legal issue not
been deemed so important, CBS would surely have put off the
hospital report for a week and devoted ``60 Minutes II'' to the
Littleton incident, said Jeff Fager, the program's executive
producer.
</P>
<P>
   The competition with the news from Colorado on NBC resulted in
the lowest rating for ``60 Minutes II.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
