<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-24-HOURS-ART-NYT     04-24 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-24-HOURS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY UNFOLDS, IN WASHINGTON AND THE BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's anniversary pageant is playing on two
stages, as political theater and in the theater of war, and its
powerful rhetoric clashes with the forces of battle in Belgrade and
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was alone in his residence Thursday night
shortly after 8 p.m., reviewing his summit speeches, work left
undone in a hectic week. At that moment, the state television
station in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, exploded in flames, wrecked by
NATO's missiles.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 a.m. Friday, black limousines bearing prime ministers
tore through downtown Washington toward the White House, and green
tractors hauling refugees groaned toward a mosque in the Macedonian
border town of Lipkovo. Among the exiles was an old man named Rifat
Bajrami.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs have made me live like an animal,'' he said. ``For
what? What harm have I brought to them? A man spends his entire
life building a home for himself. Then his life is destroyed by
irrational hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, rescue workers searched the rubble of the ruined
television station for survivors as Clinton took to the world's
airwaves, opening the summit meeting in Washington at 9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic's forces burn and loot homes and murder innocent
people,'' he said. ``Our forces deliver food and shelter and hope
to the displaced. Mr. Milosevic fans the flames of anger between
nations and peoples.'' The Serbian leader, he said, ``knows only
one way to achieve his aims _ through force.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke, Branko Novakovic, a retired Yugoslav diplomat
with pleasant memories of his nine years in Washington, looked out
his seventh-floor apartment window in Belgrade at the ruins of the
former Communist Party headquarters, hit by NATO on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Novakovic, who is 78, awoke Friday morning after a fitful night
punctuated by explosions, turned on his radio, and heard of the
television station's destruction _ a dozen dead, many missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very bad news,'' he said over a clear telephone line. ``This
has been bombed, that has been bombed. Many people are living in
shelters, under very hard conditions, and they are very distressed,
psychologically in a poor condition. They don't know what to expect
the next day. They live in fear. Some people cannot bear it. The
bombing goes on, and they don't understand why.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not guilty,'' he added. ``They did not expect this
from the countries they considered friends. They used to like these
countries and now they are beginning to hate them.''
</P>
<P>
   The words of Clinton's opening speech were read to him.
``Whatever he thinks and whoever they blame, this is not the right
way to do it,'' Novakovic said. ``We don't have any idea what the
situation is down there in Kosovo. But to keep the whole population
under siege for so long, this is horrible. It is not human.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 1 p.m. in Washington, NATO's 19 leaders began
speaking in turn, some at length. The shortest speech by far was
from Costas Simitis, the prime minister of Greece, a nation less
than enthusiastic about NATO's air war. It was a kind of parable,
and this was it in its entirety:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, 50 years ago, in 1949, the government
troops entered a Greek village and killed two young people. Asked
why, they answered: They were Bulgarian communists. Two days later,
the rebels came and they killed also two young people. Asked why,
they said: They were American fascists. NATO was and should be an
effort to put an end to such practices and such mentalities. NATO
should be an effort to secure cooperation, peace and prosperity. I
think it's a great aim and we must work for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton quoted a 1949 speech by Dean Acheson, the secretary of
state who was present at the creation of NATO and who hoped it
would ``free the minds of men in many nations from a haunting sense
of insecurity and enable them to work and plan with confidence in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   By 3 p.m., the leaders had finished speaking, and the exiles
from Malisevo, a village of 800 homes outside Gnjilane in Kosovo,
were bedding down on blankets laid over newly spread crushed stone
in a cleared garbage dump. They had just arrived at a refugee camp
in Neprosteno, Macedonia, and they told their stories to a
researcher for Human Rights Watch, Ben Ward.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian paramilitary squads had come to the village. They
stole everything they could and separated the old from the young.
The young were told to lie face down with hands behind heads. The
masked men pulled out a list of peoples' names and told their
captives to inform or die. Two men, ages 18 and 20, were shot.
Another man, age 34, was ordered to bury them with his bare hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that came through strongly was the absolute terror
people felt,'' Ward said by telephone from Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   It was 4:15 p.m. Washington time when air-raid sirens pierced
the night in Belgrade. A few minutes later, a bolt of lightning
flashed and an enormous thunderclap broke over Washington, setting
off electronic security alarms in the streets near the White House,
a neighborhood on high alert against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:40 p.m., the national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said
the consensus of NATO's leaders was to attack ``more, not less;
stronger, not weaker.'' The alliance would step up its attack on
the political, military and economic architecture of Milosevic's
power by aiming more bombs and missiles at Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade at that hour, Gordana Ristic, 33, was preparing to
spend another night in the basement-cum-bomb shelter of her
apartment building, a mile from the heart of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really horrible night last night,'' she said by
telephone. ``There were explosions every few minutes after 2 a.m.
This morning I woke up in a totally strange situation. I went to my
job, marketing and public relations, in the center of Belgrade, and
when I came in I looked around to see if everything was in its
right place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought: `Maybe this is my last day. Tomorrow things will
not be there. My plants. My computer.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I really love Belgrade,'' added Ms. Ristic, no fan of
Milosevic, but of late a Serbian nationalist. ``I'm sorry that
leaders in your country are not willing to read history. You
destroy what is material in this country. Buildings. Bridges. But
never people.''
</P>
<P>
   A reporter read her some of Clinton's speeches at the summit
meeting. She sounded torn between anger and tears. ``This is the
bottom to which civilization, in which I believed, has gone,'' she
said. ``Clinton is playing a role, singing a song in an opera. It
kills me.''
</P>
<P>
   As she slept, NATO's leaders dined on soft-shell crabs and
spring lamb in the East Room of the White House. Dessert was a
little chocolate globe. Jessye Norman sang arias after dinner. And
as the last limousine left, near midnight, Saturday morning's
all-clear sounded in Belgrade, dawn came up over the Balkans, and
rivulets of people rose in the mountains and began to flow down
toward the mosque in Lipkovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
