<HEADLINE>
AT NATO SUMMIT, CORPORATE SPONSORS PURSUE BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (lb) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the leaders of NATO, meeting here, debate the
next steps in the Balkan war, the leaders of District Cablevision
are hoping their participation in the alliance's 50th-anniversary
summit meeting will bring them more business from Washington's big
convention hotels.
</P>
<P>
   District Cablevision, the cable-television franchise for the
District of Columbia, is among 41 companies that have paid from
$25,000 to $250,000 in cash, goods or services to become an
official sponsor of the NATO summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them signed up many months ago, long before anyone knew
that the summit meeting would be a war council rather than a
celebration. Yet none seems bashful or apologetic about using the
gathering to pursue their commercial interests _ and several firms
said through spokesmen that they actively wanted to show their
support for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Altruism is scarcely the only motivation, so it is no
coincidence that most of the highest-paying corporate sponsors are
large U.S. companies with important business interests in Europe _
like Boeing, TRW and United Technologies. They donated $250,000
each. Intelsat, Northrop Grumman and Raytheon donated $50,000 to
$100,000 each toward the total summit-meeting cost estimated at $24
million _ one-third of it met by corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those companies are defense contractors who make the
weapons being used against Yugoslavia. Boeing and Raytheon produce
the cruise missiles that have devastated Belgrade; Raytheon also
makes HARM anti-radar missiles, while Boeing makes the Apache
helicopter. Northrup Grumman is one of the leading producers of jet
fighters and other warplanes. Like other defense contractors, it
does business not just with the Pentagon but with most of the
defense ministries of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsors earn the right to send representatives to
receptions and parties. Along with heads of state, most NATO
countries are also sending trade representatives. And depending on
the size of their donations, some corporate leaders have also been
awarded honorary titles.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Notebaert, chairman of Ameritech, the regional Bell
telephone company based in Chicago, is vice chairman of the host
committee board of directors. The host committee is managing
sponsorship of the summit meeting. Ameritech now controls
Tele-Denmark, the Danish phone company.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the largest foreign investor in European
telecommunications,'' he said in a statement, ``Ameritech is proud
to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   With its $250,000 donation, Lucent Technologies was also named
to the host committee's ``board of directors.'' On Thursday, Lucent
reported a 33 percent increase in quarterly revenues _ helped
greatly, the company said, by strong overseas sales.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are providing services. Daimler-Chrysler is
providing Mercedes limousines and Jeeps; Motorola, cell phones;
Microsoft, software that is running on the computers in NATO
offices.
</P>
<P>
   In every conference and reception site, delegates and visitors
see bouquets of flowers, donated by USA Floral Services, a
worldwide flower wholesaler, and worth $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flowers are an instrument of peace,'' said Christina Vaughn,
an executive with USA Floral. ``That is our contribution to the
summit. You know, if two or three of them negotiate in front of a
vase of white flowers, maybe it will help.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``the most important thing, the No. 1 goal of our company,''
she finally confessed, ``is to increase the per capita spending on
flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelman Public Relations Worldwide donated $50,000, and its
company spokeswoman, Dana Vickers Shelley, said, ``We want to show
our support for the federal government, our support for the global
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   But Edelman _ with offices in Brussels, London, Paris, Madrid,
Milan, Dublin, Frankfurt and Hamburg, among 34 locations worldwide
_ is also providing public-relations services for the summit
meeting, and Ms. Shelley is serving as a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we have copiers that work, phones that work _
that's because of the sponsors,'' Ms. Shelley said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Being a corporate sponsor is not like sponsoring the Olympics,
or the NCAA basketball championship. The flower arrangements, for
example, are not labeled with the floral equivalent of the Nike
logo. But notices of the sponsors are not subtle.
</P>
<P>
   There is little mystery behind Coca-Cola's interest in
sponsoring the summit meeting, or Honeywell's. Both have
significant business in Europe. But what about Potomac Electric
Power Co., the Washington area's electric company, or District
Cablevision?
</P>
<P>
   Jean Davis, a spokeswoman for the cable company, said District
Cablevision agreed to run cable to 12 local hotels in recent days
so delegates staying there could follow the summit meeting on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do our part to make the city look good,'' Ms. Davis
said. At the same time, she continued, ``We are hoping that the
hotel operators will see the benefits of our service and decide
they want to keep it after the summit is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
