u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      04-24 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMED FORCE IS ACCEPTABLE TO BELGRADE, RUSSIAN INSISTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's special envoy to the Balkan conflict tried
again Saturday to edge the two sides in the war closer to a
cease-fire and a compromise, insisting _ despite earlier Yugoslav
denials _ that Yugoslavia would accept an international military
force in Kosovo as part of a broader peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's Foreign Ministry had said only hours earlier that
the nation would permit only an unarmed U.N. force to supervise a
peace accord, something NATO leaders have unequivocally rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The special Russian envoy, former Prime Minister Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin, met with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for
much of Thursday trying unsuccessfully to work out terms of a
cease-fire. He had said earlier that Milosevic would also accept
``wide autonomy'' for the Kosovo region in return for a NATO
cease-fire and the resumption of peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic had agreed to autonomy, a reduction of Serbian forces
in Kosovo and an outside force to supervise a Kosovo peace during
failed negotiations earlier this year. It was unclear how much
Chernomyrdin's latest proposal advanced that position, if it did at
all, but the offer nevertheless represented more than Milosevic had
been willing to discuss since the bombing began in March.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after a political party conference in Moscow,
Chernomyrdin said it was time for Western leaders to offer some
compromise in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia will convince the two sides to come to a peaceful
compromise,'' he said. ``Yugoslavia has already made a compromise.
Now I shall talk with NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders have set down five inviolable conditions for a
peace agreement, including total withdrawal of Serbian troops from
Kosovo, autonomy for the region and an armed international presence
to patrol the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's statement came against a backdrop of growing
tensions between Russia and the Western alliance over the
Yugoslavia bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday Foreign Minister Igor S. Ivanov responded to NATO's
decision to put an oil embargo in place against Yugoslavia by
stating that Russia would continue to ship oil there ``in keeping
with our international commitments.'' Ivanov spoke in Cairo, where
he was meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. Russia is one
of Yugoslavia's largest suppliers of oil.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have said they would inspect ships on the high
seas for oil products, but they have neither ruled in or out the
use of military force to stop vessels from making deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   In the central Russian city of Ekaterinburg Saturday, a bomb
exploded near the building that houses the U.S. and British
consulates, blowing out windows and causing minor damage but no
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Russian security police said they believed the explosion had no
connection with the NATO campaign, which has openly angered many
Russians. Witnesses said the bomb appeared to have been left by a
car in a garage near the consulate building.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
