<HEADER>
A1670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMINICAN-POLITICS-AR     04-24 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-POLITICS-ART-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FORMER PRESIDENT, 92, IS STILL A STRONGMAN IN DOMINICAN
POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ In a dusty neighborhood of
wooden barracks here that house 1,600 families left homeless in a
hurricane last year, Yudelki C. Savinon said she appreciated
President Leonel Fernandez's efforts to help the victims, including
starting construction on permanent housing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   But even in her gratitude, she longs for another leader whom she
regards almost as a father, one who is 92, blind and ailing. His
name and face have been plastered all over this capital in posters
and murals that proclaim, ``Balaguer _ one more time, out of
necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He can do anything, as long as he wants it,'' Ms. Savinon, 65,
said of Joaquin Balaguer, the strongman who ruled here for 22 years
and for whom she would vote again.
</P>
<P>
   Balaguer was forced to step down in 1996 by a constitutional
amendment that bars a second consecutive term for a president. But
because the measure also prevents Fernandez from running again,
Balaguer looms as a potential candidate for the elections in May
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The turn of events reassures some and haunts others among the
nearly 8 million Dominicans. But it hardly surprises anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Balaguer loves power more than life itself,'' said
Milagros Ortiz Bosch, a niece of former President Juan Bosch, and
one of the people who are vying for the nomination of the Dominican
Revolutionary Party, one of three major parties. ``He wants a quota
of power.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of Balaguer's candidacy, political analysts
said, underscores how the nation that elected Fernandez in 1996,
expecting sweeping changes, is still in transition from an
authoritarian tradition to modern democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts said Fernandez's administration had had mixed
results. He has presided over high economic growth and made the
Dominican Republic an active player in Caribbean affairs after
decades of isolation. Under his leadership, the nation restored
diplomatic ties with Cuba, began high-level contacts with Haiti and
was host to several top-level international meetings, with another
planned for this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's admired as a young president with a relatively novel
platform, with an understanding of the need to modernize
institutions and with a very accessible personality,'' Jose Oviedo,
a sociologist at Catholic University here, said.
</P>
<P>
   But Fernandez, 45, a lawyer who grew up in New York, is also
criticized for not having done enough about corruption and
patronage, or about poverty, a fundamental problem for 60 percent
of the population.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane that killed more than 200 Dominicans in September
and exposed serious flaws in warning and emergency systems ``showed
how inadequate the state still is in the fulfillment of its
obligations,'' said Anibal de Castro, publisher of Rumbo, a
newsmagazine.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who inherited the problems from Balaguer, was forced
into an alliance with Balaguer and his Social Christian Reformist
Party to win in 1996. That, analysts and American diplomats said,
has tied Fernandez's hands in making certain changes.
</P>
<P>
   He has also joined the Reformists in decidedly undemocratic
maneuvers to wrest control from the Revolutionary Party, which
dominated congressional and municipal elections in May and now has
a majority of legislative seats and mayoralties.
</P>
<P>
   In one highly publicized incident in January, the police
surrounded the headquarters of the Dominican Municipal League,
through which the central government channels money to
municipalities. The police moved to prevent elections for league
leadership during a fight for control of the institution among the
three major parties. Fernandez eventually called for a dialogue
among the parties, and the dispute is now in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a country that is stumbling toward a new way of
government,'' an American diplomat here said. ``It's not pretty.
But it's not particularly violent or repressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The parties have scheduled their nominating conventions for this
year. Advertising is flooding the news media and the streets for
the ``precandidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Balaguer himself has not spoken on whether he wants to be a
candidate. But political veterans say the Reformists do nothing
without his consent. One called the party ``his personal
property.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say Balaguer's chances of returning to the presidency
are remote because his party has less than 10 percent backing in
polls, trailing the Revolutionary Party, with 35, and Fernandez's
Dominican Liberation Party, with 27.
</P>
<P>
   Because no party has a majority, the Reformist push to nominate
Balaguer is a way to maximize its political influence as a swing
force. That makes him more likely to be a kingmaker than a serious
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But Balaguer's readiness to enter the fray hinges on his health,
which was set back this year. He was flown to Houston to treat
circulatory problems and the flu. He returned walking better and
looking more alert, many said, and apparently ready to seek a
seventh presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is extraordinarily lucid,'' Donald Reid Cabral, 76, acting
president of Balaguer's party, said. ``One is surprised at how many
things he does during a day. He writes. He answers letters. He sees
10 to 15 people a day.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Balaguer, who remains a prolific writer and released his latest
book, on ancient Greece, last week, declined an interview request
through Reid Cabral. The former president said he was booked up.
</P>
<P>
   In a television broadcast on Monday about the book, ``Eternal
Greece,'' he looked frail and shrunken, sitting in a high-back
chair, as he listened with semiclosed eyes to speeches in his
praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried in a simple language within the reach of all human
intelligence to make available to Dominican youths a fundamental
aspect of the universal culture, that of eternal Greece,'' Balaguer
said in a raspy whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Many Dominicans smile and roll their eyes when Balaguer is
mentioned, saying that nothing about the long-serving former
president surprises them. But some stressed that even when the
country seems to take a step backward, it is going inevitably
forward toward democracy, as shown by the two elections since
Balaguer ruled politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is marching slowly but profoundly toward
solidifying its democracy,'' said de Castro, the publisher. ``In
the next years, we'll see a strengthening of institutions, an
understanding of how the separation of powers works, and we'll have
more accountable gs, no matter who wins.''
</P>
</TEXT>
