<SLUG> BC-PARADE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite bad press, `Parade' on march
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Atlanta-bred playwright Alfred Uhry, the parade
has not passed by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parade,'' his controversial musical about the 1915 Atlanta
lynching of murder suspect Leo Frank, drew sharply mixed reviews
and ran less than three months on Broadway, but Uhry is convinced
``the show will outlive us all.'' Awards may spark interest in
revivals. The Lincoln Center production is the surprising leader
among all Broadway shows, with 13 nominations for the Drama Desk
Awards, announced earlier this week, to be presented May 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parade'' is also a shoo-in for Tony Award nominations (to be
announced May 3) if for no other reason than the scarcity of
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Uhry, whose ``The Last Night of Ballyhoo'' overcame a New York
Times pan to win the 1997 Tony for best play, noted by phone
Wednesday from his New York home, ``The Tony voters almost never
like a show that's closed.'' Yet there is no overwhelming favorite
for 1999's best musical. ``Fosse'' is a hit, but some observers
question whether an anthology of old material shouldn't be
classified as a revival. Judging by reviews of its Houston tryout,
``The Civil War'' is a long shot to garner good notices.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, revivals of ``Parade'' are under consideration at
regional theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The Prince Music Theatre in Philadelphia is close to a decision
on whether to mount ``Parade'' in its 1999-2000 season, said
artistic director Marjorie Samoff. Also, Chris Manos, producer of
Theater of the Stars, the summer musical series based at the Fox
Theatre, is considering ``Parade'' for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a serious piece, and I wouldn't make a penny on it,''
Manos said, ``but it has great qualities and deserves to be seen in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Uhry, though still smarting from the ``bum rap'' the musical
received (meaning, mainly, its pan in the Times), says, ``I never
had a doubt the show would survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Driving Miss Daisy'' author is delighted by the irony of
Monday's release date of the ``Parade'' cast album (music and
lyrics by Jason Robert Brown). April 26 is Confederate Memorial
Day, the day Mary Phagan was murdered by an unknown assailant while
a parade (hence the title of the musical) moved through the streets
of downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
