<HEADER>
A1680 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-24 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FROM BRADLEY, A REFRESHING WHIFF OF IDEALISM ON RACE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By   BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I looked around to see who might be yawning or nodding off. Bill
Bradley had been speaking for more than half an hour, and there had
been no jokes, no glorious turns of phrase, no splendidly worded
calls to action. In fact, the former senator who is now running for
the Democratic nomination for president had a tendency to botch
this line or that, and then go back and dutifully say it correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King he's not.
</P>
<P>
   But the young men and women in the Wollman Lounge at Cooper
Union were paying close attention, and their body language was
interesting. Bradley was talking about race relations, a topic that
is talked about incessantly but still makes most people
uncomfortable. Yet as he spoke last Tuesday afternoon the people in
the audience were focused intently on his every utterance, with
some of them leaning forward in their seats, as if straining to
hear at least one clear and intelligent voice in the midst of a
maddening din.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's approach to race relations is an almost irresistible
target for cynics. He did not tell his audience that Americans can
do better, but rather that we can be better.
</P>
<P>
   He said the road that lies ahead ``for those of us who want
better racial understanding'' stretches far beyond the struggles of
the civil rights movement, or the continuing fight over affirmative
action and equal treatment in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our task is more difficult,'' he said, ``and more subtle _ but
if we're successful, more long-lasting. It is to vanquish racial
discord from our hearts and spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   As you watch Bradley earnestly delivering his speech you come to
realize he actually believes this is possible. Maybe he knows
something. Maybe it's not so strange for someone who has been a
champion athlete and a U.S. senator (and who thinks he can be
president) to aim incredibly high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care about getting beyond the stupidity of racial division
to a time when we can accept each other for who we are,'' he said.
For whatever reasons, probably the quiet sincerity of Bradley's
delivery and the trusting and attentive attitude of his young
audience, the words did not sound platitudinous.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it would take an almost unimaginable effort to
hoist ourselves to the level of social and moral excellence
envisioned by Bradley did not seem to concern him. ``For something
so palpably right to be so demonstrably hard to accomplish only
strengthens my determination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's speech would have gotten more media attention if it
had not been delivered on the same day that the massacre occurred
at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. But the speech was not
a one-time thing. Bradley has made his commitment to ``a deeper
racial unity'' a cornerstone of his campaign and insists it will be
a major focus of his administration if he is elected President.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ronald Reagan was president, everyone knew that if you
wanted to please the boss you talked about cutting taxes,
increasing military spending and fighting Communism,'' he said.
``If I'm president, I want one thing to be known: If you want to
please the boss, one of the things you'd better show is how your
department or agency has furthered tolerance and racial
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   This is risky stuff. The economy and whatever is happening in
Kosovo next year will be far higher on the list of most voters'
concerns than a quest for deeper racial unity. I asked Bradley in
an interview why he had decided to make race relations such an
important part of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because this is one of my most deeply held beliefs,'' he said.
``And it's important, I think, when you run for president that you
share the deepest part of yourself with the people so they
understand who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll find out soon enough whether a heartfelt commitment to
racial unity is a plus or a minus in a national campaign.
Meanwhile, it's refreshing to have a presidential candidate engage
the subject in a sustained and unequivocal way.
</P>
<P>
   Commentators have had a field day with politicians who believe
in little or nothing and are shaped largely by the polls. Now comes
Bill Bradley with, gasp, a whiff of the idealist about him. He
thinks the public is ready for honest leadership on some of the
weightier issues of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
