<HEADER>
A1682 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRS-SKYBOX25-COX     04-24 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-SKYBOX25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS decision puts tax deduction for skybox leases in jeopardy
 &HT;    By Angela Shah
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Major Texas universities are worried they could
lose one of their best selling points in leasing stadium skyboxes,
potentially costing them millions in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Athletics directors at Texas schools are watching a dispute
between an Iowa State booster and the Internal Revenue Service over
donors' ability to take a tax deduction on part of the cost of
leasing skyboxes.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether the IRS should treat gifts to athletic
departments, for which donors receive the use of luxury suite
seating, the same way it treats gifts for special game tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Groff, Texas A&AMP;M University's athletic director, said many
schools are ``totally dependent'' on the deduction. ``If we lose
that ability for people to write that off, it would be a major loss
to athletics,'' he said. ``It would wipe us out, I can tell you
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year _ if they aren't able to deduct them _ we wouldn't
be able to sell them for half the price,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas officials say revoking donors' ability to
take tax deductions on lease prices could jeopardize almost
one-fourth of UT athletics' $30 million annual operating budget.
UT, which has built 64 skyboxes in the past two years, raises about
$7 million a year through premium seating.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute revolves around a 1986 revision of U.S. tax laws
that allowed for the cost of tickets to athletic events to be
deducted under the ``80-20'' rule. The rule said athletic tickets
are not tax deductible. But because some schools were offering
tickets only with minimum donations, the IRS allowed donors to
deduct 80 percent of the donation.
</P>
<P>
   Athletics officials nationwide have applied that rule to skybox
leases for years.
</P>
<P>
   In the Iowa State dispute, booster Rod French paid $200,000 in
1996 for a 10-year lease on a stadium suite. Iowa State determined
the market value of the suite and parking spaces to be $20,520, and
French's corporation took a deduction on 80 percent of the
remaining $179,480. The IRS denied the deduction. French's appeal
is pending with the IRS's national office in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Heidenreich, with the IRS's regional office in Dallas,
said there is no language allowing deductions on skybox packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your purpose is to help the school, you give the money with
no strings attached,'' Heidenreich said.
</P>
<P>
   Athletics officials at UT, Texas A&AMP;M and Texas Tech University
said they advise donors who buy skybox leases to consult an
attorney when taking any deductions. However, brochures for all
three schools advertise the tax deduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax deductions are a very attractive feature which does
attract donors,'' said Red McCombs, a San Antonio businessman and
UT alumnus who leases a skybox on Royal-Memorial Stadium's west
side. ``It would very definitely have a very serious effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Heidenreich would not comment directly on the Iowa State case
but said other university donors could find themselves in the same
situation. He said he is unaware whether the IRS is looking at
skybox leases at Texas schools.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
