u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS     04-24 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID THE FUNERALS, WORDS FROM BEYOND THE GRAVE  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Still reeling from the worst school shooting
in national memory, this community embarked Saturday on a numbing
weekend of funerals for some of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   With emotions still raw, a girl from the loose group of students
known as the trench coat mafia stood at the first memorial service
and apologized before 900 mourners for the actions of the suspects,
also members of the Columbine High School clique.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no sign that they would do this,'' said the girl,
Nicole Makham, of the suspects, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.
Addressing a church filled with the family and friends of John
Tomlin Jr., one of those slain, she said on Friday, ``We would just
like to say that we're sorry for what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop of loss, as many as 150 investigators
worked on the case, with much of their effort concentrated on
trying to discover whether anyone helped the suspects take about 30
bombs into the school.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators quoted in The Denver Post on Saturday speculated
that some bombs may have been taken into the school last Saturday,
when the school was open for a party after the prom.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department, Steve
Davis, said Saturday morning that the authorities had received an
e-mail after the shooting containing what may be a suicide message
from Harris. Noting that the e-mail arrived either Thursday or
Friday, Davis said someone else may have sent Harris' note or it
may be a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the possibility exists that it is a hoax,'' he said.
``We want to verify its authenticity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rocky Mountain News on Saturday published the contents of
what it said was a note left by Harris on Monday, the day before
the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In the note, Harris shifted all responsibility from himself to
adults in his world. ``I may have taken their lives and my own _
but it was your doing,'' the note reads.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said Saturday he did not know if the message published by
the newspaper was the same as that in the e-mail received by the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen people, including a teacher and the two suspects, died
in the shooting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a representative of the sheriff's office had said
that there were other people who seemed to have had ``limited
participation, knowledge'' related to the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said Saturday that the authorities had not ruled out
another gunman, or any suspects. But, he added, ``We still haven't
named anyone else as a suspect, there have not been any arrests or
charges filed against anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation continues, a picture emerges of a suburban
world where adults had superficial understandings of the lives of
the two teen-age suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Only two months ago, the two graduated from a yearlong
court-ordered juvenile diversion program in Jefferson County. After
completing the program and anger management classes, both had their
records wiped clean. They had pleaded guilty to breaking into a car
last year and stealing electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Frank DeAngelis, the principal of the 1,800-student high school,
said on Friday that no teacher had alerted him to behavior problems
in the suspects, both seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never heard of the trench coat mafia until Tuesday,''
the principal said, although the group had a small photo in the
1998 yearbook. In his first public comments since the massacre,
DeAngelis said that school records indicated the two young men had
never been ``suspended or expelled or in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, dozens of students have been suspended and
arrested for making what were regarded as threats to carry out
copycat attacks. In big cities, small towns and suburbs like this
one, schools have been evacuated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
