<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-PROP-187-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANT MEASURE SPLITS CALIFORNIA DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last fall, when Cruz Bustamante, a soft-spoken
assemblyman from California's farm-rich Central Valley, was
campaigning to become the first Hispanic official elected statewide
in more than a century, he ran a series of television commercials
that brought new meaning to the phrase ``low-key.'' In them,
Bustamante talked quietly of parents and children and ended by
saying, ``I'd appreciate your consideration for lieutenant
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week in Sacramento, Bustamante made a big noise by
announcing that he not only opposed the efforts of his fellow
Democrat, Gov. Gray Davis, to seek federal court mediation in a
lawsuit over Proposition 187 _ the ballot measure to curtail social
services for illegal immigrants _ but would also file a
friend-of-the-court brief aimed at blocking the governor's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   That news landed with a thud in the Capitol's corridors, opening
to public view tensions that had been simmering quietly for weeks.
And it exposed Davis to precisely the sort of criticism, from an
influential member of the state's growing Hispanic political
establishment, that he had hoped to avoid by seeking mediation in
the legal fight over Proposition 187.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was passed by nearly 60 percent of voters in 1994,
but has been tied up in court ever since, and last year a federal
judge ruled most of it unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels uncomfortable to be in this position with a
Democratic governor,'' Bustamante said in a telephone interview on
Friday. ``I respect the governor tremendously and probably will be
able to work with him on the other 99 issues that we agree on. But
this is something that is core to me. It's an issue of principle
and of conscience, and I can't back off.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most other Hispanic officials here, Bustamante had urged
Davis to drop the state's appeal of a lawsuit filed by opponents of
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis, who campaigned last year for an end to divisive
``wedge-issue'' politics and opposed Proposition 187 personally,
argued that the California Constitution compelled him to seek an
appellate court ruling _ a contention disputed by some legal
experts _ and sought mediation as an alternative to filing an
outright appeal with the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is no stranger to Sacramento infighting, or the
indignities of being No. 2. He served four years as lieutenant
governor under Pete Wilson, his predecessor, a Republican who went
so far as to try to move Davis' offices out of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   So Davis' political advisers regarded Bustamante's declaration
of independence as a virtual declaration of war, and by week's end
some were talking quietly of Bustamante's potential influence with
the governor in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lieutenant governor, for all practical purposes, doesn't
matter,'' one Davis confidant said.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante's advisers counter by complaining that although Davis
eagerly campaigned with Bustamante last year and basked in the glow
of his alliance with the first Hispanic statewide official since
1871, the governor has largely failed to include Bustamante in
important deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, allies of Bustamante say, the governor did not even
grant him a private audience to make his case against appealing the
Prop. 187 lawsuit, instead summoning him to a group meeting just
before the decision was to be announced. Bustamante declined to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely inappropriate to claim that there's going to
be a real partnership and you then take the most fundamental issue
of the last two decades for this constituency and you don't make
him a part of whatever decision-making process you have.''
Bustamante's political consultant, Richie Ross, said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis aides contend that Bustamante promised the governor last
week that he would urge the parties in the case to work to settle
their dispute constructively, only to have his staff announce
publicly that he intended to ask the appeals court to uphold the
lower court ruling.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bustamante, a barber's son who grew up in the farm town of
Dinuba and now lives in Fresno, made political history in 1996 by
becoming the first Hispanic speaker of the state Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   During his less than two years in that job, even some of his
Democratic allies said that he was not a forceful leader in budget
and policy debates with Wilson, but he earned a reputation for
candor. ``I think with Cruz, what you see is what you get,'' said
state Sen. Jim Brulte, an influential Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante insisted that he still wanted to be a ``team player''
with Davis, and said his position was really no different from that
of other Hispanic politicians who have been less vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just happen to be saying what everyone else is thinking,''
he said. ``Sometimes there's a risk in that. There's a risk this
could damage my relationship with the governor. I hope it doesn't.
I am still on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   But allies of Bustamante said Davis warned him last week that if
the dispute continued, the governor would expect Bustamante to step
down from positions to which Davis has appointed him, like the
co-chairmanship of a commission on the states' 21st-century
infrastructure needs.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Davis also said it was unclear whether Bustamante could
even file a court brief, since the governor's request for mediation
means that there is no formal appeal pending.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever retribution they might threaten in private, the
last thing the Davis team wants is a nasty public fight with the
state's top-ranking Hispanic politician. Davis' press secretary,
Mike Bustamante, who is no relation to the lieutenant governor,
went out of his way to sound a conciliatory note.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor feels very comfortable with the fact that every
day more people begin to see the wisdom of his decision to proceed
with mediation,'' the press secretary said. ``Being a leader means
sometimes taking a path that isn't the most popular path, but the
best path to take.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
