<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DEPRIVATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE TRAPPED IN KOSOVO DESPERATE FOR FOOD, MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Food and medicine are urgently needed by the
tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians on the run in Kosovo, and by
those still living in towns but barred from shopping in Serbian
stores, said Albanian doctors from Kosovo who arrived in Macedonia
in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jennifer Leaning, a member of the Boston-based group
Physicians for Human Rights, interviewed 18 doctors who recently
arrived in Macedonia, who reported that many of those living in the
rough or in remote mountain hamlets were ``trapped'' by Yugoslav
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar Albanians are still living in the capital, Pristina, and
in the towns of Mitrovica, Prizren and Pec, the doctors from Kosovo
told Dr. Lansing. But they are barred from shopping in Serbian
stores, which are the only ones open, and they are are struggling
to find food.
</P>
<P>
   One doctor, who requested anonymity, arrived last week from
western Kosovo reportedly saying that he had visited 3,000 people
sheltering in the countryside just a few miles outside the town of
Pec. ``Some of the people are living in small homes, but a lot of
them are in the open,'' said Dr. Leaning.
</P>
<P>
   The same doctor reportedly estimated that 15,000 people were
living in the Rugova Canyon, a long river valley west of Pec.
Doctors with them ``have no gauze, no antibiotics, no pain
medicine, no syringes, no intravenous fusions, no needles. They
cannot do anything with no medicine,'' Dr. Leaning said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do not die of starvation. But when weakened by
malnutrition, they die of dehydration, exposure or infection,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many ethnic Albanians remain inside Kosovo. Dr.
Leaning said the estimates range from 200,000 to 800,000 people,
dispersed across the whole region.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has no immediate plan to conduct airdrops in Kosovo. The
alliance is concerned for the safety of pilots of cargo planes,
which are slow and heavy and would have to fly low to drop food.
Kosovo's mountainous terrain and the uncertainty that the food
would reach Albanians are also drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   American planes, under the U.N. flag, made successful airdrops
during the 1992-95 war in Bosnia. There, however, NATO controlled
the air and could target the enclaves with more certainty that the
drops would reach the Muslims who needed food. In Kosovo, there are
more people to reach, and they are much more scattered.
</P>
<P>
   Backpacking medicines in over mountain trails is considered
impractical and dangerous, since the Yugoslav army has mined a
10-mile stretch along the border of Kosovo to prevent armed
Albanian rebels from infiltrating weapons and supplies, said Luan
Jaha, an ethnic Albanian doctor who recently left Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
