<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES ARE FORCED TO LEAVE THEIR VALUED TRACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ After being given just minutes to make the
heartbreaking choice of what to take with them and what to leave
behind as they were being expelled from their homes in Kosovo,
thousands of refugees here now are being forced to make another
hard decision.
</P>
<P>
   Local Albanian authorities have sent special policemen into the
refugees' tractor camps to order them to leave Kukes, saying there
are too many people now too close to the border with Kosovo.
Albanian officials are also working on an evacuation plan for the
entire city, which is only 10 miles from the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go now. Tomorrow will be too late,'' the policemen shout
through bullhorns as they walk, carrying rifles, through uneven
rows of tractors that, rigged up with wooden frames and plastic
sheeting, have served as homes to many refugees since they arrived
in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Such scenes are terrifyingly similar to refugees' expulsion by
Serbian police in Kosovo over the past month. But while some
followed the orders, others have decided to dig in even deeper
here, vowing not to leave until they are forced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go,'' said Abdullah Haziri, 56, ``the tractor goes with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Most refugees do not want to stay in the mud and chaos of the
camps. But neither do they want to leave behind the tractors, old
and battered though they might be, that represent just about the
only thing of value besides their own lives that they have left.
Many of these refugees are farmers, with no other motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian authorities are transporting the refugees by bus to
other towns within Albania, and are not allowing them to take their
tractors with them. They fear that if one or more of the
slow-moving tractors breaks down, the road _ the only road leading
out of Kukes _ will become clogged, blocking relief supplies from
coming through.
</P>
<P>
   So the refugees must decide what to do with their tractors. Some
pay local Albanians $15 to $500 to store their machines for a
month, hoping they can return by then.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no guarantee that the tractors will still be here
by the time the refugees come back. Criminals have already popped
up at the camps, and even items that are bolted down get stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Some refugees have sold their tractors to local Albanians,
settling for a small percentage of what they are worth.
</P>
<P>
   Other men send their families' women and children on buses to
other cities and towns in the region, and stay behind to guard the
tractors. While they may keep the tractor safe, they run the real
risk of being separated from their families because it is not
always clear where the buses are headed.
</P>
<P>
   The forced clearing of Kukes has upset not only fearful refugees
but the relief agencies here as well. Some have criticized the U.N.
high commissioner for refugees for having allowed the refugees to
settle so close to the border in the first place. Now they say the
United Nations should stand up to the police and insist that they
stop.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials reject the charge. ``In our discussions with the
government we really stressed the point that any form of force must
be avoided,'' said Daniel Enders, head of the U.N. agency's
operation in Kukes. However, Enders said, the refugees cannot be
allowed to settle here either.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Kukes is already overcrowded, with around 100,000
refugees living in the fields or doubled up in crumbling
communist-era apartment buildings. While clean water is not a
problem now, experts say it will be once the weather warms.
</P>
<P>
   There also are security concerns. The separatist Kosovo
Liberation Army recruits and trains in and around the city, and
several Serbian rockets landed just outside the city limits the
week before last. At 10 miles from the border, Kukes is well short
of the 50-mile distance from borders that U.N. regulations require
for refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the policy of the United Nations to expel people.
Once is enough,'' said Jacques Franquin, a spokesman for the U.N.
refugee agency. ``But these people have no choice. They have to
go.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So far, about 3,000 people who arrived on 200 to 300 tractors
have left Kukes, the United Nations said. But as many as 11,000
people remain, and with them about 1,200 tractors. Some of these
people have lived outdoors, in soaking rains and unseasonably cold
temperatures that have left many weakened and sick.
</P>
<P>
   But while some have agreed to leave, others are digging in, and
vow not to go until they are absolutely forced to. ``They'll have
to physically force me out,'' said Ymer Rahmani, 43, a miner from
the Mitrovica area in northern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the crisis, there have been two basic
groups of tractor refugees: those who never unpacked and those who
put down roots immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Rahmani belongs to the latter. On the day he arrived in Kukes on
his 8-year-old tractor, he paid the equivalent of $20 for wood
strips and plastic sheets. With the material, he built a small
tent, about 12 feet long and 8 feet wide. He dug a trench around it
and covered the wagon behind it with a plastic tarp given to him by
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 days since he arrived, he and his extended family _ 15
people altogether _ have established their own domestic
tranquillity. They have set up the old wood-burning stove they
brought from Kosovo, and Rahmani's wife, Zahide, bakes bread in it
every day.
</P>
<P>
   They also use the stove to heat water that they use to wash
themselves and their clothes. With a neighbor, they built an
outhouse from wood strips and burlap.
</P>
<P>
   Rahmani said he might leave if the authorities could tell him
exactly where he was going, and what conditions he would find
there. And, of course, if he could take his tractor along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never leave the tractor,'' he said. ``It's all I have
left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
