<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, April 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A flow of moist air from the western Gulf of Mexico north
through the Plains states will result in an expanding area of damp
conditions. Strong, shifting winds between the ground and 10,000
feet will combine with warm, humid air over parts of western Texas
and Oklahoma to produce potent afternoon thunderstorms which may
spawn a few tornadoes. Farther north over parts of the central
Plains and central Mississippi Valley, frequent showers and a few
imbedded thunderstorms will result in locally heavy rainfall.
Patchy light showers will occur from the western Dakotas to
northeastern Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled and cool weather will cover much of the interior West.
Variable clouds with scattered valley showers and intermittent
mountain snow will be common, especially where moist winds ascend
the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front accompanied by showers will bring an end to the
recent mild weather in the Pacific Northwest. Gusty onshore breezes
will follow the front along the Washington and Oregon coasts.
Farther south, the California and the deserts of the Southwest will
be sunny and mild.
</P>
<P>
   After a cold dawn with widespread suburban and rural frost in
the Northeast, abundant sunshine will boost temperatures to within
a few degrees of seasonal values during the afternoon. Patchy
clouds will accompany the arrival of the milder air in upstate New
York and New England. Farther south, patchy clouds and
thundershowers will surround a wavering front in the Southeastern
states.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Last Frost
</P>
<P>
   The growing season is about to begin in many parts of the
Northeast. From the mid-April to late May most of the Northeast
typically has its last frost of the spring. There can be dramatic
variations in frost dates, however, over very short distances. The
heat generated in cities can account for up to 30 days difference
between the date of the last urban and the last suburban frost.
Nearby bodies of water also will help prevent frost. Moreover,
since cold air is heavier than warm, chill collects in lowlands on
calm spring mornings making valleys more susceptible to frost than
hillsides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
