<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-REFERENDUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN VOTE COULD YIELD MORE POWER FOR PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ For the last month, Venezuela's new
president, Hugo Chavez, has been demanding that Congress be
dissolved and threatening to declare a state of emergency, which
would allow him to rule by decree.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, he also vowed to disband the Supreme Court
after it rebuked him for exceeding his authority. And he has
derided leaders of the main opposition party as ``a nest of dying
venomous vipers.''
</P>
<P>
   Against that contentious political backdrop, Venezuelans will
troop to the polls Sunday to vote on a proposition to convene a
constitutional assembly to write a new charter for this South
American country of 23 million people. If the proposal is approved
as expected, the prospects that Chavez will soon get the expanded
powers he wants will automatically be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez is a 44-year-old cashiered army colonel who led a coup
attempt in 1992 that killed dozens of people. But he has been
calling for a ``peaceful revolution'' ever since he arrived on the
scene as an independent candidate last year.
</P>
<P>
   He envisions a 131-member elected assembly creating a
constitution that will bring ``a true democracy'' to Venezuela,
which in recent years has become the largest single exporter of oil
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Chavez say his purpose in stirring up the recent
turbulence was to insure that his supporters go to the polls
Sunday. At the peak of the confrontation in mid-April, the
president's followers blocked the entrance to the capitol building
for two days, preventing lawmakers from entering or leaving the
building, and shouted insults and imprecations at the legislators.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, an abashed, discredited and weary Congress
approved an ``enabling'' law that grants Chavez fast-track
authority to rule by decree on economic matters for the next six
months. But he has made it clear that he will settle for nothing
less than a complete and permanent overhaul of the structure of the
Venezuelan state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutions in Venezuela have broken into pieces,'' he said
in an interview late last month, ``and it is necessary to rebuild
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we reconstruct the architecture of a political system
that has lost legitimacy and ethical content, whose powers are
worm-eaten and decadent, it will not be possible to carry out an
integrated national project of social, economic, political and
cultural development.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders say, though, that those arguments are a
facade for a more sinister scheme.
</P>
<P>
   They note that Chavez has said he wants any new constitution to
allow him to seek a second consecutive five-year term, something
the current charter prohibits. And they contend that the
president's real objective is to establish a dictatorship under the
cloak of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants us to give him a blank check, to sign everything over
to him,'' said Sen. Alberto Franceschi of the Project Venezuela
Party. ``He wants complete power, as in a banana republic, so that
his followers can go to the constituent assembly and propose a
tropical monarchy with Chavez as emperor.''
</P>
<P>
   In a public letter issued this week, Chavez's predecessor,
Rafael Caldera, said that ``my conscience impedes me from
participating'' in a vote he described as intended to destroy, not
strengthen, the rule of law. He cited as especially dangerous
Chavez's ``insistence on the proposal to eliminate `no immediate
re-election.'''
</P>
<P>
   Protests have also been made about the fairness of the
government's efforts to insure that voters endorse the president's
proposal. Citing equal-time provisions in the electoral code, the
National Electoral Commission last week ordered Chavez's press
office to stop official advertisements and television commercials
urging a yes vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez, who won 57 percent of the vote in December's
presidential election, has a job approval rating of more than 80
percent at the moment, according to recent polls. His calls to
sweep away an inefficient state apparatus seem to have struck a
deep chord among Venezuelans, who feel that the country's vast oil
wealth has been squandered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constitution of 1961 is a straitjacket that needs to be
removed,'' said Jose Cabeza, a bellhop at a hotel here. ``It was
drawn up not to enable the people to express their will, but to
permit a pack of corrupt politicians to line their pockets and
perpetuate themselves in power.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the outcome of the vote Sunday seems barely in
doubt, with even the phrasing of the issues on the ballot intended
to coax a yes response.
</P>
<P>
   Do you want to ``transform the state and create a new juridical
order that permits the effective functioning of a social and
participatory democracy?'' the first of the two referendum
questions says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
