<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AARON DESERVES TO INHERIT DIMAGGIO'S TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years Joe DiMaggio was always introduced at
Yankee Stadium as ``baseball's greatest living player.'' But with
his memory joining those of Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Mickey Mantle
and Miller Huggins Sunday in the Stadium's monument park beyond
left-center field, it's time to identify the heir to that
``greatest living'' label.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams was the first name to come to mind, and he's the
greatest living hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Mays would be many people's choice, and he's the greatest
living center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   But Hank Aaron, now 65, deserves to inherit the title of
baseball's ``greatest living'' player, with the emphasis on player
_ hitter, slugger, fielder, base runner, work ethic, dignity,
leader by example, statesman of the game. The same qualities that
DiMaggio had.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron, of course, also has the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everybody knows he hit the most home runs, 755, but
he also drove in the most runs, 2,297, and scored more runs, 2,174,
than anybody except Ty Cobb. He had more hits, 3,771, than anybody
except Pete Rose and Cobb. He played more games, 3,298, than
anybody except Rose and Carl Yastrzemski.
</P>
<P>
   Until he approached and then surpassed Ruth's record of 714
homers, he did it all without much acclaim. Even after his 715th,
he slipped into relative obscurity again. And now, 25 years after
hitting that 715th homer, he's finally being appreciated again. If
he's bitter, it doesn't show.
</P>
<P>
   ``All good things come to those who wait,'' he was saying the
other day. ``I played in Milwaukee and Atlanta. I had no other
choice but to wait. I have no animosity against anybody. I just had
to wait my time.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in New York to promote his book, ``Home Run'' (Total
Sports, $39.95), which celebrates the 25th anniversary of his
breaking the Babe's record. The profits will go to the Hank Aaron
Chasing the Dream Foundation that has already awarded financial
support to 44 youngsters in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to identify and reward elementary and middle-school
students who were working hard to achieve their dreams,'' Henry's
wife, Billye, said. ``It could be acting lessons, computer classes,
whatever. But to qualify for support, an applicant must also
succeed in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter where Hank Aaron goes, he is asked if he thinks his
record of 755 homers will be broken someday, especially after Mark
McGwire's record 70 homers last year. McGwire started this season
with 457 homers, but he's 35. And realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you can be named the greatest home run hitter is
to beat Hank Aaron's record,'' McGwire is quoted in Aaron's book.
``Hitting 70 home runs is not that record. The greatest ever is
Hank Aaron. He hit 755, didn't he? That is the greatest, and that's
quite a few years down the road for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if McGwire averaged 50 homers for another five seasons, his
total would be 707, still far short of 755.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Aaron thinks Ken Griffey Jr., who started the season
with 350 homers at age 29, has the best chance to threaten 755
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Griffey's still young enough,'' Aaron said. ``If he keeps
doing what he's doing, he's got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a career-threatening injury, Griffey should continue as
a productive slugger for another 10 seasons or more, especially if
the designated hitter remains. And if he were to average 40 homers
for the next 10 years, he would have 750 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Seattle for opening day there,'' Aaron said, ``I
had a long talk with Griffey. I told him the only thing that stands
in his way is if he got hurt or got complacent. You start thinking
you're better than what you are.''
</P>
<P>
   If Griffey did average 40 homers for the next 10 seasons, it
would mean doing what only Aaron did.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do what Hank did, you must be very consistent until late in
your career,'' said Frank Robinson, who hit 586 homers. ``I was
ahead of his pace hitting home runs early in my career. But he hit
a lot of home runs late in his career. That's difficult to do.
You're supposed to be on the decline then.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, when Aaron was 37, he hit 47 homers, his one-season
high. In 1973, when he was 39, he hit 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought anybody would hit 70,'' he said, alluding to
McGwire's record. ``But it couldn't have happened at a better time.
It put baseball back on the front pages. Imagine, 70 home runs.
When I hit my little 40 homers, I thought I was doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   But by hitting those 40 homers, more or less, for so many
seasons, Hank Aaron was doing great, doing what nobody else has
ever done. That's why he's now baseball's greatest living player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN     04-24 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AARON DESERVES TO INHERIT DIMAGGIO'S TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years Joe DiMaggio was always introduced at
Yankee Stadium as ``baseball's greatest living player.'' But with
