<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1728 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POLITICS25-COX     04-24 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLITICS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kosovo reveals GOP intervention-isolation split still exists
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 10 Republican presidential hopefuls agree on
one thing about the fighting in Yugoslavia. They do not like
President Clinton's conduct of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, they accuse the president of ordering air strikes
without a clear idea of U.S. goals and how to achieve them.
</P>
<P>
   But, reflecting an age-old split in the GOP, the candidates
differ over whether U.S. vital interests are at stake and whether
American combat troops should be used in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, they find themselves on both sides of Clinton, with Sen.
John McCain (R-Ariz.) leading the charge for sending in U.S. troops
and commentator Pat Buchanan saying the dispute between Serbs and
ethnic Albanians is none of America's business.
</P>
<P>
   NATO air strikes in Yugoslavia have forced the candidates into
an unexpected debate on foreign policy, an area in which many lack
expertise. ``They have been blindsided by world events,'' said Ross
Baker, a Rutgers University political scientist and expert on
presidential elections. ``Few of them feel terribly comfortable
speaking out on these issues. Politically, it's kind of a
labyrinth.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, McCain has been the most outspoken about using
massive force _ including ground troops _ to compel Serbian troops
to leave Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do what is necessary even if there is significant
risk associated with that, or don't do it,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the leader in campaign fund-raising
and in opinion polls, has absorbed the most criticism for his
stance, which analysts initially called timid. Bush now favors
doing whatever is necessary to win, even if that includes the use
of ground troops. Former Red Cross president Elizabeth Dole also
has moved close to McCain's position, calling for troops to be
pre-positioned in the region so that they could quickly move into
Kosovo if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must win this war and win it absolutely,'' she told an Iowa
audience Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dole is the only candidate to have visited the region since the
fighting began, touring refugee camps in Macedonia last weekend.
Neither Bush nor Dole has officially entered the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Magazine publisher Steve Forbes and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar
Alexander support the bombing campaign, but they oppose sending in
U.S. combat troops.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they would arm the Kosovo Liberation Army, the rebels
who have been fighting the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experts say it would take several months to move NATO forces
into Kosovo,'' Forbes said. ``In that time, we could train and
equip tens of thousands of willing Kosovars to do the job
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Five candidates are opposed to any American military
involvement: conservative activist Gary Bauer, Rep. John Kasich
(R-Ohio), former Vice President Dan Quayle, Sen. Bob Smith (R-N.H.)
and Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich and Quayle have led the way in calling for a negotiated
solution in the Balkans. Kasich doubts that U.S. intervention will
resolve a ``centuries-old civil war.''
</P>
<P>
   The political ramifications of the candidates' stands on Kosovo
are as murky as the military situation itself.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's early, unambiguous statements may have helped him. His
standing has improved in several polls, and in South Carolina, one
lawmaker who had favored Bush told the Los Angeles Times he would
support McCain because of their views on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is not clear that Bush has done himself any irreparable
damage.
</P>
<P>
   In Baker's view, the electorate does not typically reward the
boldest candidates or punish the most cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ross) Perot could get up and be a truth teller and so could
(Democratic presidential candidate Paul) Tsongas to some extent in
'92,'' Baker said. ``But it is hard to say that it really gained
them much except an initial burst of attention. The ultimate prize
has tended to go to the more cautious candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in elections in which foreign policy and war have
dominated, the winning candidate has taken a nuanced position, open
to interpretation, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon had a secret plan for ending the Vietnam war in
1968, a position he said differed from the Johnson administration,
but he did not offer specifics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, Dwight Eisenhower pledged to visit Korea if elected.
Implicit in his promise was that he would work out an end to the
fighting, but Eisenhower provided no details.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also have to reckon with the fact that most
Americans are not yet paying attention, according to a poll
conducted by the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   Only 17 percent of Americans are familiar with McCain's
position, which was the best-known among the candidates, the poll
found.
</P>
<P>
   Past elections and the poll results lead Baker to conclude that
the wiser political course may be caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain, for the boldness of his statement, may be
advocating a position that a year from now may be very much in
disfavor,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Clarity is a good thing, but you can have too much of a good
thing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' Baker said, ``that Walter Mondale was praised for
clarity in saying he would raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
