<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO'S NEXT APPLICANTS PREEN, JOSTLE AND HOPE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Embassy of Bulgaria, five diplomats strong, was
humming with hope.
</P>
<P>
   The second secretary, a world-class linguist and stateswoman,
was dashing about, even making coffee for any visitor who asked.
</P>
<P>
   In similar spirit, Bulgaria's handsomely uniformed military
attache would operate the fax machine when need be this weekend as
the NATO summit meeting took over the city _ a dizzying event for
the warrens of resident diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the iron doors of the Bulgarian Embassy, of course, even
the ambassador, Filip Dimitrov, was not above driving himself
hither and yon. He has been without an embassy driver lately but
hardly at a loss as he campaigns persistently and smartly for
Bulgaria to be in the next wave of NATO inductees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's for sure,'' said Dimitrov, a former prime minister in
Bulgaria's initial flirtation with democratic government nine years
ago and back now as his nation's resident salesman here for its
case to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't _ what's the proper word? _ mess it up ourselves
we'll naturally, soon, in due time, however you call it, be members
of NATO,'' he declared in an interview as he bolted about the city
from airport arrival ceremony to NATO briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to see as many people as you can and try to bring home
the message,'' Dimitrov said of his special pitch for admittance to
the club during the larger NATO anniversary celebration.
</P>
<P>
   For all the sad preoccupation with Kosovo and the NATO bombing
of Yugoslavia, the summit meeting is laced with a certain yearning,
too, on the part of the next wave of applicants for NATO, including
Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   These nations desperately want admission to the alliance as a
priceless step in their climb through post-Soviet democratic
recovery and economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   On the cusp of the summit meeting, a half-dozen competitive
aspirants are vying like long-distance runners dreaming of victory
as they jostle toward the starting line. Prime Ministers Janez
Drnovsek of Slovenia and Mikulas Dzurinda of Slovakia went jogging
together Saturday morning to symbolize their own rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   The competition was ``advanced'' by hired media specialists who,
with some justification, are treating the NATO gathering like the
latest slice of political Americana _ a convention that lacks
balloons but not a horde of back-slapping candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Bulgaria has hired BSMG Worldwide, a public
affairs company, and a separate lobbying specialist, Jefferson
Waterman International, for stratagems on how to approach NATO. ``I
think they're very well positioned,'' said Jim Mezzaros, BSMG's
principal executive.
</P>
<P>
   But Dimitrov seems at least as good a strategist in the cause.
He is an eloquent, bearded lawyer who ignored politics during the
Communist decades but caught his nation's eye as the author of a
best-selling book, a rewriting of the Arthurian legend seen as a
subtle and inspiring parable on the need for political justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to achieve now is not just a safe Bulgaria,
a safe home,'' he said, noting that the nation has enjoyed four
peaceful elections since the fall of Communism and that its economy
is Western-oriented, growing 4.5 percent last year. ``Now we want a
safe neighborhood,'' he emphasized, polishing his nation's
credentials for regional stability. He proudly noted that Bulgaria
is tending to Kosovo refugees at the Macedonian border and
absorbing without complaint the economic disruption of the NATO
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Dimitrov was carrying an important dispatch from home in his
pocket. It is a fresh ruling by Bulgaria's constitutional court
that it would be legal for NATO to use the nation's airspace in its
attempt to defend the Kosovo Albanians, who are on the run from the
forces of Slobodan Milosevic. It is a troth of sorts, an important
credential for the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our day is Sunday,'' Dimitrov declared happily of NATO's
special agenda meetings with neighboring states and NATO
applicants. His visiting colleagues from Sofia, President Petar
Stoyanov and Foreign Minister Nadezhda Mihailova, will be more than
ready for the occasion, the Bulgarian ambassador promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sunday, the agenda brings the representatives of the
aspiring nations into the room,'' exulted Dimitrov, sounding as if
he would be among the first through the door.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
