A1733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-24 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: JETER HAS INGREDIENTS TO BE ANOTHER YANKEE GREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Derek Jeter, on several occasions, had the pleasure
of meeting Joe DiMaggio, and the pleasure, at least on the surface,
was usually all his.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hello and a handshake,'' Jeter said. ``He pretty much
kept to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The truly great Yankees come in all shapes, sizes and
personalities. When Mickey Mantle died, Willie Randolph fondly
recalled being a rookie infielder, and Mantle, on opening day,
1976, suddenly appearing at his dressing stall with a smile as wide
as Oklahoma. ``That was Mickey,'' said Randolph, the Yankees'
third-base coach. ``He never big-leagued me.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't DiMaggio, old and more aloof than ever by 1996, when
Jeter claimed shortstop at Yankee Stadium for a generation, unless
the demon dollar someday wreaks historical havoc. That was fine
with Jeter, who as a child summered at his grandparents' house in
northern New Jersey. He didn't need DiMaggio to compare batting
stances or recite his Hall of Fame statistics. Only one number
mattered to a 21-year-old who wanted so much to be right where he
was.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was No. 5, then and forever, a single-digit legend. And
Jeter, like a child born into royalty, was No. 2, about to launch
his own reign in pinstripes that could one day take him from
shortstop out to Monument Park, where DiMaggio's new granite
memorial will be unveiled Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fitting for Derek to have one of the last single-digit
numbers that remains,'' David Cone said. ``I'm not sure if it was
intentional, but whoever made that decision, it was a pretty good
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   There are great Yankee moments, and there are great Yankees, and
people should not confuse the two. On Friday night, when David
Wells returned with Toronto to pitch against the champions he
helped make, the Yankees replayed the last out of his perfect game
against Minnesota last May 17, just as Wells was taking the mound.
</P>
<P>
   It was a classy gesture, compared with say, the cheesy half-time
video the Knicks played when Charles Oakley came home in his
Toronto Raptors Barney suit.
</P>
<P>
   This display of appreciation and warmth on a cold, damp night
was long dissipated by the time Chili Davis, appropriately enough,
doubled home two seventh-inning runs, sending Wells off to a 6-4
defeat and the rest of his career. It sure would spice up the
season if he and the young Blue Jays could push the Yankees in the
American League East, but these Yankees won before David Wells, and
they will win after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely made his mark in Yankee history in a short
period of time,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   They were two endearing seasons, one memorable. Wells pitched 10
years in the majors before he set foot in the Yankee clubhouse. The
notion of him as Mr. Yankee is about as far off base as DiMaggio
being remembered as Mr. Coffee. Bucky Dent won a pennant in Boston
with a home run for the Yankees in 1978, which made him the
architect of a great Yankee moment, not a great Yankee. The
standards are higher around these parts.
</P>
<P>
   Wells may be a Babe Ruth fanatic, a student of Yankee history,
but Jeter is living it. His rocketing career is being nurtured by
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't too many teams in any sport where there is so
much tradition and where so many players are showing up to remind
you of it,'' Jeter said. ``When I first got here, I had a chance to
play with Mattingly, and that was an honor. In spring training, you
look up and you see Goose Gossage, and then walk around the corner
and you see Reggie Jackson. You come here, and Yogi Berra is
throwing out the first ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, 24 and already a two-time champion, said, ``You get
spoiled around here.''
</P>
<P>
   When he joined the Yankees in September 1995 and was handed No.
2, Jeter said he figured it was the smallest jersey, the best fit
for a wiry middle infielder. He was asked if he knew which other
Yankees had worn No. 2, and didn't have to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crosetti and Murcer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Someone in the clubhouse said that Wayne Tolleson, a 1970s spare
infielder, also wore No. 2. Maybe there was a grand design to this
assignment, maybe not. All Jeter knows is that he has one of two
remaining single-digit numbers. His manager, Joe Torre, No. 6, has
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Torre already has two rings, one more than Billy Martin, retired
No. 1. On another day when this most famous of American sports
franchises relishes its past, it is not unreasonable to wonder if
both numbers, 2 and 6, will ever again be worn by anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being No. 2. It's been mine since I got here,'' Jeter
said. ``But I don't think about the retired-number stuff. I'm just
getting started.''
</P>
<P>
   He goes about his work with an attitude that presumes nothing,
which is why Cone calls him ``the future captain of the Yankees.''
Jeter is filling out now in that No. 2 jersey, driving the ball
with power, hitting around .400.
</P>
<P>
   Three years does not make a great Yankee any more than Wells'
two, but Jeter isn't going anywhere soon. He has a chance to be the
last single-digit hero, another monument to Yankee history, Joe
DiMaggio's neighbor forever. The pleasure in achieving it would be
all his.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
