<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-DIMAGGIO-     04-24 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-DIMAGGIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A NATION TURNS ITS EYES TO CENTER FIELD, ONE MORE
TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The most haunting question in all of sports _ ``Where
have you gone, Joe DiMaggio?'' _ should be answered Sunday. Joe
DiMaggio has gone to the monument valley beyond center field in
Yankee Stadium. While his body is not buried there, his spirit will
be consecrated in that hallowed ground.
</P>
<P>
   What each of us makes of his spirit, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Private to the point of paranoia, DiMaggio took charge of his
final illness with the same steely reserve that informed his
baseball career, his marriage to Marilyn Monroe, his afterlife as
living legend. He was his own curator. He allowed us to believe
that his genius, like Albert Einstein's, Greta Garbo's, Orson
Welles', had earned him the right to be left alone except when he
wanted attention, to be excused whatever smudges might appear on
the shiny image.
</P>
<P>
   We scrabbled to justify his aloofness as dignity (but never
shyness or contempt), to find grounds for forgiveness in his
coffee-maker commercials, to place him in historical context. He
had ridden into our consciousness just as the myths of the frontier
West were receding, one of a posse of cowboys in the outfield who
became our new manly heroes, lone individuals standing just outside
the group, our last defense.
</P>
<P>
   He was the son of an immigrant, but graceful and cool, so all
the immigrants' sons who were writing about sports identified with
him and, in the words of the old sports editor Stanley Woodward,
``Godded him up.'' DiMaggio was a demanding employee, especially
around contract time, but fans forgave him because he seemed like
such a passionate performer.
</P>
<P>
   But that still doesn't quite explain this: Even though some of
his replacements in that very same outfield _ Mickey Mantle, Reggie
Jackson, yes, Darryl Strawberry _ were infinitely more interesting
and entertaining as human beings, it is DiMaggio who will continue
to be beatified.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, a major New York City highway will be renamed for
DiMaggio, a major mistake. He may not deserve such a civic
immortality, but he certainly doesn't deserve to be cursed by
thousands of motorists every day stuck on an outmoded, graceless
road. He will end up remembered for traffic jams, overheated cars,
noise and fumes.
</P>
<P>
   But then he does owe New York. The other great outfielders of
his era might have become crossover personalities had they played
here in the days when all the national media were only a cab ride
away. Stan Musial, a harmonica rascal of almost silly geniality,
could have become Lawrence Welk as a Yankee. Ted Williams was the
man whom John Wayne tried to play in movies. When you recall that
another Marine fighter pilot, John Glenn, spoke of the joy and
comfort of flying into combat with Ted Williams on his wing, it is
hard to ever again take another outfielder more seriously. Ted
Williams' spit was too good for the fans it hit.
</P>
<P>
   So why DiMaggio? There could be clues in the retirements of
Michael Jordan and Wayne Gretzky, two men of privacy, discretion
and cool who quit while they were still pleasures to watch. But
Jordan and Gretzky overwhelmed and ennobled their sports; they
might as well have been superior beings from another planet.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was not in their league.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, he didn't embarrass us, perhaps because we
never got into all the nooks and crannies of his life. He was just
smart enough to know he wasn't smart enough to unspool sound bites
and commentary. We saw just enough to be able to make up the rest
of him. Always dressed for dinner at ``21,'' he drifted through the
rest of his life with the same outward economy he displayed as he
drifted under fly balls. He knew just where they would drop.
</P>
<P>
   This was a lonely man of the night, we could imagine, a Sinatra
without the mean streak. His skin color helped him; when Hank Aaron
broke Babe Ruth's career home-run record, DiMaggio's 56-game
hitting streak suddenly became the most important record in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry was supposed to be the next DiMaggio. You could look
it up. When the New York Mets brought him up in 1983, before his
time, an unfinished 19-year-old, the front-office people actually
compared him to the Clipper. What was done for Darryl and to him,
what he could and couldn't do for himself, is another story, yet
unfinished, too, but I must admit I have felt far more human
interest for him than for DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Commentators have been beating up on Strawberry for letting us
down. Poor Darryl, a wildly talented, madly destructive charmer,
let only himself down. A case could be made for how poorly he was
served by the Mets, and how even the Yankees needed to show more
support. A recovering addict and recovering cancer patient who is a
fading athlete unsure of his place on a team needs help and
encouragement to come back from a slip.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this could never have happened to the Great DiMaggio.
The Clipper was too tightly wrapped, the cops, gangsters and news
media would have protected him, and he usually had a bobo at his
side to hold his coat and bimbo, much less anything that could have
been considered a controlled substance. Another haunting question
is this: Groomed to mature rather than just star, would Strawberry
have become the next DiMaggio?
</P>
<P>
   Last haunting question: Where will you go, Darryl Strawberry?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
