<HEADLINE>
ROBERT JOHNSTON, NAVAL ENGINEER WHO DESIGNED HYDROFOILS, DIES AT
80  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Mass., Wash., Canada)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert James Johnston, a naval engineer who became an innovative
designer of hydrofoils and other high-speed watercraft, died April
16 at his home in Daytona Beach, Fla. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston focused on improving hydrofoils, which skim over the
water on winglike structures attached to the hull, enabling the
craft to go faster than conventional boats and ships. In 1993 the
International Hydrofoil Society singled out his lifetime
contributions as a ``significant force in the design, development
and application of hydrofoils.''
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Purdue University in 1940 and received
advanced degrees in naval architecture and marine engineering from
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1947. His work in the
Office of Naval Research in and after World War II led to the
construction of the Navy's first hydrofoil missile ships.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Navy with the rank of captain in the
mid-1950s, he held executive positions in industry and directed
hydrofoil projects for the Grumman Corporation, including a
commercial hydrofoil, the Dolphin. He returned to the Navy in 1973
as the civilian manager of its Advanced Hydrofoil Program, which
built and deployed hydrofoil gunships.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s he founded a firm to provide data on
high-speed watercraft.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Marcia McColly Johnston; her
daughters, Cynthia Redick of Washington and Alicia Stickel of
Toronto; his son, David, also of Washington, and seven
grandchildren. His first wife, Dixie Girard Johnston, died in 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
