<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BRUCKMANN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONALD JOHN BRUCKMAN, SUPPORTER OF GARDENS AND ANIMALS, DIES AT
70  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Donald John Bruckmann, a New York investment banker
who was the board chairman of the Animal Medical Center, a trustee
and former chairman of the New York Botanical Garden and an
enthusiastic gardener, sailor and conservationist, died Wednesday
at his home on Manhattan's Upper East Side. He was 70 and also
lived in East Hampton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He had been ill with prostate cancer, said Thomas J. Hubbard,
his longtime friend and successor as chairman of the Botanical
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckmann retired in 1983 as president of Dean Witter Reynolds
International. At his death he also was a director of the historic
Garden Conservancy, which was restored under his leadership as
board chairman of the Botanical Garden.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Montclair, N.J., he graduated from Lafayette College
in Easton, Pa., in 1950 and served as a lieutenant in the Army
during the Korean conflict. He graduated from Columbia University
Law School in 1955 and worked at the New York firm of Simpson,
Thatcher &AMP; Bartlett until 1960.
</P>
<P>
   He served as a director of the Wall Street firms of Smith Barney
&AMP; Company and Dean Witter Reynolds before being named chief
executive and president of Dean Witter Reynolds International in
1974. From then until 1996 he was a director and financial adviser
at Bank Audi (USA).
</P>
<P>
   He was a breeder of shelties _ Shetland sheep dogs that look
like a smaller version of collies _ and his association with the
Animal Medical Center dated to 1976, when he sought midwifery
assistance. He felt that all life was precious and that pets
deserved the same level of technology and care available to people.
</P>
<P>
   He became a supporter and joined the board of the center in
1980. Elected chairman in 1996, he led the hospital through a
period of renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckmann became a director of the New York Botanical Garden, in
the Bronx, in 1974 and served as chairman from 1977 to 1987. Under
his stewardship the Conservatory was reborn, the Peggy Rockefeller
Rose Garden was planned, a new Children's Garden was dedicated, and
the Botanical Garden set up its Institute of Economic Botany.
</P>
<P>
   He created a two-acre garden of his own on Lily Pond Lane in the
Hamptons, complete with a pond and stretching from the road to the
dunes. The property is included in sightseeing tours by garden
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   He was a former vice chairman of the Asia Society and past
chairman of the Cooper-Hewitt Museum of Design. A Republican, he
served as vice chairman of the Pennsylvania Avenue Corp. during the
Nixon administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckmann is survived by his wife of 42 years, Polly Thudium
Bruckmann.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
