<HEADER>
A1755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-GORDON25-COX     04-24 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winston Cup champ hitting bumps in '99
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Pain and frustration, strangers to Jeff Gordon
throughout his seven-year NASCAR career, have become frequent
companions since his victory at the season-opening Daytona 500 in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who has won three of the last four Winston Cup titles,
still has sore ribs from a crash at Texas Motor Speedway nearly a
month ago. He hasn't finished two of the eight Winston Cup races
this year, equaling his total DNFs in 33 events last season.
</P>
<P>
   Add in the emergence of Jeff Burton and Bobby Labonte as serious
contenders, along with the usual challenges from Dale Jarrett and
Mark Martin, and Gordon isn't counting on running away with a
fourth title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's other people kind of imagining things,'' Gordon
said. ``We know how tough the competition is in Winston Cup. We
know how tough it is to be on the leaderboard and win a race. We
know racing is a tough sport, where you have your ups and you have
your downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of ups, and we're still having a lot of ups
this year, but maybe we're just not getting the results that we had
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, going into today's DieHard 500 at Talladega
Superspeedway, Gordon is fourth in the Winston Cup standings, 129
points behind leader Burton. With 26 events remaining on the
schedule, Gordon says his Hendrick Motorsports team isn't about to
panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in pretty good shape,'' Gordon said. ``We're not
having that just unbelievable year like we had last year, where it
just seemed like nothing went wrong, but we don't expect to have
years like that every year. This is one of those years where you've
got to work hard, keep your head and keep going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Gordon's results early this year aren't much different
from those in his three championship seasons. Last year, when
Gordon beat Martin for the title by 364 points, he was fourth in
points after eight races, 106 behind leader Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Gordon was third and 94 points behind Jarrett at this
point. During his first title season in 1995, Gordon was third and
trailed the leader by 70 points after eight events.
</P>
<P>
   ``As great as last season was, we're really not any different in
points from where we were last year, except for maybe one more
win,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Evernham, crew chief for Gordon's Rainbow Warriors, agrees.
``It's like I told our guys,'' Evernham said. ``We're right on
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his strong standing in points, Gordon has faced more
obstacles than in seasons past. After winning the Daytona 500 for
the second time, the engine in Gordon's No. 24 Chevrolet blew up
the following week at North Carolina Speedway, where he finished
39th after failing to complete the final 83 laps. The last time
Gordon failed to finish a Winston Cup race because of an engine
failure was in March 1997 at Atlanta Motor Speedway, where he
placed 42nd.
</P>
<P>
   After his jaw-dropping mechanical problems at Rockingham, Gordon
rallied to win at Atlanta two weeks later, and then he finished
third at Darlington. Over the last month, however, Gordon hasn't
been able avoid the wrecks that he's missed in the past.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas on March 28, Gordon blew a tire and crashed into the
outside wall only 68 laps into the 334-lap race. He finished 43rd,
his worst outing in 197 career Cup starts.
</P>
<P>
   At Bristol two weeks ago, Gordon and rookie Tony Stewart were
knocked out of contention during a pileup sparked by Jerry Nadeau.
Gordon's car received extensive damage, but he was able to recover
and finish fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have as much good luck as we've had, you're going to
have some tough times eventually,'' Gordon said. ``I look at this
year and see a blown engine (at Rockingham), a cut tire (at Texas),
and, of course, Bristol was just short-track racing. To be where
we're at in points and have the trouble that we've had, I'm still
very impressed with the way the team has reacted, especially with
the performances where we haven't had problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 27, says he has never dealt with injuries during his
racing career, which includes several years of driving sprint cars
and midgets in Indiana. He comes into today's race in better shape
than the previous two races, when his ribs were battered on short
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some serious wrecks, and I think because of my
physical size, it helps me come out of them a little better than
some other guys who have a little more mass to them,'' he said.
``I'm 145 or 150 pounds, depending on the time of the race because
I sweat it off. When you hit the wall that hard you don't create as
much force and usually don't do as much damage. A bigger guy will
do a lot more damage to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the wall a couple of years ago at Michigan really,
really hard. I was pretty sore, but I was fine for the race. I
flipped several times in the midgets and sprint cars and tried to
tear my head off, but I've been very fortunate, knock on wood, that
I haven't broken any bones. I've never had an injury that kept me
out of a race car.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon says the only time he's been kept out of a car was when
he was about 16, when a bad case of poison ivy prevented him from
driving in a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poison ivy was a bad situation,'' he said. ``If you live
in Indiana, you know there's a lot of poison ivy around, and a lot
of pollen. I never had any allergies until I moved to Indiana. Now,
I'm allergic to everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one day I was pulling some vines off the house, just
doing some housework. In Indiana, out in the country, you can burn
leaves, so we threw the poison ivy in the fire. We always had a
little methanol back in the shop from the race car and you can
really get the fire going that way. I remember watching it burn,
and that night it had gone through all my clothes. ... Some poison
ivy scratched my arm, and I couldn't even bend it, and I had to
cancel my race that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
