<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-EASTNOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pistons harmony just not in cards
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Minnesota, the media got Christian Laettner. That
and his coaches weren't up to his standards.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the media got him again. That and his teammates
couldn't stand criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, well, here's a start: Wednesday night on the flight
home from a loss in Charlotte, Laettner and Jerry Stackhouse got
into an argument over the nightly card game. Stackhouse, suffering
from the loss of his sister, concerned over his girlfriend's
difficult pregnancy, nursing an injury, wanted out. Laettner
repeatedly called him a name that denotes weakness in a man.
Stackhouse took exception.
</P>
<P>
   According to an obeserver on the plane, Stackhouse punched
Laettner, the two scuffled and fell into the lap of radio announcer
George Blaha.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons say it didn't happen. But writers on Friday noted
Laettner with a very blackened eye, Stackhouse with scratches on
his right hand. The Pistons have closed down the card game and
threatened any player who talks with a $25,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Laettner was supposed to return from injury today, but may have
aggravated his healing rib.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, just another day in the life of a slumping team.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching carousel
</P>
<P>
   TNT commentator Doc Rivers, who has run clinics for NBA players
the past two offseasons but has no other coaching experience, and
Paul Silas, who has turned the Charlotte Hornets around since Dave
Cowens resigned, figure to be hot commodities at season's end.
Silas wants to stay in Charlotte. Rivers is flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams making changes will be forced to turn to unproven
assistants such as Gar Heard, Maurice Cheeks and Rick Carlisle or
dip into the recycle bin for a Bob Hill, Doug Collins or Del
Harris. University of Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins tops the list of
college coaches, while former Georgetown coach John Thompson has
been mentioned with the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Loose tongues
</P>
<P>
   After ripping Charles Barkley for ripping him, Allen Iverson had
second thoughts _ sort of. Iverson's original response: ``To me,
he's the Houston Rockets' problem. Can't no little kid come up to
me and ask why I spit on him. But he's got kids that can come up
and ask him. He's nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Iverson said, ``I don't hate the guy. I don't have any
problems with him. I was wrong to say those things because all I
did was step down to his level, which was wrong for me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The word from Bird
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird says he has no problem with Iverson. ``Who says five
years from now everybody won't have cornrows? Things change. If the
kid can play, he can play. I think he's going to get better. I'm
happy to see him in our league.'' ... The Pacers get booed at home
after every close loss, and Bird says they're not tough. ``They
call that booing? That wasn't booing. You should walk off the
Boston Garden floor when they're booing. They'd meet you out in the
parking lot by your car. Wait until some of these fans wait out
there in the parking lot and challenge them to a fist fight, like
they did in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
