<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1759 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE25-COX     04-24 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wormy Big Apple
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Someone had to take the hit in New York for the
Knicks' underachievement this season. It was not going to be the
coach because Jeff Van Gundy had the backing of the players. It was
not going to be Madison Square Garden president because Dave
Checketts would not dare fire himself.
</P>
<P>
   That left the general manager, Ernie Grunfeld, as the fall guy.
</P>
<P>
   With unlimited resources, Grunfeld spent $68 million on a roster
that went into the weekend out of the playoffs. Not good anywhere,
but particularly in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Grunfeld traded the heart of the team in Charles Oakley
for a soft and unproductive Marcus Camby and the soul of the team
in John Starks for embattled and inconsistent Latrell Sprewell,
moves that broke the Knicks, but were only part of the reason
Grunfeld was bounced.
</P>
<P>
   Back to that later. The question of the day: Why would Checketts
fire Grunfeld with just eight games to go in the regular season?
That's where this story gets fishy.
</P>
<P>
   When Checketts announced Wednesday that Grunfeld had been kicked
downstairs, the Knicks were only 1 1/2 games out of a playoff
position. There was time to make the postseason, and with no
clear-cut dominant team in the Eastern Conference, no telling what
a hot Knicks team could have done.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts had assured that neither Van Gundy nor Grunfeld would
be let go after the season, saying ``we're all responsible'' for
the team's woes. But with the New York Rangers, also owned by MSG,
out of the NHL playoffs for the last two seasons and the Knicks in
a position to miss the postseason for the first time in 12 years,
Checketts' job hung in the balance, too.
</P>
<P>
   Smart guy that he is, Checketts realized this and made a move on
Grunfeld before his bosses made a move on him. What else could be
the motivation for axing Grunfeld now? Certainly, firing a general
manager would do nothing toward firing up the team. For sure, only
coaching changes spark a reversal in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I did what I did was,'' Checketts said, ``frankly,
so that for those eight games and hopefully the playoffs I can be
involved in a day-to-day way _ and, this summer, understand fully
what the issues of this club are and where we go next.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to go likely will be Van Gundy _ unless the Knicks make a
remarkable about-face. Any reversal would come too late for
Grunfeld, who cannot justifiably feel like the scapegoat when
reviewing his entire tenure with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, his shipping of Oakley and Starks were his ultimate
downfall, but Grunfeld contributed to his own demise with a
collection of questionable moves. His draft record is abominable:
Jerrod Mustaf, Greg Anthony, Hubert Davis, John Wallace, John
Thomas, Walter McCarty, Dontae Jones, Monty Williams and Charlie
Ward. Only Ward remains with the team.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he traded a first-round draft choice to Dallas for
guard Rolando Blackman, 34, who was hurt and never reached his old
stature. He traded Mark Jackson for Doc Rivers (who got hurt), Bo
Kimble (no factor) and 6-foot-10 Charles Smith (who never fit in).
</P>
<P>
   And the huge contracts of Patrick Ewing, Ward, Allan Houston,
Larry Johnson, Chris Childs and Camby have the Knicks strapped,
with limited maneuverability. So, he had to go. Where the Knicks go
from here, no one knows. But Grunfeld won't have the burden, which
isn't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
