<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charlotte showing chemistry
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service ATLANTA _ Usually, it takes a few years
<TEXT>
to determine the value of a significant trade. But the Charlotte
Hornets are showing that it can be measured in a matter of weeks.
<P>
   With nine straight wins going into the weekend, the Hornets'
acquisition of guard Eddie Jones and center Elden Campbell for
Glenn Rice looks decidedly Charlotte teal blue. Jones and Campbell
have been at the heart of the Hornets' resurgence. After looking to
be out of playoff contention when the deal with the Los Angeles
Lakers went down, Charlotte took over eighth place last week in the
Eastern Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, interim coach Paul Silas, with 17 wins in 26
games after replacing Dave Cowens, likely has done enough to get
the long-term job. The Hornets are playing with much more
confidence and greater unselfishness.
</P>
<P>
   Silas' work with Campbell has restored his confidence, while
Jones has functioned fluidly and freely, knowing he will get ample
shots and playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hornets guard David Wesley: ``I know we've shocked people.
A lot of people had given up hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, hope has turned into expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In L.A., Rice has been ordinary and the Lakers less than that.
The chemistry that has carried Charlotte is nonexistent in L.A. And
with the Lakers in fifth place in the West, it is not outrageous to
consider that they might be eliminated from the playoffs in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   MORE KNICKS MESS
</P>
<P>
   Guard Charlie Ward, a devout Christian, felt the wrath of
Madison Square Garden President Dave Checketts when Ward passed to
teammates an opinion article written by Reggie White. In it, White
criticized women journalists in locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that some guys may be uncomfortable with it,'' Ward
said. ``Or their wives may have the same values expressed in the
article.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts was hot. ``I had a discussion with (Ward) about
that,'' he said. ``I believe in the freedom of speech, but he may
not use our locker room as his pulpit. It's not allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a New York magazine article on Latrell Sprewell
talked of Larry Johnson's affinity for ``tricking the Knicks' young
publicist, Lori Hamamoto, into seeing him naked.'' It went on to
say Johnson would sit naked at his locker room stall after games
with a towel over his lap, then uncross his legs while pretending
to lift his towel. ``Look over here and tell me what my free-throw
percentage was tonight,'' Johnson said to Hamamoto, according to
the article.
</P>
<P>
   Hamamoto said there was no sexual harassment and that she and
Johnson have a great working relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnson: ``I don't flash people. Definitely not Lori.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
