<HEADER>
A1761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-WESTNOTES25-C     04-24 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-WESTNOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs set sights on dethroning Jazz
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Spurs suddenly find themselves within striking
distance of the conference lead. Three consecutive wins, over
Portland, Houston and Utah, can do that. Tuesday's 83-69 triumph in
Salt Lake City was a boost to a team scorched by the Jazz there in
the playoffs a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team _ more than any other team I've been on _ just
absolutely hates losing,'' David Robinson said. ``We almost hate
each other when we lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan enhanced his growing reputation with 36 points, 10
rebounds and 7 blocks against the Jazz. ``We're trying to dethrone
them,'' Duncan said. ``That's the way it is. They've been doing
this for a number of years. This is one game. We haven't knocked
them off, yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan scored 14 points in the third quarter. Six came on
20-footers off the pick-and-roll, a play that's synonymous with the
Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was phenomenal. He was awesome,'' Greg Ostertag said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't spare the Rod(man)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the suggestion that Kurt Rambis started Dennis Rodman's
exit by booting him from practice for being late, the truth is that
Jerry West and Mitch Kupchak reached the decision while Portland
was cleaning up against the Lakers the night before. Both were at
the Desert Classic in Phoenix, getting frequent updates by
telephone from a Laker official. They told Rambis, who had avoided
calling Rodman on anything before, to crack down on him the next
time he got an inch out of line.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Lakers' defense has fallen apart since the Glen
Rice trade. Before the deal, the Lakers were a top offensive team,
had a 15-6 record and were middle-of-the-pack defensively, giving
up an average of 92.6 points. In the first 20 games after the
trade, they maintained their offensive pace, but lost 10 times as
opponents averaged 99.3 during the stretch. points. Deduction: Rice
could be traded in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Not drowning his sorrows
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen's DUI arrest Thursday morning came after
Houston's 109-95 embarrassment at home against Dallas, but there's
no link between Pippen's erratic play _ he was 2-for-8 in the game
_ and what happened later.
</P>
<P>
   In Pippen's case, he went to dinner, drank beers and was heading
home when he mistakenly turned onto Main Street in Houston,
believing it was one of the downtown one-way streets heading out of
the city, and ran a red light. Stopped, Pippen did not take a
breathalyzer test but failed a field sobriety test.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested at 1:30 a.m., released at 6:50 a.m. and was home
at 7:30. He and the Rockets barely cared at all about playing the
Mavericks until they were whipped so thoroughly that the Mavs began
taunting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was jaw-jacking them all night,'' Mavericks forward Gary
Trent said, laughing openly. ``I told Scottie Pippen, there's only
one No. 33 that was going to show up tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen wasn't talking, about the game or the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
