<SLUG> BC-FBC-UTVOLS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols looking to repeat championship victory
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _Tennessee's Fiesta Bowl victory over Florida
State and the national championship that went with it are almost
four months old. But a quick trip up and down Cumberland Avenue,
better known as ``The Strip,'' makes it clear that the Big Orange
celebration will not be stopping anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Here in East Tennessee, creativity knows no bounds. If you can
sell it, somebody has slapped a big orange ``T'' and the words
``1999 National Champions'' on it. And somebody, somewhere, has
proudly put it in their den.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday a radio voice was hawking color prints of scenes from
Tennessee's Fiesta Bowl victory. Squeeze the bottom left-hand
corner and the voice of John Ward, Tennessee's legendary radio
broadcaster, counts down the game's final seconds. Sterling Marlin,
the Tennessee-born stock car driver, has turned his Busch Grand
National car into a high-speed tribute to his beloved Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, about 15,000 participants in this gleeful insanity
gathered at Neyland Stadium for the annual Orange and White spring
game. Yes, they were curious about next season's team, which has a
good chance of winning the school's third consecutive SEC
Championship. But more importantly, they wanted just one more
opportunity to celebrate the Volunteers' first national title since
1951.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame them. If I was a fan I'd be doing it too,'' said
center Spencer Riley. ``The important thing is that we're not doing
it. We stopped celebrating a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 45-5 record the past four seasons and a veteran team
returning for 1999, you might think Tennessee's spring practice
would be low key. You'd be wrong. From the first day of winter
conditioning in January to Saturday's end of spring drills, head
coach Phillip Fulmer has pushed this team even harder than the one
before, lest they even be tempted to become complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been crazy or anything in our approach but the
message has been clear,'' said Fulmer, now 67-11.
</P>
<P>
   The message: Getting to the top may be hard. Staying on top is
even harder. Fulmer made his point in several ways.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's first full practice of the spring lasted two hours
and 50 minutes, a marathon by Fulmer's standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that,'' said offensive tackle Chad Clifton, ``we knew it
was going to be different.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago during a seven-on-seven tackling drill,
Fulmer detected a lack of intensity. Fulmer stood over the players
and for the next 15 minutes they repeated the drill until the head
coach was satisfied and the players were exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after that Fulmer publicly dressed down some of
Tennessee's talented but little-used underclassmen, saying they
were ``fat and happy'' after watching the veterans win 24 of their
last 26 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real wake-up call for some of those guys,'' said
quarterback Tee Martin. ``If this team is going to be as good as we
think it can be, a lot of those guys are going to have to step
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer's stern approach is not so much psychological window
dressing, but a straightforward attempt to push this particular
team to its potential, which is considerable. Simply put, if the
Vols can win at Florida on Sept. 18, they are good enough to get
back in the national championship mix.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, Martin returns for his senior season with a 13-0
record as a starter. His favorite receiver, Peerless Price, is
gone, but the stable of pass catchers at Tennessee remains deep.
The offensive line will again be the SEC's best and running back
Jamal Lewis is back after sitting out the last half of the 1998
season with a knee injury. The defense will miss the leadership of
linebacker Al Wilson, the first-round choice of the Denver Broncos,
but still has plenty of talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind that we can be as good as last
year and even better if we work at it,'' said Lewis, who has had no
contact this spring but pronounced himself ready to go. ``These
guys are still hungry. They remember what it felt like after the
Fiesta Bowl. We want to feel that way again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
