<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-RETIRE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elway to announce retirement
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Placing health above the potential to make history,
Denver Broncos star John Elway has decided to retire after 16 NFL
seasons, thus bypassing the opportunity in '99 to become the first
quarterback to author a Super Bowl three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than prolong the suspense about his future, as he did
last spring, Elway decided last week to leave the game and began
informing family and friends. He originally planned to announce his
retirement last Wednesday but postponed the media session in the
wake of the tragedy at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
Despite published reports that a news conference will be held
Monday at noon, the only certainty is that the end of Elway's
brilliant career will be made official early in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Indications are that Broncos owner Pat Bowlen and coach Mike
Shanahan are aware of the decision. The silence emanating from team
headquarters and Elway's business associates through Saturday was
deafening, but also telling. Agent Marvin Demoff, reached in
Florida, declined comment. Jeff Sperbeck, who supervises Elway's
marketing endeavors, did not return telephone calls. Jack Elway,
his father and the director of pro scouting for the Broncos, said
he ''could not address'' his son's future.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, 38, was at an undisclosed site in Florida playing golf
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it is true, I'm sure it's a decision based on health and
lifestyle and spending more time with his family,'' said
quarterback Bubby Brister, who would succeed Elway as the Denver
starter. ''There's no doubt John still loves the competition. But
the last couple of years, even with winning the Super Bowls, have
been tough ones physically. Me and everyone else were surprised
when he came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver has reached a contract agreement in principle with former
Falcons quarterback Chris Miller to augment Brister and second-year
veteran Brian Griese, who played in only one game last season. A
series of concussions forced Miller to curtail his career after the
1995 season, but he has recently been cleared to play by several
neurologists.
</P>
<P>
   Elway holds the league record for most victories by a starting
quarterback (148) and ranks No. 27 in all-time passer rating
(79.9). He is second in career attempts (7,250), completions
(4,123) and passing yards (51,475) and third in touchdown passes
(300).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
