<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colorado tragedy too close for West
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last week's tragedy at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., hit a little too close to home for Arizona
Cardinals backup offensive lineman Derek West. His brother, Ryan,
teaches drafting and computer technology at Columbine and he
coaches the offensive and defensive line. But Ryan West currently
is on a one-year sabbatical as he pursues a career as a
professional baseball umpire, so he wasn't on campus on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, I went to bed and couldn't sleep the whole night,''
Derek West said. Added guard Lester Holmes: ``(Derek) said he spent
the whole night playing the `What if?' game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan West's classroom is around a corner from the library, where
most of the slayings occurred. One of the deceased students,
Matthew Kechter, played offensive line for him. He knew another
victim, Isaiah Shoels, a member of the football team. Kevin Harris,
older brother of suspect Eric Harris, is a former defensive
lineman. While a thousand miles away _ working a game at Clinton,
Iowa, in the Class-A Midwest League _ Ryan West was in anguish.
``It tore my heart out watching (on TV),'' Ryan West said. ``I kept
wondering if I might have made some kind of difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Chasing Ricky
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans coach Mike Ditka has taken plenty of flak for
trading all his draft choices this year, with first- and
third-rounders in 2000, to secure Heisman tailback Ricky Williams.
It turns out, though, Ditka and Saints general manager Billy
Kuharich weren't the only ones who offered a king's ransom for
Williams. After taking quarterback Tim Couch with the first overall
selection, Cleveland Vice President Dwight Clark phoned Redskins GM
Charley Casserly and offered the Browns' remaining 12 picks. By
that time Casserly, who actually wanted Williams but deferred to
coach Norv Turner, had agreed to a trade-down with the Saints and a
trade-up with the Bears. To this point, Cleveland has downplayed
the tailback position. It looks like journeyman Terry Kirby will be
the starter, backed up by Sedrick Shaw. Word is, the Browns want to
wait until next year to spend big bucks on a back. Among the
potential unrestricted free agents next spring are Jamal Anderson
(Atlanta), James Stewart (Jacksonville) and Karim Abdul-Jabbar
(Miami). Disgruntled Bengals tailback Corey Dillon will be a
restricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Wise guys
</P>
<P>
   The suspicion that Oregon quarterback Akili Smith had unfair
assistance improving his Wonderlic test score repeatedly has been
denied by agent Leigh Steinberg. The first choice of the Bengals
raised his score from 17 to 37 (maximum: 50) after a tutor hired by
the agent worked with him. Steinberg claimed Smith didn't obtain a
copy of the test before he took it a second time. Notable, though,
is that Jason Maas, the quarterback with whom Smith split time his
junior season, recently had a 43 after getting a score down in the
mid-teens his first time around. ``We were study buddies,'' Smith
said. The scores of the other first-round quarterbacks: Couch, 22;
Donovan McNabb, 16; Cade McNown, 28; and Daunte Culpepper, 22.
</P>
<P>
   Iron fisted
</P>
<P>
   Given that his NFL resume features stints as an assistant for
Bill Parcells and Tom Coughlin, it isn't surprising that Browns
rookie coach Chris Palmer is running a tight ship. The approach to
discipline was obvious Thursday when Palmer released defensive
tackle Antonio Anderson, a two-year veteran with size (6-6, 318)
and potential, but a player whose work ethic didn't meet Palmer's
standards. The next player out the door could be Clemson linebacker
Rahim Abdullah, a second-round pick who missed a plane and was late
to a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Cap-ology
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' salary-cap figure for starting quarterback Vinny
Testaverde in 1999 is $1.3 million. The team's salary-cap charge
for quarterback Neil O'Donnell, who was cut last spring by the Jets
and last week by the Bengals, is $2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Corner market
</P>
<P>
   The veteran free-agent pool has been picked over and, outside of
starters such as LB Jamir Miller (Arizona), OG Matt O'Dwyer (N.Y.
Jets), DT Jerry Ball (Minnesota), DE Marco Coleman (San Diego), LB
Marvcus Patton (Washington) and LB Anthony Davis (Kansas City),
there isn't much left. The one position, however, where teams are
going to land bargins is at corner. High-profile players Ashley
Ambrose (Cincinnati), Ryan McNeil (St. Louis) and Darrien Gordon
(Denver) still are available.
</P>
<P>
   Jump(y) street
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't played in two seasons, but former Falcons defensive
tackle Jumpy Geathers hopes to make a comeback at 38. One of the
most powerful inside defenders in recent league history, Geathers
terrorized guards for 14 seasons with his trademark ``forklift''
pass-rush maneuver. His agent, Brett Senior, has phoned several
teams, including the Falcons, but hasn't gotten any nibbles yet.
``No player wants to end his career injured,'' Senior said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus Jumpy looks at the (lack of) quality in the league and
thinks he's still as good as most guys out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bargain basement
</P>
<P>
   One AFC personnel director's take on the best ``value'' choices
in each round of the draft: First round _ OT Aaron Gibson
(Detroit); Second _ LB Barry Gardner (Philadelphia) and WR Peerless
Price (Buffalo); Third _ CB Chris Watson (Denver) and FS Marquis
Smith (Cleveland); Fourth _ RB Sedrick Irvin (Detroit); Fifth _ TE
Jerame Tuman (Pittsburgh); Sixth _ OG J.P. Machado (N.Y. Jets);
Seventh _ SS Anthony Poindexter (Baltimore).
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   One reason the Dallas draft was panned: Jerry Jones chose three
players who tested positive for drugs in college and three others
who were red-flagged for injuries on most draft boards.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
