<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-CAPTJUDY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charting course of fun
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Judy Helmey deals in the memory business, both
in recounting the stories about her infamous father and in
providing fishing experiences to last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran charter-boat captain with 33 years of know-how on the
sea in and around Wilmington Island, Helmey doesn't have a day on
the water go by without both kinds of memories.
</P>
<P>
   Affectionately and professionally known as Captain Judy, Helmey,
46, is the proprietor of Miss Judy Charters, one of the most
popular charter operations on the north Georgia coast. With first
mate Ali Young, also certified by the U.S. Coast Guard as a charter
captain and a valuable partner for 18 years, Helmey will charm an
adult male client by calling him ``Hon'' and baiting the hook for
him, make a youngster feel like the best angler on the boat and, of
course, entertain all with her inherited wit and charm. Both were
passed down from her colorful late father, Sherman. One of
Savannah's most well-known and fun-loving characters, the elder
Helmey lived such a full life that stories of his dealings with
booze, women and Al Capone still are being told. He passed away in
1994 at the age of 92.
</P>
<P>
   In his lifetime, Captain Sherman was married seven times (``He
really enjoyed the ladies,'' Captain Judy says), enjoyed a large
share of fun and mastered fishing and most things mechanical.
</P>
<P>
   It was the mechanical abilities that hooked Sherman Helmey up
with Capone, who one night during Prohibition showed up at Helmey's
auto-repair shop, asking if Helmey could deliver a car to the old
Savannah Hotel. ```What's your name?' my father asked,'' Judy
Helmey said. ```Al Capone,' he answered.'' That was the start of a
business venture that had Sherman Helmey building customized cars
to carry illegal booze for Capone.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Helmey also was a skilled charter-boat captain, who
regaled clients with his stories of Capone and other adventures.
Judy was always with her father _ ``He didn't know what else to do
with me'' _ and learned the trade first-hand. She was tending to
the steering wheel and the baiting hooks at the age of 6 and earned
her captain's license by 18.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, with stints at professional water skiing,
real-estate sales and general contracting, she has made her mark on
the ocean, including the discovery of a lost shipwreck, the
Barnstable, a large wooden freighter that disappeared in 1921.
</P>
<P>
   Along with taking clients out, she writes a weekly fishing
report for several state newspapers and is ready to publish her
second book. The first, called ``My Father, the Sea and Me,'' was
published in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, what I'll be remembered for will be my stories
about my father, told through the eyes of a child,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A day on the water with Captain Judy provides her clients with
their own story-telling fodder.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent outing with members of a family in its second
generation of hiring her, the No. 1 concern was creating a memory
for an 8-year-old girl. And when Brittany Roy, whose father Jeff,
29, fished with Helmey as a teen-ager, caught her first saltwater
fish, it was time for all to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, I thank the fish god,'' said Helmey, after Brittany
reeled in a two-foot little tunny, a smaller cousin of the
yellowfin tuna, caught while fast trolling a cedar plug along the
surface some 20 miles off shore. ``Now I feel better. ... Y'all
see? I told you Brittany would catch the first fish. Did you like
that, Brittany?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was yucky,'' she replied. ``OK, Dad, it's your turn to
get all messy.''
</P>
<P>
   Messy or not, Brittany had a magical day, and plenty of stories
to tell her classmates back in Bolling Brook, Ill., about her
family's spring break trip to Skidaway Island; she not only caught
the only large fish trolling, she also caught more and bigger black
sea bass bottom fishing on an artificial reef than anyone else and
clicked so well with Young that the two spent much of the travel
time sitting together and goofing around in the back of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without her I don't know if I'd still be doing this,'' Captain
Judy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs a lot of money to come fishing, so it's important to
them,'' Helmey said. ``So, it's got to be important to us, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
