<HEADER>
A1766 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISH-GACOAST25-COX     04-24 1944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-GACOAST25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shores of plenty reel 'em in
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARIEN, Ga. _ There are so many tidal creeks and cuts in the
salt marshes around the Altamaha River Delta that only the locals
know where they are. And many of them aren't talking.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing guide Wendell Harper, who has studied since his boyhood
the intricate waterways that make up one of the most fertile
fishing areas in the state, knows where many of those locals live,
including alligators.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one, a 10-footer,'' Harper said while navigating up an
unnamed creek in search of a good spotted sea trout bite on a windy
March day. The big reptile, one of several gators seen on the short
stretch of creek, flicked his tail, sending him sliding down a mud
bank into the water as the boat passed. ``I tell you what, there's
some big boys up in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper, 46, one of the Georgia coast's most knowledgeable _ and
consequently one of the most sought after _ fishing guides, knows a
thing or two about the gators. Up until last year he would trap
them for the state, dragging them out of such places as swimming
pools, golf course ponds and tourist-covered beaches. He used to
stay busy enough that ``alligator trapping'' had its own line item
on his income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd give us the alligator,'' he says. ``That was our pay.''
</P>
<P>
   You never know what you'll see on a fishing trip with Harper at
the tail end of the second-largest watershed east of the
Mississippi. There are the gators, frequently a beautiful sunrise,
hundreds of different species of birds, and acres upon acres of
marshland, all part of what Harper, a hometown boy making a living
from his boyhood playground, calls ``God's country.''
</P>
<P>
   The focal point is the fishing, however, and Harper is one of
the best at finding them, whether they are his bread-and-butter sea
trout and red drum, or the big tarpon and sharks that pay a visit
every summer. Within a relatively short drive of Atlanta _ around
four hours to Savannah, six or more hours to St. Mary's _ Georgia
boasts some of the finest saltwater fishing in the Southeast. And
it's still relatively unknown, although people are beginning to
realize that they don't have to go to Florida or Louisiana to catch
trophy-sized saltwater fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started promoting coastal fishing 10 or 12 years ago, and
people who come up to me and say, `I didn't know there were big
trout and redfish fishing in Georgia,' or king mackerel, or shark,
or tarpon. They just didn't know,'' Harper said. ``But people are
just beginning to find out that we have a super fishery year-round.
We have something going on every month.''
</P>
<P>
   And the locations to fish are as varied as the species of fish
and techniques used to catch them. Georgia has nearly 20 offshore
artificial reefs, consisting of anything from scrap vessels to
concrete blocks to old tires sunk onto barren sandy areas, where
the bottom fishing is consistently excellent. ``Live bottoms,''
natural reefs like the Gray's Reef and Savannah and Brunswick
Snapper Banks, also are hangouts for bottom-dwellers. There also
are eight Navy combat aircraft training towers 30 to 40 nautical
miles offshore, where baitfish attract open water giants like tuna,
wahoo and sailfish. The Gulf Stream, the warm-water superhighway
that runs some 80 miles off shore, also contain the big fish of the
blue water.
</P>
<P>
   The publication ``Georgia's Offshore Fishing Guide,'' available
from the state Coastal Resources Division, is a must-have for
saltwater anglers. It covers locations, techniques and popular
species, and has a large map which locates many of the offshore
structures.
</P>
<P>
   While fishing won't replace what has put coastal Georgia on the
map _ beaches, golf, tennis and shopping _ it is finding a niche
and begging for more attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brunswick area for a long time was looked at as a golf and
tennis resort, but we're starting to see fishing as a viable
alternative,'' said Mark Noble, a charter captain of more than 20
years who is based at Golden Isle Marina near St. Simons Island.
``The local economy gets a heck of a boost from fishing every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's hard to find statistics that back that up, there's
little question that recreational sport fishing has made an
economic impact along the coast. According to Georgia Department of
Industry, Trade and Tourism statistics, more than $1.9 billion was
generated in 1997 (the latest available stats) by tourism in the
state's Region 9, which includes the coastal counties of Bryan,
Camden, Chatham, Glynn, Liberty and McIntosh. Driving the increase
were Savannah (Chatham) and the Brunswick/Golden Isles (Glynn).
It's safe to say that a significant percentage of that figure comes
from fishing; even the Brunswick and The Golden Isles of Georgia
Visitors Bureau includes it in its promotional literature and
videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think enough of it we have it in our footage,'' said Bill
Tipton, executive director of the bureau. ``We want people to know
that fishing is part of the package.''
</P>
<P>
   And more local merchants are making money because of it. Harper
is taking clients out as many as 300 days per year, and he also is
a spokesperson for such big-name sponsors like Quantum, Yamaha,
Lowrance and Costa del Mar. The former mill worker claims to have
been skunked only four times in his life, and has caught limits of
trout (25 per person) in every month of the year, which is
difficult for most anglers to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quit a good job to do this,'' said Harper, who also competes
in king mackerel tournaments. ``If they made eight days in a week,
I'd fish eight days.''
</P>
<P>
   Noble, holder of two state fishing records (bull shark, thresher
shark), fishes 230 to 240 days per year. He helped organize the
Golden Isles Association, a network of guides who work out of
Golden Isle Marina, just to deal with his overflowing client list.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't fish, I don't eat,'' said the 37-year-old who grew
up on St. Simons Island. ``By the time I was 13, I knew I was going
to make my living fishing. By the time I was 16, I was working on a
charter boat. With a wife and two kids, I have to fish a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotels, restaurants and marinas feel the impact, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When business is good, it's about as good as it can be,'' said
Rick Smith, co-owner of Two-Way Fish Camp, located on the South
Altamaha River north of the hustle and bustle of Brunswick.
Two-Way, where Harper is based, sells live bait year-round, one of
the few marinas along the coast that does that. ``It gets pretty
hectic.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden Isles Marina will host several tournaments this summer,
including the big Golden Isle Kingfish Classic king mackerel
tournament, which will attract 130 to 150 boats the last weekend of
June. ``It's a zoo that weekend,'' said marina owner Boyce Mann.
``It's chaotic. My property gets overrun with people, boats and
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not usually the case for individual charter outings,
however. The excitement comes from what's pulling at the end of
your line. ``If you want to come down and have a fish abuse you,
come for the shark and tarpon,'' Noble said. ``The tarpon pick up
in the summer. I've seen grown men shake their heads and say there
ain't no way a fish can fight that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly appealing to freshwater bass fishermen may be the
red drum. When they mature and leave the tidal creeks, fish in the
40-pound range can be caught in the late summer to early fall near
the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we call bass,'' Mann says. ``Those little ol'
largemouth are nothing compared to them.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information on fishing coastal Georgia, contact the
state Coastal Resources Division (912-264-7218), or any of the
local chambers of commerce/visitors bureaus: Chatham
County/Savannah (912-728-2662); Brunswick/Golden Isles
(912-265-0620), Camden County/Kings Bay (912-729-5840), McIntosh
County (912-437-4192), Liberty County/Hinesville (912-368-4445),
Bryan County/Richmond Hill (800-807-4848).
</P>
<P>
   THINGS TO KNOW BEFORE YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   If you plan a fishing trip to Georgia's coast, here are some
things to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   Using your own boat
</P>
<P>
   _ Get some instruction. There's nothing better than learning
first-hand. Inexperienced boaters should not go out without a
guide.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get a good, detailed map of the area, but also ask local
experts about any problem areas. Sandbars shift and new creeks are
sometimes formed after storms. Many maps are years old.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check the tide tables. Tides fluctuate seven feet or more from
high to low tide.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure your electronics work. Depth finders can help you
avoid trouble, and a working radio is a must in case of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a thorough check of your boat before you go to help
prevent a break-down.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring a captain
</P>
<P>
   _ What does price include? Find out if there are any additional
charges, like for bait, gas, food, tackle.
</P>
<P>
   _ What kinds of fish will you catch? Find out if you can keep
your catch, whether you can set your own hook (on big fish), and if
you can have your catch cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   _ Can the captain terminate a trip? Find out the policy for
shortening a trip because of bad weather and whether you have a say
in that decision.
</P>
<P>
   _ You are entitled to information about captain's Coast Guard
certification status, insurance coverage and boat inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget
</P>
<P>
   _ The essentials: Sunscreen, camera, rain gear (if needed), and
most important, motion sickness medicine. It's better to be safe
than sorry.
</P>
<P>
   GOT-TO-DO COASTAL FISHING TRIPS
</P>
<P>
   While the fishing is great along the Georgia coast from Tybee
Island to St. Mary's, here are some trips that can turn a
freshwater bass fisherman into Captain Ahab.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tarpon: Monsters over 100 pounds raise heart rates July
through September, peaking in August, on sandbars and shoal areas.
Try Cabretta Inlet on Sapelo Island, Pelican Spit off Sea Island
and the St. Andrews Sound between Cumberland and Jekyll islands.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spotted sea trout: The bread-and-butter fish for many guides
can be caught year-round in tidal creeks, but September through
November is peak time. You can't go wrong anywhere, but Wassaw
Sound near Savannah and the Altamaha Sound near the Golden Isles
are among the best.
</P>
<P>
   _ Red drum: Also known as redfish and spottails, they are called
``bull reds'' when they reach 20 pounds. Bulls in the 40-pound
range can be caught mid-September to mid-November near beaches,
either surfcasting from the beach or from a boat anchored at the
breakers. Big reds can be found in places like McQueen's Inlet on
St. Catherine's Island, sandbars in the Altmaha River Delta and the
mouth of the Satilla River.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whiting: Family-oriented fishing that doesn't require a big
boat peaks during the spring, and is becoming more popular. Small
(the state record is under three pounds) but tasty, they can be
caught in big numbers off the St. Simon's beaches, especially due
east of the King and Prince Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   _ King mackerel: Often exceeding 30 or 40 pounds, the kings
provide excellent summertime fishing as close as five or six miles
off shore. Gray's Reef National Marine Sanctuary, the Savannah
River Ship Channel or most of the artifical reefs off the Georgia
coast will yield kings trolling and live-lining.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try these on for size: bottom fishing on the Savannah and
Bruswick Snapper Banks (around 40 miles off shore) for a variety of
species, or hire a charter for billfish, tuna and wahoo fishing for
the ``Blue Water'' of the Gulf Stream (80 or more miles).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
