<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Red drum numbers black again
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ The red drum has made a remarkable recovery
along Georgia's coastline.
</P>
<P>
   The popular species, also called redfish, was on the verge of a
population emergency less than 20 years ago because of overfishing,
as anglers, not burdened by size or creel limits, filled up their
coolers with immature reds.
</P>
<P>
   And the blackened-redfish craze made popular by New Orleans chef
Paul Prudhomme was in full swing, and many anglers were keeping
what was at one time considered a trash fish by locals.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia began bag and size limits in 1986. ``I believe we
prevented a collapse,'' said Spud Woodward, state Coastal Resources
Division marine biologist.
</P>
<P>
   Because red drum in the South Atlantic Ocean mature at the age
of 5, about 27 to 30 inches, and don't leave the tidal creeks and
estuaries until then, every fish kept before the limitations had an
effect on the population. The fish, which can be caught easily in
the creeks right alongside spotted sea trout, leave for the open
ocean once they mature and can reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were virtually no fish surviving to the maturity rate,''
said Woodward, who also is considered one of the redfish angling
experts in Brunswick and the Golden Isles. ``We were facing a
50-year moratorium on red-drum harvesting.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation was worse in the Gulf of Mexico, where commercial
netting and overfishing by recreational anglers caused the
population to plummet. Now, Mississippi is the only Gulf state that
allows commercial harvesting, and it closes the season once the
total catch reaches 35,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The resurgence of the redfish population is proof that limits
work, Woodward said. Now, with a 14-inch minimum and a bag limit of
five, none over 27 inches, redfish are providing thrills for light-
and medium-tackle anglers and fly anglers.
</P>
<P>
   Limitations are working on the Gulf, too. ``They were few and
far between back in 1990,'' said Mike Brainard, a biological
program coordinator for the Mississippi Department of Marine
Resources, Office of Fisheries. Mississippi has a bag limit of
three redfish and an 18-inch minimum, with only one over 30 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward points out that there are other species in trouble.
Snapper, grouper, tarpon, sharks and triple tails are among the
species in the biggest danger, but anglers should keep in mind that
all fish need to be conserved. If you don't plan to eat a fish, you
shouldn't keep it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to get people into the mindset that the ocean
is not an unlimited resource,'' he said. ``You can't just take,
take, take. You don't have to measure fishing success by the body
count.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
