<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King wants Thrashers' job
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dave King is going to Norway and he is taking all of
the essentials: socks, passport, resume.
</P>
<P>
   King, an assistant coach for the Montreal Canadiens and Canada
in the World Champions, May 1-17, is expected to drop in on a few
Team USA practices. But the reason is less to spy on the
competition than to seek out Thrashers general manager Don Waddell,
who has confirmed King as a candidate for the team's coaching
vacancy. Waddell will be scouting prospective draft picks and also
is assistant GM of the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expansion franchises are always exciting for coaches because
you get a chance to work with young players,'' King said from
Montreal. ``Obviously, the ability to teach is important, and I
feel I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   King, who first contacted Waddell last summer to express his
interest in the job, had moderate success in his three years as
Calgary's head coach, 1992-95. The Flames had three winning
seasons, including two division titles, and a composite record of
109-76-31 (.576), but they had three straight exits in the first
round of the playoffs. He also has coached Canada's national team
for nine years and the silver-medal Olympic team in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Nolan, another Thrashers candidate, also made preliminary
contact with Los Angeles general manager Dave Taylor after coach
Larry Robinson was fired. Nolan said he has mailed out ``25
resumes.'' But Waddell doesn't feel compelled to move quickly with
his interviews. In fact, he acknowledged for the first time the
outside chance that a coach might not be in place before the
expansion and entry drafts, June 25 and 26, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is the possible candidacy of coaches still in the
playoffs, such as Colorado assistant Bryan Trottier and Ottawa
assistant Mike Murphy. Murphy was fired after two losing seasons in
Toronto but is being given some credit for Ottawa's success.
Trottier does not have head-coaching experience. The last potential
date of the Stanley Cup finals is June 19.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell said he won't talk to any candidate whose team is in the
playoffs, saying, ``It wouldn't be fair to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Right call
</P>
<P>
   There was no complaint, only praise, when the Colorado Avalanche
followed the lead of the Rockies and Nuggets and postponed their
playoff games after the school shootings outside Denver. Colorado
shifted the first two games of the series to San Jose and Nos. 3,
4, 5 to Denver. Veteran Claude Lemieux said, ``When you see
something like this, everybody is touched. I've got a babysitter
who goes to that school. I went to pick up my car (from a repair
shop), and the service manager, his daughter, was in the school.
Denver is a big city but a small town. The more they were showing
on TV, the more faces I would recognize, whether it was kids who
were coming to hockey games or we'd see at the rinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Gretzky?
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky's desire to stay involved in the game has spawned
rumors that he might rescue one of the ailing Canadian franchises _
say, Edmonton. ``I would tell you what I'd tell anybody that came
to me with a business venture,'' Gretzky said. ``I'd look at
anything. I'll study anything. To tell you right now I'm going to
own a Canadian team, it's not true. To tell you I won't own a
Canadian team, that's not true. I haven't made a decision yet. My
focus is on my kids in school and living in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the NHL
</P>
<P>
   This is a pivotal offseason for the Chicago Blackhawks, who
ended the season with a six-game winning streak and own four picks
in the first two rounds of the draft. ... St. Louis winger Scott
Young missed an $800,000 shot at an empty net in the final
regular-season game. His 25th goal would have triggered a $300,000
incentive. Pavol Demitra, who passed up a shot for his teammate's
sake, would have collected $500,000 for an assist and his 90th
point. Demitra also had six goals disallowed this year, four
reversed on replay and two voided by the referee. ... Thrashers
assistant GM Les Jackson's name has popped up as a candidate for
expansion Minnesota's top job, but neither he nor the Thrashers
have been contacted. Jackson, who also had pursued Atlanta's GM
position after several years as an assistant in Dallas, cracked,
``I've been on that prospect list for a long time. It's turning
into a suspect list. Having said that, I'd certainly be interested
if they called.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
