<P>
   COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-UTVOLS _ KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ A year ago, after Tennessee won
the SEC championship, coach Phillip Fulmer vowed to work extra hard
to keep the Vols from becoming complacent. Now he says he'll do the
same to keep his team from being satisfied with the national
championship. It will be tall order as the Vols are loaded.
Thirty-three of the team's top 44 players return plus running back
Jamal Lewis, who missed the last half of the season with a knee
injury. If Lewis comes back at full speed, and the Vols find a
couple of receivers, there is no reason to think they can't win
their third straight SEC title. (Barnhart, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 18. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS
</P>
<P>
   Coastal Georgia fishing package
</P>
<P>
   FISH-GACOAST _ DARIEN, Ga. _ It's one of the first questions
asked by newcomers to Two-Way Fish Camp in Darien, Ga.: ``Why
Two-Way?'' The answer is quite simple, actually. Take a left and go
inland up the Altamaha River to the freshwater and its big flathead
catfish and largemouth bass. Go right and find the some of the best
saltwater fishing in the Southeast. Coastal guide Wendell Harper
almost always takes a right. (This is the main feature in a package
on fishing along the Georgia Coast). (Bernarde, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FISH-CAPTJUDY _ SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Judy Helmey of Savannah is one
of the most experienced and skilled fishing guides along Georgia's
coast. An angler all of her life, and inspired by her father, whose
notorious past included rum running for Al Capone, she thrives and
is respected in an occupation dominated by males. (Bernarde,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FISH-REDFISH _ The blackened redfish craze of the 1980s nearly
decimated the beloved gamefish in the Southeast. But now, with the
help of federal and regional legislation, they are making a
tremendous comeback all along the Southeastern shorelines. Redfish
are a popular species of choice for many Georgia anglers.
(Bernarde, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. MOVED
</P>
