<SLUG> BC-NATO-CITY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SERBIAN AMERICANS PROTEST NATO BOMBING
 &HT;    540&AMP;add. With NATO-SUMMIT.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thousands of angry Serbian Americans protested
outside the White House on Saturday, demanding that their country
stop bombing their ancestral homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey! Hey! USA! How many kids did you kill today?'' they
chanted in condemning America's leadership in the NATO air war
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   After riding buses all night from the heartland, the
demonstrators assembled in Lafayette Park just north of the White
House and marched through a downtown section of the nation's
capital. But they were not allowed within several blocks of the
Andrew Mellon Auditorium and Ronald Reagan Building, where NATO
officials are commemorating the 50th anniversary of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Waving Yugoslavian flags and wearing T-shirts with bull's-eyes
that identified them as ``NATO targets,'' the protesters called
President Clinton a war criminal and charged that the news media
had not told the nation the whole story about the centuries-old
conflict in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 600,000 Serbs expelled from Croatia in 1995,'' said
Alexander Vucelic of Mansfield, Ohio. He wondered why ``CNN and
Clinton'' weren't ``talking about ethnic cleansing and refugees
then.''
</P>
<P>
   ``America has lost its soul in this act of bombing Yugoslavia,''
said Vucelic. ``The Nazis burned books to suppress the truth. Now
America is bombing TV stations to suppress the truth,'' he said in
a reference to Friday's destruction of Yugoslavian state television
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the crowd said they opposed the regime of
Yugoslavia's President Slobodan Milosevic, but they said the NATO
bombing is unifying the Serbs and solidifying Milosevic's hold on
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is my refugee _ my mom,'' said Lana Simic of New York
City. ``On the second day of bombing, my mother came over from
Belgrade. ... To kill people in the name of saving people is
insane.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters released black balloons that they said symbolized
the lives of Yugoslavians killed in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Most members of the crowd were straight from middle America.
There were white-haired men with World War II medals pinned to
their sweaters, young couples with toddlers in target T-shirts, and
boisterous boys in Cleveland Indians caps. Older people greeted
each other with three traditional kisses on the cheeks, while
younger ones slapped high fives. A group of teen-aged girls in
bell-bottomed jeans came from St. Stevan's(cq) Serbian Orthodox
Church in Chicago and led chants of ``Long Live Serbia'' and
``NATO, Shame on You.''
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents came from Kosovo and we all have relatives still
there,'' explained Gordana Ristic, one of the girls, adding that
the anti-war movement ``is a big thing in our neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 1 million Serbian Americans and they cling to
their heritage, said Tanja Gavrilovic, who drove all night from
Cleveland to attend the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in the United States, but the first language I
spoke was Serbian. I learned English in school,'' she explained.
``What people don't know is that what Jerusalem is to Jews, that is
what Kosovo is to us. The last Serb, down to the women and
children, will fight and die before we give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirjana Vekich, daughter of Serbian immigrants, said she was
born in Chicago but regards herself as both American and Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Serbian culture is very rich,'' she said, describing how
she grew up in a neighborhood where children learned Serbian folk
dances and everyone ate cevape, a Serbian sausage. She has made
several trips to the land of her forebears. But the United States
is now her home, and she feels betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand that Serbs are fighting for our land _
in Kosovo, our holy land,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian-American rally was much larger than the
demonstration held at Lafayette Park a day earlier by
Albanian-Americans who supported the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-war demonstrators carried placards denouncing Clinton,
NATO, Secretary of State Madeline Albright, the news media, and
most pointedly, the bombing of Yugoslavia. ``Serbs Have Children,
Too,'' said one sign. ``Collateral Damage _ My Family,'' read
another.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Vucelic of Columbus, Ohio, attacked the ``hypocrisy'' of
Clinton telling students in the aftermath of the Colorado school
killings to resolve conflict without violence _ while pushing a
policy of violence against Yugoslavia. ``He should do what he
preaches,'' said Vucelic.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
