<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talladega races make drivers nervous wrecks
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ They've bumped and rubbed their way around the
short tracks for the past two weeks, but some of NASCAR's top
drivers are expecting the worst in today's DieHard 500 at Talladega
Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not many places where I wake up on Sunday morning and
I'm nervous,'' said Winston Cup points leader Jeff Burton. ``I
don't mind telling you, when I wake up at Talladega on Sunday, I'm
nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who has held the points lead for more than a month,
starts third today, behind pole-sitter Ken Schrader and Bobby
Labonte, who's fifth in points and 184 behind Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, the only driver with seven top-10 finishes in nine
events this year, says starting up front doesn't assure that he'll
avoid the inevitable big wreck on the 2.66-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about running up front, being safe,'' Burton said.
``Man, all the wrecks I see that are big start in the front, and
they're big because they're in the front and there's nowhere to go.
You can't hide from the wreck here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to Michigan or Rockingham or Charlotte, and if the car
doesn't drive right, you just slow down. But you can't do that
here. It's `Just wait for the wreck, and hope you miss it.' And if
you miss it, you tell everybody how good a job you did. And if you
get in it, you tell 'em you couldn't avoid it. That's the way I do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte won last year's race, giving Pontiac its first victory
ever in a restrictor-plate race. Labonte's average speed last year
was 163.439 mph, more than twice as fast as John Andretti's winning
speed last week at Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader, who got his first Winston Cup victory here in July
1988, says there are ways to avoid a chain-reaction wreck at
Talladega and Daytona, superspeedways where NASCAR requires
restrictor plates to curb speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there anything we can do to avoid the wreck?'' Schrader
said. ``Yeah, not run so fast and don't run in such big packs. But
the object of our sport is to go really fast and get there first.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrader has been especially fast in qualifying at Talladega,
where he won the pole for the Winston 500 in October. In that race,
however, he went from first to 21st after only one lap when a train
of cars drafted by his No. 33 Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything can happen at superspeedways like these. You just
hope it doesn't happen to you every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin, who is third in points and will start sixth today,
says he's hoping to finish 188 laps unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a big wreck here, and I just know I'm going to
be in it,'' Martin said. ``I've wrecked here a lot, and it hurts
really bad every time. Racing here is like giving drugs to a drug
addict or chocolate to a chocoholic. You can't put us in a position
where we can make a pass if we go four-wide because we're going to
take that chance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
