A1796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES25-CO     04-24 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earnhardt's last lap gets IROC victory
 &HT;    By Al Levine and Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Dale Earnhardt answered that annoying question
_ can he win again?_ by passing Rusty Wallace on the last lap and
winning Saturday's 38-lap International Race of Champions (IROC) by
.075 seconds at Talladega Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   He also won at Daytona in this series that matches 12 champions
from different types of racing. He's led only a lap in each
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the only one you need to lead,'' Earnhardt said. ``You
don't need to lead any more laps. Lead one lap, the last lap.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt is struggling to answer the question in Winston Cup,
the series he used to intimidate. He's won only once in his last
100 Cup races and hasn't led a lap since November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give me the best piece you can give me and give me equal
stuff, I can beat anybody,'' Earnhardt said. ``I still feel that
way. (Car owner Richard) Childress and the guys still feel they can
win races and win championships with the team. We've just got to
get the pieces in the right place. And I'm not saying they're not
that far apart. It's just competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the competitiveness is what's keeping him from victory
lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes every ounce of everything you can do to win today,''
Earnhardt said. ``The best engines, the best chassis, the best
bodies, the best driver, to stay on top of everything. It's not
just one part of it that's going to carry you and win. The driver
can make the difference if he makes the right decisions or the
wrong decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   He took Saturday's victory by getting an aerodynamic push from
third-place finisher Mark Martin, nudging lightly into Wallace's
rear bumper and passing Wallace on the last corner.
</P>
<P>
   Cope(ing) with hardship
</P>
<P>
   It has been a tough year for Winston Cup veteran Derrike Cope.
Cope, who won the 1990 Daytona 500 when Earnhardt cut a tire on the
final lap, was one of five drivers who failed to qualify for
today's race.
</P>
<P>
   It was Cope's fifth DNQ in nine events this year, two more than
his total in 31 races last season. Cope has failed to qualify for
three of the last five events.
</P>
<P>
   Bahari Racing officials have reportedly contacted other drivers,
including former Busch Grand National champion Steve Grissom, about
driving the No. 30 Pontiac. But Cope's contract with Bahari Racing
owner Chuck Rider runs through the 2000 season. Cope is 42nd in
points.
</P>
<P>
   Martin disgusted
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup veteran Mark Martin finished third in Saturday's
IROC race and he'll start sixth today. But Martin said he was
disgusted about speculation that he really didn't try to qualify
for this weekend's Busch race.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who is candid about his dislike of superspeedways,
failed to qualify for a Busch race for the first time since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was pretty humiliated to not run fast enough to make the
(Busch) race,'' Martin said. ''Some of the people in here (media)
said I didn't try hard enough. I didn't like that too much. We got
beat by people who were more on top of their game than we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
