<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-WARNING25-COX     04-24 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-WARNING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No easy explanation for tide of tragedy
 &HT;    Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ A rising river of disturbing currents,
some of them surface riffles that catch the eye only to disappear,
others deceptively deep and swift, snatched away 13 innocent lives
in Littleton last week.
</P>
<P>
   The suddenness and violence by which they were drawn under left
those on the banks searching for the pattern of currents that
somehow combined to subtly draw in Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold,
then violently swamp an entire high school, leaving 12 students
slain and a popular teacher to die slowly despite the toils of
horrified students to stanch the flow of blood and pull him back to
life.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer horror of it stopped a nation in the middle of a war
and forced it to confront an ugliness within as repellent as the
ugliness outside.
</P>
<P>
   The short explanation for the ugliness comes with long
footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply believe it is the culture and I think we adults have
abdicated a very substantial and important part of our authority in
the oversight of our culture,'' said William Moloney, commissioner
of the Colorado Department of Education and a writer who has
suggested that ``moral education'' is the missing link in modern
educational instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have drained our popular culture and our institutions in
general, education specifically, of any sense of moral judgment,''
said Moloney, who was appointed to his post by a Democratic
governor, Roy Romer, and kept on by a Republican, Bill Owens.
</P>
<P>
   The only virtue that survived the draining was tolerance and it
survived in the ``perverted notion'' that any idea is as good as
another, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``by that calculus, Hitler and Gandhi both qualify as
philosopher kings, albeit with different approaches to
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the nature of the place, though, doesn't
necessarily explain how it was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gallagher, president of Mesa State College, said he was
moved to tears by the experiences of the students who survived the
killings in the hallways and library of Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   The experience, he said, took him to compare his rebellious
years with those today.
</P>
<P>
   The prime difference was that he expected, he knew, those
rebellious times would end, leaving no lasting ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major difference I see is that today some of the things
are a little more long lasting'' _ from tattoos to thought
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gallagher said, young people are more independent and
free-ranging at a time when they are most susceptible to pernicious
influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We communicate with no holds barred, no family supervision.
All kinds of wild and weird things can be talked about'' but with
no influence to force reality back into the picture, Gallagher
said.
</P>
<P>
   Popular attitudes toward violence and gore have changed, as
well. The film ``Texas Chainsaw Massacre'' horrified and
fascinated, but there was no admiration for the guy wielding the
chainsaw. ``Natural Born Killers,'' though, spawns a cult following
and hero worship, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take all these things _ desensitization, the reinforcement
of anger, the lack of supervision and connection of people to
values and what the hell do you expect to see happening? Something
pretty weird,'' Gallagher said.
</P>
<P>
   What was ``pretty weird'' was also lethal and horrifying, he
said, and something that defied easy explanation.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest explanation _ that two teens so angst-ridden that
they transformed themselves into death-dealing automatons _
shattered quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought these guys were almost like robots,'' Gallagher
said. ``Then I realized they did have human characteristics _ all
the bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had emotion, laughing about blowing those people away.''
</P>
<P>
   How the killers got that way is a Gordian knot of false trails.
Harris, 18, and Klebold, 17, were good students, so nix the notion
that they were disengaged students who needed only to be reached.
</P>
<P>
   They were so-called Goths _ members of the Trenchcoat Mafia _
who dressed in clothing as dark as their ruminations posted on the
Internet. But Goths offered them no haven, either, rejecting them
as much as others did.
</P>
<P>
   They had criminal records, but both were considered salvageable.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold weren't the obvious threats they seem to be
in hindsight.
</P>
<P>
   Such killers ``could have been wearing white T-shirts as easily
as they could have been wearing black trenchcoats,'' said School
District 51 board member Denise Henning. ``I don't think there's
any one thing that you can ban in the way of apparel that would
have made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   So, said Grand Junction Acting Police Chief Marty Currie, it's
perfectly legitimate to conclude from the outburst in Littleton
that Grand Junction, or anywhere, is a no safe harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is rational'' to have such fears, said Currie, whose
department sent officers to schools after the shooting to talk with
students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does raise the level of consciousness with regard to
mortality issues.''
</P>
<P>
   A killing spree ending in suicide and the apparent effort to
destroy Columbine in a fireball explosion raises other issues, as
well, Moloney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must recognize there is such a thing as moral illiteracy,
from parents to presidents,'' said Moloney, who points to the
beginning of the ``permissive climate'' in schools as starting
during the time ``of the mind's true liberation,'' the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of 16-year-old John Tomlin, killed in the spree,
said the schools fail by ignoring important religious and moral
teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are disintegrating, partly because prayer has been
removed from them,'' said Doreen Tomlin. Asked whether the school
system had failed, the boy's father, John, said, ``The only system
that has failed is that God is left out of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Such thoughts aren't new, said Ted Albers, former president of
Mesa State College, who said modern schools have gone overboard in
their willingness to tolerate deviant behavior while also
displaying ``an indifference to spiritual values. They are
important to a strong person and doubly important to a weak one.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, ``What you'll see is the strengthening of
community, law enforcement, the schools, St. Mary's Hospital,
agencies, the religious segment, all the pillars of our society
joining hands as a team to address kids' needs,'' said Marilyn
Connor, executive director of middle school instruction for
District 51.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tribal memory is short,'' though, said Moloney. ``God, I
hope at the end of this we have a little more to show for the
experience than a new brochure _ `10 Warning Signs That You Might
Have A Mad Bomber In Your Midst.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this galvanizes public opinion and elected officials to
tackle the tougher questions. Why is it for instance, that so few
people lack the will or desire to take on Hollywood, but so many
are rubbing their hands with glee at the prospect of taking on
Charlton Heston?''
</P>
<P>
   Heston is president of the National Rifle Association. The group
scaled back plans for a Denver gathering in deference to the wounds
of the Columbine catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Hollywood might be challenged. Moloney said
he welcomes the notion of suing filmmakers for putting out works
that inspire violent acts, much as gun manufacturers now face suits
and tobacco companies have been sued with success.
</P>
<P>
   One way to prevent such outbreaks would be to make sure that
young people are aware they have a future, Henning said.
</P>
<P>
   Dark messages about the future _ ranging from predictions of the
failure of Social Security to fears of war _ ``are
disillusioning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids in this culture kind of lose a sense of hope in
their future. They start thinking there's not a future out there
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools, she said, have to connect the value of education with
the prospect of a future.
</P>
<P>
   For the educational system to regain confidence, Albers said, it
must regain the trust of students and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Through all that has changed, he said, the lessons he learned at
his first teaching job in Meeker ring true today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were honest and made it plain you there to protect
their interests, the students really warmed to you. It makes an
impression on young people when you let them know you're there to
protect them. Every parent ought to have the feeling that their
teachers are doing everything they can for their children. If every
school was filled with teachers like that ...''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
