<P>
   COLORADO SCHOOL SHOOTINGS
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SCHOOL-BOMB _ WIMBERLEY, Texas _ Law enforcement
authorities found gun powder, crudely made explosive devices,
computer disks with information on how to make bombs and numerous
documents downlaoded from the Internet with similar information in
the homes of three juveniles arrested for planning an attack at
Danforth Junior High School in Wimberley. Officials say the
juveniles gave statements and from those statements it is clear the
students were serious about targeting fellow students and teachers.
(Park, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-LEDE _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ A wrap of today's events,
including police reports that Killers Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold
spent a full year plotting their deadly melee at Columbine High
School, down to the most chilling detail. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-WRAP _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ A look back at the events of
the week following Tuesday's shooting at Columbine High School.
(Staff, Grand Junction Daily Sentinel). 50.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-WARNING _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ Are the events in a
Littleton a warning of what happens when society loosens its morals
and rules to point where anything goes? (Grand Junction Daily
Sentinel). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-MOURN _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ The media invasion and
presence is shaping how people here are mourning the shootings at
Columbine High School. 15. (Grand Junction Daily Sentinel). (Grand
Junction Daily Sentinel).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-LITTLETON _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ Profile of the community
where all this happened. Is there something about the community
that made this possible? Could community have done anything to stop
it? (Grand Junction Daily Sentinel).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-GUNS _ Texas Poll: Who owns guns and is gun ownership on
the rise? Have people taken shooting instruction? Should people
carry concealed handguns with a permit? Should gun manufacturers be
held more accountable? (Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BALKANS _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ A look at the three
neighboring countries/states of the embattled Kosovo province that
have had to bear the brunt of the Kosovar Albanian refugee exodus
and potentially the wrath of Serbian leader Slobodan Milosevic,
president of Yugoslavia. Montenegro, Albania and Macedonia each
have their own particular problems and issues that have been
stirred up and magnified by the Kosovo crisis. Developing. (Holmes,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BALKANS-BOX _ A primer box of data on Montenegro, Albania and
Macedonia. Information for a locator map. (Holmes, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Friday, April 23.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-KURDS _ KANI SHAITAN REFUGEE CAMP, Northern Iraq _ They
don't have televisions in this tent city between the mountains of
Iraqi Kurdistan, so they can't follow the happenings in Kosovo.
But, they know all about ethnic cleansing _ at the hand of Saddam
Hussein. Every week, more Kurds are forced from their homes in a
valuable oil-rich area of Iraq and trucked up to the
semi-autonomous area run for the last seven years by a provisional
Kurdish government. The U.N. Estimates that more than 200,000 Kurds
have been forced from their homes in Iraq since 1991. In this tent
city and the hallways of the grimy, foul-smelling, crumbling hotel
where many end up, refugees tell of being jailed until they agree
to leave the country, then being given an hour to pack and board
the trucks. As you might expect, Kurdish leaders point to chilling
similarities to Kosovo and are all for the NATO attacks. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, April 22.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   NATO-SUMMIT _ WASHINGTON _ A 3:30 p.m. EDT news conference by
President Clinton and Secretary General Javier Solana marks the
second day of the summit marking the 50th anniversary of NATO.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NATO-CITY _ WASHINGTON _ Pro-Serbian protests and other scenes
around the capital on the second day of the NATO summit. (Dart, Cox
News Service) 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TECHTRANSFER _ A special commission appointed by former
House Speaker Newt Gingrich has been studying the impact of
American companies selling technology to China. They have been
looking at the Clinton Administration's decision to allow satellite
sales to China, breeches of national security at Los Alamos and
whether money was improperly accepted by the administration. In
January, Rep. Chris Cox, chairman of that committee, said that the
report would make the Starr report look like ``silly putty.'' That
report is expected out next week. We will interview Cox on Friday
for a story looking at what the report will likely say. (Carr,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLITICS _ A South Carolina state representative
announced Thursday that he is switching his support from George
Bush to John McCain because of the Arizona senator's forceful
position on Kosovo. We take a look at what the various GOP
candidates are saying about Kosovo and how the issue is rippling
through the campaign. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PROMOTION _ CHICAGO _ Mayor Richard Daley, who failed the bar
exam twice before finally passing it, believes that social
promotions help the self-esteem of adults more than the self-worth
or self-esteem of kids. So he used his political muscle to put in
place a testing system that last June resulted in the holding back
more than 23,000 third, sixth and eighth graders. Teachers, kids,
outside researchers and city officials offer contrasting views of
what has happened since. This massive experiment could be repeated
all across the country if Congress goes along with President
Clinton's suggestion to ban social promotions in public schools
that accept federal aid. (Mollison, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PROMOTION-DATA _ Graphics material. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLCHOICE-EFFECTS _ The 40,000 tuition grants being given
nationally to poor kids to opt out of public schools is a lot like
an initiative in Atlanta begun in 1992. We'll focus on a mother and
two daughters who received these scholarships and talk about that
parents in this program, while they appreciate it, didn't use it to
get a vastly better education, used it instead to get a very
religious education at unaccredited schools. So if this scholarship
program is to show that we should have tax-funded vouchers, the
move to religious school raises constitutional problems with mixing
church and state and changes the very nature of public education
from a public good to a private commodity. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   IRS-SKYBOX _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Major Texas universities are
worried they could lose one of their best selling points in leasing
stadium skyboxes, potentially costing them millions in revenue.
Athletics directors at Texas schools are watching a dispute between
an Iowa State booster and the Internal Revenue Service over donors'
ability to take a tax deduction on part of the cost of leasing
skyboxes. (Shah, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
