<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-LEDE25-COX     04-24 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-LEDE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diary had Trenchcoat Mafia plan
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Columbine High School students Eric Harris
and Dylan Klebold spent a full year plotting their deadly melee at
the school, down to the most chilling detail, police said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A diary recovered at one of the boys' homes, which began in
April 1998, included maps of the campus with notations on the
cafeteria schedule and which rooms would be most crowded at various
times of the day.
</P>
<P>
   It even listed a ``rock-and-roll time'' _ the exact moment the
boys planned to enter the school with guns blazing, Jefferson
County Sheriff John Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time line of the planning of this thing,'' Stone said.
``The bottom line is they wanted to do as much damage as they could
possibly do, to burn their school down and go out in flames.''
</P>
<P>
   The handwritten document is riddled with Nazi ideology and
German phrases, Stone said, and confirms that the boys wanted to
kill their classmates as revenge for the ostracism and taunting
they said they endured from more popular students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears the whole thing was hate,'' Stone said. ``It was,
`We want to be strange and different and we don't want the jocks
making fun of us so we're going to punish you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Officials also gave little credence to an e-mail message
received by a Denver newspaper Friday, which left the impression it
was sent by one of the killers and warned of more violence to come
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have little reason to believe either suspect sent it,''
Sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis said. ``We believe it was prepared
and sent after their deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, security at area schools has been beefed up, Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police continued their search for any links that might lead to
additional suspects. Stone has believed from the start that the two
boys had too many bombs and guns to carry into the school by
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Police found more than 30 homemade bombs at the school and in
the boys' homes and cars, some of which were said to have been
strapped to their clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The two teen-agers, who killed 12 students and one teacher
before taking their own lives, carried a machine pistol, a
semi-automatic carbine rifle and two sawed-off shotguns into the
school. They both wore black leather trench coats.
</P>
<P>
   Several student witnesses have said they think a third shooter,
dressed in a white T-shirt, also was at the school. But police
think instead that one of the two killers discarded his trench
coat, noting that one of them was found dead wearing a white
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have not named anyone else as a suspect,'' Davis
said. ``But the investigators say they are getting a lot of good
information and that information may implicate others.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had hoped to finish their investigation at Columbine
within a week, but the sheer volume of evidence means it will
probably take several more weeks, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already booked over 2,000 pieces of evidence and we
haven't even scratched the surface,'' he said, noting that every
piece of shrapnel and bullet fragment must be cataloged.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives worked most of the day Saturday, but planned to take
today off. Many will attend a public memorial service near the
school, at which Vice President Al Gore is scheduled to appear.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton addressed the tragedy in his Saturday radio
message, saying he would soon send Congress a request for $12
million to set up emergency teams to help communities in the
aftermath of such incidents. He will also push measures making it
harder for teens to get guns.
</P>
<P>
   As the grisly police work continued Saturday, tearful family and
friends attended a funeral service for 17-year-old Rachel Scott,
praising the vivacious teen who had recently starred in a school
play and hoped for a career on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's small red car has been covered by flowers in the school
parking lot, where sobbing students have gathered for days,
sometimes sitting with heads bowed and their hands gently touching
the car.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine students will resume classes for the remaining three
weeks of the term on Thursday at nearby Chatfield High School,
splitting their schedule with the school's regular students.
</P>
<P>
   Police continued to defend their actions during the rampage,
saying the school's resource officer fired at the suspects within
minutes and that a make-shift SWAT team was in the building within
15 or 20 minutes of the first reports of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Stone said video footage of the incident may have
created a false impression because scenes of SWAT team members
standing around or huddled behind vehicles outside the school did
not show the teams of officers already inside the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to have one SWAT team shooting at another SWAT
team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said investigators are compiling a time line that will
hopefully show all the key incidents, including when the firing
stopped and when the suspects died, if that can be gleaned from
autopsy reports. An accurate time line might address the concerns
of relatives of slain teacher William ``Dave'' Sanders, who have
questioned whether Sanders might have been saved. After herding
students to safety, Sanders was shot in the chest and bled to death
in a classroom over a three-hour period, despite frantic cell-phone
calls to police from students with him.
</P>
<P>
   Stone also revealed that a sawed-off shotgun barrel was found in
the bedroom of one of the shooters, along with bomb-making
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be concerned about my son if I found a sawed-off shotgun
barrel in there,'' he said. ``The parents should've been aware of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents of both shooters have issued public apologies through
attorneys, but have since been in seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The diary found at one of the suspects' homes reinforces reports
from students that Harris and Klebold were motivated by rage at
being harassed by more popular students, particularly athletes.
</P>
<P>
   While administrators have said the student body has no more than
the normal amount of tension among various groups, some students
have painted a different picture.
</P>
<P>
   There were athletes at the school who would shove around people
from Klebold and Harris' group, even throwing rocks or sodas at
them, some students have claimed.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups ``hated each other,'' said Joe Stair, who
graduated from Columbine last year but hung out with the Trenchcoat
Mafia _ the self-described group of outcasts that included Harris
and Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received a lot of persecution from the athletes, so I guess
they just felt pushed too far,'' Stair said. ``These were two very
angry young men.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
