<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE TO DEBATE THE KOSOVO WAR THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The speaker of the House, Dennis Hastert of
Illinois, is preparing to move ahead with a full House debate on
the Kosovo war this week, despite reservations in both parties
about votes emphasizing legislators' profound divisions over the
nation's involvement in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a full, fair and open debate on the House floor
next week,'' Pete Jeffries, a spokesman for Hastert, said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders in both houses and both parties had been
trying to head off a floor debate on Kosovo. But Hastert's hand was
forced by Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., who has complained that
President Clinton is waging an unconstitutional, undeclared war.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell asserted his rights under the 1973 War Powers
Resolution and filed two measures for a vote _ one declaring war
and a second requiring the withdrawal of American troops from the
Kosovo conflict. The War Powers Act requires that such measures be
brought to the floor quickly for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The House is also expected to vote on several competing
measures. One would require that Clinton seek congressional support
before committing ground troops to Kosovo. Another is expected to
support the president's current course.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, John McCain, R-Ariz., has also tried to spark a
debate on Kosovo policy by introducing a measure to give Clinton
the right to use ``all necessary force'' in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Senate majority leader, has
refused to bring McCain's measure to a vote. Aides said Lott wanted
neither to give Clinton a blank check nor to comfort President
Slobodan Milosevic by defeating the resolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
