<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      04-24 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH EACH GAME, THE KNICKS COULD BE IN OR OUT OF THE PLAYOFFS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all of their bitter history with the Heat, for all of the
bile the mention of their rival brings to the surface, the Knicks
will arrive in Miami far less worried about gloating and far more
concerned with their own survival.
</P>
<P>
   Things are different now. In the past, a late-season meeting
with Miami could determine the division title or the home-court
advantage in the playoffs. Now, the Heat is at the top of the East
and the Knicks are in a fight with the Raptors for the eighth and
final playoff spot with seven games left in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're there right now, we're in the playoffs,'' said Latrell
Spewell after the Knicks held on to beat the Charlotte Hornets,
110-105, Friday night. ``But we can fall out just as easily.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone understands how precarious each game is, it's Patrick
Ewing. Almost eight weeks ago, Ewing willed his 36-year-old body to
keep going into overtime against the Heat. Panting and pouring
sweat, Ewing galloped around the paint and let go of a 13-foot
runner over P.J. Brown just before the buzzer. It kissed the rim
and bounded off. That was it. The Knicks went down, 85-84, in
overtime at the Miami Arena on March 3.
</P>
<P>
   So much has happened since. Back then, the Knicks were 9-5 with
little reason for concern. Until Friday night, the Knicks were a
.500 team and out of the playoffs. But something unusual happened.
After their 18-point, third-quarter lead against Charlotte
shriveled to 1 point with 1 minute 2 seconds left, Ewing finally
hit that elusive runner.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing stared down the shot clock as he planted himself outside
the paint with his back against Derrick Coleman and the ball in his
palm. The seconds ticked off and the crowd bubbling inside Madison
Square Garden grew edgy.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughts of all of those missed game-winners, of all the botched
free throws in the pinch this year could have been circling his
head like buzzards. But he wasn't pondering failure. Typically
Ewing, he believed he was going to take the shot, make the shot and
be the hero and perhaps be the one to start the salvage effort on
this tumultuous Knicks season.
</P>
<P>
   For once, Ewing's faith was rewarded as he delivered a 6-foot
running jumper with 24.9 seconds remaining. Ewing's shot gave them
just the lift they needed to end their four-game losing streak,
poke their heads back into the playoff standings and halt the
Hornets' nine-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the same shot I was criticized for taking the other
day,'' said Ewing, referring to his awkward miss in the final
seconds of a loss in Philadelphia. ``That's my shot. I've been
shooting that one my whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a sure thing, though. When Ewing let go of the shot,
there was a hush in the Garden as the ball bounced around the rim
before going in and giving the Knicks a 106-102 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twice, it bounced twice,'' Ewing said with a smile. No, four
times, he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Ewing said, ``it went in, didn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   It was swallowed by the net right in front of Coleman. That made
it all the sweeter for Ewing. With 2:05 left in the third quarter,
and with the Knicks' lead slipping, Ewing and Coleman had been
trading barbs. After being called for traveling, Coleman turned and
shoved Ewing in frustration. Ewing went back at Coleman. In the
middle stepped Charlie Ward, who was tossed aside by an irate
Ewing. Then, tempers cooled and each remained in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing couldn't believe Coleman was still on the court. Ewing
said Coleman threw a punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't throw a punch,'' Coleman said. ``I just shoved him.
Part of the game. He was putting on a show for the people. I said,
`Meet me in the tunnel.' He didn't say anything back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing said he didn't hear Coleman, but responded with sarcasm:
``I'm scared. I'm so afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing shakes Ewing's bravado. Not Coleman, not an endless
stream of misses this season. This time, the bounce went Ewing's
way and the Knicks prevailed in a crunch. So often, it hasn't
worked out that way for this team. So often, Ewing has been left as
the tragic figure. On four occasions this year, Ewing has had the
game-turning jumper in his hand, and each time he has been left
slumped in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night Ewing was undeterred. ``It hit the back of the
rim, the front of the rim, the side of the rim,'' Coleman said.
``That's just touch. A lot of people wouldn't have had the courage
to take that shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
