<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLEN-AUCTION-NYT &LR;      04-24 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING BUT THE ANGST: ITEMS FROM WOODY ALLEN FILMS SOLD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By COLIN MOYNIHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ The place was a nondescript warehouse in the Long
Island City area of Queens, the time Saturday. But the thousands of
objects crowding the shelves and floor in the cavernous space
potently evoked other places and times: there were radios and
clunky microphones from the 1930s and '40s, a tall wooden phone
booth with folding doors, the kind Superman would use, and a
collection of halberds, pikes and tridents of the sort you might
see in hell.
</P>
<P>
   You did see them in hell, actually, if you saw the Woody Allen
movie ``Deconstructing Harry,'' about a bitter, blocked writer who
spends some time there for his sins.
</P>
<P>
   The demonic implements and other artifacts are props, set
dressings, and wardrobe items from Allen's movies over the last 10
years, removed from storage by his production company and put up
for auction. The goals were to regain much-needed warehouse space
and to raise some money for charity.
</P>
<P>
   Just after 9 a.m., hundreds of people began to file into the
10,000-square-foot basement warehouse to look at the approximately
3,700 items, to be auctioned in 446 lots starting at 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   To Allen aficionados, the auction was a rare public opportunity
to own a piece of that quintessentially New York thing, a Woody
Allen movie. Arlene Lederman paid $20 for a replica of a wedding
cake used in ``Celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it will encourage my daughter to get married sooner,''
she said jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Andreas Brown, a bookstore owner, was hoping to add to the
archive of thousands of books, posters, scripts and stills related
to Allen that he has amassed over the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Woody Allen might end up as the most significant
figure in 20th century American film,'' Brown said. ``Fifty years
from now, all these things could be important.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction's organizers had a more prosaic view. ``We had to
make a pragmatic decision to dispose of a certain quantity or rent
another warehouse,'' Richard Brick, who has co-produced Allen's
three most recent films, said on Friday ``We decided to dispose of
a quantity. It's like cleaning out your attic.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the producers of Woody Allen's last six films,
Sweetheart Productions, have added objects used in those movies to
an existing stock of similar objects, some dating back to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   This cache, stored at another warehouse in Long Island City,
provided Sweetheart Productions with a valuable source of material,
as many of the items were recycled for use in more than one
production.
</P>
<P>
   But in December, after the shooting of Allen's latest film,
which features Sean Penn and Uma Thurman and has the working title
``Woody Allen Fall Project 1998,'' ended, members of the production
company realized they were running out of storage space. They
decided to part with about a third of their inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Brick said he proposed several options for jettisoning the
surplus material to Jean Doumanian, the producer of Allen's last
six films. In February, he said, Ms. Doumanian decided to hold an
auction and donate the proceeds to the National Alliance of Breast
Cancer Organizations, and to two AIDS research organizations, AmFar
and Elton John's AIDS Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   During two days in late February, Santo Loquasto, the celebrated
production designer for 19 of Allen's films, went through the
collected objects, and earmarked some for auction. Trucks took
those items to the auction site.
</P>
<P>
   Brick said the objects up for auction had never been appraised,
but Richard Schlesinger, the president of Top Hundred Promotional
Sales, who is to preside over the auction, said the target was
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweetheart Productions has never held an auction of our
stock,'' Brick said. ``And I don't think there has ever been a
one-day sale of movie memorabilia from one director on this scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many of those left,' he said as he gazed at the
telephone booth. He went on to point out a group of radios and
microphones that he said had been used in ``Radio Days'' and
``Bullets Over Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   He indicated several facsimiles of skulls that he said had been
used in ``Shadows and Fog,'' then paused next to the archaic
weapons used in the hell scenes in ``Deconstructing Harry.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to them was a likeness of the head of John the Baptist,
molded from polystyrene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it was a scene of hell, we weren't supposed to use
material that could catch on fire.'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
