<SLUG> BC-NY-MCGWIRE-BATS-ART-960&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS FACTORY'S BATS ARE GOING, GOING, GONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOLGEVILLE, N.Y. _ The folks here have nothing against Sammy
Sosa, calling him a fine fellow and a great ballplayer. But for a
year now, there has been no more passionate a group of Mark McGwire
fans than the people of this wooded little village on the southwest
shoulder of the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hails from California and plays his home games in St.
Louis, but his bats are made here, at the Rawlings Adirondack
factory. For generations, the sweet crack of wood on horsehide has
been music to Dolgeville, and never more so than when McGwire is
swinging. Since his assault on baseball's home run record last
summer, sales of Adirondack bats have soared, and so has employment
at the factory.
</P>
<P>
   As McGwire chased the ghosts of Roger Maris and Babe Ruth,
staying barely ahead of Sosa, the race became one of the biggest
things ever to happen to Dolgeville, population 2,300. At Motor's
Inn diner, where the old-timers gather early in the morning, at the
North Hudson Woodcraft factory, where workers make parts for pianos
and coffins, and in the village's taverns and parks, everyone
became a fan of the St. Louis Cardinals slugger, rooting for him to
beat Sosa, of the Chicago Cubs, to the record.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they both eclipsed Maris' single-season record of 61
homers in 1961, McGwire finishing with 70 and Sosa with 66.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all anyone could talk about,'' said Nadine Johnson,
owner of Motor's Inn. ``We were all so excited about McGwire, the
race and him using bats from here.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, like many other players, has a promotional deal with
Rawlings, but he favored its bats long before he was paid to do so,
before he became a star.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what the attention paid to his feats did to sales of the
Adirondack bat, Rawlings Sporting Goods, based in St. Louis, will
not say. ``It's a trade secret, but I will say it has meant
hundreds of thousands of bats,'' said Tim Socha, the plant manager.
``We've been going nuts since last summer.''
</P>
<P>
   In an ordinary year, the factory's base work force is about 25,
climbing to 55 in the busy season of winter and early spring, Socha
said. ``But we've been running around 90,'' he said, ``and we're
hiring to keep three shifts going.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Rawlings' most recent corporate report, its wood
baseball bat revenue for the six-month period ended Feb. 28 was
more than $2.3 million above the same period a year earlier, even
as sales of its other sports equipment fell. The report credited
McGwire with the increased bat sales. Rawlings had total revenue of
$170.6 million in the year ended Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Barnes has worked in the Dolgeville factory for years, but
only with the buzz of the last year has she become a true fan. ``I
never paid much attention to baseball, really,'' she said. ``But
you just couldn't help getting excited about it. I mean, these are
our bats.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is the best economic news in a long, long time for
Dolgeville, tucked in the hills north of the Mohawk River and 23
miles east of Utica. The century-old clapboard houses and the
flower beds here are well tended, but behind the trim exterior, the
village is fading, its population and job base declining steadily,
like so many places upstate that have lost the manufacturing that
once fed them.
</P>
<P>
   Jamestown lost its furniture makers and the Crescent wrench
works, Troy lost the Arrow shirt collar factory, and Schenectady
lost American Locomotive Co. and most of General Electric.
Dolgeville's soon-to-be relic is the Daniel Green shoe factory, a
great stone castle along East Canada Creek that once employed
nearly 1,000 people, but has seen a series of layoffs. Most of the
jobs have moved overseas, and the factory will cease production in
June.
</P>
<P>
   At least one resource has not deserted the region: the northern
white ash, common to upstate New York and Pennsylvania, that is
used in nearly all wooden baseball bats. Some of McGwire's bats
have returned home, after a fashion. They now rest in the Baseball
Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, an hour's drive south of here.
</P>
<P>
   The Adirondack bat was born here in the mid-1940s _ it became a
part of Rawlings in 1975 _ and early on, its fortunes rose with the
long ball. Bobby Thomson of the New York Giants popularized the
brand in 1951 by using one to hit the fabled home run that won the
Giants the National League pennant over the Brooklyn Dodgers in the
pivotal playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Wood bat makers nearly went under when aluminum bats became
popular in the 1970s. Aluminum bats last longer, they are lighter
and, most important, a ball hit by one travels faster and farther.
Though the professional leagues use only wood, aluminum bats
account for the great majority of the $115 million-a-year domestic
bat market.
</P>
<P>
   But a backlash against aluminum bats has begun. After scores
sharply increased and a number of pitchers were injured by line
drives that were too fast to defend against, the NCAA imposed new
rules last year restricting the performance of aluminum bats to
make them more like wood. Officials are considering banning them
entirely. A few collegiate and high school leagues have voluntarily
given up aluminum for wood.
</P>
<P>
   All of that is good news for Rawlings, a distant second in the
wood bat market _ how distant the company will not say _ to the
market leader, Hillerich &AMP; Bradsby of Louisville, Ky., maker of the
Louisville Slugger.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings makes about one-third of the bats used by major league
players, who are notoriously particular about their equipment.
Hitters have been known to demand _ and receive _ new bats
delivered overnight, and they have been known to reject bats for
the tiniest flaws, real or imagined. A major leaguer who plays
regularly will go through 100 to 150 bats in a season, Socha said,
at $29 apiece.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The differences between one brand and another are tiny, but as
is often noted, much of hitting is in the mind, and most players,
like McGwire, use the same model every time up, unwilling to
tolerate any unfamiliar element that might distract them. Sosa is
unusual in that he readily switches not only brands but also bat
sizes, and, in fact, has used an Adirondack bat on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   A McGwire bat is 34 1/2 inches long and a relatively light 33
ounces, compared with 36 inches and 36 ounces for his fellow power
hitters Albert Belle and Jose Canseco, who also swing Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   Their almost superstitious insistence on sameness, plus
lucrative promotional deals, makes most hitters paragons of brand
loyalty. Exclusive users of Adirondack bats have included Willie
Mays, Mike Schmidt, Reggie Jackson, Willie McCovey and Roberto
Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   Like major league teams looking for raw talent, Rawlings sends
scouts into the countryside to hunt for the best trees. The wood is
cut into cylinders, kiln-dried to make it resist cracking, turned
on a lathe, sanded into shape, heat-stamped with the company's logo
and usually dipped in a lacquer finish.
</P>
<P>
   For the bats sold to the general public, which can cost as
little as $10, the lathing and sanding are automated and take
seconds. But in a room to one side of the factory, the major league
bats are made with far greater care, each one taking several
minutes. The room is lined with hundreds of ``pattern bats,'' one
for each major league client, used to guide the lathe when a new
bat is being made. The sanding is done by hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where it happens,'' said Bill Steele, supervisor of
the major league room, pausing as if even he, after 30 years at the
factory, were still a little awed by it all. ``It was amazing what
McGwire did last year, and it's amazing what's happened to us. I'm
glad to be a part of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
