<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-24 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS NAME RECOGNITION A BUSH ACHIEVEMENT? 
WANTED BY GOP: MONEY MAN 
DORNAN WON'T QUIT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ariz., Ohio, Ind., Tenn., N.H., N.J., Calif.)   (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poll takers often include a caveat when they report the results
of Election 2000 surveys in which Gov. George W. Bush of Texas runs
unusually well, which is most of the time. They warn that at this
early stage, name recognition probably accounts for much of the
strength that Bush is demonstrating in theoretical primary matchups
with the 10 or so other hopefuls in the huge, sometimes confusing
Republican field.
</P>
<P>
   So what's in a name?
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide survey taken last weekend for the Reuters news
agency, the Zogby polling organization presented 705 likely voters
with a list of 11 possible contenders for the Republican nomination
and asked, ``If the primary were held today, which candidate would
you vote for?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush won with 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This was the order of finish for the rest of the field:
Elizabeth Dole, the former president of the American Red Cross, 17
percent; Sen. John McCain of Arizona, 9 percent; Rep. John Kasich
of Ohio and Patrick Buchanan, the commentator, 4 percent each;
former Vice President Dan Quayle and Steve Forbes, the publisher, 3
percent each; former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, Sen. Robert
Smith of New Hampshire, the conservative activist Gary Bauer and
Alan Keyes, the commentator, 1 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   Then the poll takers read the 705 likely voters brief
biographies of possible Republican candidates, but identified them
only as `Candidate A' or `Candidate B' and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Bush _ Candidate D _ came in first once again. But this time he
won with only 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer finished second with 15 percent, followed by McCain with
14 percent and Mrs. Dole with 12 percent. No other candidate
finished with more than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, where the primary field is limited to
just two contenders, Vice President Al Gore beat former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey by 65 percent to 22 percent when identified
by name and by 61 percent to 27 percent when identified only by a
brief biography.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby calculated its polling to have a margin of sampling error
of plus or minus 3.7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, of course, voters know exactly who George W. Bush is,
and not just because of his famous name. Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   When the Scripps Howard news organization polled Lone Star
voters a couple of weeks ago, asking them to cite Bush's No. 1
accomplishment in office, 45 percent said they could name nothing
specific.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, Mindy Tucker, a Bush spokeswoman, told The Dallas
Morning News, noting that the governor nevertheless had a job
approval rating of close to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is they know he has been an accomplished
governor,'' Ms. Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   In Fund-Raising Race, Democrats Set Pace
</P>
<P>
   The race is on to see which party can raise the most campaign
cash for next year's contest for control of the House of
Representatives. Given that Republicans now control the 435-seat
body by only about a dozen seats, only the presidential race is
likely to see more money-grubbing over the next 19 months.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
boasted that it had raised $6.8 million in the first quarter of
1999, more than twice as much as it had ever raised in the first
quarter of a nonelection year. ``And the biggest stuff is yet to
come,'' said Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., the chairman of the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that the Democrats smell blood, Republican fund-raisers
are running scared _ or acting that way.
</P>
<P>
   With their best money man, former Speaker Newt Gingrich, out of
office, they have no one who can remotely compete with the top
Democratic fund-raiser, President Clinton. Furthermore, the
National Republican Congressional Committee started out the 2000
campaign more than $3.5 million in the red from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's executive director, Scott Hatch, insists that
his group is coming on strong and will be ahead of the Democrats in
fund-raising by the time it files its next campaign cash report, in
late June. But in the meantime, the committee's treasurer, Donna
Anderson, is warning the faithful to fork over, and soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we are faced with an emergency situation,'' she
writes darkly in her latest fund-raising letter. ``Last month we
fell $267,500 short of the money needed to fund our incumbent
support programs. Add this $267,500 to the $538,700 we need to get
through April and you'll understand why I'm so upset. Either we
raise $806,200 by April 30 or we immediately begin slashing our
candidate recruitment efforts, delaying our candidate training
schools and curtailing our staff. In fact, if we fail to raise at
least $315,800 in the next 10 days, our entire effort to stop Bill
Clinton and the ultra-liberal Democrats from recapturing control of
the House could be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe It's the District, Not the Politician
</P>
<P>
   Robert Dornan has been accused of a lot of things. But nobody
has ever called the hard-right Southern California Republican a
quitter.
</P>
<P>
   After Loretta Sanchez, a liberal Democrat, snatched away his
Orange County congressional seat in 1996, he first charged voter
fraud and, when that went nowhere, came bellowing back in 1998,
only to be defeated a second time by Ms. Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   His old congressional district, the 46th, was once one of the
most reliably Republican and conservative in the country. But
California is ever changing, and in recent years the 46th has
steadily become more Democratic and more liberal as more and more
Hispanics have moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Dornan could not, or would not, change as his district changed.
Then he compounded his political troubles by engaging in several
yelling episodes in the House chamber that left his congressional
colleagues appalled and his constituents back home thoroughly
embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, twice repudiated, Dornan is looking to move out _ out of
the 46th but not out of politics. He says he has bought a vacant
house lot in the 48th District and also has his eye on a couple of
houses in the 45th. Both are nearby and have a political makeup
more like the old 46th than the new 46th.
</P>
<P>
   Whether voters in either would be more forgiving than those in
the 46th is but a guess. But Dornan told The Orange County Register
last week that he would move to the 48th tomorrow should the
current congressman there, Ron Packard, also a Republican
conservative, retire _ something Packard is not known to be
contemplating. And he said he was considering moving to the 45th
because the congressman there, Dana Rohrabacher, another Republican
conservative, did not help him in his contests with Ms. Sanchez,
even though, he insisted, he earlier helped Rohrabacher win an
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biggest political mistake of my life,'' Dornan said, some of
the old bombast and anger again on display. ``I still haven't
forgiven him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
