</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: CANSECO'S REVIVAL GOES SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jose Canseco is not at Yankee Stadium this weekend with the
Toronto Blue Jays; he is in Florida with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
But he is with the Blue Jays in spirit, and therein lies the tale
of the man who is contributing to the early-season success of
perhaps the two most surprising teams in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Before losing to the Yankees on Friday night, the Blue Jays were
on an eight-game winning streak, and they still lead the AL East.
Before Saturday's game, the Devil Rays have won six consecutive
games and six out of seven overall from Boston and Baltimore.
Canseco was instrumental in both streaks.
</P>
<P>
   Separated seven years ago from his brother in bashing, Mark
McGwire, Canseco has enjoyed a revival in his specialty. He clubbed
a career-high 46 home runs for the Blue Jays last season and leads
the major leagues with eight this season. The Blue Jays wanted to
re-sign him as a free agent, but he opted to move south.
Nevertheless, he left a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing he did for us last year was he talked to the other
guys,'' Gord Ash, the Toronto general manager, said. ``I think they
needed to hear from someone other than the group they had been with
for five or six years that they were good players. The motivation
they had from him and the success we had late in the year enabled
them to turn the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Ash cited the improvement of the Blue Jays' younger players,
including Carlos Delgado, Shawn Green, Shannon Stewart and Alex
Gonzalez, as examples of Canseco's good work. Delgado and Green had
their best seasons last year and have made strong starts this
season, as have Stewart and Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   In Tampa Bay, meanwhile, Canseco has applied his personal touch.
Besides the example he provides with a bat in his hands, the
34-year-old designated hitter has spread his word as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings the attitude that he's just going to take his swings
and whatever happens happens,'' Larry Rothschild, the Devil Rays'
manager, said. ``I like that attitude: I'm going to take my best
shot. If it doesn't work this time, it will work next time. That's
had an effect on our players.''
</P>
<P>
   So has the communication Canseco has had with the younger
players, Rothschild said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll spend time with them, talk to them,'' Rothschild said.
``A lot of pressure is taken off them with him here. He's been a
lightning rod for the media. The other players are left alone to do
their thing. Everything Jose has done here has been positive in
every aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Even his swagger, Rothschild added. That, too, has been a factor
because it adds to the positive attitude Canseco exudes.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie team last year, the Devil Rays hit 111 home runs,
the lowest American League total since 1992. Entering Saturday's
games, the sophomore Devil Rays had hit 21 home runs in 18 games,
the third-highest total in the league and one more than the Yankees
had hit.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the No. 2 team in home runs was the Blue Jays,
who had hit 24 despite Canseco's departure. Green led with five
home runs and Delgado had four. Furthermore, the Blue Jays through
Friday had the second-highest batting average in the league and
were tied with Cleveland for the most runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   And they have mustered this lusty offense with little production
from the DH spot that Canseco abandoned. Not that the Blue Jays
didn't try to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted $28 million for four years,'' Ash said. Canseco
earned $2.25 million last year, and the Blue Jays, Ash said,
initially offered $1.5 million guaranteed with the chance to match
that amount in bonuses, then raised those figures to $3 million
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he and Roger were extremely close,'' the general manager
said, referring to Roger Clemens, who asked to be traded. ``Once
Roger made it known he wasn't coming back, Jose wasn't going to
come back. He did a good job here and we would have liked to have
him back, but at that point we weren't where we are ownerwise and
budgetwise. By the time we got that straightened out, he was
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays, not surprisingly, wanted a hitter with power.
Their designated hitters last season hit 16 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   They gave Canseco a guaranteed $2 million for this year with a
chance to earn an additional $2.9 million if he has 650 plate
appearances. He had 658 last season. They also have options for an
additional two years at salaries of $3 million and $4 million (plus
bonuses) that can automatically vest if he has 500 plate
appearances this season and 600 next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays have a similar record to the one they had at this
early stage of their first season, but they look like a better
team. They have played well defensively, and Canseco has powered an
offense that opponents must now take seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Angelos on the Orioles  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles are ahead of the pace that resulted in
their finishing 35 games from first last season. A year ago the
Orioles won 10 of their first 12 games and after 15 games were tied
for first. After 16 this season, through Friday, they were seven
and a half games behind.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ray Miller, the manager, does not seem to be in the trouble
many people think he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm asked am I going to fire him,'' Peter Angelos, the
Orioles' owner, said. ``My answer is no, he's the manager. What's
happening cannot be attributed to his lack of managerial
competence. There are moves that could be argued with. But the
breaks are not coming the Orioles' way or Miller's way. We'll have
to fight through a difficult period in a united sense. It's a
pretty good team. I think it will get itself together and have a
good season.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox Power Outage
</P>
<P>
   Whoever said the Boston Red Sox could survive the loss of Mo
Vaughn better check the team's statistics. Entering Saturday's
games, the Red Sox had the fewest home runs in the league by far,
not having even reached double digits. Their pitchers have saved
them, but they will be hard pressed to continue bailing out the
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   The Coors Field Blues
</P>
<P>
   Inheriting the mile-high pitching problem Don Baylor endured for
six seasons, Jim Leyland was determined to take a positive approach
as the new manager of the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coors Field thing is blown way out of proportion,''
Leyland said just before the season started. ``Everybody acts like
the Rockies are the only team that pitches there. There are two
pitchers that pitch in Coors Field. All you have to do is outpitch
the other guy, because I came in as a visitor and they're not too
happy either, especially with that lineup in that ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyland, who is being paid $2 million a year to fix the problem,
said the approach, while positive, also has to be realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't duck the fact that your earned run average probably
is going to be a point higher,'' he said. ``So what? The idea is to
win. You have to pitch better than the other pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyland spoke to the pitchers about the matter. ``It's not any
trick or any kind of psychology,'' he said. ``There are two
pitchers. Pitch better than the other pitcher. Maybe you give up
four runs instead of three or two that you would've given up
somewhere else, but we can score four runs.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first homestand as the Rockies' manager, Leyland watched
his team score more than four runs in each of five games. He also
saw his pitchers give up four runs twice and more than four three
times. In consecutive games, they gave up 20 runs and 10 runs,
severely testing the new manager's positive outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle's Championship Jinx
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle has pitched in post-season games in four different
years with two teams, once with Pittsburgh, three times with
Atlanta, but has yet to play on a World Series winner. He will not
be surprised if the Braves win this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my luck,'' said Neagle, who last week made an
injury-delayed start to his season for Cincinnati. ``When I leave
something, things get better. In high school, I was a senior and we
ranked third in the nation. We were 22-0 going into the playoffs
and we lost to some rinky-dink 65 mile-an-hour pitcher. The next
year we lost eight seniors and they said they might be fifth in the
county and they won the state championship. That's happened to me
everywhere I go, every time I leave. I guess I'm a jinx.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle joined the Braves in 1996, the year after they won the
World Series. They did not win in the next three years, the length
of the left-hander's tenure with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was my fault, I'd be the first to say it,'' Neagle said.
``It was my fault and it was everybody else's fault also. The most
frustrating year for me was '96 when we were leading New York, two
games to nothing. We should've won that. But we got outplayed,
outmanaged, everything. They beat us in every facet of the game in
the last four games.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Braves have won only one World Series despite seven
successive post-season appearances, Neagle feels the team and the
town have become jaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became like a second habit for people in Atlanta _ the
organization, the fans, everyone else,'' he said. ``They kind of
lost that electricity around the ballpark. We went to San Diego for
the league championship series last year and it was incredible. It
was something new to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle said he hoped he could find that feeling with the Reds.
``If we can get into the post-season,'' he said, ``the organization
and the city will be electrified.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
