<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO HAS AN EDGE IN WESTERN CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He had scored San Antonio's last 10 points, including the
game-winning 3-pointer with one-tenth of a second left to beat
Houston. Mario Elie, fresh from shooting down his old team, then
blew kisses to the crowd and cursed at his former Rockets
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been carrying them for five years in H-town, so I think a
50-game season here should be easy,'' Elie said this past week.
``This is what I bring to the team. This is what they wanted from
me. And I'm going to go out there and express myself.''
</P>
<P>
   This is referred to as ``having edge'' in the NBA. And more than
leapers or deadeye shooters, players with Elie's attitude can
usually be found on teams that play long into the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem that his emotional outbursts would not fit in on a
team dominated by Tim Duncan and David Robinson, the laid-back twin
towers. But then, there is not a lot about the Spurs this season
that resembles the passive team of past playoff failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team, more than any other team I've been on, hates
losing,'' Robinson said. ``We almost hate each other when we
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have been in a good mood since March 2, when they
began the league's most impressive string of consistent play: 24
victories in 28 games going into Saturday night's game against the
Lakers, a feat that erased a disastrous 6-8 start and thrust San
Antonio into Western Conference title contention with Utah and
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   In what could have been a preview of the conference final, the
Spurs snapped Utah's 11-game winning streak last week, 83-69, at
the Delta Center. In the second round of the playoffs last season,
San Antonio lost to the Jazz, four games to one.
</P>
<P>
   Few critics are calling Robinson soft anymore. Or asking point
guard Avery Johnson to stop denting the rim with his jump shot. An
infusion of veteran role players who have been to the finals _ Elie
(with the Rockets), Steve Kerr (with Chicago) and Jerome Kersey
(with Portland) _ have blended nicely with the holdovers Robinson,
Johnson and Sean Elliot.
</P>
<P>
   Malik Rose, a third-year forward Charlotte gave up on, is
playing key minutes off the bench along with Antonio Daniels. And
Duncan has been awesome, averaging 22.9 points, 11 rebounds, nearly
three blocked shots and more than two assists a game over the last
two months.
</P>
<P>
   By design, Robinson's minutes are down to 31 a game and his
other numbers are down as well (15.1 points and 9.7 rebounds). But
with a strong supporting cast, he may be a better bet to retire
with a championship than either Charles Barkley or Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to say he's been soft or didn't want it enough,''
said Gregg Popovich, the Spurs' coach. ``The truth is, David hasn't
been surrounded with a championship team. You can argue whether
Patrick or Charles has been, but I know David has not. Since he's
been there the longest, everyone wants to lay it on him. But other
than Hakeem Olajuwon, who's the last center to carry their team to
a title? It's hard in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Popovich is also not buying the theory that his team has
suddenly developed heart and an ornery streak on defense. After
all, he said, the Spurs led the league in opponents' field goal
percentage last season at 41.4 percent. They only gave up 88.5
points per game. (Their numbers this season are even stingier: they
allow 40.3 percent shooting and hold teams to 84.8 points.)
</P>
<P>
   But he does acknowledge how much a player like Elie can ignite a
team on a rare lethargic night; how role players can change the
chemistry of a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides confidence and mental toughness, when we lose a game,
Mario Elie hates every one of us,'' he said. ``He walks around
like, `When you want to hate losing as much I do, come back and
talk to me.' That makes our guys feel it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest story, I think, is not about our toughness,''
Popovich added. ``It's that ownership, the players and coaches were
all patient when everyone was down on us. When we were 6-8, it was
time to cut my head off and get rid of me. But we kept going to
work every day. Consequently, we got smarter and better and started
winning.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Divac Has Worldly Concerns
</P>
<P>
   While his homeland is being bombed, the Serbian center Vlade
Divac is trying to concentrate on helping the Sacramento Kings
secure what would be only their second playoff appearance in 14
years. Frequent phone calls to make sure his family is safe have
helped. But then reality intruded on Divac's basketball life again
last Tuesday, when his 28-year-old brother, Ivan, was drafted into
the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   Divac's parents live in Prijepolje, a small province north of
Kosovo. His brother and niece live in the Serbian capital of
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Divac and his Serbian teammate Predrag (Peja) Stojavokic have
worn black armbands during games since the airstrikes against
Yugoslavia began, and they have been accused of waging a silent
protest against NATO forces. But the center and the shooting guard
for the Kings say they are not choosing sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It signifies my sympathy for all the innocent people who have
died in my homeland, including people of all nationalities,'' Divac
said. ``Since I'm not able to be there, I'm able to show that I'm
thinking about everyone back there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Webber's Numbers Stand Out
</P>
<P>
   On the two teams he played on before the Sacramento Kings, Chris
Webber took his share of criticism for being part of the problem
instead of part of the solution. And it wasn't clear if he had
learned his lesson this February, when he implied that he was
trying to make the best of a bad situation with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But with a week left in the regular season, Webber's numbers and
his play have been phenomenal. If he were to finish the season with
his current averages of 20.2 points and 13.0 rebounds a game, he
would be the first non-center to post numbers at that level since
Charles Barkley during the 1986-87 season. Shaquille O'Neal is the
last player to average more than 20 points and 13 rebounds a game,
doing it in 1993-94 for Orlando. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Malone vs. Mourning
</P>
<P>
   In a straw poll of national basketball writers being taken by
The Deseret News in Utah, Karl Malone of the Jazz and Alonzo
Mourning of the Miami Heat appear to be the clear favorites for
most valuable player. It will be interesting to see how much
genuine consideration Mourning is given in the actual vote since
Malone's relationship with the media has always been much more
chummy than that of the often-glowering Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   If Mourning does not win the award, he should receive defensive
player of the year honors. No one is more relentless or alters more
shots. For the first time in his career, it is possible to argue
that Mourning has bypassed Patrick Ewing, his one-time mentor, in
the unofficial ranking of elite centers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Riley Takes High Road
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley should have a better take than most people on the
Knicks' reassignment of Ernie Grunfeld, given that Riley, the
Heat's president and coach, worked closely with Grunfeld in New
York and wanted the job of team president before his power struggle
with Dave Checketts and subsequent departure in 1995. But Riley,
quizzed often on the subject last week, preferred to take the high
road. ``It will be construed as negative if I talk about it, so I'm
not going to,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
