<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEE-BLUEJAYS-N     04-24 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEE-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS' HOME RUN PACES YANKS OVER BLUE JAYS, 7-4 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There were no standing ovations or rabid cheers
coming from the right-field bleachers for a Blue Jay Saturday as
there had been Friday night. David Wells was in the dugout for
Saturday's game, so the focus was only on baseball, and the Yankee
Stadium fans cheered only their own, especially Chili Davis.
</P>
<P>
   After a sometimes sluggish and sloppy afternoon, Davis earned
the sort of rousing ovation that Wells secured on Friday. He
crushed a three-run homer off Dan Plesac in the bottom of the
eighth inning, a majestic shot that hit off the facade of the upper
deck in left field, to catapult the Yankees to a 7-4 victory over
the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams started the rally with a double into the
left-field corner before Tino Martinez walked on a 3-2 pitch.
Davis, who had been 0 for 6 off the left-handed Plesac in his
career, had already struck out twice and grounded out in three
at-bats. But after Plesac jumped ahead in the count, 0-2, the
designated hitter drilled a fastball to deep left to break a 4-4
tie with his fifth home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza relieved Andy Pettitte in the eighth and recorded
the victory as the Yankees (11-5) won their fourth straight game
and continued to throttle a team that had been sharper than any in
baseball. The Blue Jays (12-6), who are now percentage points
behind the first-place Yankees in the American League East, rolled
into the Bronx with an eight-game winning streak. But Toronto has
lost the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the bottom of the fourth inning, and the
Yankees trailing, 2-0, it had become obvious why Roy Halladay had
not permitted an earned run through his first 19 innings this
season. Tall and lanky, with an overhand motion and an explosive
fastball, Halladay is imposing on the mound. This was only his
seventh major league appearance, and he will not turn 22 for three
weeks, but Halladay has incredible poise and presence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he walked Ricky Ledee and that gave the Yankees an
opening. Halladay probably thought the inning was over when Luis
Sojo rapped a grounder to shortstop, but Alex Gonzalez threw wide
to Pat Kelly at second base, and the ball rolled away, enabling
Ledee to scoot to third. After Joe Girardi walked to fill the
bases, Chuck Knoblauch squirted a single to right that evened the
score at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Now Halladay was sweating a little with Derek Jeter batting.
Jeter had struck out in the first inning and singled in the third.
If Halladay could retire Jeter, he could save Gonzalez from having
to dwell on his error as well as keep the game tied. But Jeter
smacked a single to almost the same spot as Knoblauch had, just
past a diving Kelly and into right field, and two more runs scored
to put the Yankees in front, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Halladay left after four innings, still not having given up an
earned run this season.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, who was making his first start in eight days, tried to
protect the lead, but the Yankees were also guilty of sloppy
execution. After Carlos Delgado walked and Tony Fernandez doubled
in the sixth, Geronimo Berroa rolled a ball to the right of the
mound. Pettitte saw Delgado charging home and started a rundown
play that ended with Delgado being tagged out near third. Fernandez
had already reached third, but Sojo thought he had a chance to nab
Berroa, who was going to second, and he fired the ball to
Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   As Knoblauch tried to tag Berroa, the ball came loose and
Fernandez rushed home with the Blue Jays' third run. Berroa went to
third on Gonzalez's soft single to right-center between Bernie
Williams and Paul O'Neill and scored on Mike Matheny's grounder to
make the score 4-4. Pettitte allowed three earned runs and seven
hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Jays had jumped to a 2-0 lead in the first, the runs driven
in by Shawn Green's groundout and Delgado's single.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
