<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BLAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON BOMB INJURES AT LEAST SEVEN, A WEEK AFTER BOMB HURT 39
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ At least seven people were injured Saturday when an
explosion tore through a street market in an area of east London
that has a large Bangladeshi population, one week to the day after
a home-made nail-bomb went off in a crowded market in another
racially mixed area.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's blast shattered windows and started fires in
buildings at Brick Lane, casting a pall of black smoke over the
area. ``It looked like a scene from a war zone,'' said Raja Miah, a
resident who saw the aftermath of the explosion. ``I saw a car
ablaze with pieces of shrapnel and debris all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said they saw a man place a sports bag in the trunk of
a car shortly before the blast, but a police officer,
Superintendent David Finnimore, said he believed the man had been
trying to drive the bag to a nearby police station after finding it
in the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press said one of its photographers, who lives in
the area, reported that the explosion blew off the car's roof and
windows.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials and the police said the injuries from the
explosion seemed light.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, at a busy street market in racially mixed
Brixton, in south London, a man left a homemade nail-bomb near
market stalls. That explosion injured 39 people. After several
extreme right-wing groups claimed responsibility, the police said
they were treating the incident as a racial attack.
</P>
<P>
   One claim of responsibility was made from a public telephone
near the spot in south London where a black teen-ager, Stephen
Lawrence, was killed in a case that has become a national
touchstone of tensions between black Britons and the police.
British newspapers have openly accused a group of young, white
Britons of killing Lawrence, but none of them has ever been
punished.
</P>
<P>
   Oona King, a local legislator, said Saturday she believed the
bombings were ``obviously part of a backlash'' against inquiries
into police mishandling of investigations into the Lawrence murder.
The police said anti-terrorism officers were trying to establish
whether the bomb explosions were linked, as many residents Sunday
seemed to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The Brick Lane market draws hundreds of shoppers and is also
packed with people because of its well-patronized curry
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Dunstan Gunashinga, another resident, said there had been fears
of a bomb attack in Brick Lane after a series of anonymous
telephone threats this week to storekeepers in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Brick Lane was well-known to Britons two decades ago for a
campaign by anti-racism activists demanding the closure of an
office run by the far-right National Front. One of the activist
leaders, a 33-year-old schoolteacher called Blair Peach, was killed
20 years ago Saturday when the police tried to break up protests in
another part of London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
