<SLUG> BC-SYNDROME-GAY-WIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY MAN CHARGED IN A KILLING CAN USE A `BATTERED WIFE' DEFENSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Stagno was a controlling and jealous boyfriend
who threatened his live-in partner with a knife and a bottle, and
kept the only key to their Crown Heights apartment, according to
papers filed by a lawyer in Brooklyn Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   So when Stagno, 32, brandished a bottle in December 1997 and his
partner fought back, stabbing him to death, it seemed like a
classic case of ``battered-wife syndrome,'' the partner's lawyer
has argued. Except that the partner, John Pickett, 33, is a man.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, in a ruling that lawyers say is unprecedented, a
Brooklyn justice, John M. Leventhal, said Pickett could use the
battered-wife argument to bolster his claim that he killed Stagno
in self-defense. Prosecutors, who have charged him with
second-degree murder, had opposed the battered-wife claim.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, the battered-wife argument was used in a
Florida case involving two lesbians, Pickett's lawyer, Arthur
Aidala, said. But he said he knew of no case involving two men in
which the defense had been used.
</P>
<P>
   Aidala said that, despite Pickett's sex, he suffered from low
self-esteem and emotional dependency, classic elements of
battered-wife syndrome. ``He was trying to muster up the strength
and energy to leave,'' Aidala said. ``But where does a gay, black,
HIV-positive man turn for help?''
</P>
<P>
   When Pickett first moved in with Stagno in early 1997, Aidala
said, his client had a job at K-Mart. But he said that Stagno, who
was unemployed, controlled the couple's finances and gave Pickett a
daily allowance of 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   After Stagno, in a jealous rage, attacked a male K-Mart employee
with whom Pickett spoke, Pickett was fired. As his dependency and
isolation deepened, apparently the abuse escalated. In August of
1997, Stagno slashed Pickett's hand with a knife during a fight.
Though Pickett called the police, officers played down the incident
and arrested both men, said Aidala.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to end the relationship, Pickett approached the Gay
and Lesbian Anti-Violence project and met with a counselor there,
Aidala said. But on Dec. 5, after Pickett announced that he was
leaving, Stagno threatened him with a bottle and a knife, Aidala
said. Pickett then stabbed Stagno twice in the chest, killing him.
</P>
<P>
   Pickett is being held at the Rikers Island Detention Center.
Jury selection is expected to begin on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
