u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-TRENCHCOA     04-24 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-TRENCHCOATS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LITTLETON: that simple.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Koeniger, a 17-year-old junior on the Columbine Rebels
football team, acknowledged that some athletes teased the trench
coat mafia, but said the group often seemed to be asking for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're different, why wouldn't we look at them as weird?''
he asked, recalling a student last year who wore tight jeans, had
long hair and seemed to never shower.
</P>
<P>
   But like so many groups before them, the trench coat mafia
embraced what started as a kind of epithet and made it their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it up; we were like, oh, look at them, the trench coat
mafia,'' recalled Ashly Beeson, 18, who left Columbine a couple of
months ago to escape the cliques and finish her senior year at an
alternative school. ``It's nothing they gave themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As the rest of the people in town appear at makeshift memorials
of flowers and banners, sobbing on television about the events that
have overtaken the community, members of the trench coat mafia and
their friends have spent much of the past week talking to the
police.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities believe that the arsenal of bombs and other
weapons was more than two boys could carry even under their large
trench coats. If they had help, most people suspect it came from
the group.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Boles, a large woman in a housecoat, would not let a
reporter talk to her son, who quit school a few months ago and was,
she said, sleeping upstairs in the small house near noon on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just kids,'' she said, pointing out that her son plays
the cello, while his friend, Morris, plays the violin. ``All of
them are in shock. They're all destroyed; I don't know, they're
never going to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the little ones, even this one's affected, he senses our
moods,'' she said, bouncing her 5-month-old grandson Seth, whose
mother also attended Columbine, on her lap. ``His mom sat here with
us the other day. She said, `We're going to teach our kids
better.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
