<SLUG> BC-NY-OFFICE-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL BUSINESS HUNTS FOR A HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine)  (lb) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Donna Torrance did not think it would be all that
hard to find a few thousand square feet of office space to
establish a New York studio for VIA, a design and marketing firm
based in Portland, Maine. After all, there are more than 400
million square feet of office space in Manhattan. Surely something
could be found.
</P>
<P>
   Not easily, as it turned out. Hampered by a tight budget and
specific requirements, and competing with other office space users
in a hot market, it took Ms. Torrance nine months to sign a lease
for an office, on the eighth, or top, floor of a building at Canal
and Varick Streets overlooking the entrance to the Holland Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with the Manhattan real estate market was a new
experience for Ms. Torrance, whose background is in art direction
and marketing and whose biography notes that she has ``made time to
get a master's degree in publishing and marketing from Harvard,
learn to cook and do Eskimo rolls in a kayak.''
</P>
<P>
   She had to look for space, with and without brokers, hire people
and do work for clients simultaneously. She started out in her
apartment in the Flatiron District, moved into sublet space on the
second floor of the building at 417 Canal St., occupied part of the
eighth floor while workers hammered and sawed around her and
finally was able to expand into the fully built out space in
January.
</P>
<P>
   She says she is pleased with the outcome, but appears still a
little bewildered by the time and effort needed to make it all
happen. Part of the problem was that she had a combination of needs
that were hard to satisfy at any one affordable place.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the requirements was that the location had to be
safe,'' said Ms. Torrance, whose title is strategic principal in
the firm. ``This is a service business, where you have to put in
long hours at times. It had to be a place where it is safe to leave
at 3 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Another, related, requirement was that the building had to be
close to mass transit. At 3 a.m., a long walk to a subway or bus
stop can be distinctly uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Since the firm does design work, abundant natural light was
necessary, eliminating many parts of town where closely packed
buildings get little outside light.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Torrance wanted running water in the space so a kitchen
could be installed to help feed employees working long hours.
Air-conditioning was needed as well.
</P>
<P>
   And because the company is in the image-building business, the
studio had to be in a part of town that was considered cool by
others in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Situated to the west of SoHo and north of TriBeCa, the
neighborhood does not have a specific name, but it is close enough
to the better-known areas to be considered cool by association, she
argues.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine-based partners originally thought of SoHo, so Ms.
Torrance looked there early on. Not only was it too expensive at an
annual rent of $25 to $28 a square foot, but, she said, most of the
space being offered was on lower floors with no view and little
natural light. The Flatiron District was eliminated for similar
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was midtown an option, even on the far west side. ``I
quickly realized that was not an option,'' she said, adding that
areas once considered on the fringe of the central business
district were commanding annual rents over $35 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   The search became so discouraging that she split the task with
her office manager, Stephanie Lewis. ``I looked for sublet space
while Stephanie looked for real-time space,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When they found the building at 417 Canal St. after responding
to a newspaper advertisement, a lot was right about it. It is
across from a stop on the 1-9 subway line. The top floor of the
1911 building, which is owned by Trinity Church, received plenty of
light from 26 large windows and a skylight in the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skylight leaked, but it was there,'' Ms. Torrance said.
Because of the Holland Tunnel entrance there are no tall buildings
to block the light from the south, and a small park opens up the
space's eastern exposure as well.
</P>
<P>
   There was water available on the floor, although the existing
sink was old and leaked as well. And there was an air conditioner
on the roof, which Trinity Church promised to fix.
</P>
<P>
   The price was also right, at $15 a square foot early in 1998,
rising in subsequent years. It is currently $18 a square foot.
Three months of free rent were part of the deal, plus a little over
$12 a square foot for interior work.
</P>
<P>
   But the space available was 3,000 square feet, one-third more
than the 2,000 square feet Ms. Torrance was seeking. ``I figured
about 100 square feet per person, and we were planning an 18-person
office,'' she said. ``But a 2,000-square-foot space was impossible
to find.'' The extra space allowed for larger offices and a
substantial conference room.
</P>
<P>
   The drawback was the condition of the space. There was asbestos
in the flooring, and previous tenants had ripped out most of the
wiring. And it was raw space that would have to be designed and
built before there could be proper offices and meeting rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space was a mess, and I didn't want to have to hire an
architect and build out the space,'' Ms. Torrance said. ``I didn't
want to have to deal with contractors. That's not the business I'm
in.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is what she did, hiring Edward Mills Architects to
design the space, which is divided by a diagonal spine into
administrative and design areas. A new floor was put down and the
paint on the radiators hanging from the outside walls was treated
with wire brushes to create a distressed look.
</P>
<P>
   A big concern was wiring, both for electric power and for the
high capacity telecommunications links essential to a
computer-based company. ``I had to put two T-1 lines into the
building because I could not find space with T-1s already
installed,'' Ms. Torrance said.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity's real estate managers have apparently got the message
that high-capacity telecommunications are a big tenant draw and are
installing the lines at a nearby building formerly known as 75
Varick St. that it is renovating and remarketing as 1 Hudson
Square.
</P>
<P>
   Wiring was the biggest part of the job, and consumed $36,000 of
Ms. Torrance's $100,000 renovation budget.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because of the wiring cost, the rest of the space was furnished
in a fashion that appears to combine a 1950s motel look with high
tech. All the wiring is carried overhead in racks originally
designed for the French dairy industry. Some desks are old
stainless steel food-preparation tables from restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The spine that divides the space consists of fiberboard boxes
secured by sheets of semitransparent sand-blasted acrylic. ``Almost
all this stuff is recycled,'' said Johan Vipper, the design
principal of the New York studio, who contributed ideas to the
project.
</P>
<P>
   And it is in turn recyclable. ``This place is like a movie set _
if we leave we take it with us,'' Ms. Torrance said. ``We will lose
the wiring, though.''
</P>
<P>
   She rolls her eyes when describing dealing with contractors,
whose crews she said made life difficult for the studio by cutting
off power at critical times. ``They cut the wiring,'' she said,
``and without wiring we can't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, she said, they cut power to the alarm system that
helps ensure that the top-of-the-line computers VIA's people work
on are still there when they return to work in the morning. ``That
would be hot merchandise a little farther down Canal Street,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the alarm was disabled, Ms. Torrance had to hire a guard to
stay overnight to protect the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   At first, she said, she was concerned that the noise on Canal
Street from the Holland Tunnel traffic would be a nuisance. And the
noise level is near deafening at street level, with visitors to the
building forced to shout into the intercom to make themselves
understood.
</P>
<P>
   But eight stories up, it is not a problem. ``We leave our
windows open in nice weather,'' she said, ``and it is quite
pleasant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
