<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-752&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.) 
INSURANCE CAN COME IN HANDY FOR APARTMENT OWNERS, RENTERS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Marilyn Scarano returned home from work on March
18, she saw smoke billowing from the roof of her 96-unit co-op
building in Long Beach, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Watching firefighters pour water into the building, Ms. Scarano
said, her only consolation was that she and her husband, Bob, had
insurance coverage for the furniture, fixtures and personal
belongings in their apartment.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long, however, for Mrs. Scarano to discover that
their insurance would cover only a fraction of what would be needed
to restore their life to what it was before the fire. But the
Scaranos' plight paled when compared with the problems facing some
of their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day after the fire they let us back into the building to
get whatever personal belongings we could find,'' she said. ``A
couple on the sixth floor who were subleasing their apartment were
rummaging through their things looking for something they could
take with them. You could see the sky through their ceiling.
Everything in the apartment was wet and covered with soot. And
these people didn't have a dime in insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire in Long Beach _ occurring just one week after another
fire that drove residents from their homes in the Manhasset, a
134-unit co-op on Broadway at 108th Street in Manhattan _ has
focused renewed attention on why it is critical for apartment
owners and renters to have their own insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has to understand the importance of having
insurance,'' said Deborah Beck, vice president of the Real Estate
Board of New York. ``And our residential management council is now
making a strong recommendation that renters and apartment owners
should be made aware of the need for such coverage and should be
encouraged to seek it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beck explained that a common misunderstanding among rental
tenants, co-op shareholders and condominium unit owners _ is that
the building's hazard insurance policy covers their belongings in
the event of a fire or other catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to realize that the building's policy will not
cover them,'' Ms. Beck said. ``And any prudent tenant would be
remiss if they didn't explore the possibility of buying their own
insurance coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Kirschenbaum, senior managing director and general counsel
for Insignia Residential Group, a property management company in
Manhattan that is a subsidiary of Insignia/ESG, said that rental
tenants frequently fail to obtain insurance because they believe
that losses they incur that are not the result of their own actions
will be covered by someone else's insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the landlord is usually liable to a tenant only when the
landlord was negligent or engaged in willful misconduct,''
Kirschenbaum said. In most cases, he added, things like fires and
burst pipes are not the fault of the property owner.
</P>
<P>
   And even if a tenant has legal grounds to sue the responsible
party, Kirschenbaum said, that is little consolation to a displaced
tenant who needs clothes, lodging and furniture immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Tenants who have their own insurance, on the other hand, he
said, will have those immediate needs met while the insurance
company handles the business of finding out who is ultimately
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Strauss, senior vice president of The Owens Group, an
independent insurance agent based in Englewood Cliffs, N.J., said
that while having insurance coverage is important for renters, it
is critical for apartment owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is because improvements and permanent alterations in an
apartment are usually the unit owner's responsibility,'' she said,
explaining that things like kitchen cabinets, built-in storage
units, carpets, wallpaper and even refinished wood floors are
generally the responsibility of the unit owner. In fact, Ms.
Strauss said, since most ``improvements'' in a typical apartment
are already in the apartment when a new owner moves it, it is easy
to forget that they are nonetheless the current owner's
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she said, it is easy to underestimate what it would
cost to restore a fire-or water-damaged apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that for a couple with two children in an
apartment in a luxury building the coverage needed for personal
property and improvements should be at least $100,000 for each,''
Ms. Strauss said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert E. Mackoul, president of Mackoul &AMP; Associates, an
insurance agent in Lynbrook, N.Y., said that apartment residents
should also make sure they have liability coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This protects you and your family against lawsuits resulting
from injuries to other people or damage to their property,''
Mackoul said, adding that personal liability coverage also provides
protection for things that occur off the insured premises.
</P>
<P>
   Another valuable coverage for apartment owners, Mackoul said, is
loss assessment coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your building doesn't have adequate insurance coverage to
pay for property damage or a liability lawsuit,'' Mackoul said,
``this will cover your share of any assessment passed along to unit
owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackoul said that an apartment owner's policy with $100,000
coverage for personal property, $100,000 for improvements and
alterations, $300,000 in personal liability coverage and $10,000 in
loss assessment coverage would cost about $600 a year with a $500
deductible. A renter's policy would be about $350 because loss
assessment and improvements and alteration coverages are not
required.
</P>
<P>
   Mackoul pointed out that those who want ``guaranteed replacement
cost'' insurance can expect to pay up to 20 percent more in annual
premiums. Such coverage is often worth the extra cost, he said,
because standard coverage provides payments based on the
depreciated value of an item or improvement while replacement cost
coverage provides the amount needed to replace each covered item at
today's prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it takes is one bad experience to find out how important
it is to insure everything properly,'' Mackoul said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Scarano, who lost nearly everything in the fire at her
Ocean Terrace co-op, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sat down and figured out how much we lost, and
compared that to how much we were covered for, it was utterly
ridiculous,'' she said. ``People think that something like this
will never happen to them. That's what I thought. And all I can
tell you now is that I'll never put myself in the same position
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
