<SLUG> BC-NY-FORGERY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE FOR WATERGATE TAPE LEFT COLLECTORS CREDULOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John F. Kennedy. Marilyn Monroe. The Chicago mobster
Sam Giancana. Sure. But the missing Watergate tapes?
</P>
<P>
   History took another tortured turn last week in the trial of
Lawrence Cusack III, the former paralegal accused of forging papers
in Kennedy's handwriting and selling them for millions of dollars
to investors.
</P>
<P>
   As Cusack has told it, he found the documents linking the former
president to the actress and the mobster in the files of his late
father, a prominent lawyer in New York. He contended that his
father, Lawrence Cusack Jr., who had represented the Roman Catholic
Archdiocese of New York before his death in 1985, had been a
confidant of Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But as government prosecutors contended in U.S. District Court
in Manhattan last week, Cusack told even taller tales to his
partners in the effort to market the so-called Kennedy papers. He
boasted to two of them that he had found the papers of other major
political figures in his father's files, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack said that these included the papers of former Presidents
Nixon and Carter, and those of W. Averell Harriman, witnesses
testified. There was also a reel-to-reel tape that Cusack said
Nixon had given to his father, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The government did not say that Cusack had actually sold fake
Nixon or Carter papers, but the prosecutors did suggest, through
testimony, that Cusack had at least contemplated such a scheme.
They also implied that it would have been highly implausible for
the elder Cusack to have been a confidant of Kennedy and then later
enjoy the confidences of his political rival Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, rather than set off alarms in the minds of his business
partners, Cusack's extraordinary claims only further whetted their
appetites, according to their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   One partner, Thomas Cloud, a collectibles dealer from Atlanta,
told the jury that Cusack said the tape was given to his father by
Nixon's wife, Pat.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud asked Cusack whether he could hear the tape. Cusack
replied that he had wanted to have it transcribed, but had never
done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was concerned,'' Cloud testified, ``about the fragility of
it, for one thing, and the confidentiality of it, for another.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud said he told Cusack, ``It would be nice if it was the
missing minutes,'' as he put it, ``the missing minutes of
Watergate. ''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack ``kind of smiled,'' Cloud said. ``He didn't really say
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   John Reznikoff, an autograph dealer in Connecticut who was
acting as Cusack's agent in the sale of the Kennedy papers, said
that Cusack had a similar conversation with him.
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff said he had been told by Cusack that Nixon had
approached his father because he ``had some tax issues that related
to Watergate.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack also said Nixon had visited their home and given his
father ``some things for safekeeping,'' including a reel-to-reel
tape, Reznikoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff said he had once visited Cusack at home and was shown
a small mail bag that contained a tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that came from Nixon,'' Reznikoff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you at any point ask him to play the tape?'' asked the
prosecutor, Paul Engelmayer, an assistant U.S attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time,'' Reznikoff said. ``I'm thinking to myself,
maybe this is like the 18 minutes that are missing.'' He added
wistfully, ``Half dreaming, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack never did play the tape for him, Reznikoff told the jury.
He said Cusack had told him, ```First let's handle the JFK archive
and then maybe later we will handle this.' It was a carrot for the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack, 48, has sat quietly by his lawyer's side throughout the
trial, smiling occasionally, appearing confident and relaxed. He is
dressed conservatively, as if to counteract the prosecutor's
portrayal of him at the beginning of the case: In his opening
statement, Engelmayer said Cusack had embarked upon ``a life of
ferocious, unrelenting consumption: Luxury stores, luxury cars,
luxury clothes. It was built entirely upon the documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusack's lawyer, Robert Katzberg, also raised the issue of his
lifestyle early on. In his opening statement, he said Cusack's
spending habits were not the issue. If at the end of the case, he
told the jurors, ``you love this man'' but the evidence shows that
he is guilty, the jury should convict Cusack, Katzberg said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the jurors did not like his client, he added, that should
not be a factor if they otherwise felt the government had not
proved its case.
</P>
<P>
   The jury may get to decide the issue soon. The trial, once
expected to last more than a month, may conclude within a week, the
lawyers told Judge Denise Cote on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the trial has not bogged down has been the judge
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Politely but firmly, she has kept a tight reign on both sides.
Every minute seems to count.
</P>
<P>
   When Katzberg asked for ``an extra 15 minutes of lunch'' one day
last week so that he and a prosecutor could speak with an upcoming
government witness in an attempt to narrow the scope of the
testimony, he had no luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, counsel,'' Cote said. ``It will have to come out of
your sandwich time. We are not going to take an extra-long lunch
break.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
