<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US PLANS ROUND-THE-CLOCK BOMBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO deepened its month-old military campaign in
Yugoslavia on Saturday, announcing plans for an around-the-clock
air war, hinting that US attack helicopters would soon see combat,
and planning to beef up its Adriatic fleet to choke off oil
shipments to the Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as President Clinton and leaders of 18
other nations drafted a bold ``strategic concept'' for the
50-year-old NATO alliance that will formalize the intervention in
Yugoslavia and open the door to similar action in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that our strategic concept specifically endorses
the actions such as those we are undertaking in Kosovo,'' Clinton
said at a news conference, adding that for the air war against
Yugoslavia to succeed ``we need two things. One: vigorous
execution. And two: patience.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's secretary general, Javier Solana, said the alliance had
``created the elements of a new NATO'' in which protection of human
rights and democratic values would become as important as
collective security.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's defense ministers, meanwhile, promised
General Wesley K. Clark, its supreme commander, ``all the
operational assets that he requires . . . to prosecute the air
campaign with maximum effect,'' said NATO spokesman Jamie P. Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Clark also will have new ``flexibility'' to launch air attacks,
said Shea. He will get more tanker and reconnaissance aircraft to
help with continuous raids, and freedom to send the 24 AH64A Apache
attack helicopters in Albania into low-altitude combat in
Yugoslavia as soon as they are ready.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NATO will plan an interdiction program for oil
shipments bound for Montenegro, the port for its sister republic,
Serbia. The eight-ship NATO task force patrolling the Adriatic Sea
``may need to be augmented'' to carry this out, said Shea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we doing this?'' Shea asked. ``Essentially because
without oil, the Yugoslav military machine will come to a halt and
very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, on a visit to Egypt, said
his country will ignore any NATO attempt to impose an oil embargo.
``According to international law, sanctions cannot be imposed
unless they are approved by the Security Council,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and the European Union last week moved to impose the oil
embargo. But stopping ships on the high seas is especially
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac of France has expressed concern that
such action is traditionally considered an act of war. Clinton said
NATO is working on a plan that ``we don't expect . . . to lead to
violence.'' With Chirac's concerns in mind, NATO has gingerly
termed interdiction ``visit and search,'' not stop and search.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO will begin an updated round of contingency planning
for a possible ground war and has been increasing the troop
strength of its Task Force Hawk in Albania, Shea said, it is still
satisfied that the 33-day-old bombing strategy is working and is
not ready to consider a land war.
</P>
<P>
   In related developments Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   -- NATO jets pounded oil facilities and military targets
throughout Serbia proper and the province of Kosovo. The strikes
reportedly included a refinery in the northern city of Novi Sad, as
well as on areas southeast and southwest of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   -- Thousands of Serb civilians marched by candlelight to a
church in Belgrade to express their anger at the bombing Friday of
the Serb TV headquarters, according to the state Tanjug news
agency. Authorities said the attack killed 15 civilians and wounded
30.
</P>
<P>
   -- Russian's envoy to the Balkans, Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, said
in Moscow that he had no diplomatic initiatives planned beyond
those he has already taken. But he said he had received requests
from the leaders of several NATO countries to meet with them about
his efforts to end the crisis in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Serb-run Media Center in Kosovo said five ethnic Albanian
children died and six were hurt when they accidentally set off a
NATO cluster bomb in a field where it had fallen without
detonating. There was no independent confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   -- In Lafayette Park across Pennsylvania Avenue from the White
House, more than 4,000 pro-Serb activists, most of them
Serbian-Americans, protested the NATO bombing campaign against
Kosovo. They also held a Serbian-Orthodox religious service and
released hundreds of black balloons.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators compared NATO to Nazi Germany and shouted that
Kosovo is part of Serbia. Their shouts, while louder than those of
a smaller group of Albanians who rallied the day before, were
barely audible at the site of the summit in the Ronald Reagan
Building. Between the demonstrators and the NATO leaders were
blocks of a no-access zone in the Federal Triangle area, as well as
layer upon layer of security _ from Secret Service agents to SWAT
teams to gun-toting bicycle policemen.
</P>
<P>
   The political leaders of NATO devised their new alliance
strategy while meeting inside the gilded Mellon Auditoriam, where
their predecessors vowed to defend one another against the Soviet
Union half a century ago. NATO's revised mission, they said, will
allow aggressive action to protect human rights, placing them above
an individual nation's right to sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has pledged, said Solana, to become an ``upholder of
democratic values both within and beyond our borders.'' When asked
if NATO would act only under authorization by the UN Security
Council, he said, ``No.'' Solana indicated that Euro-American
security issues could include protection of Persian Gulf oil
supplies. During the 1991 Gulf War, NATO forces operated against
Iraq, but not under the NATO banner.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this summit, Kosovo and similar conflicts have been
high on the agenda as presidents and prime ministers discussed
turning their Cold War military alliance into a 21st-century tool
for stamping out the kind of ethnic persecution that has raged in
the Balkans for most of the 1990s and that killed tens of millions
in Europe between 1914 and 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis in Kosovo has underscored the importance of NATO
and the imperative of modernizing our lives for 21st-century
challenges,'' Clinton told leaders of NATO nations, plus
delegations from 25 other nations in Europe and central Asia that
are part of a looser NATO partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's closest NATO ally, British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
last week foreshadowed the change in NATO's strategy when he called
for ``a new doctrine of international community.'' Rather than
refraining from military intervention in the affairs of a sovereign
nation _ a position Western leaders have taken since the end of
World War II _ Blair's notion is to justify intervention to protect
Western values.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acts of genocide can never be a purely internal matter,'' said
Blair, outlining a five-step decision-making process that Western
nations would use before sending forces.
</P>
<P>
   These steps include being sure of the case for intervention,
exhausting all diplomatic efforts, studying the military
feasibility of intervention, ensuring that nations involved can
deal with a long-term commitment, and resolving any issues of
national interest among member nations.
</P>
<P>
   Non-NATO nations are sure to oppose the new intervention policy,
arguing that it could herald an era in which big powers again
impose their wills on little ones.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from the Blair doctrine is UN
authorization, which was not explicitly obtained before Operation
Allied Force began but was considered crucial in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Solana and other NATO officials say earlier UN resolutions on
Kosovo provided justification to act, but they have also drafted a
resolution that will mirror NATO's conditions for stopping the
bombing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
