<HEADLINE>
NATO EMBARGO PLAN PRODUCES RIFT WITH FRANCE, ANGER FROM RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Exposing a rift in their own ranks and risking a
potential head-on collision with Russia, NATO leaders began
planning Saturday to stop and search ships suspected of carrying
oil to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal in the decision, which they reached Friday night, was
to choke off fuel used by military forces arrayed against ethic
Albanians in Kosovo, the rebellious southernmost province of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As French President Jacques Chirac voiced misgivings about
stopping ships and Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said his
country would ignore any NATO decision to do so, alliance leaders
defended the plan, which could sharply escalate the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said at a news conference Saturday that it
made no military sense to allow new oil shipments to arrive in
Montenegro, Yugoslavia's junior republic that has a port on the
Adriatic Sea, while NATO pilots bomb refineries throughout Serbia,
the nation's dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we justify risking the lives of the pilots to go up
and destroy the refinery and the supply capacity of Serbia and then
say, `But it's okay with us if people want to continue to supply
this nation and its outlaw actions in Kosovo in another way,'?''
Clinton asked.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana vowed
to do ``whatever is in our means and our capabilities'' to shut
down the shipments, including the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea called the proposed interdiction a
``visit-and-search regime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we doing this? Essentially because without oil, the
Yugoslav military machine will come to a halt and very quickly,''
Shea said. ``It is very important for us to continue ... to tighten
the taps, switch off the oil tap completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few days, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the top
commander of the 19-member North Atlantic Treaty Organization, will
put together a blueprint for the interdiction mission, which would
expand the military campaign against Yugoslavia that began March 24
with aerial assaults.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's embargo, which followed a similar action taken Friday by
the 15-member European Union, covers the supply of oil and refined
products to Yugoslavia but specifically excludes supplies for
relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   France's Chirac, while expressing support for the oil embargo,
told reporters Saturday that searching a ship on the high seas,
which directly challenges a nation's sovereignty, is a``very
sensitive'' matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``To search is fine if the ship that you want to search allows
itself to be searched,'' Chirac said. ``But let's assume that the
ship doesn't allow itself to be searched and that you have to board
it forcibly ... That's an act of war,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Friday of NATO leaders, France was the only NATO
ally to express reservations about the proposal, Chirac said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Ivanov, explaining Russia's intention to ignore the
embargo, said, ``According to international law, sanctions cannot
be imposed unless they are approved by the (United Nations)
Security Council. We abide by the international law and not NATO
decisions,'' Ivanov said Saturday in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue delivering oil in keeping with our
international commitments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which has veto power in the Security Council, has had a
prickly relationship with NATO. It has opposed the alliance's
recent expansion to include Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic.
But it has also sought to broker a peace settlement between its
longtime ally, Yugoslavia, and the western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin warned that
the world ``may slip toward a third world war, the final war'' as a
result of NATO's bombing. Chernomyrdin said he had received
invitations from NATO countries to discuss his recent mediation
efforts with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to end the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Solana, seeking to encourage Russia's efforts despite the
escalating tension over the embargo, said he appreciates ``very,
very much what the Russian authorities are doing, what Chernomyrdin
is doing, and I wish that he succeeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Solana added that NATO's diplomatic contacts with Russia ``will
be intensified'' because of the interdiction proposal. ``And I hope
very much that we'll get a common position with the Russians on the
issue,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he did not expect sea searches to lead to violence
but added that ``we have to be firm about it'' and ``take every
reasonable means'' to ensure the success of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a questioner who asked if NATO is drifting into an
unending war, the president called once more for patience among the
allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that this air campaign has been going on for a
particularly long time,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Persian Gulf there were 44 days of bombing before there
was any kind of land action. And the land was flatter, the targets
were clearer, the weather was better,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO leaders approved a new ``strategic concept''
Saturday that authorizes the alliance to confront crises beyond its
borders. The document lays out a framework for addressing growing
risks to European stability such as terrorism, rogue states with
weapons of mass destruction, and ethnic and regional conflicts like
that in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
