<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1880 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-BOS &LR;      04-24 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIARY TOLD OF PLOT TO KILL CLASSMATES, DESTROY SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN AND LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The two students who opened fire at Columbine
High School detailed plans to kill their classmates and destroy
their school in a hand-written diary that included a schedule timed
to coincide with Adolf Hitler's birth date, investigators said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing suspicion that Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold had
help carrying assault weapons into the school and planting
explosives throughout the building, Jefferson County investigators
described a diary filled with reverence for Hitler and his message
of hate.
</P>
<P>
   Now investigators appear poised to go after others who may have
been involved in ``going for the big kill,'' as Sheriff John Stone
called Tuesday's attack. The pair set a strict schedule, which they
followed for as long as possible, intending to slay many more than
the 12 students and one teacher who died. Then, also according to
plan, the pair took their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line of this thing was that they wanted to do as
much damage as possible,'' Stone said. ``They wanted to blow the
place up, and take everyone with them.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rachel Stone, a 17-year-old junior, was buried Saturday after
a memorial service filled with sobbing students, investigators
combed the sprawling high school for clues.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after horror erupted in the hallways, ballistic
evidence continues to point to only two gunmen. Stone said bullet
casings recovered so far match only those weapons used by the
presumed killers.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators Saturday went further toward suggesting that
the pair had accomplices, though no potential suspects have been
named. Police have recovered more than 30 homemade explosives from
the school, as well as two sawed-off shotguns, a semiautomatic
rifle, and a semiautomatic handgun, leading them to believe that
others had to have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have felt that from day one,'' Stone said. ``It's kind of
hard to go into a school building, guns blazing, when you have more
guns than you can carry.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Deputy Steve Davis: ``We have to be extremely careful with
the information we release. We don't want to tip our hand to any
potential suspect or suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the start, Columbine students have said they spotted
a third gunman wielding a weapon and running through the hallways.
While stressing that witnesses could have been confused by the
chaos that followed the first shots and explosions, investigators
said they are not ruling out those accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the school, the presumed killers' own homes yielded
abundant evidence, investigators disclosed Saturday. Although they
would not say whether the thick journal came from the home of
Harris and Klebold, they noted that it was found in plain sight,
along with pipe bombs and hate literature.
</P>
<P>
   The diary covered exactly one year, marking April 20, Hitler's
birth date, as the day the conspirators would ``rock 'n roll,''
Stone said. Also in the pages were diagrams of the school
identifying exits and alarms and noting times when the greatest
number of students would be in one place.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said a trail of electronic evidence, including
communications between members of the ``Trenchcoat Mafia,'' is
being reviewed. Harris and Klebold belonged to the group of
outcasts, known for their antisocial behavior and fascination with
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be one, two, or six more involved, we don't know,''
Stone said. ``But we will bring them to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorting truth from rumor, evidence from false leads, has been
complicated by Internet high jinks. People from around the country
have posted messages on line claiming they have information about
the killings or were even involved themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One anonymous Internet posting forwarded to investigators,
purportedly written by Harris, was deemed a likely fake Saturday.
But federal agents could not determine its origin, or rule out the
possibility that the note calling for other deaths was sent by an
accomplice of the pair.
</P>
<P>
   Because the note also predicted that Monday would not pass
without more deaths, county officials have stepped up security at
schools.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they defended the actions of local deputies
and SWAT teams who were unable to reach some victims until three
hours after they were gunned down. A deputy sheriff assigned to the
school did fire at one of the student gunmen soon after the
shooting began, but did not pursue him through the buildiing.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said that SWAT teams, aware of the deadly exposives placed
around the school, had to move carefully, unable to predict how
many shooters there were or what might trigger one of the bombs.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators said they expect to be documenting the damage
inside Columbine High School for weeks, prayer vigils and burials
continued.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 mourners turned out for a Friday night memorial
service for three of the victims _ Kelly Fleming, Daniel Mauser,
and Matthew Ketcher _ and filled the church with photographs and
mementos such as spelling bee awards, football jerseys, and stuffed
animals. Linda Mauser led the congregation in tribute to her only
son, who surprised her recently with a gold crucifix he had bought
during a school club's trip to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what this cross has meant to me the last few
days,'' said Mauser, speaking as photos of her 15-year-old son were
displayed behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands turned out again Saturday for the funeral service of
Rachel Scott, 17, a committed Evangelical Christian whose charm
drew hundreds of friends and strangers to cover her car in the
school parking lot with flowers and loving notes.
</P>
<P>
   At her funeral, the first for any of the 13 victims, friends
arrived early to sign her coffin as they might have signed her
yearbook under other cirumstances. If anything underscored the
tender age of most of the victims of the Columbine shooting, it was
the hearts and flowers and promises ``never to forget you'' doodled
on the casket.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a warrior,'' said the pastor, Bruce Porter. ``But she
didn't fight with implements of destruction. Rachel fought with the
implements of love and compassion and caring and mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the senselessness of the shooting, he said: ``We have
to ask ourselves some hard questions. What has happened to us as a
people that this should happen to us? How did we get here?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
