<HEADER>
A1882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HARVEY-RECAP25-CO     04-24 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HARVEY-RECAP25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Country boy:' Shellman turns out nation's best in Harvey
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELLMAN, Ga. _ There he was, the most decorated high school
basketball player in Georgia history, the Naismith, USA Today and
Parade Magazine national player of the year, Mr. Georgia
Basketball, sweeping his mama's front porch on the hottest day of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   That scene tells you all you need to know about Donnell Harvey.
The 6-foot-8, 230-pound power forward who signed with Florida last
week is the most famous athlete to come out of Randolph County
since Rosie Greer and Larry Holmes left here 30 years ago. Yet he
remains so down to Earth that he doesn't mind sweeping a little of
it off the porch every once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say I'm just a country boy,'' Harvey says in
his low, slow drawl. And he's not kidding.
</P>
<P>
   You can't get much more country than Shellman. This Southwest
Georgia town of a few hundred pops up out of nowhere among the
soybean fields and railroad lines along Highway 82. Outside of
farming and pulpwood, there's not much industry to speak of here.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Harvey's mother, Laura Powell, has to commute 54
miles a day to her assembly-line job at a lighting manufacturing
plant in Eufala, Ala. It's an exhausting ritual that leaves her
tired much of the time and forced her to miss nearly all of
Harvey's high school basketball games. But she does it so Donnell
and his brothers Deidrick Harvey and Travious Powell can ``have
everything they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't much. The tiny dwelling that houses Harvey, his mom
and one of his brothers consists of a couple of small bedrooms, a
bathroom, a kitchen, and a living room so cramped with a sofa,
loveseat, stereo system, television and coffee table that the rangy
Harvey can't even stretch his legs when he sits down. Instead, when
he sinks back into the soft-cushioned couch, his knees remain just
below chest level.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered throughout the neatly-kept but cluttered room is the
multitude of hardware that has been heaped upon Harvey for his
tremendous basketball ability. A Naismith Trophy over here, a
McDonald's All-America plaque over there, there are literally
dozens of them and there is no rhyme or reason to their
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't find anywhere else to put them,'' explains
Harvey's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey has a car, or at least he used to before the 1984 Mazda
626 quit cranking several weeks ago. It's been down the street at
the shop ever since, but Harvey hasn't had the money to let the
mechanics figure out what's wrong. So it just sits there. Which is
OK because Harvey always knew basketball was going to get him out
of Randolph County.
</P>
<P>
   As hard as Harvey's house is to find, though, head coaches from
every major Division I school in the South did manage to track it
down. They tend to find you when you're the No. 1-rated prospect in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Dennis Rodman without tattoos'' is the now-infamous
description assistant coach Winfred Williams gave Harvey. Only
that's not entirely accurate. Harvey in fact has two tattoos, both
on his left shoulder. The one on top says ``Big D'' and one below
is a clown face. ``Because I like to clown around,'' Harvey
explains.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey averaged 23 points, 14 rebounds and five blocked shots
for the Red Devils. It's amazing how grown men fawn over you when
you're 6-feet-8 with a self-professed affinity for defense and
rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mitchell-Baker game, all the heavy hitters were there:
Billy Donovan from Florida, Tubby Smith from Kentucky, Cliff Ellis
from Auburn, Ron Jirsa from Georgia, Bobby Cremins from Georgia
Tech, Clyde Drexler from Houston. There were some others but those
are the ones everybody seems to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sight to behold,'' recalls Williams, who as
eighth-grade coach first discovered Harvey, ``all those big-time
coaches sitting in the bleachers to see Donnell.''
</P>
<P>
   But playing in front of college coaches was the easy part.
Harvey did that all last summer as a member of Wallace Prather's
Atlanta Celtics AAU team. The hard part was when he was at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone never stopped ringing,'' Harvey says. ``Every five
minutes, somebody would call. If it wasn't a coach, then it was a
sportswriter wanting to know if I'd made up my mind yet. Sometimes
I just wouldn't answer it or I'd leave the house and go somewhere
with my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Florida won the Donnell Harvey Sweepstakes,
edging out Auburn, Georgia and Clemson. Harvey made the
announcement at a well-attended news conference at his school
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey says he chose the Gators because they promised he'd start
immediately and he felt they offered the quickest route to the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went to the Sweet Sixteen last year,'' he says. ``They'll
make it farther than that with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey didn't choose Auburn because ``Chris (Porter) plays the
same position as me'' and eliminated Clemson mainly because it was
too far away.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia would appear to be the biggest loser in all this because
Harvey says he grew up always believing he would ``wear the red and
black and play for the Bulldogs.'' But Jirsa's firing in March
coupled with Jumaine Jones' decision to test the NBA draft repelled
Harvey from Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Though Harvey looks forward to his days in Gainesville, Fla., he
plans to remain there only as long as necessary. Harvey makes it
clear that playing in the NBA is his ultimate goal and he'll remain
in college only as long as it takes to achieve that objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking to get somewhere with basketball,'' he says.
``Hopefully I can make (the NBA) so I can move my parents and
grandparents from here.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't mean move them from the country, mind you, just from
the small house on Buford Circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of like living in the country, being from a small
town,'' Harvey says with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? To this point, it certainly has served him well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
