<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS FUNDS TO CURB SCHOOL VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Saturday he will ask
Congress for more money to help defuse school violence and keep
guns out of the hands of violent juveniles, saying government has a
responsibility to ``counter the culture of violence'' that led to
the Colorado high school tragedy last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do more to prevent violence in our schools,'' Clinton
said in his weekly radio address, which he devoted to last week's
shooting at Columbine High School in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would send a request next week to Capitol Hill for
$12 million to fund emergency teams to help communities respond
``when tragedy strikes.'' His legislation also would finance more
counselors and mentors, conflict-resolution programs and metal
detectors in schools.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the funding requests would be
contained in the federal reauthorization of the Elementary and
Secondary Schools Act.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would also propose a crime bill designed to
crack down on gun shows and illegal gun trafficking, ban violent
juveniles from ever being able to buy a gun, and close loopholes
that allow juveniles to own assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
   Four weapons, including a 9mm semiautomatic pistol, a 9mm
semiautomatic rifle, and two sawed-off shotguns were used in the
Littleton shooting, authorities said. They said the pistol was
bought at a store in the Denver area, but not by either of the two
students presumed to be the killers, who both died of
self-inflicted gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We marvel at the bravery of the fatally wounded teacher who
led 40 students to safety,'' Clinton said. ``We look with
admiration at the medics and the police officers who rushed to the
scene to save lives; the clergy, the counselors, the local leaders
who immediately began the painful process of helping people to
heal; and the parents and students who in the face of hatred
refused to return it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``At a moment of such terrible, terrible
violence, these people didn't turn away, and we can't either.
Instead every one of us must take responsibility to counter the
culture of violence. The government must take responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Americans must replace a ``culture of violence'' with a
``culture of values'' and also urged parents to ``refuse to buy
products that glorify violence.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican response to Clinton's radio address, Colorado
Governor Bill Owens said the events in Littleton ``warn us there is
a virus loose within our culture,'' adding: ``too may of our young
people are susceptible to it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also urged parents to pay more attention to what their
children may be watching on television, what video games they play,
what World Wide Web sites they log on to. ``Do you know if your
child has a home page?'' Owens asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
