<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT`S BACK TO BASICS FOR MALIGNED DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The defense for UCLA's football team is taking the
first step to rebuilding its riddled reputation. And it's a step
backward.
</P>
<P>
   Under new defensive coordinator Bob Field, the Bruins are back
to the basics this month at spring practice: tackling drills,
alignment drills, assignment drills. They've spent time shedding
blocks and finding the ball in flight. Yes, Field is installing a
new system, but at a rate the players can handle and with one eye
fixed on the fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to take the approach, `Let's not put in a lot, but
what we do, let's do well,' '' Field said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a welcomed change for the Bruins, whose circuitry was often
overloaded last season. To absorb Nick Aliotti's complicated system
_ to learn all the names and concepts and assignments _ they
bypassed the basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Field is really teaching us the game in a way that's
easy to understand,'' cornerback Marques Anderson said. ``We're
tackling every day. We're doing ball drills and backpedaling drills
_ the simple stuff we got away from last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Good, bad, out: Although nine starters return, the defense isn't
at full strength because of myriad injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Tackles Anthony Fletcher (hamstring) and Ken Kocher (knee) are
out, linebacker Robert Thomas (back) has practiced sparingly and
cornerback Jason Bell (heel) hasn't played a down.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries have given several reserves a chance to show their
stuff, including outside linebacker Ali Abdul-Azziz, cornerback Joe
Hunter and defensive end Rusty Williams.
</P>
<P>
   One nagging problem is the safety spot opposite Jason Stephens.
Neither Eric Whitfield nor Audie Attar have tempered coach Bob
Toledo's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really pleased with their performances right now,''
Toledo said. ``We've got to get better. They've missed a lot of
tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   Another safety candidate is redshirt freshman Lovell Houston. A
heralded recruit last year _ he chose UCLA over Washington and
Florida State _ Houston is recovering from surgery on both
shoulders and cannot participate in contact drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in as a cornerback, but they've moved me to safety,''
Houston said. ``Coach Toledo said it was an executive decision, and
it's fine with me. I'm picking up the defense real well, and I'll
be ready to go in August.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaching changes: The offensive staff has returned intact, but
there are new faces and responsibilities defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Field will coach the secondary in addition to his coordinator
duties. Marc Dove has the linebackers, both inside and outside. The
newcomers, Jethro Franklin and John Pearce, will coach the line.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce, who coached with Toledo at Texas A&AMP;M, has the defensive
ends.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, the former Fresno State player and assistant _ he
sacked Troy Aikman four times in the 1987 game _ is coaching the
tackles. He replaces Terry Tumey, who became an assistant with the
Denver Broncos, and will fill Tumey's spot in recruiting the city.
</P>
<P>
   No shows: Cornerback Ryan Roques, receiver Freddie Mitchell and
tight end Gabe Crecion have shunned baseball to concentrate on
football. As usual, receiver Danny Farmer has skipped spring
practice to continue playing for the volleyball team, and
linebacker Ed Stansbury is with track and field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
