A1911 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WILLIAMS-NYT &LR;      04-24 0306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN WILLIAMS, 85, WRITER ON PHILATELY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By BARTH HEALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Norman Williams, a British lawyer best known as a prolific
writer about stamps and stamp collecting, died on April 9 in
London. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was best known to American collectors as the co-author
with his brother Maurice of ``Fundamentals of Philately,'' an
exhaustive study of the printing methods used to make stamps _ from
the monochrome engraved stamps of the 19th century through the
stamp issues of multicolor offset presses in the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Until his death Williams also wrote a column for the weekly
Linn's Stamp News, which announced his death in its issue last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams brothers wrote more than 30 books and thousands of
articles. They also edited journals and lectured widely. Norman
Williams specialized in stamps known as Cinderellas _ stamps used
not to pay postage but for tax receipts, publicity, propaganda and
the like, or stamps used to pay for delivering mail from remote
places without routine postal service, like some small islands in
British waters.
</P>
<P>
   His final work was the Encyclopaedia of Rare and Famous Stamps,
published in two volumes in 1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also spent 64 years as a court reporter for the Inc.
Council of Law Reporting for England and Wales. In this role, from
which he retired less than two years ago, he was responsible for
setting out the facts of cases in such detail that judges and
lawyers could decide what precedents may have been set.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Williams died in 1976. Norman Williams is survived by
his wife, Denise, whom he married in 1943 when on leave from his
duties as an artillery officer in West Africa; two sons, Marcus and
Robin, and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
