<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT &LR;      04-24 0273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COMBAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The NATO air campaign entered its second month, targeting
military and industrial sites across Yugoslavia, including the
cities of Novi Sad and Nis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Albania said NATO ground troops may use that country for
staging before entering Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hungary has agreed to open all of its military air bases to
NATO war planes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRISONERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The president of the International Committee of the Red Cross
left for Belgrade, Yugoslavia, to discuss access to three captured
American soldiers with the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFUGEES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.N. refugee agency estimated the number of Kosovars in
neighboring countries at more than 610,000. Most _ 363,000 _ are in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER DEVELOPMENTS  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Russian foreign minister said Russia would ignore a NATO
oil embargo against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   _ A NATO spokesman said that some retired Yugoslav generals are
under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   _ The conflict is costing the German airline Lufthansa more than
$5.5 million a day because NATO's use of its Frankfurt hub is
causing flight delays and diversions, the news magazine Der Spiegel
reported.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thousands of Belgrade residents marched to a church near the
bomb-shattered headquarters of Serbian state television to protest
a NATO attack on Friday that Yugoslav authorities say killed 15
people and injured 30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE WEB  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Yugoslavia is available
from The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
