A1918 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN     04-24 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON KEEPS UP INTENSITY FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It was last August when Garret Anderson
failed to run out a grounder back to the pitcher in Baltimore,
prompting Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins to yank him from the
game.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins says Anderson's ``whole approach since the start of
spring training is completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Anderson's new approach had to do with the fact that the
Angels started the spring with four outfielders and he would have
to fight for playing time. But even though Jim Edmonds is out with
an injury, Anderson continues to work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things I need to do for myself to make myself a
more complete player,'' Anderson said. ``I'm not really worried
about how other people perceive me as a player. But I worry about
what I think about myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to erase in anybody's mind what other people
think of me. I'm doing in my mind what I think I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Two ends of the spectrum: When the Angels win, they win big. In
their seven victories, they've won by an average margin of 5.7
runs.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Angels lose, it's usually a tight, tough loss. Of
their 11 losses, six have come by one run, including Saturday's 4-3
loss to the Royals. Overall, they are 1-6 in one-run games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown we can play different parts of the game,'' Angels
right fielder Tim Salmon said. ``It's just a matter of putting it
together and picking each other up. It's just one of those weird
things that happens. You get good hitting, you have no pitching.
You get good pitching, you have no hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen the road trip. It couldn't get any worse, or
harder, or hurt more. But we'll figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Up and down: After getting two hits in the Angels' victory over
the Mariners on April 16, shortstop Andy Sheets was hitting .350.
Since then, Sheets is 1 for 21, his average falling to .246.
</P>
<P>
   He's also been struggling defensively _ his error Saturday was
his sixth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last week's been terrible, Sheets said. ``I'm making
errors, striking out, not driving in runs when I've had
opportunities. Maybe I'm trying to do too much at times.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets, acquired in a trade with the Padres for Phil Nevin on
March 29, will be the Angels' regular shortstop until Gary
DiSarcina returns from a broken bone in his left forearm in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
