   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- April 24, 1999 -- NATO-24-HOURS, 4-24 --
As NATO leaders meet at the Pentagon Saturday morning, their
anniversary pageant is playing on two stages, as political theater
and in the theater of war, and its powerful rhetoric clashes with
the forces of battle in Belgrade and the Balkans. By 3 p.m., the
leaders had finished speaking, and the exiles from Malisevo, a
village of 800 homes outside Gnjilane in Kosovo, were bedding down
on blankets laid over newly spread crushed stone in a cleared
garbage dump. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LOS ANGELES -- April 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SOLDIER-3, 4-24
-- Andrew Ramirez Sr., 55, father of Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, one
of the three American soldiers being held in Serbia. In the three
weeks since the bruised faces of Sgt. Ramirez, 24 and two other
American soldiers first filled television screens across the United
States, the families hopes for an early release of the Americans,
captured on March 31, have vanished. ``To me he is still a baby,''
says Andrew Sr. (Verne G. Kopytoff/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LOS ANGELES -- April 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SOLDIER-2, 4-24
-- Vivian Ramirez, mother of Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, one of the
three American soldiers being held in Serbia. As hopes for her
son's early release have vanished, the Ramirez family stuggles with
uncertainty. ``I don't want to close my eyes and picture him in a
dark room, maybe all dirty or hurt or hungry,'' says Mrs. Ramirez.
Three American soldiers, including Sgt. Ramirez, 24, were captured
on the Macedonian border on March 31 and are now being held in
seclusion. (Jill Connelly/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HAVANA, Cuba -- April 24, 1999 --
CUBA-BASEBALL-DEFECTORS-4, 4-24 -- To help make ends meat in
Havana, the Colina family -- Miguel, Miriam, Rene and Daisy -- get
$300 a month from Roberto, who is a designated hitter in the minor
leagues of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays organization. Roberto, a former
first baseman on the Cuban national team, defected in 1996 and has
managed both to support his family and reunite with his wife and
daughter in Florida as he tries to earn a spot with the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays in the majors. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) KUKES, Albania -- April 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
4-24 -- Her family beside her and their possessions stowed in a
tree, an elderly woman waited Saturday to board a bus to leave a
camp in Kukes. As when they were forced to leave their homes in
Kosovo, thousands of refugees in Kukes are now being forced to make
a similar decision. Local Albanian authorities have sent police
into the refugees' camps to order them to leave Kukes, saying there
are too many people now too close to the border with Kosovo.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) KUKES, Albania -- April 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
4-24 -- Her family beside her and their possessions stowed in a
tree, an elderly woman waited Saturday to board a bus to leave a
camp in Kukes. As when they were forced to leave their homes in
Kosovo, thousands of refugees in Kukes are now being forced to make
