are too many people now too close to the border with Kosovo.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LEXINGTON, Mass. -- April 24, 1999 -- RELIGION-WOMEN,
4-24 -- Rebecca Cohen, 26, in the tradition of her mother, the Rev.
Helen Lutton Cohen, will be ordained in the Unitarian Universalist
church, in which women clergy outnumber men. For one generation in
a family to follow another into the ministry is an old story, which
can be told with reference to men like Cotton Mather and Martin
Luther King Jr., sons following their fathers, but for a daughter
to follow her mother represents a new trend. (Cynthia Howe/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HAVANA, Cuba -- April 24, 1999 --
CUBA-BASEBALL-DEFECTORS-3, 4-24 -- Children playing a game of
baseball in Havana. Since 1991, roughly 30 of Cuba's best baseball
players have defected. Although the Cuban government acts as if
defecting baseball players have ceased to exist, they are
considered folk heroes to many on the streets, where the game is a
passion. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) REMEDIOS, Cuba -- April 24, 1999 --
CUBA-BASEBALL-DEFECTORS-2, 4-24 -- Children organizing a game in a
park in Remedios, Cuba, where Jorge Luis Toca developed the skills
that led him to a contract with the New York Mets after he defected
last year. Since 1991, roughly 30 of Cuba's best baseball players
have defected. For all of them, the decision is a calculated gamble
with conflicting ambitions and risks involving their careers and
families. For their families left behind, the players are often
something between invisible and heroic. (Angel Franco/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HAVANA, Cuba -- April 24, 1999 --
CUBA-BASEBALL-DEFECTORS-1, 4-24 -- Reynaldo Ordonez Fiallo, the
6-year-old son the New York Mets' Ray Ordonez in Havana. The boy
was an infant when his father left Cuba in 1993. Since 1991,
roughly 30 of Cuba's best baseball players have defected. For all
of them, the decision is a calculated gamble with conflicting
ambitions and risks involving their careers and families. (Angel
Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 24, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-TRENCHCOATS-3, 4-24 -- Ashly Beeson, 18, a former
student at Columbine High School, says the name ``trench coat
mafia'' was given to a group of outcasts at Columbine by other
students. Two group members Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17,
stormed into the suburban Denver school on Tuesday firing shotguns
and tossing pipe bombs. Fifteen people were killed including the
two suspects who committed suicide hours after the rampage started.
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 24, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-TRENCHCOATS-2, 4-24 -- In the parking lot at Columbine
High School, flowers, candles and posters enshrine a red Acura that
belonged to Rachel Scott, one of 14 students who died in the
massacre at the school -- including Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan
Klebold, 17, the gunmen who stormed the school on Tuesday. Many
investigators strongly believe the two young men had some kind of
help in preparing for their attack or in bringing more than 30
home-made explosive devices into the school. (Monica Almeida/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- April 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SOLDIER-1, 4-24 --
Andrew Ramirez, one of the three American soldiers being held in
Serbia, with his mother, Vivian, and a nephew, Austin, in a family
photo. As hopes for his early release have vanished, the family
stuggles with uncertainty. Three American soldiers, including Staff
Sgt. Ramirez, 24, were captured on the Macedonian border on March
31 and are now being held in seclusion. (Jill Connelly/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 24, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-PSYCHOLOGY, 4-24 -- Some of the memorial messages left
near Columbine High School on Friday. The baseball, possibly a
tribute to William David Sanders, a coach at Columbine High School.
Two students stormed into the suburban Denver school on Tuesday
firing shotguns and tossing pipe bombs. Fifteen people were killed
including the two suspects who committed suicide hours after the
rampage started. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 24, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-TRENCHCOATS-1, 4-24 -- Students from a high school in
Aurora, another Denver suburb, laying flowers on Friday at a
memorial near Columbine High School. Two students, Eric Harris, 18,
and Dylan Klebold, 17, stormed into the suburban Denver school on
Tuesday firing shotguns and tossing pipe bombs. Fifteen people were
killed including the two suspects who committed suicide hours after
the rampage started. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ATHENS -- April 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-GREECE, 4-24 --
Constantina Vafiadou, 16, left, and her sister, Eleni, 18, at a
recent protest in Athens over the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia. Both
Constantina and Eleni oppose the war. ``The war is about the U.S.
pursuing its own expansionist strategic interests,'' says Eleni.
``It's ludicrous to say the bombing is to help humanity.'' More
than any other country in NATO, Greece has been struggling between
loyalty to the Western alliance and outrage over the bombing
nearby. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
