<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-765&AMP;ADD     04-24 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY'S OUTSIDER STATUS LOOMS LARGE IN POSSIBLE SENATE BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a peek at how Mayor Rudolph Giuliani might run a
campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton for Senate next year, go no
farther than the Giuliani Web site devoted to a daily electronic
thrashing of the first lady. ``Born in Illinois and carried to
power in Arkansas, with no connection of any kind to New York,
Hillary has set her sights on the New York Senate seat,'' the site,
HillaryNo.com, tells visitors.
</P>
<P>
   In the unsettled atmosphere that envelops this
still-hypothetical race, one thing has become clear in the last few
days: Mrs. Clinton's residency, or her lack thereof in New York, is
looming as a major factor in the prospective race, and even, her
friends say, in the first lady's decision whether to run at all.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's advisers say that the mayor, after initially saying
he would not make an issue of Mrs. Clinton's years of growing up in
Illinois and living in Arkansas, is now prepared to turn her
non-New York pedigree into one of his main attacks against her.
Giuliani has taken to describing Mrs. Clinton as a carpetbagger,
while pointedly joking to audiences upstate _ where his advisers
believe that resentment of Mrs. Clinton's lack of New York
residency is particular deep _ that perhaps he should move to
Arkansas and run for Senate there.
</P>
<P>
   ``People across the state have expressed their concern about the
issue,'' said Bruce Teitelbaum, the director of Giuliani's Senate
exploratory committee, which set up the HillaryNo site. ``Many
people have told us there's a lack of confidence with someone who
knows nothing about the state and who has never lived in the state,
and whether a person like that has an understanding of the needs of
the people of the state of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mrs. Clinton's advisers, who have noted public polls showing
that support for the first lady has slipped, say they are reviewing
ways to counter what they say appears to be a potent line of
attack. The first lady's three days in New York last week, combined
with a last-minute decision to return this Thursday to address the
state Democratic Party, along with the new authority she is
displaying in talking about New York culture and history, marked
the start of an effort to transform her from a Washington celebrity
into a more familiar figure in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly appears that Giuliani thinks it is an issue,''
said Harold Ickes, the former senior White House aide who is
overseeing Mrs. Clinton's exploration of a Senate race. ``And it
may well be an issue. Mrs. Clinton is going to have to spend some
time assuring voters that she indeed wants to represent New York,
which she does.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a legitimate question that voters may raise,'' Ickes
said. ``I don't know how deeply it cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the calculation going on in both camps, however, the
actual political significance of the fact that Mrs. Clinton has
never lived in New York remains one of the larger mysteries of this
prospective matchup. While Giuliani's decision to attack her on the
issue could persuade Mrs. Clinton not to run _ and that could very
well be Giuliani's real motivation _ there is much debate in
political circles about how problematic it would be for Mrs.
Clinton to move to New York, declare her candidacy and run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule is, don't do it,'' said Charles Cook Jr., author of a
Washington-based political report that follows congressional races.
``But if there was going to be an exception, this would be it.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, whose retirement in
2000 has created the opening that Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani are now
examining, argued in an interview that the state is so diverse, and
has such a history of embracing outsiders in all kinds of
professions, that never having been a resident would pose only a
minor difficulty to the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being someone from another place is a fact of life for huge
numbers of our citizens,'' Moynihan said. ``The Constitution says
you have to be a citizen of the state at the time that you are
elected. We have in the Constitution a presumption that you're not
necessarily born there or raised there.''
</P>
<P>
   In some episodes in political history, being a carpetbagger
proved a liability, notably when Pete Dawkins, a Republican, moved
to New Jersey to run for Senate against Frank Lautenberg in 1988.
He lost.
</P>
<P>
   But there are as many examples where it did not matter. Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., defused the charge overnight by observing
that the longest he had ever lived in one place was the five and a
half years he spent as a prisoner of war in North Vietnam.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There are reasons to believe that Mrs. Clinton can surmount the
issue in New York. Early public polls suggest that voters are
evenly divided over whether they would consider Mrs. Clinton's
residency in deciding how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Carroll, the director of the Quinnipiac Poll, said his
polling found that half the respondents had concerns about Mrs.
Clinton's being from out of state, but he said the figure was far
lower than he would expect to find in other states. ``In most other
states, it would be 95 percent,'' Carroll said. ``But in New York,
it seems to be less of a problem. We are a national place.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the men who have held Moynihan's seat moved in from out
of state: Robert F. Kennedy, a Democrat from Massachusetts, and
James Buckley, a Conservative from Connecticut. Each was helped to
victory by other factors _ Kennedy benefited from Lyndon Johnson's
landslide victory of 1964 and the aura of the Kennedy name, while
Buckley slipped through in a three-way race in 1970 _but their
successes have been cited by Mrs. Clinton's supporters as evidence
that one does not have to have lived in New York to run here.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, several consultants said, might not be the ideal
person to make this particular charge against the first lady.
Upstate, his attempts to portray her as an interloper might be
undercut by the equally foreign image of a New York City mayor
campaigning through the mountains and farmland north of Peekskill.
</P>
<P>
   And Mrs. Clinton might turn out to have a particular immunity to
this line of attack because she represents a new kind of public
figure in America: someone who has no clear geographical
identification whatsoever. She grew up in the suburbs of Chicago,
and moved with President Clinton to Arkansas, before coming to
Washington. She has no particular accent or visible cultural
markers. Her political philosophy is more New York than Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who respect her _ as well as those who dislike her
_ don't consider that she came from Chicago,'' said Rep. Charles
Rangel, D-N.Y., who has promoted her candidacy. ``They consider her
as a national figure, and God knows, that's what we need in a
national state.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But even Dick Morris, the political consultant, was
unable to offer any advice about how to defuse an issue he
considers politically lethal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly think she is not going to run because of this,''
Morris said. ``She will carefully and calmly assess the polling and
make a reasoned decision not to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
