<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1939 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SUMMIT25-COX     04-24 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CALLS FOR 'PATIENCE' TO LET WAR STRATEGY WORK
 &HT;    700&AMP;add. With NATO-CITY.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Saturday that NATO must be
prepared ``to pay the price of time'' in order to prevail in its
air war against Yugoslavia, as an alliance plan to choke off
Belgrade's oil imports ran into snags.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the buildup of NATO troops and tanks in Albania and
Macedonia does not signal that the alliance is creeping toward a
ground war in the neighboring Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not drifting. We are moving forward with a strategy that
I believe strongly will succeed,'' Clinton said at a news
conference on the second day of a summit marking the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced we will prevail if we have the patience,'' he
said. ``We have to be prepared not only to execute with
determination, but to pay the price of time.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke, NATO continued to to pound away at targets
across Yugoslavia's dominant republic of Serbia, striking a pair of
radio and television towers, three airfields, a railroad bridge and
Serb forces, tanks and artillery deployed across Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With roughly 20,000 U.S. and allied troops rimming Kosovo from
neighboring Albania and Macedonia, and another 10,000 scheduled to
arrive over the coming week, speculation has centered on the
possibility of NATO ground operations inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana repeated that there is no
intention of deploying ground forces, though the alliance is
actively assessing the requirements for such a move.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's position from the start of the air campaign has been that
it would send ground troops into Kosovo as a peace-keeping force
once hostilities have ceased, but would not attempt to fight their
way into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600,000 ethnic Albanians have fled Kosovo's borders in
the face of Serb attacks on civilians and towns across the tiny
province of Kosovo. Roughly an equal number are believed to have
fled their homes and to have gone into hiding in the rugged
mountains inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As leaders from the 19-nation alliance reaffirmed their
commitment to the air strikes on Yugoslavia, a campaign now
beginning its second month, snags began appearing in NATO's plan
for an international oil embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Russia, a major oil exporter,
would ignore the embargo, which he called illegal unless approved
by the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   And President Jacques Chirac of France balked at the prospect of
NATO sailors using force to board and inspect ships bound for
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``To search is fine if the ship that you want to search allows
itself to be searched,'' Chirac said at a news conference, but
forcible boardings constitute war. ``We need to be very, very
careful and study all the aspects before we make a final
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With U.S. and allied pilots attacking Yugoslavia's oil supplies,
Clinton said, it makes no sense to permit NATO's foe from
resupplying itself through imports.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we justify risking the lives of the pilots to go up
and destroy the refinery and the supply capacity of Serbia,''
Clinton asked, ``and then say, 'But it's okay with us if people
want to continue to supply this nation and its outlaw actions in
Kosovo in another way?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he did not want the oil embargo to lead to fighting
on the high seas, ``but we have to be firm about it'' and willing
to use ``every reasonable means'' to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia is the subject of a U.N. weapons embargo. The Clinton
administration maintains that oil meets the definition of
restricted items under that embargo, because Serb forces use oil to
power the tanks, trucks and aircraft used to wage repression
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, NATO ordered its military commander, U.S. Army Gen.
Wesley Clark, to put together a plan for enforcing an oil embargo
against Yugoslavia by searching tankers at sea and diverting any
that were found to be ferrying oil toward Yugoslav ports in the
state of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Any plan Clark prepares would have to go before NATO's political
wing, the North Atlantic Council, and would require unanimous
consent of all 19 member states before it could be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   After 32 days of air strikes, NATO is grinding away at Serb
forces across Kosovo, but has been unable to drive them out of the
province.
</P>
<P>
   As it has become increasingly apparent that the campaign will
not end quickly, as NATO leaders had hoped, the alliance has come
to view oil as the Achilles heel of its opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without oil, the Yugoslav military machine will come to a
halt, and
</P>
<P>
   very quickly,'' said NATO spokesman Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warplanes have repeatedly bombed Yugoslavia's two oil
refineries, in Novi Sad and Pancevo, and now believe both are out
of business. Daily strikes on fuel storage and distribution areas,
as well as the roads and bridges needed to deliver fuel to forces
in the field, have stripped Yugoslavia's army of perhaps 70 percent
of its available fuel, said Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said Serb forces have been reduced to siphoning gasoline
from automobiles left inside Kosovo by fleeing ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are that desperate now to find fuel wherever they can,''
said Shea. ``They are critically dependent on trying to get oil
from outside sources.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO leaders are scheduled to meet Sunday with delegates
from the states neighboring Yugoslavia for discussions centered on
how to help those countries with the political, economic and
military threats the conflict poses for them.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is also working on a comprehensive plan to help bring
long-term stability to a region torn by a decade of ethnic
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a powerful set of magnets pulling the people
together,'' said Clinton, ``and those have to be economic, as well
as political, and security.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
