<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROYALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON'S TWO HOMERS DON'T ERASE MISTAKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Try as he might, Tim Salmon couldn't carry
the Anaheim Angels on his back.
</P>
<P>
   His two home runs couldn't make up for the day shortstop Andy
Sheets had.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets, filling in until the injured Gary DiSarcina returns
around the All-Star break, made a fourth-inning error that led to
two unearned runs and another miscue in the eighth that gave the
Kansas City Royals a 4-3 victory Saturday afternoon before 15,664
at Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the eighth, the Royals had the bases loaded
with one out in a 3-3 game when Mike Sweeney hit a sharp grounder
to the left of Sheets. Sheets fielded the ball cleanly, stepped on
second and threw to first.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of completing the inning-ending double play, the
ball was in the dirt and first baseman Darin Erstad couldn't come
up with it.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the play is not ruled an error because a double play
cannot be assumed. But the result was just as damaging. Rey Sanchez
scored from third to break the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just (messed) it up, there's nothing else you can say,''
Sheets said. ``It just can't happen. Those plays have got to be
made.... You've got to put it behind you and go out and play
tomorrow. It helps to know you've got a chance to redeem
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins and a number of players consoled Sheets
after the game, including Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every guy in the clubhouse feels for him,'' Salmon said.
``We've all been there at some point. If you haven't made a mistake
like that you haven't been playing very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the last guy in the world you want to see that happen to.
He's a great fit _ his temperament, his personality, the way he
plays the game. He's about as good as you can get to fill in for
DiSarcina. He's a good guy, you hate to see things like that
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheets' official error came in the fourth inning when Sweeney
hit a line drive at him. But the ball whizzed over his head into
left field. The Royals turned it into two unearned runs against
Angels starter Steve Sparks (52/3 innings, two unearned runs, five
hits).
</P>
<P>
   What made the play difficult was that Sparks' pitch was a
knuckleball, and it remained a knuckleball after it was hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came in a knuckleball and went out a knuckleball,'' Angels
catcher Matt Walbeck said. ``Right before it went into his glove _
boom, it took off. The last time I saw that was Justin Baughman.
Remember that?''
</P>
<P>
   Baughman was hit in the mouth and suffered a slight concussion
and laceration that required 60 stitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played very well,'' Collins said of Sheets. ``He just had
a bad inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The game started promisingly for the Angels. Sparks' knuckleball
was dancing according to Walbeck and Salmon continued to smoke the
ball in day games.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon hit a two-run homer off Royals starter Jeff Suppan in the
fourth inning for a 2-0 lead. In the sixth, his solo homer (No. 6)
broke a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   In three day games this season, Salmon is hitting .692 (9 for
13) with four homers and 14 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the ball really well today,'' Salmon said. ``That's when
the game is supposed to be played _ during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Sparks left with two out in the sixth, the Angels
bullpen couldn't hold the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine gave up a double to Sweeney in the seventh, and he
eventually scored on a sacrifice fly by Scott Leius to tie the
game. Two walks in the inning _ one allowed by Levine and the other
by Mike Holtz _ helped fuel the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hurt ourselves with the bases on balls,'' Collins said.
``We didn't let them swing the bat, and that's what hurt us. You
continue to open up opportunities, sooner or later they're going to
get a hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
