<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SUMMIT-NYT &LR;      04-24 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO NOW BELLWETHER AS WELL AS BATTLEFIELD  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The leaders of NATO tried to turn away from the war
in Kosovo and devote the second day of their summit meeting to the
lofty subjects for which they had gathered. But they could not
escape the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   As they approved a new strategic concept to redefine NATO's
role, which has been under study for several years, and debated
whether the U.N. Security Council should have a say in its actions,
Kosovo kept coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many allies _ probably just about every ally _ mentioned
Kosovo as kind of a metaphor for what the new NATO is supposed to
be all about,'' said a senior Clinton administration official,
briefing reporters during a break in the debate over the fine print
of the final communique.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said the official, the new NATO that would emerge in the
communique outlining its future missions was already being put to
the test in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But as a measure of the behind-the-scenes differences on whether
Kosovo is a test case for NATO's new phase, one of NATO's most
senior soldiers, Gen. Klaus Naumann of Germany, said: ``Kosovo is
not a precedent for the strategic concept. NATO is not going to
become an alliance for intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the day _ with the exception of lunch, where officials
said the conversation reverted to Kosovo _ was spent hammering out
language on an expansive role for the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The new concept allows NATO to enter crises outside the
territory of the member states but still confines its jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of communism has forced NATO to search for a new
role beyond that of a mutual defense pact. NATO essentially chose
the role of being a regional policeman on the watch against ethnic
wars, terrorism and weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana, sought to dampen
criticism, saying: ``NATO is not a universal organization; NATO is
a territorial limited organization: its aim, commitment, engagement
is to what we call the Euro-Atlantic issue, the Euro-Atlantic
area.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that there may be ``challenges that may arise from
outside the Euro-Atlantic area that may have an effect in the
Euro-Atlantic area,'' but that the main concern was the stability
of the region itself.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the communique and strategic concept documents
was delayed by objections by Turkey over alleged favoritism to
European Union countries within NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, which would like to join the European Union, protested
that the European members would be allowed to carry out military
operations using NATO assets.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also tried to deal with NATO's relationship with the
United Nations. The documents noted the ``authority of the Security
Council and its primordial responsibility'' for peace and security
in the world. There was instant disagreement over what this meant.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac of France, a firm believer in the
mandate of the U.N. Security Council, told reporters that NATO
peacekeeping operations would require the Council's authorization.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO cannot and will not be able to act without the
authorization of this international organization,'' Chirac said.
The French have pushed for Security Council backing for any
military presence as part of a settlement with Yugoslavia over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At a separate news conference, Solana, asked whether NATO would
need a Security Council resolution to intervene outside members'
territory, said, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   The war in Kosovo does not have a U.N. mandate on the ground,
diplomats have argued, that the intervention was taken to prevent a
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have always expressed
reluctance about requiring a U.N.mandate, saying that China and
Russia should not be given a veto over NATO's work.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he was pleased the new strategic concept
endorsed ``the actions such as those we are undertaking in
Kosovo,'' where there is no U.N. mandate.
</P>
<P>
   If the summit meeting was not the gala that was originally
planned, convened as it was under the shadow of the Balkan
conflict, it was a celebration for the nations _ the Czech
Republic, Poland and Hungary _ who formally joined last month.
</P>
<P>
   They offered countries aspiring to join action plans under which
the alliance would measure progress on how countries _ like
Romania, Bulgaria and Slovenia _ were advancing in meeting
requirements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
