<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-LITTLETON25-CO     04-24 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-LITTLETON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Community looks within for answers
 &HT;    By Chris Barker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ They are tucked among rolling slopes and
divided by small streams that trickle down from the Rocky Mountain
foothills _ thousands of homes built on wide, curving streets.
</P>
<P>
   Rising in clustered neighborhoods with names like Coventry and
Marina Pointe, wood-shingled homes have sprung up in place of horse
ranches that just 25 years ago dappled both sides of Wadsworth
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   It is the suburban result of Denver's growth _ massive bedroom
communities built behind miles of eight-foot fences that insulate
residents from the noise of high-speed six-lane roads.
</P>
<P>
   It is where some came to escape the crime of the big city, which
may be why Tuesday's slaughter at Columbine High School was so
shocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the middle of New York City, it's the middle of
suburban Jefferson County,'' said Amy Ericson, a 1986 graduate of
Columbine and mother of four.
</P>
<P>
   According to authorities investigating the shooting rampage at
Columbine High School, the neighborhood is home to two young
killers _ trenchcoat-clad outcasts who plotted and hated for a year
before carrying out their plan. And while investigators piece
together the events that led to the tragedy, searching for an
answer that will soothe anguished residents, a community is
learning hard lessons about itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult for people to feel a real sense of
community here in south JeffCo,'' said Don Marxhausen, a minister
at St. Phillip's Lutheran Church in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Problems like alcoholism and divorce didn't skip Denver's
suburbs, Marxhausen said. Residents need to recognize the pain in
their children, and the community must take responsibility for
finding a solution, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine shootings should jolt the community _ as well as
the nation _ into action, said a visibly shaken Dave Thomas,
Jefferson County's district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Influences on young people _ from video games to music to the
Internet _ must be examined for clues to what went wrong, he said.
Court probation programs _ like the one that both suspects
successfully completed under the supervision of Thomas' office _
must be re-examined, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of this has to do with how we treat each other
and our respect for human life and human property,'' said Thomas,
whose two grown children graduated from Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   Young people who live in the area must share responsibility for
fixing what went wrong at Columbine, several area students said.
Although the countless rows of tan and gray houses may look the
same, the children of south Jefferson County don't always match.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids were tormented for years,'' said Andrew Mitchell, a
17-year-old Lakewood High School student visiting a makeshift
memorial near Columbine, of suspects Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.
``After a while, it builds up and you explode _ this is how they
did it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell, dressed in black and sporting dyed black hair and
heavy boots, said only good can now come from the shootings, which
shined a spotlight on a subculture of students who dress in dark
clothes and call themselves ``Goths.''
</P>
<P>
   Students who had never paid attention to him before approached
and smiled and talked with Mitchell the day after the shootings, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually proud of my high school for once in my life,''
Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Other students said everyone was welcome at Columbine, and that
teasing is part of any high school experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone gets criticized at our school, it's just part of
life, you've got to deal with it,'' said Lindsey Mean, a
17-year-old student.
</P>
<P>
   For Randy Lapp, whose son Justin escaped the library where most
of the dead were found, the shootings could mark a parental
failure.
</P>
<P>
   If Harris and Klebold had had more discipline at home, the
tragedy may have never happened, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Good Lord put a little meat on their rear end for a
reason,'' Lapp said.
</P>
<P>
   Stealing candy and smoking pot was about as far afield from the
law as Columbine students ever got, said Daniel Ruiz, 17, a former
student.
</P>
<P>
   But psychological problems exist despite the affluence of many
students, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numerous parents in this neighborhood, they're completely
oblivious of what we do,'' Ruiz said. ``They think they know but
they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
