A2003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-GUNS25-COX     04-24 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GUNS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texans in poll back concealed handguns
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Just before last week's deadly school shooting
in Colorado, Texans surveyed for a new Texas Poll clearly affirmed
their support for the state's concealed-carry handgun law and
flatly rejected the idea of holding gun makers primarily
responsible for gun-related violence.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, released today, showed that 53 percent of 1,003 Texans
questioned own some type of gun and 46 percent had taken some type
of gun training. Among gun owners, 64 percent had taken some
shooting instruction.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey, conducted from March 31 to April 17, has a
margin of error of 3 percentage points and a slightly higher margin
of error for the subgroup of gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   Gun owners were more likely to support the state's 1995
concealed-carry handgun law; 73 percent of them said they support
allowing private citizens to carry concealed handguns with a
permit. Of all the people asked, 62 percent said they support such
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Senate recently approved a bill to prevent cities,
counties and other smaller government entities from suing gun
makers without lawmakers' permission for costs associated with
gun-related violence, including law enforcement expenses and
emergency care. The cities of Atlanta and New Orleans have filed
such lawsuits, modeled after successful litigation against tobacco
companies by numerous states, including Texas, seeking compensation
for smoking-related health-care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if cities and counties should be allowed to seek money
from gun makers because of costs associated with gun-related
violence, 23 percent of the 1,003 Texans said yes, 68 percent said
no and 9 percent weren't sure or declined to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Among gun owners, 13 percent said cities and counties should be
allowed to file such lawsuits, 79 percent said no and 8 percent
weren't sure or refused to answer.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who they believe is most responsible for gun-related
violence, 94 percent of the full group said the criminal and 3
percent the gun manufacturer. Of gun owners, 98 percent said
criminals are most responsible for gun-related crimes and 1 percent
said gun manufacturers are most responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Butts, of Texans Against Gun Violence, called those numbers
terrible. She added, though, that while the clear majority of
people wouldn't hold gun makers most responsible, there are valid
arguments that gun manufacturers have some responsibility for the
country's gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of anti-lawyer sentiment,'' she said,
adding that if some of the pending gun-related lawsuits are
successful, the number of people who would support lawsuits against
gun makers would increase.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Suzanna Gratia Hupp (R-Lampasas), said people are
simply smart enough to see the danger in allowing such cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We truly believe in holding the criminal responsible for his
crime and not the maker of the tool he used,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hupp is the House sponsor of the bill to keep cities and local
government agencies from suing gun makers without lawmakers'
approval. She said lawsuits against gun makers for gun-related
violence would open the door for auto makers to be sued for
drunken-driving deaths and knife makers for stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people are wise enough to see the incredibly
dangerous precedent it sets,'' Hupp said. The gun-lawsuit bill,
Senate Bill 717, has cleared the Senate and is awaiting action by
the full House.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
