u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-DIARY-HNS &LR;      04-24 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-DIARY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
GUNMAN KEPT DIARY OUTLINING PLANS TO DESTROY SCHOOL, SHERIFF SAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ One of the gunmen in the Columbine High
School massacre kept a diary outlining in meticulous detail his
plans to destroy the school and kill as many students as he could,
Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The first entry in the diary was made April 19, 1998, and the
last notation was entered Tuesday, the day of the attack. Stone
said the diary contained frequent neo-Nazi and German references
and specified the attack would be carried out on the April 20
anniversary of Adolf Hitler's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were after a big kill. They were going for a big kill,''
Stone said. ``It also talked about how they wanted to burn the
school down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to do as much damage as they could, destroy the
school and destroy as many students as they could,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The diary also offered a prophetic declaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``They expected to die,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, dressed in black trench
coats and ski masks, entered Columbine High at 11:15 a.m. Tuesday
with an arsenal of semi-automatic weapons, shotguns and handmade
bombs. They killed 12 students and a teacher before taking their
own lives.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 explosive devices were found inside the school and
in or underneath cars in the school parking lot. The bombs ranged
in size from small carbon dioxide canisters wrapped with BBs to a
20-pound propane tank bomb found in the cafeteria kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of 10 students were found in the library. Two were
found outside the school. The teacher, Dave Sanders, died in a
classroom where he was taken by students after he was wounded. He
died as SWAT officers worked to secure the school.
</P>
<P>
   According to autopsy reports, all 12 students and Sanders died
from gunshot wounds and the two gunmen died from self-inflicted
gunshot wounds. Another 23 students were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said the diary stated how the two were different from
their peers and described their hatred for ``jocks, because they're
always putting us down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were targeting these people because they felt they were
different,'' the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the diary outlined their plan in detail, including
notations on how to build the bombs, how many would be needed and
how they would get the guns needed to execute their massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Other details included hand signals they would give each other
during the attack, where the lighting was bad in the school, places
to hide and how many students would be in the cafeteria. He said
the two had a map of the campus with notations on how they would
carry out the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been on their mind. They've been planning this thing
for a considerable amount of time,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   The two had planned the attack for 11:15 a.m., because they
believed the cafeteria would be full. The diary stated it would be
the time for them to ``rock and roll,'' Stone said. About 900 of
the 1,900 students attending the school were in the cafeteria when
the attackers burst in.
</P>
<P>
   Stone declined to say who kept the diary or from which
teen-ager's home it was seized. Authorities searched the homes of
both. Stone said, however, that he was amazed that Harris' parents
were supposedly oblivious to their son's activities. He said a
sawed-off shotgun seized from Harris' bedroom was found on a
dresser and Nazi propaganda was displayed openly in his room.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined to say if the diary mentioned the names of
others involved in the planning or listed members of their social
group, the ``Trenchcoat Mafia.'' He said the diary listed e-mail
addresses that were being checked.
</P>
<P>
   Though no other suspects have been arrested in connection with
the attack, Stone said he firmly believes others were involved,
either in the planning or its execution, primarily because of the
size of the arsenal the two had in the school.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the 30 bombs, the two had a semi-automatic carbine, a
TEC-9 semi-automatic pistol, a pump shotgun, a double-barreled
shotgun and a large amount of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to go into a room blazing, carrying all
these devices,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a tape released Friday of two 911 calls from the school on
the day of the shooting has a caller referring to a suspect wearing
a white T-shirt, giving credence to the possibility of a third
gunman.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Davis, Jefferson County Sheriff's spokesman, said one
of the dead gunmen was found without his trench coat, clad in a
white T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the students did say there were three people,'' Davis
said. ``We've been looking for three people but so far we've only
been able to find two.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 investigators have collected more than 2,000
pieces of evidence and interviewed more than 500 people in the
investigation, which is expected to take weeks to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be totally reconstructing this,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, police discounted an anonymous e-mail sent to the
sheriff's office Friday that blamed the shooting on parents,
teachers and the students who tormented the two shooters. The
e-mail also threatened a second attack on April 26.
</P>
<P>
   The note, as reprinted by the Rocky Mountain News, read, ``By
now, it's over. If you are reading this, my mission is complete. I
have finished revolutionizing the neoeuphoric infliction of my
internal terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your children who have ridiculed me, who have chosen not to
accept me, who have treated me like I am not worth their time are
dead. THEY ARE (expletive) DEAD.''
</P>
<P>
   The note ends with, ``You may think the horror ends with the
bullet in my head, but you wouldn't be so lucky. All that I can
leave you with to decipher what more extensive death is to come is
`12Skizto.' You have until April 26th. Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the coded message referred to a song titled 12, by
the band Insane Clown Posse. He said it is doubtful the note was
written by Harris or Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time we have little reason to believe that either one
of our suspects sent that note or authored it,'' Davis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
