<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PARAMILITARIES     04-24 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PARAMILITARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES SAY KILLINGS AND RAPES BY PARAMILITARY UNITS ARE FUELING
THE EXODUS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ Serbian paramilitaries reportedly rampaged
through two ethnic Albanian villages in central Kosovo last Sunday,
killing as many as 40 people, including four or five young women
who were raped and then executed, refugees arriving here said on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees said their accounts were based on talks with
survivors. One man, Sali, said he ventured into one of the villages
a day after the killings from his neighboring settlement, heard
that some of his relatives had perished and was taken to a swath of
freshly dug earth measuring about 10 feet by 30 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the grave after they buried them,'' he said, refusing to
give his last name as he sobbed. ``Four of my uncles are in that
grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Sali and other refugees said they had been told that
paramilitaries had forced local Gypsies to collect the bodies of
those shot by Serbs and to bury them in a mass grave.
</P>
<P>
   None of the accounts of the refugees could be independently
confirmed. But three men gave independent and similar accounts of
the reported attacks on Sunday in the two villages west of Lipljan,
which they called Ribar i Vogel and Rufc i Ri. Officials from the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said four to five refugees also
described the attack to them.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees arriving here have consistently reported that
paramilitary units have been responsible for some of the most
vicious attacks in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees arriving Saturday said that the attack on Sunday was
part of an offensive that began on April 14. They said that 14
Albanian villages were fully or partly burned in just a day around
the town of Lipljan.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of refugees from other parts of Kosovo have flooded
into the area, they added.
</P>
<P>
   A pediatrician who was among the 2,200 ethnic Albanians who
arrived here Saturday said that pneumonia, diarrhea, bronchitis and
other infectious diseases are spreading. He and other refugees
urgently called for food to be air dropped to people trapped in the
hills.
</P>
<P>
   Fatmir Tixhaj, 23, said Serb border guards blocked him from
leaving Kosovo during five previous attempts to flee. He also said
fights often erupt among panicked people trying to board the one
train out of southeastern Kosovo to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks like the one last Sunday are fueling the exodus,
refugees said. Sali and another villager who would not give his
name said the Serbian police chief from Lipljan visited Ribar i
Vogel the night before the reported attack took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told the villagers, `There are paramilitaries coming here
tomorrow,''' Sali recounted. ```They are not under our control.
They will rob you and take your cars. Give them what they want
because they won't kill you.'''
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 the following morning, the refugees said, two dozen
heavily armed paramilitaries wearing black ski masks reportedly
entered the village in vehicles without license plates.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors told the refugees who were interviewed Saturday that
the armed men moved from house to house, forcing the village's
occupants to gather on its main street. There, they were divided
into three groups _ women and the elderly, men of fighting age, and
Gypsies, the refugees said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 25 men were taken to a nearby field, according to the
refugees. One of them, the brother of a prominent local businessman
reportedly killed by Serbs on the day NATO air strikes began,
turned over $5,000 in cash seconds before the paramilitaries opened
fire, killing 16 men, the refugees said.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees said local villagers told them that paramilitaries
had also killed two elderly adults in their homes, then raped and
murdered four or five local women. They then burned Ribar i Vogel,
and moved on to the nearby village of Rufc i Ri. The refugees said
they had heard from residents of that village that some two dozen
villagers were killed there.
</P>
<P>
   Sali and the two other local men gave slightly different figures
for the total number killed in the villages. But all gave detailed
accounts of a group execution in the first village, four to five
women being raped and murdered, and a later attack on the second
village.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
