<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-PIZZA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TWO GUNMEN CALLED `EXCELLENT EMPLOYEES' BY PIZZA SHOP MANAGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   By LISA TEACHEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Despite the revelation Saturday that two
teen-age gunmen plotted for at least a year to massacre students at
their high school, a pizza place co-worker described a very
different public side.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were good kids as far as we knew,'' said a manager of a
local pizza delivery restaurant where Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan
Klebold, 17, worked part time as cooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew these kids as people, not the monsters that everybody
is calling them,'' said the co-manager of Blackjack Pizza, who
would only identify himself as Jason.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold worked after school about five days a week at
one of the pizza chain's stores just a few blocks from suburban
Columbine High School, southwest of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve students and a teacher were killed and 23 others wounded
Tuesday when Harris and Klebold stormed the school with guns and
homemade bombs. The teens committed suicide inside the school after
their deadly rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County authorities on Saturday said they had found a
diary belonging to one of the boys. Entries in the diary suggest
the pair developed their plot for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   The teens belonged to a clique called the ``Trenchcoat Mafia''
after the style of long black coats the members wore.
</P>
<P>
   The pizza manager said Harris and Klebold sometimes wore their
coats to work but their fashion statement was never taken as a
symbol of violent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had mentioned they were part of a group that wore the
coats,'' Jason said. ``It just sounded like a regular group of kids
to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this stuff on the news about them being loners, that's not
true,'' Jason said. ``They had other friends. They were fairly
outgoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a former member of the group recently told a national
television audience that Harris' life was ``pretty much in
shambles'' in part because he recently lost his job, Jason said
both boys worked the Friday before the shooting but had been given
the weekend off to attend the school's prom.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way would we fire them. They weren't even close to being
reprimanded,'' Jason said. ``They were excellent employees. Two of
our best workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason said they were always on time, never called in sick and
always wore their uniforms. Each was usually scheduled to work five
days a week after school but at least one day a week one was off
while the other worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were here more than they were not, except when they had
to be at school,'' Jason said. ``They were good at their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In their private lives, Harris was apparently fascinated with
Adolf Hitler. It also has been reported the pair would salute like
Nazis and shout ``Heil Hitler'' after a good score during bowling
classes. But friends have said Klebold, whose grandfather built a
Jewish community center in Ohio, was less racist than Harris.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the teens ever made racist comments at work, Jason
said, ``I would rather not comment on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Harris maintained a Web site on the Internet with
detailed instructions for making bombs from easily obtained items,
Jason said he could not recall the teens talking at work about guns
or bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no signs this was going to happen,'' Jason said.
``He (Harris) just seemed like an intelligent boy. He had his
moments of being quiet and moments of being hyper just like
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pizza restaurant's part-time workers are students at
Columbine High School and knew the gunmen and their victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been kind of short-staffed around here since this
happened, but our corporation has been very good to us about it,''
Jason said. ``We feel for all the families and kids. It's just
major grief here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
