u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-MEMORIAL-HNS     04-24 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-MEMORIAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
2,500 ATTEND FUNERAL OF TEEN EULOGIZED AS WRITER, CHURCHGOER
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By JIM HENDERSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LITTLETON, Colo. _ They prayed for divine intervention to ``take
out of us our hatred ... our anger.''
</P>
<P>
   They held hands and sang Amazing Grace.
</P>
<P>
   With sobs and impassioned words, they remembered a young friend
and relative and then laid her to rest in a white wood casket
signed with messages of love.
</P>
<P>
   This was the weekend that Littleton began to bury its dead. At
Trinity Christian Center on Saturday, nearly 2,500 mourners said
goodbye to 17-year-old Rachel Scott. They and the ministers who
officiated searched, as they have all week, for a meaning and a
redemption in Tuesday's massacre at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was one of 13 people _ 12 students and a teacher _ killed
when two Columbine students, Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold,
17, terrorized the school for four hours with guns and bombs. The
two then killed themselves in the library.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tragedy has shaken every one of us to the very core of
our being,'' said the Rev. Bruce Porter. ``We are all in a state of
shock. But, it's vitally important that we ask ourselves some hard
questions. What has happened to us as a people that this would
happen to us? What has happened to us? How did we get here?''
</P>
<P>
   After consoling the gathering with scriptures, Porter offered
his thoughts on what has gone awry in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took the 10 commandments from our schools and wreaked
murder and violence and hatred,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Scott was eulogized Saturday partly as an aspiring writer
and thespian, but mostly as a devout churchgoer who ``accepted
everyone'' and spread her own gospel through her circle of friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She taught me the value of life,'' one friend said. ``She
taught me to love every second you have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She made me feel like the most important person in the
world,'' another said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life was like one big amusement park to Rachel,'' said
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made people laugh. She wrote poetry and she cared so much
about people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of her classmates stood in the aisles and tearfully
embraced.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down on the closed coffin, Porter told the high school
students in the gathering: ``Don't despair of life. Don't despair
of what has happened to you. The torch has fallen from Rachel's
hand. Who will pick it up again?''
</P>
<P>
   Adults had failed them, he told the students. Politicians had
failed them and the police had failed them. But, he said, they
could succeed where other had not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick up the torch. You have the power, young people.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been the theme of memorial services held in Littleton
in the past few days, a resolve to give meaning to the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   As the town has emerged from its initial shock, it has searched,
sometimes awkwardly, always painfully, for its next step.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the day Scott's classmate, John Tomlin, was
memorialized before his body was transported to Wisconsin for
burial, District Attorney Dave Thomas appeared before reporters and
asked for their help in finding that next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be some meaning in this,'' he said, frustrated by
the absence of answers. ``These deaths cannot be in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   During Scott's funeral, a friend, Mike Tatu, sang a song he
wrote for her after her death. ``Why did you have to leave?'' it
asked.
</P>
<P>
   It is a question that will be at the forefront of Littleton's
thoughts for some time.
</P>
<P>
   The town still has 13 more funerals to face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
