<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2096 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SUMMIT-HNS &LR;      04-24 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO CONFLICT FORCES NATO TO DELAY, DILUTE KEY DISCUSSIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CRAGG HINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO leaders' focus on Kosovo has been both a
reason and an excuse for diluted attention to key issues in the
alliance's future, including further expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on the fight in the Balkans, however, also has
given unexpected emphasis to the growing importance the West
attaches to human rights _ even at the expense of national
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we are moving into a system of international
relations in which human rights ... are much more important, and
more important even than sovereignty rights,'' NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Solana and other NATO leaders, including President Clinton, are
finding that the public in Western Europe and North America are
responding more positively to the fight against Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic when it is expressed in terms of his campaign
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo rather than in more traditional
terms of national or regional interests.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day summit ends today after meetings intended to
illustrate NATO's outreach to central and Eastern European nations.
Leaders of the 19 NATO member nations will meet with
representatives of all but one of the 24 additional nations in the
Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council. Russia is boycotting the summit
because it opposes NATO's air attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO leaders also will hold a special session with seven of
Yugoslavia's neighbors, looking ahead to programs that will help
the region rebuild after the fighting in Kosovo has ended, Solana
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will develop the initiative mainly in three areas _
security, economics and democracy-building _ that will be no doubt
crucial to the integration'' of the southeastern Europe, Solana
said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders Saturday adopted the alliance's first new
``strategic concept'' policy since 1991, when the Soviet Union was
collapsing. The Balkan conflict has dampened enthusiasm of some
NATO nations for making the new plan any more robust or covering
any more territory than necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said the latest outline emphasizes ``new challenges such
as regional conflicts, weapons of mass destruction, nuclear
proliferation and transnational threats such as terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general called the new plan ``a road map to help
us navigate through the challenges that await us in the next
half-century. It also marks the transition from an alliance that
was concerned mainly with collective defense to one that will be a
guarantee of security in Europe and upholder of democratic values
both within and beyond our borders.''
</P>
<P>
   While recognizing the need to respond to ``out of area''
conflicts such as in Kosovo, the plan does not take in the
unlimited horizon that the Clinton administration was proposing.
The most immediate effect is likely to be that NATO will not have a
direct, automatic role in conflicts in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the geographical extent,'' Solana said, ``as you
know, NATO is not a universal organization. NATO is a territorially
limited organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its aim, its commitment, its engagement is to what we call the
Euro-Atlantic area. And we are prepared to cooperate to the
security and the stability of the Euro-Atlantic area,'' Solana
said.
</P>
<P>
   As at almost any international meeting, there was jockeying to
get in diplomatic verbiage which can mean different things to
different people _ or nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new NATO points stresses the ``primary
responsibility'' of the U.N. Security Council for world peace,
without giving that often-contentious body power to block NATO
action.
</P>
<P>
   Solana rejected the suggestion that the wording, reportedly
advanced by France, meant that the Security Council _ where Russia
and China are among the five nations with veto power _ would have
to approve any future NATO military operation.
</P>
<P>
   As an illustration of the varying interpretations, French
President Jacques Chirac said NATO ``cannot and will not act
without the acquiescence'' of the United Nations, while Dutch Prime
Minister Wim Kok said NATO action will be ``based on the general
principles of the U.N. charter.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Solana stressed that NATO wanted to
``strengthen our partnership'' with the absent Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders did not address substantively the NATO issue that
most upsets Russia, further expansion into former Soviet-bloc
territory. No timetable was adopted for a second round of
admissions from the old Eastern Bloc _ home to all nine candidate
nations: Albania, Bulgaria, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Macedonia,
Romania, Slovakia and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   For some current NATO nations not yet ready for another
expansion round, the attention the summit had to give to the
Yugoslav conflict was a plausible excuse for delaying the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is committed to keeping its door open,'' Solana insisted.
The recent addition of Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland to NATO
``will not be the last. I'd like to emphasize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Solana said NATO is working with applicant nations ``day by day,
with a very specific plan ..., so the moment when they are prepared
to be NATO members will not be a dramatic moment, it will be a
natural moment.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders also moved toward approving a plan under which
alliance forces could be split off and operate for a time wholly as
a European Union entity, on the assumption that there could be
small dust-ups on the continent that the United States would not be
interested in policing.
</P>
<P>
   Final agreement on the section was held up by objections from
Turkey which, over its continuing objections, is not a member of
the EU.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 2215EDT &QL; 
