<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2218 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STLD     04-24 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO CAPAIGN ENTERS SECOND MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to recast lead; story expands to 2 takes)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS and ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO began its second month of bombing against
Yugoslavia Saturday with new strikes against military targets that
disrupted civilian electrical and water supplies, as the alliance's
leaders took steps to expand the war effort, including an agreement
to use air bases in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting here to commemorate the alliance's 50th anniversary,
NATO's leaders vowed to sharpen pressure on Yugoslavia's president,
Slobodan Milosevic, to end his campaign against Albanians in
Kosovo. The prime minister of Hungary, Viktor Orban, disclosed
Saturday that his country had agreed to allow NATO war planes to
operate from all three of its military airfields.
</P>
<P>
   With the supreme commander of NATO, Gen. Wesley Clark,
requesting 400 more aircraft for intensified strikes, the assent by
Hungary gives the alliance the ability to attack with more
firepower from more approaches nearby. Hungary, one of the
alliance's three new members, is the only NATO country to share a
border with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Broadening its war effort on another level, NATO leaders agreed
on Friday to impose an oil embargo enforced by NATO warships plying
the Adriatic Sea. Although details of that blockade must still be
worked out, the Pentagon said Saturday that allied warships would
search tankers and divert those found to be carrying oil to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official said the allied ships would fire on any
vessels that defied the blockade, first as a warning and then to
disable, if not sink, violators. While NATO already has a
considerable armada in the Adriatic and Ionian Seas, it could take
a week to organize a blockade.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, appearing at the summit conference after a
second day of meetings with leaders of NATO's 18 other members,
defended the gambit, even though some allies, including France, had
expressed reservations about its legality. ``If we want this
campaign to succeed with economic and political pressure and with
the air action, then we have to take every reasonable means to give
it the chance to succeed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's latest step brought a new denunciation from Russia, which
has strongly opposed the raids on Yugoslavia. Russian officials
vowed to continue shipping oil to Yugoslavia's ports on the
Adriatic coast, raising the prospect of confrontations at sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blockade is bad,'' Russia's special envoy to Yugoslavia,
Viktor Chernomyrdin, said Saturday in Moscow. ``The problem in
Kosovo can be solved neither by bombing nor by a blockade.''
</P>
<P>
   The second day of NATO's summit meeting shifted to a discussion
of the alliance's long-range strategies, including how NATO can use
its collective resources to slow the spread of nuclear, biological
and chemical weapons. But the air war in the Balkans loomed over
the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In opening remarks Saturday morning, Clinton urged his
colleagues to remember the three American soldiers who have been
held as prisoners of war in Yugoslavia since they were captured
along the Macedonian border on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The International Committee of the Red Cross announced Saturday
that its director, Cornelio Sommaruga, would meet with Milosevic in
Belgrade on Monday to discuss the fate of the three Americans and
the plight of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Clinton derided Yugoslavia's refusal to allow
the Red Cross to visit the prisoners, as explicitly required by the
Geneva Convention of 1949, despite Milosevic's pledge in a
television interview this past week. The Red Cross's spokeswoman in
Geneva, Amanda Williamson, said, ``We will be reminding the
Yugoslav authorities of their responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   After cloudy weather limited NATO's air strikes overnight on
Friday, allied missiles and aircraft carried out attacks Saturday
night in Novi Sad and Nis, Yugoslavia's second and third-largest
cities after Belgrade. The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported an
intense barrage of 26 missiles during a half hour in Nis. The
agency said the railway, water mains, an office building and an
industrial complex had all been hit.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials said the strikes in Nis had focused
on the airfield and the barracks of the Third Army, the force
leading the offensive against Albanians in Kosovo. They reported
attacks on the oil refinery in Novi Sad, which has been hit before,
as well as an oil storage installation, two other airfields, still
more radar sites and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   As the bombings continue, they are starting to take a toll on
Yugoslavia's civilian society. Strikes on electrical grids have
caused outages. Water pressure has become erratic in some cities.
In many cases, water mains are carried on the bridges that NATO has
been knocking down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is, of course, also an aspect of civilian
inconvenience,'' NATO's spokesman, Jamie Shea, said Saturday. ``I
acknowledge that, but it's not our intention _ I want to make this
clear _ to in any way render the life of Serbs even more difficult
than it already is. Our intention is simply to target the military
power apparatus.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's state television network, whose studios in Belgrade
were struck early on Friday, went off the air again early Saturday
and did not resume for five hours. There was no immediate
explanation for the disruption, but NATO struck radio and
television relay towers at Kragujevac and Novi Sad overnight. Shea
openly threatened to hit state television again and again until it
was knocked off the air.
</P>
<P>
   Early on Sunday morning, air strikes cut state television's
satellite transmissions and seriously affected reception in
Belgrade, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   The network is among a new category of targets that Clark has
received permission to strike, but the strikes have caused deep
misgivings among some allies.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's foreign minister, Lamberto Dini, said Saturday that he
had not known about the attack in advance and did not support it.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton distanced himself somewhat from the military
decision to strike at the television studio headquarters, saying
NATO's commanders considered the television network ``an essential
instrument of Mr. Milosevic's command and control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not in a conventional sense therefore a media outlet,''
he said. ``That was a decision they made, and I did not reverse
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite misgivings, NATO's allies appeared unified at the summit
meeting, which was marked by the alliance's determination to
intensify the campaign, now in its 32nd day. Clinton appealed again
for patience, noting that the United States and its allies bombed
Iraq's forces for 44 days in the prelude to the Persian Gulf war in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that this air campaign has been going on for a
particularly long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the campaign expanding to around-the-clock bombings and
hundreds of aircraft overcrowding Italy's skies, Hungary's
willingness to open its airfields became critical.
</P>
<P>
   For Hungary, the conflict with Yugoslavia has proved
particularly troubling. Its leaders have expressed fear that a more
active role could put at risk some 300,000 ethnic Hungarians living
in Vojvodina, another Serbian province whose autonomy was stripped
along with Kosovo's in 1989. ``It's extremely complicated for
Hungary,'' Orban said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While sympathetic, NATO officials told Hungary that as a NATO
ally it now had an obligation to open up the bases, according to a
senior NATO official. Many of the 300 additional American warplanes
are expected eventually to end up in Hungary, where NATO officers
are already assessing bases in Taszar, Kecskemet and Papa.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech Republic, another new member, also has offered its
bases, according to a spokesman for President Vaclav Havel, but
they are less crucial to NATO's plans. NATO also received
permission from Bulgaria and Romania, to the east of Yugoslavia, to
make use of their airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the intensification of the air war, NATO has been forced
to consider the blockade to stop the flow of oil to Yugoslavia's
military. Although air raids have damaged the country's two
principal refineries and scores of depots, Yugoslavia is still
receiving shipments through its ports. Some NATO commanders have
argued for the destruction of the oil sites at the ports, but NATO
political leaders worry about significant strikes in the Yugoslav
federation's smaller republic, Montenegro, whose government is seen
as less hostile to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Although Yugoslav forces are still able to wage war, NATO
officials say they have detected what they interpret to be signs of
strain in Milosevic's control. A spokesman for Prime Minister Tony
Blair of Britain, Alastair Campbell, said a number of Yugoslav
generals and retired generals had been arrested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
