<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2223 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-TROUT-LADN     04-24 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-TROUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON OPENING DAY OF TROUT SEASON, BIGGER IS BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMMOTH LAKES, Calif. _ Size matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only caught two and I let 'em go,'' said Alan Hurni of
Canoga Park. He cast a juicy gob of Power Bait and a night crawler
in hopes a trophy trout would find the bait an irresistible cherry
atop a sundae. ``I'm only after the big one.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment expressed Saturday morning at Lower Twin Lake
outside of Bridgeport prevailed among experienced anglers on
opening day of trout season in the Eastern Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   Sure it was the first chance in six months to catch fish here,
but it was also the first chance to catch big fish, so why settle
for the little ones? The smiles aren't nearly as wide in snapshots
of guys holding stringers of 1-pound foot-long trout stocked
earlier in the week as the fellows hoisting 5-plus-pound bruisers
wider than the space between their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Illusions of grandeur only become grander as the angler's beard
grows longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my fish big, over 2 pounds, at least. I've got a lot of
neighbors to feed,'' said Billy Ray Ellis, 64, of Frazier Park, who
began fishing the Eastern Sierra in 1959. A splash of Sierra Gold
processed bait dressed his hook before daybreak at the north end of
Grant Lake in the June Lake Loop. A pair of loons sang their
distinctive call as snow-capped San Joaquin Mountain rose in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed if I drive all the way up here, spend all
that money and catch only 6-inchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis comes to the less-visited side of Grant for the opener
because it has consistently produced lunkers for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've landed more than 10 4-pounders right here, where I'm
standing,'' said the white-haired West Virginia native. Around the
corner, just to the south, he has taken 7\- and 7}-pounders.
</P>
<P>
   Familiarity plays a major role for those who race after
whoppers; it breeds confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Vic McCarty keeps chasing the memory of an 8-pounder he caught
as a teen-ager fishing Grant Lake in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still see the dorsal fin and the tail fin cutting the
water,'' said McCarty of Oak Hills, north of San Bernardino, who
fishes Grant 10 times a season. ``That's why I fish this lake;
there are some big fish here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't catch a 4-, 5-, 6-pound trout very often. Every fish
I catch is fun, don't get me wrong, but when you catch a big fish,
it's different.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you got something (worthy). You're backing off the
drag, jumping up to see what you got and the next thing you know
your jeans are knee deep in the water. You don't get that with
little fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's Bob Groover is less enthusiastic about the ``every
fish.'' ``I'm going for size,'' he explained after displaying a
6-pound, 9-ounce rainbow hooked at dawn on yellow Power Bait
shore-fishing at Lower Twin Lake. He released a dozen smaller
specimens before keeping the one trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago I fished to fish, and now I'm targeting bigger
fish,'' Groover said.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident, no small coincidence he landed one of the
day's largest fish. In 1996 he claims to have caught 110 Eastern
Sierra trout that tilted the scales at more than 5 pounds; he
releases everything smaller. His largest is a 10\ trout that won
the annual fishing derby at Convict Lake.
</P>
<P>
   One of the niceties of living in the area, huh? He's a grocery
clerk, but I have to wonder if the guy ever really works.
</P>
<P>
   Is a 6-pound, 9-ounce fish still exciting?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' Groover affirmed. ``I thought I was going to
lose it because a boat ran right over the line and the fish jumped.
I thought it was going to get caught up in the propeller.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knows where the big fish swim; he hedged his bets by
casting lines at Bridgeport's Twin Lakes, which have produced the
largest trout for the last four opening days.
</P>
<P>
   For some fishermen, they may be destined to catch ``the big
one''; it's in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the plight of Sacramento's Paul Aguirre. His older
brother, Jason, took last year's opening-day big-fish honors with a
7-pound, 10-ounce brown out of Upper Twin Lake. His father, Sid,
performed the same feat in an opener earlier this decade, snatching
a 13-pounder at Lower Twin Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, that guy, jerk, he's a king around here,'' Aguirre
joshed about his father while fishing the East Walker River as it
spills out of Bridgeport Reservoir. ``He's consistently in the
4-pound range.''
</P>
<P>
   The family enjoys a friendly competition each year, but Paul is
on the short end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm due,'' he said. ``I'm just waiting for my trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fish for small fish. In fact, it's gotten to the point
where I throw back pretty decent fish _ 2 pounds or better. I have
to catch up with my dad and my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for most anglers, any fish will do, and, for some,
believe it or not, the smaller the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I like 'em perfect pan size,'' said Daniel Westbrook
of Phelan, northeast of Wrightwood. ``They don't taste as good any
bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an eater, not a trophy guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, size matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
