<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2237 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLUMN-SPORTS-LITTLET     04-24 1771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-SPORTS-LITTLETON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tragedy strikes a familiar chord in us all
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Gary Morris was on his way to lunch Tuesday
morning, walking near the front entrance of Columbine High School
when he stopped to get a drink of water.
</P>
<P>
   He said hello to a friend who plays for the girls soccer team,
which had lost just one game all year, is ranked No. 10 in the
nation and was supposed to play undefeated Green Mountain for the
league championship Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You goin' to the game?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' Morris said. ``I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   He was wearing his favorite baseball cap, a worn white cap with
the bill bent just the way he liked and the words ``Texas Tech
Football'' inscribed on the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I want to go to college,'' Morris, 16, said.
``I've never been there, but I know Tech has a good architecture
program and that's what I want to study. Do you know if they have a
wrestling team down there?''
</P>
<P>
   Morris is, in high school parlance, a jock.
</P>
<P>
   He is about 5-9, stoutly built, with strawberry blond hair, a
few freckles and bright, hazel eyes. He once played football for
the Columbine Rebels but then turned to wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   As he leaned over the water fountain in the main hallway of
Columbine High, a resounding blast jolted him and he clicked his
teeth against the water fountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought, `Fireworks,''' Morris said. ``You know,
it's senior-prank time around here.''
</P>
<P>
   But then there were more pops, then crashes, then screams. There
were students running in every direction and teachers slamming
classroom doors and telling kids to run. He saw ``Mr. Sanders'' _
Dave Sanders, the popular girls basketball and softball coach, who
gave his life to save 100 or more students.
</P>
<P>
   Morris saw other students running through the halls in a frenzy.
Up ahead, he saw one figure fall to the floor. Then, there was
another blast that blew the windows out of a nearby office and sent
glass clattering across the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right there,'' Morris said, ``I started running.''
</P>
<P>
   The front entrance was close to where Morris was standing, but
``for some reason I ran in the other direction to a door that was
farther down the hall. That's where I got out. I don't know why I
did that, but I wouldn't be standing here if I had gone to the
front door. They came through that (front) door and started
shooting. I know they would have killed me. They knew me. And with
this hat on, they would have killed me. They hated jocks.''
</P>
<P>
   They were Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. Few people knew them
before Tuesday afternoon. Yet we all did.
</P>
<P>
   They were the quiet, dark outcasts that rebelled against the
mainstream. They dressed differently, lived differently and felt
disenfranchised.
</P>
<P>
   They were ignored or picked on by those who proudly wore the
school colors, those who went to the pep rallies, wore the spirit
ribbons and corsages, painted football banners, decorated the
commons for prom night, put in extra hours in the weight room and
were part of something that most students considered important at
the school.
</P>
<P>
   That's how somehow this dreadful massacre at Columbine High has
become intertwined with the sports world. We all knew, or know,
high school students who go their own way and are quietly and
mysteriously different from the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it was when I was in high school. That's how it is
now, perhaps at every high school in America. That's probably how
it will be forever.
</P>
<P>
   If kids sometimes can be cruel, like the saying goes, then high
school kids sometimes can be cruel, cliquish and unrelenting.
</P>
<P>
   And usually, the differences between cliques are most defined
and most intense in the relationship between the in-crowd athletes
and the dark group that considers athletes the epitome of what they
do not want to be.
</P>
<P>
   Choose your nickname. I remember the ``cons.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 1979. We would walk to the field house after football
practice and hear heckles from the cons, who usually sat under a
tree in the parking lot of Edison High School in San Antonio. Once,
one of the cons shot a few rounds from a BB gun at us and a
full-fledged brawl broke out, rocks thrown, bottles breaking, until
the coaches gained control. We would exchange glares in the
hallways every day thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a proud memory, but a vivid one.
</P>
<P>
   Time changes only the nicknames given to these groups. At
different schools and in different eras, they might be called the
``heads'' or ``stoners'' or ``gothics'' or ``freaks'' or ``nerds''
or ``rednecks'' or ``boyz'' or ``geeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the ``Trenchcoat Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   Different. Dark. At war with the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   They often are not bad, only different. Often, they grow up to
make more of their lives than the captain of the football team or
the head cheerleader. Bill Gates is said to have been an outcast in
high school _ nerdy, quiet and different. Now he runs Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   But when a kid is in high school and he lives in a world that
can be cruel, cliquish and unrelenting, the differences between the
in crowd and the outcasts are potentially explosive and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric and Dylan loved to be hated,'' said Tyler Jackman, 17,
who is not involved in sports at Columbine but knew Harris and
Klebold from a video class they took together. ``People say the
jocks picked on them, but it's like they wanted people to talk
about them and notice them. I used to think, `You guys want
everyone to hate you.' Especially the jocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackman saw a video confiscated this week by law enforcement
authorities investigating Tuesday's massacre. The video Harris and
Klebold made was the final exam for the video class last year.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Jackman said there is one scene in which a student
wearing a Columbine basketball jersey is being beaten and kicked by
Klebold and Harris. There is another scene in which an athlete is
walking down the hall of the school flexing his muscles, only to be
jumped and beaten by actors wearing trench coats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the school knew the jocks and the Trenchcoat
Mafia didn't like each other,'' Jackman said. ``They fought all the
time. They'd pass each other in the hall and (stuff) would happen.
You just never thought it would go this far.''
</P>
<P>
   A boys varsity soccer player, who asked to remain anonymous,
said: ``They wanted to get the jocks. When this happened (Tuesday),
I was running and turned the corner and looked right at one of
them. I just sort of froze. He told me, `I've got a problem with
jocks, but I don't have a problem with you.' That's all he said.
And he kept going. I ran out of the building and kept hearing
shots. I was thinking to myself, People are dying in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The alleged attackers killed 12 students and Sanders, before
apparently killing themselves. Nearly two dozen others were
injured. Not all the victims were athletes, but amid the chaos
several athletes were systematically sought out.
</P>
<P>
   Isaiah Shoels, a former football player and bodybuilder, was
killed execution-style. Mattew Kechter, a football player, was
killed. Steven Curnow, a soccer player, was killed. Another soccer
player was injured. Corey DePooter, a wrestler, was killed. Another
wrestler was injured. Lauren Townsend, the popular captain of the
volleyball team and in line to be class valedictorian, was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they had a hit list,'' said Noah Smeltzer, a two-sport
athlete at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Several students reported one of the gunmen announcing in the
library during the rampage: ``All jocks stand up. We're going to
kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said Harris marked next to pictures of classmates in his
yearbook ``dead,'' ``dying'' or ``save.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was like two different kinds of people getting
attention,'' Morris said. ``The athletes were out there trying to
do something positive, something that people wanted to go see. The
Trenchcoat Mafia wanted those people to notice them because they
were different. They wanted to be the exact opposite. They would do
things just to off the jocks and then they'd start calling each
other names or fight. Dylan and Eric liked that.''
</P>
<P>
   They wanted people to notice them. Sadly, the entire world has.
</P>
<P>
   There was no big game Friday evening. Instead, there was a
memorial service, the first of what will be a terribly sad,
seemingly endless stream of services for the victims of Tuesday's
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no league championship. No baseball season. No
more school this year at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday evening, girls soccer coach Peter Horvath went to one
of his player's homes, where the team met and tried to come to
grips with the devastation. They talked about what Klebold and
Harris did. They talked about the hatred they must have had, the
inexplicable defiance.
</P>
<P>
   The soccer team voted to try to complete the season, probably
late next week. Thursday, they gathered as a team for the first
time since Tuesday. They went on a long run not far from the
makeshift memorial at Clement Park near the school, where streams
of ribbons, banners, balloons and jerseys from virtually every high
school in the area decorated the park, as Columbine students wept.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball coach Robin Ortiz attended a meeting of district
coaches Wednesday, where it was decided the remainder of the season
would be canceled. Instead, a tournament will be played late next
week, where playoff seeds will be determined and all proceeds will
go to a fund established for the victims of Columbine High.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't seem to like other people,'' Noelle Porter, 17,
said. ``They always wanted to prove something about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   They did and the school never will be the same. The vivid high
school memories these kids will carry with them for the rest of
their lives will not be about big games, dances, proms and pep
rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to become a place with no jocks, no preps, no
druggies, nothing like that at all,'' Dustin Gordon, 18, said. ``We
have to tear down all the walls and just be Columbine, like any
other school.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's just it. It was like any other school until Tuesday.
It was like a school all of us have attended.
</P>
<P>
   That's what should send a shock up all our spines and jolt us
into helping our kids understand that no matter if you are an
athlete, a cheerleader, a geek or an outcast, it's high school.
</P>
<P>
   It can give us beautiful memories that we carry with us forever.
It can be cruel, cliquish and unrelenting.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine Rebels should be our cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
