<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2258 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BECKETT-HNS &LR;      04-24 1521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BECKETT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
High school ace confident in ability
<TEXT>
<P>
   By BRIAN McTAGGART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
OPPOSING fans heckle him, kids love him and everybody wants a piece
of him. For Josh Beckett, he wouldn't want it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why this likable Spring High School senior, who
has been blessed with a cannon for a right arm, is billed as the
next can't-miss pitching prospect from a state that has produced
more than a few.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know how good Beckett is, just ask one of the
handful of radar gun-toting scouts who are at each game he pitches,
charting every sizzling 95 mph fastball and every knee-buckling
curveball.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want a better idea of what ignites Kid Heat's fire,
just ask the man himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the best, buddy,'' he said. ``That's why I'm so relaxed
out there. You've got to have some arrogant bones in your body,
especially to be a pitcher in the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Beckett, the major leagues might not be too far away.
</P>
<P>
   He's expected to be the No. 1 overall selection in June's
major-league baseball amateur draft, a pick that belongs to Tampa
Bay. Devil Rays scout Doug Gassaway, a Texas scout for more than 30
years, has called Beckett one of the best he has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett, 8-0 with a 0.24 ERA this year for the Lions (21-5), has
struck out 119 and allowed only 18 hits, five runs (two earned) and
23 walks in 59 innings pitched. His next start will come Tuesday at
home against Cypress Falls as Spring tries to clinch the District
16-5A title.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's star began rising among scouts last year when talk
surfaced that he would be a coveted draft pick. Beckett mania soon
followed.
</P>
<P>
   In Beckett's last start Tuesday against Cypress Creek, a group
of Little Leaguers clamored around his 6-5 frame after the game,
handed him baseballs and caps to sign and asked questions usually
reserved for veteran professionals.
</P>
<P>
   One week earlier at Cy-Fair, more than 40 kids and adults had to
be ushered off the bullpen mound so Beckett and catcher Stephen
Ghutzman, also a preseason All-American, could get in their
pre-game workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually getting worse,'' Lions coach Kenny Humphreys
said. ``But it's not a case where it's a bad deal. Young kids are
looking for role models, heroes and things like that, and they've
just attached themselves to him. His name is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphreys first heard Beckett's name when Beckett played against
Humphreys' son Kyle as an 11-year-old in the Spring Little League.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time you could tell he had a good, live arm,''
Humphreys said. ``He had a good fastball and good breaking stuff,
but you didn't know where it was going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, if he didn't strike you out, he was upset. By no
means was he the dominant player he is now, but he knew by spending
time and effort he could be something.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Beckett enrolled at Spring, Humphreys was head
baseball coach and had the pitcher on the junior varsity as a
freshman. Beckett's stuff was good, but something magical happened
to his right arm between his freshman and sophomore seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I first got noticed by scouts and my summer-league
coach, Clay Hill,'' Beckett said. ``I went that whole freshman year
on the JV and had some trouble in the classroom. It was tough
because I wasn't throwing that hard, 86 (mph) tops. That summer I
was throwing 92 or 93. I guess it was puberty, I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett went 9-3 as a sophomore with a 1.25 ERA and 150
strikeouts, and followed that up by going 13-2 last year (both
losses were 2-1) with a 0.39 ERA and 179 strikeouts. Each year,
Dobie's Nathan Mitchell eliminated Spring and Beckett from the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into this season, Beckett was tabbed the top high school
prospect in the nation and was featured in several well-known
publications, including Sports Illustrated, USA Today and Texas
Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Beckett found himself recognized by people he didn't
know and he even received a marriage proposal from a fan at a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's been the weirdest thing to happen so far,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before things got too wild, Beckett and his family sought advice
from Rick George, who's son, Chris, was a first-round pick by
Kansas City in last year's draft after leading Klein to the state
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick just said we really need to look at things in a logical
progression,'' said Beckett's father, John. ``First, you need to
get an adviser and then you deal with the scouts and you set up
some sort of visitation things with those guys. Basically, you set
limits and you know what the limits are and then you expect them to
respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's laid-back off-the-field mentality has enabled him to
handle all the attention with ease. But on the field, Beckett is an
intense competitor. He no longer gets angry when he doesn't strike
everybody out, but he remains an intense and intimidating
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get too many guys out there that are soft and don't have
the mentality,'' he said. ``They just want to go out there and be
all composed. One game I tried to do that and coach Humphreys came
out there and told me not to be so passive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I build on my arrogance and whenever I throw a fastball by
them I might shake my head or something. That helps me.''
</P>
<P>
   It also has opened him up to criticism from those who don't like
his mound antics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get heckled worse than anybody,'' he said. ``I get it bad. I
get called all kinds of stuff that's unreal. Whenever you give up a
hit, that's even worse because it gets blown completely out of
proportion. I'm not unhittable. I'd hit myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The taunting is tough for his father, a mechanical engineer who
stands near the Spring dugout each game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how hard that is for me to stand there and
listen to people,'' he said. ``It really kind of disgusts me. It's
been going on for a year or so but the first couple of times it
happened this year my senses were really kind of acute to it. You
would think that people would be happy for someone being able to
fulfill a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphreys said Beckett, 18, usually silences the hecklers with
his play on the mound and at the plate. Beckett is among area
leaders in batting average (.536) and has a school-record 10
homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been times he's come back at them but it's been in the
manner of his aggressiveness with a `here, take that' kind of
deal,'' he said. ``He's a very draftable player as a hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett grew up idolizing fellow Houston-area fireballers Nolan
Ryan and Roger Clemens. But it's Chicago Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood,
last year's National League Rookie of the Year, to whom he's most
often compared.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of similarities between the two,'' said The
Woodlands coach Mike McGilvray, who coached Wood at Grand Prairie
High School and faced Beckett this year. ``The thing that Kerry
would do is just compete, and I see that in (Josh). Both of them
throw very effortlessly. Josh doesn't have any wasted motion and is
mechanically sound. Kerry was the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a guy that's very similar to Kerry and a lot of people
are saying he's a little bit better than Kerry at this point. That
might be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's fastball was clocked as high as 99 mph this past
summer and 97 during this high school season. He's consistently
around 94.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has great command of his pitches, including a
curveball that's referred to as ``a 12-6 curve.'' The numbers refer
to a clock face and his curve drops straight down from 12 to 6.
Beckett knows he'll need more than a fastball to reach the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have your other stuff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all his professional aspirations, Beckett has maintained
his focus on winning a state championship, and Spring might have
the team to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real big,'' he said. ``My team deserves it because we've
been playing together since we were little, and coach Humphreys
deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft falls before the state tournament in Austin and by
that time Beckett could be staring millions of dollars in the face.
University of Miami third baseman Pat Burrell, the top pick in last
year's draft, received a $3.15 million signing bonus as part of a
five-year $8 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, Detroit, Arizona and Minnesota own the next four picks
after Tampa Bay and any of those would be fine with Beckett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really banking on any team,'' he said. ``There's a lot
of good stuff happening. But I think I can work up (to the majors)
as fast as Kerry Wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett has signed with Blinn College in case he doesn't sign
professionally, but he'll likely be drafted no lower than third and
offered money he can't pass up.
</P>
<P>
   It might then be only a matter of time before Beckett's name is
mentioned with Ryan, Clemens and Wood. He wouldn't want it any
other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the men, they stood above the rest,'' he said. ``Any
strikeout record worth having is in a Texas pitcher's pocket right
now. I might come join them one day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
