u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--Astros-Reds-HNS &LR;      04-24 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Reds-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Reds' call to bullpen offers relief to Astros
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ It's not often the Astros want to see the opposing
manager replace a soft-tossing lefthander with a hard-throwing
righty.
</P>
<P>
   But when it happened Saturday, you could see the life return to
the dugout _ not to mention the bats _ as the Astros snatched
victory from the clutches of defeat in a spirit-lifting game at
Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati manager Jack McKeon called off Steve Avery just in
time for the Astros to nab a come-from-behind, 4-3 victory at the
expense of Danny Graves, who stifled the Astros for two innings on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   To say the Astros were lucky to win Saturday's game would take
away from their resilient effort. But good luck finding an Astro
who thought the team had much chance of mounting a rally against
Avery, who had the Astros under his command.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avery had us frustrated,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
``We didn't have many chances against him. He was changing speeds
and painting the corners and we couldn't hit him. And then they
bring in a guy who's throwing in the 90s, and we start hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just goes to show you that a well-placed 85 mile per hour
pitch is better than a 93 mile per hour pitch thrown right down the
middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds had a 3-1 lead when Graves (1-3) entered the game. The
Astros promptly loaded the bases against him with two singles and a
walk, and Ken Caminiti's 1,500th career hit _ a single to right _
drove in two runs to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell scored the winning run on a fielder's-choice
grounder by Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon put himself in position to be second-guessed by using
Graves after the righthander had pitched two innings and thrown 26
pitches in Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Graves) obviously didn't have the kind of stuff he had
last night,'' Caminiti said. ``I don't know if he was tired from
the back-to-back games or what, but his stuff wasn't as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Graves' collapse, Reds relievers had allowed only one
earned run in their previous 15 innings. The Astros have two
relievers who can top that. Scott Elarton pitched two innings
Saturday and Billy Wagner worked the ninth for his fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   As a tandem, Elarton (2-0) and Wagner have pitched 17 scoreless
innings, allowing seven hits and eight walks. They have combined
for 29 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   And while Wagner is 5-for-5 in save opportunities, he hasn't
mastered the art of easy conversions. As is often the case, this
one took some effort.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner struck out Brian Johnson to open the ninth inning, but
Johnson reached on Tony Eusebio's passed ball. The next batter,
Chris Stynes, put down a sacrifice, which Wagner fielded. He had an
opportunity to throw out pinch runner Aaron Boone at second but
sailed his throw into center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a perfect double-play ball,'' Wagner said. ``I didn't
have a good grip on the ball and I was thinking to myself that I
should just hold onto it. But my arm wouldn't listen. That inning
could have been disastrous, but we didn't panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to get an easy save, but as long as we win it
doesn't matter how we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and none out, Wagner induced a
pop-out bunt from Pokey Reese, then struck out Jeffrey Hammonds and
Mike Cameron to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving them five outs in the ninth inning was not the way we
wanted to do it,'' Dierker said. ``We had just enough left in us to
still win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery had robbed them of just about everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Astros for the first time since 1996, when he pitched
for Atlanta, Avery exhibited the type of mastery that has helped
him compile a 2.55 ERA in 17 career appearances against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   He retired 20 of the 27 batters he faced Saturday and didn't
allow a hit until Bagwell's infield single in the fourth. Carl
Everett singled home the Astros' run against Avery in the seventh
inning. That one was unearned thanks to Cameron's error in center
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avery wasn't throwing hard, but he had a good changeup and
nobody could hit it,'' Eusebio said. ``When he threw his changeup,
it was swing and miss. He has better command than when he played
for the Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   One pitch marred an otherwise solid outing by Astros starter
Mike Hampton. The Reds, who were out-hit 6-5 by the Astros, got
their runs on Barry Larkin's three-run homer in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larkin's not on top of his game right now,'' Hampton said of
the Reds shortstop, who is hitting .164. ``But if you make a
mistake to him, he's going to make you pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Avery was pitching, I knew it was going to be a
low-scoring game. I'm just glad we were able to stay close enough
to come back and win it in the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
