A2271 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUNTING-GUSEWELLE-KAN     04-24 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNTING-GUSEWELLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL REASON FOR DECOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As you read this, you very likely will be sitting at your
breakfast table _ warm, dry and nibbling at some light
refreshment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I already will have been a full week in the place where this
time of the year always finds me _ in the springtime woods,
pretending to hunt turkeys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If it is raining, I will be wet to the skin. But wet or dry, I
will be asleep against my tree. After a week of getting up at 4
o'clock every morning, you find you can sleep anywhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is how Indian fakirs do it. They hunt turkeys for several
weeks, then they are perfectly willing to walk barefoot on glowing
coals to get to their bed, even if it is a bed of nails. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fortnight ago, I had to go to the country on another matter. I
pulled in the cabin drive, and started down to the pond to see if
by chance the dogwoods were in bloom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two turkeys _ a mature gobbler and one that might have been a
yearling _ were standing by my lane. They held their ground,
seeming rather indignant at the intrusion. Then, stately and
unhurried, they strode off into the woods. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But that was before the season on them opened. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By now _ long before now, actually _ those two will have
gathered all their kin and acquaintances and vanished into some
other dimension of space and time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every year it's the same. In March and early April, wild turkeys
are everywhere. I get letters from folks who complain that turkeys
are tramping down the petunias in their flower gardens and making
messes on the porch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mention that the time for the hunt is nearing and people snicker
at the notion that it might be considered sport. They tell of
seeing flocks _ no, herds _ of turkeys grazing beside the road.
Fifty of them. Or maybe it was 100. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You hunt them with a gun?'' they say incredulously. ``Why, I
could have killed one with a stick.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By opening day, however, the turkeys killable with sticks no
longer are available. Which is why, in recent years, I have come to
depend more and more on decoys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Decoys used to be bulky, hard-bodied objects that were awkward
to carry and clattered against brush as you walked, alerting every
living creature in the woods that Nimrod was on the prowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the technology has greatly advanced. Now they are made of a
kind of flexible foam rubber, and several of them easily can be
wadded into the pockets of a hunting coat. When removed, they
return to their original shape and may be strategically positioned
around the tree against which you are sleeping. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Their coloring is quite realistic. And because of their light
weight, the slightest breath of a breeze causes them to shift and
nod on their stakes. The similarity in appearance to an actual
turkey is remarkable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some hunters believe that decoys attract a gobbler, or at least
distract him as he comes unsuspecting to his doom. I have no
experience with that, but I will take their word for it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I like decoys for another reason. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Say you have been in the woods since 5 in the morning and it is
now a little after 6, with the dawn just coming. You have been
napping against your tree for 30 minutes or so when a good-size bug
crawls up your pant leg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In that intermediate state between sleep and waking, you wonder
idly if it is an ant, a beetle, or possibly a scorpion. Your eyes
open. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And what you see, in the blue first light of morning, is a
turkey standing directly out in front of you. Your pulse rate goes
to 200. The moment is electric _ what every turkey hunter dreams
of. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that it's your decoy out there. Go ahead and shoot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is as good as it's likely to get. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
