<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2272 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESIDENT-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      04-24 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENT-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL RACES ARE CHANGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Funny how the winds of change blow through presidential
politics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, the race to watch was on the GOP side, where a
whole boatload of candidates were lining up. But now George W. Bush
looks all but invincible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic side was supposed to be boring because the race
appeared so utterly predictable. Al Gore, with his vice
presidential trappings, was the man; Bill Bradley the
afterthought. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But now the Democrats may be the party with the donnybrook.
Wooden Al, the self-proclaimed Internet inventor, is bleeding
polling points by the gallon. Bradley is looking as if he might
have a chance, which is more than he could have hoped for at this
point against a sitting vice president. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A mid-April survey in New Hampshire, site of the first
presidential primary, had Gore at 52 percent and Bradley at 35.
Said pollster John Zogby: ``Gore is perilously close to 50 percent,
and Bradley has gained dramatically in the last month. With numbers
like these, Bradley could win in New Hampshire.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bradley already is in an enviable position for a long
shot: If Gore slips, Bradley is there to grab the baton because no
other Democrat is in the race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, the former NBA star, helped his cause by raising $4.3
million this year, a total that surpassed expectations. Gore took
in $8.9 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley is drawing attention for his ``big ideas,'' such as
combating racism, which contrasts nicely with the bite-size
proposals that Gore espouses, such as fighting traffic congestion.
To be sure, Bradley has yet to detail how he would accomplish his
goals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In prosperous times, when issues fade in importance, Bradley's
biggest selling point may be the fresh start he offers the nation.
He is, perhaps more than anything else, not Bill Clinton. Where the
president is slick, Bradley is plodding. Where Clinton's
extracurricular activities are legend, Bradley comes off as
terribly old-fashioned _ in a soothing way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gore's also a Dudley Do-right. The difference is Gore has been
so fiercely loyal to the president, as he must, that he and Clinton
appear linked forever. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gore can't criticize Clinton. He must support him in the wake of
the Monica Lewinsky scandal. He must back the president's policies
in Bosnia. Bradley, meantime, can express the doubts he shares with
many Americans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fresh starts, after times of turmoil, are enormously appealing
prospects in American politics. That's why one Kansas Democrat told
me Friday that, sure, people are still talking about Gore. But
they're also saying, ``Don't rule out Bill Bradley.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's why a leading Colorado Democrat told the Rocky Mountain
News last week that ``We're afraid Gore might be painted with some
of the Clinton stuff.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the recent Kansas City, Mo., mayor's race, George Blackwood
was in Gore's position, the second-in-command who focused like a
laser beam on the city's good times. Blackwood refused to admit
that change was needed, a stand that turned off many voters already
uneasy about the corruption that rocked City Hall in recent years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Blackwood ran as an insider because he did not
want to criticize Mayor Emanuel Cleaver, whose support he
desperately sought. Gore faces something of the same issue. He must
distance himself from Clinton, but not in a way that appears
disloyal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gore remains an enormously tough opponent. The Democrat
establishment is squarely on his side. Bradley has yet to pick up
the backing of a single member of Congress. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats, beware. You've got a race. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
