<DOCNO> NYT19990424.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENTS-VIOLENCE-KAN &LR;      04-24 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-VIOLENCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS NEED TO EXAMINE THEIR ROLE IN WAKE OF COLORADO TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD AND LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where were the parents? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did the mothers and fathers of teen-age gunmen Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold make crucial mistakes? How could they not have seen
what was coming? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the horror at Columbine High School in suburban
Denver, these are questions every parent must be asking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And with good reason. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just do the math on the time that went into preparations. The
killers: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Made pipe bombs and had at least one propane tank with
explosives attached, weighing 25 pounds, and put together an
enormous ammunition supply. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Developed Web sites filled with hate and instructions on how to
make bombs, painted their faces, and learned and practiced German
expressions and Nazi salutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Collected swastikas and black clothing, and apparently,
memorized their hyperviolent video games _ enough so their rampage
inside the school echoed the games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if Harris and Klebold were amazingly efficient at their
abhorrent activities, it's work that had to take weeks, if not
months, to finish. Were the children so skilled at concealing what
was going on? Could their parents have been oblivious to all this? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday in Colorado, Sheriff John Stone of Jefferson County,
site of the massacre, placed some of the blame on the killers'
parents. Stone said investigators found a shotgun barrel on a
dresser and bomb-making materials in one of the youths' homes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this stuff was clearly visible, and the parents
should have known,'' Stone told reporters. ``I think parents should
be accountable for their kids' actions.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Others contend that the parents of Harris and Klebold, none of
whom have commented on the shootings beyond statements expressing
sympathy that were released by their attorneys, might not be
especially different from many parents in the United States. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This probably isn't the result of exceptionally bad parenting,
unfortunately,'' said Kansas City, Mo., area child psychologist
Jerry Wyckoff. ``Instead, it's more likely the result of average
parenting, just like most of what goes on out in Littleton, or in
our community.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean there are hundreds of thousands of kids about
to explode in American neighborhoods. Nobody knows, or ever will
know, just why these two kids turned into killers. Was it the real
presence of true evil on Earth? Insanity? The violent, irrational
dynamics that can develop in a group? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wyckoff says that, in his experience, the intense boredom,
disaffection and alienation that can contribute to such horrors as
the massacre at Columbine are more prevalent in middle- and
upper-middle-class suburbs, where kids typically have lots of money
and lots of free time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Generally, in those circumstances, Wyckoff said: ``What we have
are parents who are providing their kids with everything they could
ever need, except supervision. So the kids fill time by getting
lost in violent games and music and television. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, the parents are sitting upstairs hoping
everything downstairs is OK. Most of the time it is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's not.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Heide has evaluated 90 kids who have killed. She is a
University of South Florida-Tampa psychologist and criminologist
and author of two books on the subject. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most consistent link among young killers she has studied? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They all talk about the lack of limits they lived under,'' she
said. ``Parents have to be the ones who set the limits. We have to
understand that kids who keep getting away with greater and greater
wrongs may well continue to push out. We all know where that can
lead.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She points out that setting limits does not make for a popular
parent, in the short term. But in time, children not only respect
limits but crave them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Debora Bell-Dolan, a University of Missouri child psychologist,
says setting limits begins with talking and listening, and getting
involved in a child's life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can almost hear the conversation these boys had with their
parents,'' she said. ``They'd ask their sons where they were going
and they would say something like `working on a project in the
garage.' And the parents would think, `Oh, that's great. Just like
Boy Scouts.' Too few parents would take a great enough interest to
actually go out and take a look at what that project might be.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree that involvement, including a willingness to sneak
a peek through a child's room every now and then, is exactly what
is needed. If a child is playing violent games, it might not be
necessary to ban the game from the house. But the parent should
play the game with the child enough to know exactly what is going
on, and should talk about the game and the difference between
fantasy and reality. If there is a problem, the parent has to be
willing to then ban the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for violent music and movies. It also goes for
everyday life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, experts also agreed that any parent not using the
Columbine tragedy as a way to start talking about typical teen-age
problems was making a sad mistake. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, you start this dialogue when your children are young
and continue it through adulthood,'' Bell-Dolan said. ``But if that
relationship hasn't existed during the first 15 years of your
child's life, start it now _ today.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This message isn't only for the more affluent. Experts agree the
violence that springs from poorer, inner-city neighborhoods has
similar roots, a lack of parental supervision and involvement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gary Martasin, a parent of suburban kids and the public
relations director for the Hickman Mills School District in Jackson
County, Mo., said he insisted on knowing where his son is at all
times. ``My son has a beeper,'' he said. ``I look at it as an
electronic leash. When that goes off, if it's me, he has five
minutes to call me back, or he's grounded.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Or, for instance, this weekend, 13-year-old Pamela Todd of Blue
Springs, Mo., wanted to attend the Korn heavy-metal rock concert at
Kemper Arena in Kansas City, Mo. As she stood in line waiting to
enter, her sparkled eyes and pale, eerie lipstick fit right into
the crowd around her. However, Jim and Sydney Todd, her dad and
mom, seemed out of place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``She really wanted to go, and there was no way I was going to
let her go alone,'' Jim Todd said. ``So we compromised.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pamela's thoughts on her parents' attendance: ``They're cool.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Todd pointed out he wasn't in any way looking forward to the
music, and Sydney Todd brought earplugs. But he did see the concert
as a chance to spend extra time with his daughter, and despite the
noise awaiting inside, the trip appeared worthwhile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bottom line, as parents, is we've got to help our
children build a good moral foundation,'' he said. ``But I also
think, after they start growing up, too often we allow everything
else going on in our lives to cut down the time with our children.
I mean, I'm obviously only here for my daughter tonight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But I am here for her.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
