<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIX OF ABORTION, SOCIAL SECURITY JUST TOO CONTROVERSIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a columnist gets extra credit for stimulating reader
reaction, last week's effort playing off U.S. Sen. Sam Brownback's
remarks about abortion and Social Security was a bell ringer.
</P>
<P>
   The column agreed with the Kansas Republican's contention that
abortions undermined Social Security's long-term funding. The
response was both humongous and overwhelmingly critical. Of more
than 50 e-mails, StarTouch responses and phone calls, only three
readers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Sam Brownback was a moron, but you, from whom I
expect more logic and reason, apparently are worse than he is,''
was the reaction from a StarTouch respondent whose comments were
typical.
</P>
<P>
   Most critics were as caustic as they were disinclined to
acknowledge the narrow economic context of my column. Brownback
said abortions reduced the potential pool of taxpayers needed to
support the long-range funding needs of Social Security. This is
inarguable, and goes beyond mere opinion. As support for the
argument, credible estimates of the potential financial effects
were offered from respectable, albeit biased, sources.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, all who disagreed with the premise failed to
confront the ineluctable fact that Social Security's demographic
problem is a shrinking pool of taxpaying contributors and an
expanding pool of beneficiaries. Here's a sample of some dissenting
e-mail observations and my view of why the comments miss the mark:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe any responsible person would advocate
increasing the population more than it already is...our planet can
hold just so many people.'' (OK, how many people would that be?
Sorry, but Malthus is still wrong. Try to think of human beings not
as burdens, but as resources, because that is what most of them
become.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You stated the math is simple, citing 16 workers for one
Social Security beneficiary a half-century ago compared to (three
workers) today...you are not comparing `apples to apples.' Fifty
years ago there were fewer eligible beneficiaries than there are
today.'' (My point exactly. Thank you for helping me make it.)
</P>
<P>
   ``A potential flaw with this argument is that it seems very
unlikely the average aborted pregnancy would have resulted in a
person who would have been the same as the average not-aborted
pregnancy....Therefore, it is not at all clear that aborted people
would contribute as much to society as you are suggesting.'' (We
cannot be certain on this point. What we do know with certainty,
though, is that Social Security's viability depends on adequate
numbers of taxpayers to finance the system. Period.)
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you reconcile (this view) with the fact that since the
beginning of the century birth rates of every successive generation
(have) been declining.'' (No reconciliation is needed. Your
observation is correct. Declining birth rates due to other factors
are indeed another demographic problem for Social Security. It
could even be argued that they exacerbate abortion's impact.)
</P>
<P>
   ``/{The Kansas City Star/} would be a better newspaper if you
resigned to get a job for which you are qualified.'' (You are not
alone in that opinion. By the way, what job might that be?)
</P>
<P>
   Thank you all for your feedback. It wasn't fun, but it was
instructive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
