<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETS STILL MISFIRING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The post-game atmosphere in the visitor's dressing room at the
Sports Arena usually seems as foreboding as a bachelor party.
</P>
<P>
   But something peculiar happened there on Friday night. After a
hotshot team was outscored by the Clippers, the place turned into
Jerry Springer's green room.
</P>
<P>
   For our top-ranked rant, we take you to the space occupied by
Antoine Carr:
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here to play for no sorry-assed quittin' team,''
said Carr, a veteran of two Utah Jazz NBA Finals losses who now
plays for the Houston Rockets. Carr probably is upset because the
Rockets are supposed to win the NBA championship every time Michael
Jordan retires. ``I don't need this; I could play for Timbuktu.''
</P>
<P>
   We doubt that Timbuktu has cap room, Antoine.
</P>
<P>
   Hold on, someone else is clearing his throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't panic after one loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the words of Charles Barkley, a notepad-stuffin'
Rocket who made the above statement about three hours before Carr
started up. Barkley was whipping through the preamble to his
nightly chat with the sporting press, and his panic postponement
referred to Wednesday's defeat at the hands of the astonishingly
mortal Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who wants an NBA championship ring badly enough to have
signed for the million-dollar exception, insists everything is fine
on Planet Chuck.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody's got a better life than me,'' he said, ``I really
want to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, the basketball side of Barkley's life was made
miserable by a young Clipper named Maurice Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Seated a 10-foot bank shot away from Barkley was first-year
Rocket Scottie Pippen, who has more rings than the Olympic logo.
After Wednesday's loss to Dallas, Pippen allegedly drove his jalopy
through a red traffic light. He was pulled over by cops who quickly
suspected Jordan's ex-faithful sidekick of having a blood-alcohol
number that eclipsed his field-goal percentage.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Pip spun away from any legal chitchat, but did manage
to put the Clippers' final days at the Sports Arena into grim
perspective:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like they're leaving the Boston Garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Woof.
</P>
<P>
   Seated across the aisle from Pippen was Hakeem Olajuwon, the
Hall of Fame-bound center and last surviving member of the Rockets'
two championship crews. Teamed with Barkley and Pippen, he
represents more star power than Mike Ovitz. But when the Clips were
finished with 'em, the Rockets were a mediocre 27-17.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Pippen still looks uncomfortable pushing buttons in the
Rocket offense, which usually winds up going low postal, anyway.
Houston starts a pair of extremely gifted rookie guards who can do
everything except pass muster as card-carrying assist guys. Othella
Harrington, who excelled as a low-post reserve, has been lost to
foot surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But they still expect to maintain adequate savvy for a playoff
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can beat any team in the league,'' Barkley said, ``but we
have to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   A reporter with a straight face asks if that beating includes
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Lakers make the playoffs, we'll be there,'' Barkley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they rallied to drag the Clippers into overtime,
that was the Rockets' best shot of the night.
</P>
<P>
   (sub) Tap City for draft?
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Draft, which is expected to be thinner than a
sportswriter's wallet, could receive a boost if Lamar Odom decides
to become part of it. If Rhode Island's 6-foot-9 point forward has
made his decision, he's keeping it a secret.
</P>
<P>
   If he goes for the loot, Odom who is projected as a top-three
pick must break the news to the NBA by midnight on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't come out,'' said one NBA talent jockey, ``I'll
be shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Corey Maggette, the precocious acrobat from Duke,
said he has yet to decide if he'll return to school for his
sophomore season or enter the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Blake, the NBA's pit bull of player evaluation, had a
typically frosty opinion when asked of Maggette's immediate pro
impact. ``He's had one good game,'' said Blake of the 6-5 swingman
who was unable to crack Duke's starting lineup as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Attention, draft wizards ... last week's pre-draft Desert
Classic in Tempe didn't exactly inspire rhapsodies from NBA
personnel hounds.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if any of the participants were swell players, one
judge said, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   But James Posey, an active and intense small forward from
Xavier, was the favorite of many others.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Posey can't play in this league,'' one longtime scout said,
``the NBA is in much better shape than most people think.''
</P>
<P>
   The lottery (sometimes referred to as ``The Clipper Variety
Hour'') will be held May 22.
</P>
<P>
   (sub) Another title for Edney
</P>
<P>
   Former Long Beach Poly High and UCLA star Tyus Edney was voted
the Most Valuable Player in Thursday's Euro League championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   Edney, who saved UCLA's championship bacon in 1995 before taking
a brief NBA spin, scored 14 points, grabbed six rebounds and handed
out six assists for Lithuanian powerhouse Zaligiris Kaunus in an
82-74 upset of Kinder Bologna. You get bonus points if you remember
that Michael Olowokandi spent a few weeks playing for Kinder.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the final, Kinder had to go through Bologna's
TeamSystem, and former Long Beach State standout Andrew Betts.
</P>
<P>
   (sub) Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Raptors don't have Charles Oakley under contract for
next season, but they do have the first-round draft pick of the
miserable Denver Nuggets, who coughed up that baby to get Chauncey
Billups out of Toronto. ... He's a rap star, an agent, a failed
player and now in cahoots with Converse. He's Percy Miller, also
known as Master P, and his ``No Limit'' empire has made an
agreement with Converse to produce a sneaker called ``The Smooth.''
You may have seen Cleveland's Brevin Knight selling the shoe in a
commercial. According to rumor, Miller's next gig is ``Master P
Theatre.'' ... This just in: Michael Jordan thinks Vancouver's Mike
Bibby is the NBA's best rookie! Here's a stunner: like Mike, Bibby
is represented by David Falk. ... According to at least one of
their Pistons' teammates, Christian Laettner (an ex-Duke star) and
Jerry Stackhouse (North Carolina) scrapped over a card-game dispute
on the team plane. Gee, if Nike decides to do another March Madness
blood-doping commercial, we've just discovered the perfect rats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-24-99 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
